Patricia Miranda]]|USA}}\n|-\n|{{flagmedalist|[[Alena Adashinskaya]]|RUS}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|55 kg<br>{{DetailsLink|2006 World Wrestling Championships \u2013 Women's freestyle 55 kg}}\n|rowspan=2|{{flagmedalist|[[Saori Yoshida]]|JPN}}\n|rowspan=2|{{flagmedalist|[[Mariya Ivanova|Mariya Yahorava]]|BLR|1995}}\n|{{flagmedalist|[[Minerva Montero]]|ESP}}\n|-\n|{{flagmedalist|[[Ida-Theres Karlsson-Nerell|Ida-Theres Karlsson]]|SWE}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|59 kg<br>{{DetailsLink|2006 World Wrestling Championships \u2013 Women's freestyle 59 kg}}\n|rowspan=2|{{flagmedalist|[[Ayako Shoda]]|JPN}}\n|rowspan=2|{{flagmedalist|[[Su Lihui]]|CHN}}\n|{{flagmedalist|[[Alka Tomar]]|IND}}\n|-\n|{{flagmedalist|[[Nataliya Synyshyn]]|UKR}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|63 kg<br>{{DetailsLink|2006 World Wrestling Championships \u2013 Women's freestyle 63 kg}}\n|rowspan=2|{{flagmedalist|[[Kaori Icho]]|JPN}}\n|rowspan=2|{{flagmedalist|[[Xu Haiyan]]|CHN}}\n|{{flagmedalist|[[Monika Michalik|Monika Rogien]]|POL}}\n|-\n|{{flagmedalist|[[Helena Allandi]]|SWE}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|67 kg<br>{{DetailsLink|2006 World Wrestling Championships \u2013 Women's freestyle 67 kg}}\n|rowspan=2|{{flagmedalist|[[Jing Ruixue]]|CHN}}\n|rowspan=2|{{flagmedalist|[[Martine Dugrenier]]|CAN}}\n|{{flagmedalist|[[Maria M\u00fcller (wrestler)|Maria M\u00fcller]]|GER}}\n|-\n|{{flagmedalist|[[Eri Sakamoto]]|JPN}}\n|-\n|rowspan=2|72 kg<br>{{DetailsLink|2006 World Wrestling Championships \u2013 Women's freestyle 72 kg}}\n|rowspan=2|{{flagmedalist|[[Stanka Zlateva]]|BUL}}\n|rowspan=2|{{flagmedalist|[[Kyoko Hamaguchi]]|JPN}}\n|{{flagmedalist|[[Elena Perepelkina]]|RUS}}\n|-\n|{{flagmedalist|[[Kristie Marano]]|USA}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20060512193547/http://www.fila-wrestling.com:80/download/monsenguan06.pdf Schedule]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20080629222649/http://www.themat.com/specialevents/2006/worlds/default.php Themat.com]\n\n==External links==\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20061108112016/http://guangzhou.fila-wrestling.com/index.php Official website]\n{{WC FILA}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:2006 Fila Wrestling World Championships}}\n[[Category:2006 in sport wrestling|FILA Wrestling World Championships]]\n[[Category:2006 in Chinese sport|Wrestling World Championships]]\n[[Category:World Wrestling Championships]]\n[[Category:International wrestling competitions hosted by China|Wrestling World Championships]]\n[[Category:2006 World Wrestling Championships| ]]\n", "name_user": "Mohsen1248", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMen's Greco-Roman", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2006_World_Wrestling_Championships"}
{"title_page": "Violence against women", "text_new": "{{short description|Violent acts committed primarily against women and girls}}\n[[File:MURDER-SCALE-4-2019.jpg|thumb|A map of the world showing Murders per 100,000 population committed against women, 2019]]\n{{For|the journal|Violence Against Women (journal)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{pp-semi-sock|small=yes}}\n{{Violence against women}}\n{{Feminism sidebar}}\n{{Discrimination sidebar|state=collapsed}}\n'''Violence against women''' ('''VAW'''), also known as '''gender-based violence'''<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Russo | first1 = Nancy Felipe | last2 = Pirlott | first2 = Angela | title = Gender-based violence: concepts, methods, and findings | journal = [[Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences]] |issue=Violence and Exploitation Against Women and Girls | volume = 1087 | pages = 178&ndash;205 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] and [[Oxfam]] | doi = 10.1196/annals.1385.024 | pmid = 17189506 | date = November 2006 | ref = harv | bibcode = 2006NYASA1087..178R }}</ref> and '''sexual and gender-based violence''' ('''SGBV'''),<ref>[http://www.who.int/hac/techguidance/pht/SGBV/en/ Sexual and Gender-based Violence] (WHO)</ref> are violent acts the victims of which are primarily or exclusively [[woman|women]] or girls. Such violence is often considered a form of [[hate crime]],<ref>''Citations'':\n* {{cite book | last = Angelari | first = Marguerite | chapter = Hate crime statutes: a promising tool for fighting violence against women | chapterurl = https://books.google.com/books?id=2YdCbgXjr-EC&pg=PA405 | editor-last = Maschke | editor-first = Karen J. | title = Pornography, sex work, and hate speech | pages = 405&ndash;448 | publisher = Taylor and Francis | location = New York | year = 1997 | isbn = 9780815325208 }} \n* {{cite book | last = Gerstenfeld | first = Phyllis B. | chapter = The hate debate: constitutional and policy problems | chapterurl = https://books.google.com/books?id=DiBIZcx1nPcC&pg=PA58 | editor-last = Gerstenfeld | editor-first = Phyllis B. | title = Hate crimes: causes, controls, and controversies | page = 58 | publisher = Sage | location = Thousand Oaks, California | year = 2013 | isbn = 9781452256627 }}\n* {{cite book | last = McPhail | first = Beverly | chapter = Gender-bias hate crimes: a review | chapterurl = https://books.google.com/books?id=2ZNnXj_SbOsC&pg=PA271 | editor-last = Perry | editor-first = Barbara | title = Hate and bias crime: a reader | page = 271 | publisher = Routledge | location = New York | year = 2003 | isbn = 9780415944076 }}</ref> committed against women or girls specifically because they are female, and can take many forms. \n\nVAW has a very long history, though the incidents and intensity of such violence has varied over time and even today varies between societies. Such violence is often seen as a mechanism for the subjugation of women, whether in society in general or in an [[interpersonal relationship]]. Such violence may arise from a sense of [[entitlement]], [[superior (hierarchy)|superior]]ity, [[misogyny]] or similar attitudes in the perpetrator, or because of his violent nature, especially against women. \n\nThe UN [[Declaration on the Elimination of Violence Against Women]] states, \"violence against women is a manifestation of historically unequal power relations between men and women\" and \"violence against women is one of the crucial social mechanisms by which women are forced into a subordinate position compared with men.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.un-documents.net/a48r104.htm |title=A/RES/48/104 - Declaration on the Elimination of Violence against Women |publisher=United Nations General Assembly |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Kofi Annan]], [[Secretary-General of the United Nations]], declared in a 2006 report posted on the [[United Nations Development Fund for Women]] (UNIFEM) website:<blockquote>Violence against women and girls is a problem of [[pandemic]] proportions. At least one out of every three women around the world has been beaten, coerced into sex, or otherwise abused in her lifetime with the abuser usually someone known to her.<ref name=\"Moradian\">{{cite web |url=http://en.tolerancy.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=176:2009-09-15-08-37-55&catid=43:events-a-reports&Itemid=90 |title=Domestic Violence against Single and Married Women in Iranian Society |last=Moradian |first=Azad |work=Tolerancy.org |publisher=[[The Chicago School of Professional Psychology]] |date=10 September 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425230632/http://en.tolerancy.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=176%3A2009-09-15-08-37-55&catid=43%3Aevents-a-reports&Itemid=90 |archivedate=25 April 2012 |accessdate=1 March 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref></blockquote>\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Types of violence==\nViolence against women can fit into several broad categories. These include violence carried out by individuals as well as states. Some of the forms of violence perpetrated by individuals are: [[rape]], [[domestic violence]], [[sexual harassment]], [[acid throwing]], [[reproductive coercion]], [[female infanticide]], [[sex selective abortion|prenatal sex selection]], [[obstetric violence]], [[Online Gender-Based Violence|online gender-based violence]] and [[mob violence]]; as well as harmful customary or traditional practices such as [[honor killings]], [[dowry death|dowry violence]], [[female genital mutilation]], [[marriage by abduction]] and [[forced marriage]]. There are forms of violence which may be perpetrated or condoned by the government, such as [[war rape]]; [[sexual violence]] and [[sexual slavery]] during conflict; [[forced sterilization]]; [[forced abortion]]; violence by the police and authoritative personnel; [[stoning]] and [[flogging]]. Many forms of VAW, such as [[trafficking in women]] and [[forced prostitution]] are often perpetrated by organized criminal networks.<ref name=\"Pr\u00fcgl, E. 2013\">{{cite book | last = Pr\u00fcgl | first = Elisabeth (Director) | title = Violence Against Women. Gender and International Affairs Class 2013. Lecture conducted from The Graduate Institute of International and Development Studies (IHEID) | location = Geneva, Switzerland | date = 25 November 2013 }}</ref> Histrorically, there have been forms of organized WAV, such as the [[Witch trials in the early modern period]] or the [[sexual slavery]] of the [[Comfort women]].\n\nThe [[World Health Organization]] (WHO), in its research on VAW, has analyzed and categorized the different forms of VAW occurring through all stages of life from before birth to old age.<ref name=\"WHO_VAW\">{{cite book | last = WHO | author-link = World Health Organization | title = Violence against women: Definition and scope of the problem, 1, 1-3 | url = http://www.who.int/gender/violence/v4.pdf | publisher = [[World Health Organization]] | date = July 1997 | access-date = 30 November 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn recent years, there has been a trend of approaching VAW at an international level  through means such as conventions or, in the [[European Union]], through [[Directive (European Union)|directive]]s (such as the directive against [[sexual harassment]], and the directive against [[human trafficking]]).<ref>{{cite web | title = Directive 2002/73/EC - equal treatment of 23 September 2002 amending Council Directive 76/207/EEC on the implementation of the principle of equal treatment for men and women as regards access to employment, vocational training and promotion, and working conditions | url = http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=CONSLEG:1976L0207:20021005:EN:PDF |format=PDF | date = September 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=OJ:L:2011:101:0001:0011:EN:PDF |format=PDF |title= Directive 2011/36/EU of the European Parliament and of the Council of 5 April 2011 on preventing and combating trafficking in human beings and protecting its victims, and replacing Council Framework Decision 2002/629/JH |work=Official Journal of the European Union |accessdate=4 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Definition==\nA number of international instruments that aim to eliminate violence against women and domestic violence have been enacted by various international bodies. These generally start with a definition of what such violence is, with a view to combating such practices. The Istanbul Convention ([[Council of Europe Convention on preventing and combating violence against women and domestic violence]]) of the [[Council of Europe]] describes VAW \"as a violation of human rights and a form of discrimination against women\" and defines VAW as \"all acts of gender-based violence that result in, or are likely to result in, physical, sexual, psychological or economic harm or suffering to women, including threats of such acts, coercion or arbitrary deprivation of liberty, whether occurring in public or in private life.<ref name=\"COE 210\">{{cite web |url=https://www.coe.int/en/web/conventions/full-list/-/conventions/treaty/210 |title=Details of Treaty No.210: Council of Europe Convention on preventing and combating violence against women and domestic violence |publisher=Council of Europe |date= |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe 1979 [[Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women]] (CEDAW) of the [[United Nations General Assembly]] makes recommendations relating to VAW,<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |title=General recommendations made by the Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination against Women |url=https://www.un.org/womenwatch/daw/cedaw/recommendations/recomm.htm#recom1 |website=www.un.org |accessdate=2015-05-08 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150510132556/http://www.un.org/womenwatch/daw/cedaw/recommendations/recomm.htm#recom1 |archivedate=10 May 2015 |df=dmy-all }}, General Recommendations 12 and 19</ref> and the [[Vienna Declaration and Programme of Action]] mentions VAW.<ref>{{cite web |date=12 July 1993 |url=http://www.refworld.org/cgi-bin/texis/vtx/rwmain?page=topic&tocid=459d17822&toid=459b17a82&docid=3ae6b39ec&skip=O |title=Vienna Declaration and Programme of Action |publisher=UN General Assembly |accessdate=3 April 2016}}, paragraph 18</ref> However, the 1993 [[United Nations General Assembly]] resolution on the [[Declaration on the Elimination of Violence Against Women]] was the first international instrument to explicitly define VAW and elaborate on the subject.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unwomen.org/en/what-we-do/ending-violence-against-women/global-norms-and-standards |title=What We Do: Ending Violence against Women: Global Norms and Standards |publisher=UN Women |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> Other definitions of VAW are set out in the 1994 ''Inter-American Convention on the Prevention, Punishment, and Eradication of Violence against Women''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oas.org/juridico/english/treaties/a-61.html |title=Inter-American Convention On The Prevention, Punishment And Eradication Of Violence Against Women \"Convention Of Belem Do Para\" |publisher=Organization of American States |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> and by the 2003 [[Maputo Protocol]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.achpr.org/files/instruments/women-protocol/achpr_instr_proto_women_eng.pdf |title=Protocol to the African Charter on Human and Peoples' Rights on the Rights of Women in Africa |publisher=African Commission on Human and Peoples' Rights |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, the term ''gender-based violence'' refers to \"any acts or threats of acts intended to hurt or make women suffer physically, sexually or psychologically, and which affect women because they are women or affect women disproportionately\".<ref>{{cite book | last = Richters | first = J.M. Annemiek | title = Women, culture and violence: a development, health and human rights issue | publisher = Women and Autonomy Centre (VENA), Leiden University | location = Leiden, The Netherlands | year = 1994 | url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KvbtAAAAMAAJ | oclc = 905570045 | isbn = 9789072631374 }}</ref> The definition of gender-based violence is most often \"used interchangeably with violence against women\",<ref name=\"Krantz\">{{cite journal | last1 = Krantz | first1 = Gunilla | last2 = Garcia-Moreno | first2 = Claudia | title = Violence against women | journal = [[Journal of Epidemiology and Community Health]] | volume = 59 | issue = 10 | pages = 818&ndash;821 | publisher = [[BMJ Group]] | doi = 10.1136/jech.2004.022756 | jstor = 25570854 | pmid = 16166351 | pmc = 1732916 | date = October 2005 | ref = harv }}</ref> and some articles on VAW reiterate these conceptions by suggesting that men are the main perpetrators of this violence.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Sen | first = Purna | title = Development practice and violence against women | journal = Gender & Development | volume = 6 | issue = 3 | pages = 7&ndash;16 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] and [[Oxfam]] | doi = 10.1080/741922827 | pmid = 12294415 | jstor = 4030497 | date = November 1998 | ref = harv }}</ref> Moreover, the definition stated by the 1993 Declaration on the Elimination of Violence Against Women also supported the notion that violence is rooted in the inequality between men and women when the term violence is used together with the term 'gender-based.'<ref name=\"Krantz\"/>\n\nIn ''Recommendation Rec(2002)5 of the Committee of Ministers to member states on the protection of women against violence'', the Council of Europe stipulated that VAW \"includes, but is not limited to, the following\":<ref>{{cite web |date=30 April 2002 |url=https://wcd.coe.int/ViewDoc.jsp?id=280915&Site=CM&BackColorInternet=C3C3C3&BackColorIntranet=EDB021&BackColorLogged=F5D383 |format=PDF |title=Recommendations of the Committee of Ministers to member states on the protection of women against violence |publisher=Council of Europe Committee of Ministers |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n:a. violence occurring in the family or domestic unit, including, ''inter alia'', physical and mental aggression, emotional and psychological abuse, rape and sexual abuse, incest, rape between spouses, regular or occasional partners and cohabitants, crimes committed in the name of honour, female genital and sexual mutilation and other traditional practices harmful to women, such as forced marriages;\n\n:b. violence occurring within the general community, including, ''inter alia'', rape, sexual abuse, sexual harassment and intimidation at work, in institutions or elsewhere trafficking in women for the purposes of sexual exploitation and economic exploitation and sex tourism;\n\n:c. violence perpetrated or condoned by the state or its officials;\n\n:d. violation of the human rights of women in situations of armed conflict, in particular the taking of hostages, forced displacement, systematic rape, sexual slavery, forced pregnancy, and trafficking for the purposes of sexual exploitation and economic exploitation.\n\nThese definitions of VAW as being gender-based are seen by some to be unsatisfactory and problematic. These definitions are conceptualized in an understanding of society as patriarchal, signifying unequal relations between men and women.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Ert\u00fcrk | first = Yakin | title = Towards a post-patriarchal gender order: confronting the universality and the particularity of violence against women | journal = Sociologisk Forskning | volume = 46 | issue = 4 | pages = 61&ndash;70 | publisher = Sveriges Sociologf\u00f6rbund [Swedish Sociological Association] | jstor = 20853687 | date = 2009 | ref = harv }}</ref> Opponents of such definitions argue that the definitions disregard violence against men and that the term ''[[gender]]'', as used in ''gender based violence'', only refers to women. Other critics argue that employing the term ''gender'' in this particular way may introduce notions of inferiority and subordination for femininity and superiority for masculinity.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Visaria | first = Leela | title = Violence against women: a field study | journal = [[Economic and Political Weekly]] | volume = 35 | issue = 20 | pages = 1742&ndash;1751 | publisher = Sameeksha Trust, Mumbai, India | jstor = 4409296 | date = 13 May 2000 | ref = harv }}</ref><ref name=\"Michau, L. 2007 pp.96\">{{cite journal | last = Michau | first = Lori | title = Approaching old problems in new ways: community mobilisation as a primary prevention strategy to combat violence against women | journal = Gender & Development | volume = 15 | issue = 1 | pages = 95&ndash;109 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] and [[Oxfam]] | doi = 10.1080/13552070601179144 | jstor = 20461184 | date = March 2007 | ref = harv }}</ref> There is no widely accepted current definition that covers all the dimensions of gender-based violence rather than the one for women that tends to reproduce the concept of binary oppositions: masculinity versus femininity.<ref name=\"Pr\u00fcgl, E. 2013\"/>\n\n==History==\n\n===Overview===\n[[File:Grandville Cent Proverbes page69.png|thumb|right|An illustration from [[Jean Ignace Isidore G\u00e9rard|JJ Grandville]]'s ''Cent Proverbes'' (1845) captioned \"Qui aime bien ch\u00e2tie bien\" (''Who loves well, punishes well''). A man beating a woman is shown in the back.]]\n[[File:Torturing and execution of witches in medieval miniature.jpg|thumb|Burning witches, with others held in Stocks]]\n[[File:Sati ceremony.jpg|thumb|[[Sati (practice)|Sati]] (a Hindu practice whereby a [[widow]] immolates herself on the funeral pyre of her husband) ceremony.]]\n[[File:Bound feet (X-ray).jpg|thumb|X-ray of [[bound feet]], China]]\nThe history of violence against women remains vague in scientific literature. This is in part because many kinds of violence against women (specifically rape, sexual assault, and domestic violence) are under-reported, often due to societal norms, taboos, stigma, and the sensitive nature of the subject.<ref name=\"WHO World Report on violence and health\" /><ref name=\"VAM: Global scope & magnitude\">{{cite journal | last1 = Watts | first1 = Charlotte | last2 = Zimmerman | first2 = Cathy | title = Violence against women: global scope and magnitude | journal = [[The Lancet]] | volume = 359 | issue = 9313 | pages = 1232&ndash;1237 | publisher = [[Elsevier]] | pmid = 11955557 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(02)08221-1 | date = 6 April 2002 | ref = harv }}</ref> It is widely recognized that even today, a lack of reliable and continuous data is an obstacle to forming a clear picture of violence against women.<ref name=\"UN In-depth Study on all Forms of Violence Against Women\">{{cite book | last = UN | author-link = United Nations |title=In-depth study on all forms of violence against women. Report of the Secretary-General.|url=http://www.un.org/womenwatch/daw/vaw/violenceagainstwomenstudydoc.pdf1|publisher=United Nations General Assembly | id = A/61/122/Add | date = 2006 |accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the history of violence against women is difficult to track, it is clear that much of the violence was accepted, condoned and even legally sanctioned.<ref name=\"Film script\">{{cite book|last=Ireland|first=Patricia | title=No Safe Place: Violence Against Women (script) |url=https://www.pbs.org/kued/nosafeplace/script/script.html|publisher=[[PBS]] documentary |date =1996|accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> Examples include that Roman law gave men the right to chastise their wives, even to the point of death,<ref name=\"Roman Law\">{{cite journal | last = Stedman | first = Berne | title = Right of husband to chastise wife | journal = [[Virginia Law Review|The Virginia Law Register]] | volume = 3 | issue = 4 | pages = 241&ndash;248 | publisher = [[University of Virginia School of Law]] | doi = 10.2307/1106112 | jstor = 1106112 | date = August 1917 | ref = harv }} Also available at [http://heinonline.org/HOL/LandingPage?handle=hein.journals/valrgn3&div=35&id=&page= HeinOnline]. Full text available here [https://archive.org/stream/jstor-1106112/1106112_djvu.txt].</ref> and the burning of witches, which was condoned by both the church and the state (although this was not a practice exclusively against women).<ref name=\"Film script\" />\n\nThe history of violence against women is closely related to the historical view of women as property and a gender role of subservience.<ref>{{cite book| last = Toren | first = Christina | chapter = Transforming love: representing Fijian hierarchy | chapterurl = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KGXezlZnjF8C&pg=PA36 | editor-last1 = Harvey | editor-first1 = Penelope | editor-last2= Gow | editor-first2 = Peter  | title = Sex and violence: issues in representation and experience | pages = 18&ndash;39 | publisher = Routledge | location = London New York | year = 1994 | isbn = 9780415057349 }}</ref> Explanations of [[patriarchy]] and an overall world system or status quo in which gender inequalities exist and are perpetuated are cited to explain the scope and history of violence against women.<ref name=\"VAM: Global scope & magnitude\" /><ref name=\"UN In-depth Study on all Forms of Violence Against Women\" /> The UN Declaration on the Elimination of Violence against Women (1993) states, \"violence against women is a manifestation of historically unequal power relations between men and women, which have led to domination over and discrimination against women by men and to the prevention of the full advancement of women, and that violence against women is one of the crucial social mechanisms by which women are forced into a subordinate position compared with men.\"<ref>{{cite book | last = UN | author-link = United Nations | title = Declaration on the Elimination of Violence against Women | id = A/RES/48/104 | url = https://www.un.org/documents/ga/res/48/a48r104.htm | publisher = United Nations }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = UNFPA | author-link = United Nations Population Fund | title = Addressing gender-based violence: advancing human rights | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141021001255/http://www.unfpa.org/rights/violence.htm | archive-date = 21 October 2014 | url = http://www.unfpa.org/rights/violence.htm | publisher = [[United Nations Population Fund]] (UNFPA) }}</ref>\n\nAccording to the UN, \"there is no region of the world, no country and no culture in which women's freedom from violence has been secured.\"<ref name=\"UN In-depth Study on all Forms of Violence Against Women\" /> Several forms of violence are more prevalent in certain parts of the world, often in [[developing countries]]. For example, [[dowry death|dowry violence]] and [[bride burning]] is associated with [[India]], [[Bangladesh]], [[Sri Lanka]], and [[Nepal]]. [[Acid throwing]] is also associated with these countries, as well as in [[Southeast Asia]], including [[Cambodia]]. [[Honor killing]] is associated with the [[Middle East]] and [[South Asia]]. [[Female genital mutilation]] is found mostly in [[Africa]], and to a lesser extent in the Middle East and some other parts of Asia. [[Marriage by abduction]] is found in [[Ethiopia]], [[Central Asia]] and the [[Caucasus]]. Abuse related to payment of [[bride price]] (such as violence, trafficking and forced marriage) is linked to parts of Sub-Saharan Africa and Oceania. (Also see [[lobolo]].)<ref>{{cite news | title = Papua New Guinea: police cite bride price major factor in marital violence | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150218182845/http://www.violenceisnotourculture.org/News-and-Views/papua-new-guinea-police-cite-bride-price-major-factor-marital-violence | archive-date = 18 February 2015 |url= http://www.violenceisnotourculture.org/News-and-Views/papua-new-guinea-police-cite-bride-price-major-factor-marital-violence | work = Island Business |via=Violence is not our Culture |date=21 November 2011 |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=An exploratory study of bride price and domestic violence in Bundibugyo District, Uganda |url=http://www.mrc.ac.za/gender/Bridepricedomesticviolence.pdf |publisher=Centre for Human Rights Advancement (CEHURA) and [[South African Medical Research Council]] |date=April 2012 |accessdate=6 August 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130717105205/http://www.mrc.ac.za/gender/Bridepricedomesticviolence.pdf |archive-date=17 July 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nCertain regions are no longer associated with a specific form of violence, but such violence was common until quite recently in those places; this is true of honor-based crimes in Southern/Mediterranean Europe.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Kirti | first1 = Anand | last2 = Kumar | first2 = Prateek | last3 = Yadav | first3 = Rachana | title = The face of honour based crimes: global concerns and solutions | journal = International Journal of Criminal Justice Sciences | volume = 6 | issue = 1&ndash;2 | pages = 343&ndash;357 | publisher = South Asian Society of Criminology & Victimology (SASCV) | date = 2011 | url = http://www.sascv.org/ijcjs/pdfs/kirtietalicjs2011i&iind.pdf | ref = harv }}</ref> For instance, in [[Italy]], before 1981, the Criminal Code provided for mitigating circumstances in case of a killing of a woman or her sexual partner for reasons related to honor, providing for a reduced sentence.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Barazzetti | first1 = Donatella | last2 = Garreffa | first2 = Franca | last3 = Marsico | first3 = Rosaria | title = Daphne Project \"Proposing new indicators: measuring violence's effects, GVEI (Gender Violence Effects Indicators)\" | url = http://www.surt.org/gvei/docs/national_report_italy.pdf | publisher = Centre Women\u2019s Studies \"Milly Villa\", [[University of Calabria]] | location = Rende, Italy | date = July 2007 | quote = Before 1981, Art. 587 read: He who causes the death of a spouse, daughter, or sister upon discovering her in illegitimate carnal relations and in the heat of passion caused by the offence to his honour or that of his family will be sentenced to three to seven years. The same sentence shall apply to whom, in the above circumstances, causes the death of the person involved in illegitimate carnal relations with his spouse, daughter, or sister.}}</ref>\n\nInvoking culture to explain particular forms of violence against women risks appearing to legitimize them. There is also debate and controversy about the ways in which cultural traditions, local customs and social expectations, as well as various interpretations of religion, interact with abusive practices.<ref name=\"UN In-depth Study on all Forms of Violence Against Women\" /><ref>{{cite book | last = Narayan | first = Uma | chapter = Cross\u2010cultural connections, border\u2010crossings, and \"Death by Culture\": thinking about dowry-murders in India and domestic\u2010violence murders in the United States | chapterurl = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lzQ49LnmL_cC&pg=PA81 | editor-last = Narayan | editor-first = Uma | title = Dislocating cultures: identities, traditions, and Third-World feminism | pages = 81&ndash;118 | publisher = Routledge | location = New York | year = 1997 | isbn = 9780415914192 | ref = harv }}</ref> Specifically, cultural justifications for certain violent acts against women are asserted by some states and social groups within many countries claiming to defend their traditions. These justifications are questionable precisely because the defenses are generally voiced by political leaders or traditional authorities, not by those actually affected.<ref name=\"UN In-depth Study on all Forms of Violence Against Women\" /> The need for sensitivity and respect of culture is an element that cannot be ignored either; thus a sensitive debate has ensued and is ongoing.\n\nThere has also been a history of recognizing the harmful effects of this violence. In the 1870s, courts in the United States stopped recognizing the common-law principle that a husband had the right to \"physically chastise an errant wife\".<ref>{{cite book | last = Calvert | first = Robert | chapter = Criminal and civil liability in husband-wife assaults | chapterurl = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=fCpHAAAAMAAJ | editor-last1 = Steinmetz | editor-first1 = Suzanne | editor-last2 = Straus | editor-first2 = Murray A. | author-link2 = Murray A. Straus | title = Violence in the family | pages = 88&ndash;91 | publisher = Harper & Row | location = New York | year = 1974 | isbn = 9780060464196 | ref = harv }}</ref> The first state to rescind this right was Alabama in 1871.<ref name=\"USDOJ-History of VAWA\" /> In the UK the right of a husband to inflict moderate [[corporal punishment]] on his wife to keep her \"within the bounds of duty\" was removed in 1891.<ref>R. v. Jackson [1891]. 1 Q.B. 671</ref><ref>{{cite book | chapter = Corporal punishment | title = Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Eleventh Edition | edition = 11th | year = 1911 | title-link = Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Eleventh Edition }}</ref>\n\nIn the 20th and 21st centuries, and in particular since the 1990s, there has been increased activity on both the national and international levels to research, raise awareness and advocate for the prevention of all kinds of violence against women.<ref name=\"UN In-depth Study on all Forms of Violence Against Women\" /> Most often, violence against women has been framed as a health issue, and also as a violation of human rights. A study in 2002 estimated that at least one in five women in the world had been physically or sexually abused by a man sometime in their lives, and \"gender-based violence accounts for as much death and ill-health in women aged 15\u201344 years as cancer, and is a greater cause of ill-health than malaria and traffic accidents combined.\"<ref name=\"VAW: A Global Burden\" />\n\nCertain characteristics of violence against women have emerged from the research. For example, acts of violence against women are often not unique episodes, but are ongoing over time. More often than not, the violence is perpetrated by someone the woman knows, not by a stranger.<ref name=\"VAM: Global scope & magnitude\" /> The research seems to provide convincing evidence that violence against women is a severe and pervasive problem the world over, with devastating effects on the health and well-being of women and children.<ref name=\"UN In-depth Study on all Forms of Violence Against Women\" />\n\n===Milestones===\nSome of the most important milestones on the international level for the prevention of violence against women include:\n\n*The 1979 [[Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination against Women]] (CEDAW), which recognizes violence as a part of discrimination against women in recommendations 12 and 19.<ref name=\"UN Women: Global Norms & Standards\">{{cite web|title=Global norms and standards: Ending violence against women|url=http://www.unwomen.org/en/what-we-do/ending-violence-against-women/global-norms-and-standards|publisher=[[UN Women]]|accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref>\n*The 1993 [[World Conference on Human Rights]], which recognized violence against women as a human rights violation, and which contributed to the following UN declaration.<ref name=\"UN Women: Global Norms & Standards\" />\n*The 1993 UN [[Declaration on the Elimination of Violence against Women]] was the first international instrument explicitly defining and addressing violence against women. This document specifically refers to the historically forever-present nature of gender inequalities in understanding violence against women.<ref name=\"UN Women: Global Norms & Standards\"/> (Include current 2nd paragraph here). This Declaration, as well as the World Conference of the same year, is often viewed as a \"turning point\" at which the consideration of violence against women by the international community began to be taken much more seriously, and after which more countries mobilized around this problem.<ref name=\"VAW: A Global Burden\">{{cite journal | last1 = Venis | first1 = Sarah | last2 = Horton | first2 = Richard | title = Violence against women: a global burden | journal = [[The Lancet]] | volume = 359 | issue = 9313 | page = 1172 | publisher = [[Elsevier]] | pmid = 11955533 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(02)08251-X | date = 6 April 2002 | ref = harv }}</ref><ref name=\"WHO Multicountry Study\">{{cite book | last = Garcia-Moreno | first = Claudia | title = WHO multi-country study on women's health and domestic violence against women: initial results on prevalence, health outcomes and women's responses | publisher = [[World Health Organization]] | location = Geneva, Switzerland | year = 2005 | url = https://www.who.int/reproductivehealth/publications/violence/24159358X/en/ | isbn = 9789241593588 }}</ref>\n*The 1994 [[International Conference on Population and Development]], linking violence against women to reproductive health and rights, and also providing recommendations to governments on how to prevent and respond to violence against women and girls.<ref name=\"UN Women: Global Norms & Standards\"/>\n*In 1996, the [[World Health Assembly]] (WHA) declared violence a major public health issue, and included in the subtypes recognized were intimate partner violence and sexual violence, two kinds of violence often perpetrated as violence against women. This was followed by a WHO report in 2002 (see below).<ref name=\"WHO World Report on violence and health\">{{cite book | last1 = Krug | first1 = Etienne G. | last2 = Dahlberg | first2 = Linda L. | last3 = Mercy | first3 = James A. | last4 = Zwi | first4 = Anthony B. | last5 = Lozano | first5 = Rafael | title = World report on violence and health | publisher = [[World Health Organization]] | location = Geneva, Switzerland | year = 2002 | url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=db9OHpk-TksC&printsec=frontcover | isbn = 9789241545617 }}\n:''Also available as'':\n:* {{cite journal | last1 = Krug | first1 = Etienne G. | last2 = Dahlberg | first2 = Linda L. | last3 = Mercy | first3 = James A. | last4 = Zwi | first4 = Anthony B. | last5 = Lozano | first5 = Rafael | title = The world report on violence and health | journal = [[The Lancet]] | volume = 360 | issue = 9339 | pages = 1083&ndash;1088 | publisher = [[Elsevier]] | pmid = 12384003 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(02)11133-0 | date = 5 October 2002 | ref = harv | url = http://www.revistabiomedica.org/index.php/biomedica/article/view/1182 }}</ref> The UN also created the Trust Fund to Support Actions to Eliminate Violence Against Women.<ref name=\"Fried\">{{cite journal | last =Fried | first = Susana T. | title = Violence against women | journal = [[Health and Human Rights|Health and Human Rights Journal]] | volume = 6 | issue = 2 | pages = 88&ndash;111 | publisher = [[Harvard University Press]] | doi = 10.2307/4065431 | jstor = 4065431 | date = 2003 | ref = harv }} [https://cdn2.sph.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/125/2014/04/6-Fried.pdf Pdf.]</ref> \n*In 1999, the UN adopted the [[Optional Protocol to the Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination against Women]] and designated 25 November as the [[International Day for the Elimination of Violence against Women]].<ref name=\"VAW: A Global Burden\" /> \n*In 2002, as a follow-up of the WHA declaration in 1996 of violence as a major public health issue, the [[World Health Organization]] published the first World Report on Violence and Health, which addressed many types of violence and their effect on public health, including forms of violence affecting women particularly strongly. The report specifically noted the sharp rise in civil society organizations and activities directed at responding to gender-based violence against women from the 1970s to the 1990s.<ref name=\"WHO World Report on violence and health\" /> \n*In 2004, the [[World Health Organization]] published its \"Multi-country study on Women's Health and Domestic Violence against Women\", a study of women's health and [[domestic violence]] by surveying over 24,000 women in 10 countries from all regions of the world, which assessed the prevalence and extent of violence against women, particularly violence by intimate partners, and linked this with health outcomes to women as well as documenting strategies and services that women use to cope with intimate-partner violence.<ref name=\"WHO Multicountry Study\" />\n*The 2006 UN Secretary General's \"In-depth study on all forms of violence against women\", the first comprehensive international document on the issue.<ref name=\"UN In-depth Study on all Forms of Violence Against Women\" />\n*The 2011 Council of Europe [[Convention on preventing and combating violence against women and domestic violence]], which is the second regional legally-binding instrument on violence against women and girls.<ref name=\"UN Women: Global Norms & Standards\"/> \n*In 2013, the [[United Nations Commission on the Status of Women]] (CSW) adopted, by consensus, Agreed Conclusions on the elimination and prevention of all forms of violence against women and girls (formerly, there were no agreed-upon conclusions).<ref name=\"UN Women: Global Norms & Standards\"/>\n*Also in 2013, the [[UN General Assembly]] passed its first resolution calling for the protection of [[human rights defender|defenders]] of women's human rights.<ref name=\"Norway Post\">{{cite news | last = NRK |title=Protection of women human rights defenders | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131213142536/http://www.norwaypost.no/index.php/news/latest-news/29260-protection-of-women-human-rights-defenders | archive-date = 13 December 2013 |url=http://www.norwaypost.no/index.php/news/latest-news/29260-protection-of-women-human-rights-defenders |work=The Norway Post |date=30 November 2013 |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> The resolution urges states to put in place gender-specific laws and policies for the protection of women's [[human rights defender]]s and to ensure that defenders themselves are involved in the design and implementation of these measures, and calls on states to protect women's human rights defenders from reprisals for cooperating with the UN and to ensure their unhindered access to and communication with international human rights bodies and mechanisms.<ref name=\"awid.org\">{{cite web |url=http://www.awid.org/Library/UN-adopts-landmark-resolution-on-Protecting-Women-Human-Rights-Defenders |title=UN adopts landmark resolution on Protecting Women Human Rights Defenders |publisher=[[Association for Women's Rights in Development]] (AWID) |date=28 November 2013 |accessdate=6 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819203819/http://www.awid.org/Library/UN-adopts-landmark-resolution-on-Protecting-Women-Human-Rights-Defenders |archivedate=19 August 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, on the national level, individual countries have also organized efforts (legally, politically, socially) to prevent, reduce and punish violence against women. As a particular case study, here are some developments since the 1960s in the United States to oppose and treat violence against women:<ref name=\"USDOJ-History of VAWA\">{{cite web|last=U.S. Department of Justice, Office of Violence Against Women (OVM)|title=The History of the Violence Against Women Act|url=http://www.ovw.usdoj.gov/docs/history-vawa.pdf|publisher=U.S. Department of Justice|accessdate=2 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111017204719/http://www.ovw.usdoj.gov/docs/history-vawa.pdf|archivedate=17 October 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n*1967: One of the country's first domestic violence shelters opened in Maine.\n*1972: The country's first rape help hotline opened in Washington, D.C.\n*1978: Two national coalitions, the National Coalition Against Sexual Assault and the [[National Coalition Against Domestic Violence]], were formed, to raise awareness of these two forms of violence against women.\n*1984: The U.S. Attorney General created the Department of Justice Task Force on Family Violence, to address ways in which the criminal justice system and community response to domestic violence should be improved.\n*1994: Passage of the [[Violence Against Women Act]] or VAWA, legislation included in the [[Violent Crime Control and Law Enforcement Act]] of 1994, sponsored by then-Senator Joseph Biden, which required a strengthened community response to crimes of domestic violence and sexual assault, strengthened federal penalties for repeat sex offenders and strengthened legislative protection of victims, among many other provisions.\n*2000: President Clinton signed into law the VAWA of 2000, further strengthening federal laws, and emphasizing assistance of immigrant victims, elderly victims, victims with disabilities, and victims of dating violence.\n*2006: President Bush signed into law the VAWA of 2006, with an emphasis on programs to address violence against youth victims, and establishing programs for Engaging Men and Youth, and Culturally and Linguistically Specific Services.\n*2007: The National Teen Dating Abuse Hotline opened.\n*2009: President Obama declared April as Sexual Assault Awareness Month.\n*2013: President Obama signed into law the VAWA of 2015, which granted Native American tribes the ability to prosecute non-Native offenders, and regulated reports of sexual assault on college campuses.<ref>{{cite book | last = Kohlman | first = Cindy | title = Violence Against Women Act (VAWA) New Reporting Requirements Effective July 1, 2015 \u2013 Are You Ready? | url = https://www.inceptia.org | publisher = Inceptia Institute | date = 9 June 2015 }}\n:''See also'':\n:* {{cite book | last = ACE | author-link = American Council on Education | title = New requirements imposed by the Violence Against Women Reauthorization Act | url = http://www.acenet.edu/news-room/Documents/VAWA-Summary.pdf | publisher = [[American Council on Education]] | date = 1 April 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Fee|first1=Stephen |display-authors=etal | title=Tribal Justice: Prosecuting Non-Natives for Sexual Assault on Reservations (transcript) |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/show/tribal-justice-prosecuting-non-natives-sexual-assault-indian-reservations|publisher=[[PBS]] documentary |date =5 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nOther countries have also enacted comparable legislative, political and social instruments to address violence against women. Experts in the international community generally believe, however, that solely enacting punitive legislation for prevention and punishment of violence against women is not sufficient to address the problem. For example, although much stricter laws on violence against women have been passed in Bangladesh, violence against women is still rising.<ref name=\"VAW: A Global Burden\" /> Instead, it is thought that wide societal changes to address gender inequalities and women's empowerment will be the way to reduce violence against women.<ref name=\"UN In-depth Study on all Forms of Violence Against Women\" /><ref name=\"VAW: A Global Burden\" /><ref name=\"Nigeria-Female Hawkers-Interventions\">{{cite journal | last1 = Fawole | first1 = Olufunmilayo I. | last2 = Ajuwon | first2 = Ademola J. | last3 = Osungbade | first3 = Kayode O. | last4 = Faweya | first4 = Olufemi C. | title = Interventions for violence prevention among young female hawkers in motor parks in South-Western Nigeria: a review of effectiveness | journal = African Journal of Reproductive Health [La Revue Africaine de la Sant\u00e9 Reproductive] | volume = 7 | issue = 1 | pages = 71&ndash;82 | publisher = Women's Health and Action Research Centre (WHARC) | doi = 10.2307/3583347 | jstor = 3583347 | date = April 2003 | ref = harv | hdl = 1807/2587 }}</ref><ref name=\"WHO VAM Factsheet\">{{cite book | last = WHO | author-link = World Health Organization |title=Violence against women|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs239/en/|publisher=[[World Health Organization]]| date = 1 September 2011|accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Effect on society==\nAccording to an article in the [[Health and Human Rights (journal)|Health and Human Rights Journal]],<ref name=\"Fried\" /> regardless of many years of advocacy and involvement of many feminist activist organizations, the issue of violence against women still \"remains one of the most pervasive forms of human rights violations worldwide\".<ref name=\"Fried\" />{{rp|91}} The violence against women can occur in both public and private spheres of life and at any time of their life span. Violence against women often keeps women from wholly contributing to social, economic, and political development of their communities.<ref name=\"Fried\"/> Many women are terrified by these threats of violence and this essentially influences their lives so that they are impeded to exercise their human rights; for instance, they fear contributing to the development of their communities socially, economically and politically. Apart from that, the causes that trigger VAW or gender-based violence can go beyond just the issue of gender and into the issues of age, class, culture, ethnicity, religion, sexual orientation and specific geographical area of their origins.\n\nImportantly, other than the issue of social divisions, violence can also extend into the realm of health issues and become a direct concern of the public health sector.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Colarossi | first = Lisa | title = A response to Danis & Lockhart: What guides social work knowledge about violence against women? | journal = Journal of Social Work Education | volume = 41 | issue = 1 | pages = 147&ndash;159 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] on behalf of the [[Council on Social Work Education]] (CSWE) |doi=10.5175/JSWE.2005.200400418 | jstor = 23044038 | date = Winter 2005 | ref = harv}}\n:''See also'':\n:* {{cite journal | last1 = Danis | first1 = Fran S. | last2 = Lockhart | first2 = Lettie | title = Guest Editorial &ndash; Domestic violence and social work education: what do we know, what do we need to know? | journal = Journal of Social Work Education, Special Section: Domestic Violence and Social Work Education | volume = 39 | issue = 2 | pages = 215&ndash;224 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] on behalf of the [[Council on Social Work Education]] (CSWE) | doi = 10.1080/10437797.2003.10779132 | jstor = 23044061 | date = Spring\u2013Summer 2003 | ref = harv }}</ref> A health issue such as [[HIV/AIDS]] is another cause that also leads to violence. Women who have HIV/AIDS infection are also among the targets of the violence.<ref name=\"Fried\" />{{rp|91}} The [[World Health Organization]] reports that violence against women puts an undue burden on health care services, as women who have suffered violence are more likely to need health services and at higher cost, compared to women who have not suffered violence.<ref name=\"WHO VAM Factsheet\" /> Another statement that confirms an understanding of VAW as being a significant health issue is apparent in the recommendation adopted by the Council of Europe, violence against women in private sphere, at home or [[domestic violence]], is the main reason of \"death and disability\" among the women who encountered violence.<ref name=\"Fried\" />{{rp|91}}\n\nIn addition, several studies have shown a link between poor treatment of women and international violence. These studies show that one of the best predictors of inter- and intranational violence is the maltreatment of women in the society.<ref>{{cite news | last = Maffly | first = Brian | title = BYU study links women's safety, nation's peace | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100202080318/http://www.sltrib.com/ci_11967564 | archive-date = 2 February 2010 | url = http://www.sltrib.com/ci_11967564 | work = [[The Salt Lake Tribune]] | date = 21 March 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last1 = Strearmer | first1 = Matthew | last2 = Emmett | first2 = Chad F.|url=http://www.womanstats.org/images/StearmerEmmettAPSA07.pdf |title=The great divide: Revealing differences in the Islamic world regarding the status of women and its impact on international peace |publisher= [[WomanStats Project]] |date=2007 |accessdate=6 August 2014}} Paper prepared for presentation at the annual meeting of the [[American Political Science Association]], Chicago, Illinois, 29 August \u2013 1 September 2007.</ref>\n\n== Typology ==\nViolence against women may be classified according to different approaches. \n\n=== WHO's life cycle typology ===\nThe [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) has developed a typology of violence against women based on their cultural life cycles. \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| '''Phase''' || '''Type of violence'''\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n| Pre-birth || Sex-selective abortion; effects of battering during pregnancy on birth outcomes\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n| Infancy || Female infanticide; physical, sexual and psychological abuse\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n| Girlhood || Child marriage; female genital mutilation; physical, sexual and psychological abuse; incest; child prostitution and pornography\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n| Adolescence and adulthood || Dating and courtship violence (e.g. acid throwing and date rape); economically coerced sex (e.g. school girls having sex with \"sugar daddies\" in return for school fees); incest; sexual abuse in the workplace; rape; sexual harassment; forced prostitution and pornography; trafficking in women; partner violence; marital rape; dowry abuse and murders; partner homicide; psychological abuse; abuse of women with disabilities; forced pregnancy\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n| Elderly || Forced \"suicide\" or homicide of widows for economic reasons; sexual, physical and psychological abuse<ref name=\"WHO_VAW\" />\n|}\n\nSignificant progress towards the protection of women from violence has been made on international level as a product of collective effort of lobbying by many women's rights movements; international organizations to civil society groups. As a result, worldwide governments and international as well as civil society organizations actively work to combat violence against women through a variety of programs. Among the major achievements of the women's rights movements against violence on girls and women, the landmark accomplishments are the \"[[Declaration on the Elimination of Violence Against Women]]\" that implies \"political will towards addressing VAW \" and the legal binding agreement, \"the Convention on Elimination of all forms of Discrimination Against Women ([[CEDAW]])\".<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Rosche | first1 = Daniela | last2 = Dawe | first2 = Alexandra | title = Oxfam Briefing Note: Ending violence against women the case for a comprehensive international action plan | page = 2 | publisher = [[Oxfam|Oxfam GB]] | location = Oxford | year = 2013 | url = http://www.oxfam.org/sites/www.oxfam.org/files/bn-ending-violence-against-women-action-plan-220213-en.pdf | isbn = 9781780772639 | access-date = 2 December 2013 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170925212852/https://www.oxfam.org/sites/www.oxfam.org/files/bn-ending-violence-against-women-action-plan-220213-en.pdf | archive-date = 25 September 2017 | url-status = dead }}</ref> In addition, the UN General Assembly resolution also designated 25 November as [[International Day for the Elimination of Violence against Women]].<ref>{{cite book | last = UN | author-link = United Nations | title = International Day for the Elimination of Violence against Women | url = https://www.un.org/womenwatch/daw/news/vawd.html | website = un.org | publisher = [[United Nations]] |date= 17 December 1999|accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== ''The Lancet'''s over time typology ===\n[[File:Typology of Violence Against Women over Time.png|thumbnail|300 px|A diagram of typology of violence against women over time, as conceived by authors [[Charlotte Watts]] & Cathy Zimmerman.]]\n\nA typology similar to the WHO's from an article on violence against women published in the academic journal ''[[The Lancet]]'' shows the different types of violence perpetrated against women according to what time period in a women's life the violence takes place.<ref name=\"VAM: Global scope & magnitude\" /> However, it also classifies the types of violence according to the perpetrator. One important point to note is that more of the types of violence inflicted on women are perpetrated by someone the woman knows, either a family member or intimate partner, rather than a stranger.\n\n=== Council of Europe's nine forms of violence ===\nThe Gender Equality Commission of the [[Council of Europe]] identifies nine forms of violence against women based on subject and context rather than life cycle or time period:<ref name=\"Hagemann-White\">{{Cite web |url=https://rm.coe.int/16805915e9 |title=Analytical study of the results of the 4th round of monitoring the implementation of Recommendation Rec(2002)5 on the protection of women against violence in Council of Europe member states |author=Carol Hagemann-White |page=7, 8, 11 |publisher=Council of Europe Equality Division |date=February 2014 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://edoc.coe.int/en/fundamental-freedoms/5949-state-of-democracy-human-rights-and-the-rule-of-law-in-europe.html |title=State of democracy, human rights and the rule of law in Europe (2014) |author=[[Thorbj\u00f8rn Jagland]] |work=Report by the Secretary General of the Council of Europe |page=48 |publisher=Council of Europe |date=May 2014 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n*'Violence within the family or domestic violence'\n*'Rape and sexual violence'\n*'Sexual harassment'\n*'Violence in institutional environments'\n*'Female genital mutilation'\n*'Forced marriages'\n*'Violence in conflict and post-conflict situations'\n*'Killings in the name of honour'\n*'Failure to respect freedom of choice with regard to reproduction'\n\n==Forms of violence==\nViolence against women can take a number of forms and arise in a number of situations:\n\n===Rape===\n{{main|Rape}}\nWomen are most often the victims of rape, which is usually perpetrated by men known to them.<ref>''Relevant citations'':\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Abbey | first1 = Antonia | last2 = BeShears | first2 = Renee | last3 = Clinton-Sherrod | first3 = A. Monique | last4 = McAuslan | first4 = Pam  | title = Similarities and differences in women's sexual assault experiences based on tactics used by the perpetrator | journal = [[Psychology of Women Quarterly]] | volume = 28 | issue = 4 | pages = 323&ndash;332 | publisher = [[Sage Publications|Sage]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1471-6402.2004.00149.x | pmid = 26257466 | pmc = 4527559 | date = December 2004 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130108020408/http://www.hawaii.edu/hivandaids/Similarities_And_Differences_In_Women_s_Sexual_Assault_Experiences_Based_On_Tactics.pdf | url-status = dead | archivedate = 8 January 2013 | df = dmy-all | url = http://www.hawaii.edu/hivandaids/Similarities_And_Differences_In_Women_s_Sexual_Assault_Experiences_Based_On_Tactics.pdf | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.rainn.org/statistics/|title=Statistics | website = rainn.org |publisher= [[Rape, Abuse & Incest National Network]] (RAINN) |accessdate=1 January 2008}}\n* {{cite book | last = Tjaden | first1 = Patricia | last2 = Thoennes | first2 = Nancy | title = Extent, nature, and consequences of rape victimization: findings From the national violence against women survey | url = https://www.ncjrs.gov/App/Publications/abstract.aspx?ID=210346 | publisher = [[National Criminal Justice Reference Service]], U.S. Department of Justice Office of Justice Programs | date = January 2006 }} [http://www.ncjrs.gov/pdffiles1/nij/210346.pdf Pdf.]\n* {{cite web | last = ABS | author-link = Australian Bureau of Statistics | title = Sexual assault in Australia: a statistical overview, 2004 |url=http://www.abs.gov.au/ausstats/abs@.nsf/mf/4523.0 |website =abs.gov.au | publisher = [[Australian Bureau of Statistics]] |date=7 September 2004 |accessdate=31 December 2010}}\n* {{cite book | last = Myhill | first1 = Andy | last2 = Allen | first2 = Jonathan | title = Rape and sexual assault of women: findings from the British Crime Survey | url = http://rds.homeoffice.gov.uk/rds/pdfs2/r159.pdf | accessdate = 31 December 2010 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20110218135832/http://rds.homeoffice.gov.uk/rds/pdfs2/r159.pdf | archivedate = 18 February 2011 | df=dmy-all | publisher = [[Home Office]] | location = London | year = 2002 | series = [[Home Office]] Findings No. 159 }}</ref> The rate of reporting, prosecution and convictions for rape varies considerably in different jurisdictions, and reflects to some extent the society's attitudes to such crimes. It is considered the most underreported violent crime.<ref>{{cite book | last = AMA | author-link = American Medical Association | title = Strategies for the treatment and prevention of sexual assault | publisher = [[American Medical Association]] | location = Chicago, Illinois | year = 1995 | oclc = 33901581 }}</ref><ref name=\"rds.homeoffice.gov.uk\">{{cite book | last1 = Kelly | first1 = Liz | last2 = Regan | first2 = Linda | last3 = Lovett | first3 = Jo | author-link = Liz Kelly | title = A gap or a chasm?: Attrition in reported rape cases | publisher = Home Office Research, Development and Statistics Directorate | location = London | id = 293 | year = 2005 | isbn = 9781844735556 | archiveurl = http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20110218135832/rds.homeoffice.gov.uk/rds/pdfs05/hors293.pdf | archivedate = 18 February 2011 | url = http://rds.homeoffice.gov.uk/rds/pdfs05/hors293.pdf | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all | accessdate = 31 December 2010 }}</ref> Following a rape, a victim may face violence or threats of violence from the rapist, and, in many cultures, from the victim's own family and relatives. Violence or intimidation of the victim may be perpetrated by the rapist or by friends and relatives of the rapist, as a way of preventing the victims from reporting the rape, of punishing them for reporting it, or of forcing them to withdraw the complaint; or it may be perpetrated by the relatives of the victim as a punishment for \"bringing shame\" to the family. This is especially the case in cultures where female [[virginity]] is highly valued and considered mandatory before marriage; in extreme cases, rape victims are killed in [[honor killings]]. Victims may also be forced by their families to marry the rapist in order to restore the family's \"honor\".<ref>''Relevant articles'':\n* {{cite news | last = PTI | author-link =Press Trust of India | title = Rape victim threatened to withdraw case in UP | url = http://zeenews.india.com/news/uttar-pradesh/rape-victim-threatened-to-withdraw-case-in-up_694364.html | work = [[Zee News]] | publisher = [[Essel Group]] | location = Mumbai, India | date = 19 March 2011 | accessdate = 3 February 2013 }}\n* {{cite news | last = Staff writer | title =Stigmatization of rape & honor killings |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121108041415/http://www.wisemuslimwomen.org/currentissues/stigmitizationofrape/ | archive-date = 8 November 2012 | url = http://www.wisemuslimwomen.org/currentissues/stigmitizationofrape/ | work = WISE Muslim Women | publisher = [[Women's Islamic Initiative in Spirituality and Equality]] | date = 31 January 2002 | accessdate = 3 February 2013 }}\n* {{cite news | last = Harter | first = Pascale | title = Libya rape victims 'face honour killings' | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-13760895 | work = [[BBC News]] | date=14 June 2011 |accessdate= 3 February 2013 }}\n* {{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Morocco protest after raped Amina Filali kills herself | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-17379721 | work = [[BBC News]] | date = 15 March 2012 | accessdate = 19 November 2013}}</ref> In Lebanon, the [[Campaign Against Lebanese Rape Law - Article 522]] was launched in December 2016 to abolish the article that permitted a rapist to escape prison by marrying his victim.\n\nInternationally, the incidence of rapes recorded by police during 2008 varied between 0.1 per 100,000 people in [[Egypt]] and 91.6 per 100,000 people in [[Lesotho]] with 4.9 per 100,000 people in [[Lithuania]] as the [[median]].<ref name=\"unodc1\">{{cite book | last = UNODC | author-link = United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime | title = Rape at the National Level, number of police recorded offenses | url = http://www.unodc.org/documents/data-and-analysis/Crime-statistics/Sexual_violence_sv_against_children_and_rape.xls | format = spreadsheet | publisher = [[United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime]] }}</ref> In some countries, rape is not reported or properly recorded by police because of the consequences on the victim and the stigma attached to it.\n\n===Marital rape===\n{{Main|Marital rape|domestic violence}}\nMarital or spousal rape was once widely condoned or ignored by law, and is now widely considered an unacceptable violence against women and repudiated by international conventions and increasingly criminalized. Still, in many countries, spousal rape either remains legal, or is illegal but widely tolerated and accepted as a husband's prerogative. The criminalization of spousal rape is recent, having occurred during the past few decades. Traditional understanding and views of [[marriage]], [[rape]], [[sexuality]], [[gender roles]] and [[self determination]] have started to be challenged in most Western countries during the 1960s and 1970s, which has led to the subsequent criminalization of marital rape during the following decades. With a few notable exceptions, it was during the past 30 years when most laws against marital rape have been enacted. Some countries in Scandinavia and in the former Communist Bloc of Europe made spousal rape illegal before 1970, but most Western countries criminalized it only in the 1980s and 1990s. In many parts of the world the laws against marital rape are very new, having been enacted in the 2000s.\n\nIn [[Canada]], marital rape was made illegal in 1983, when several legal changes were made, including changing the rape statute to ''sexual assault'', and making the laws gender neutral.<ref name=grady>{{cite book | last = Grady | first = William | title = Crime in Canadian context: debates and controversies | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = Don Mills, Ontario | year = 2011 | isbn = 9780195433784 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last1 = Brennan | first1 = Shannon| last2 = Taylor-Butts | first2 = Andrea | title = Sexual assault in Canada, 2004 | publisher = Canadian Centre for Justice Statistics | location = Ottawa | year = 2008 |url=http://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/85f0033m/85f0033m2008019-eng.pdf | isbn = 9781100111636 |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = SIECCAN |title=Sexual assault in Canada: what do we know? |publisher=The Sex Information and Education Council of Canada (SIECCAN) | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140722071229/http://sexualityandu.ca/uploads/files/SexualAssault-OCT2011-ENG.pdf | archive-date = 22 July 2014 |url=http://sexualityandu.ca/uploads/files/SexualAssault-OCT2011-ENG.pdf | date = October 2011 |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> In [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] spousal rape was outlawed in 1990.<ref name=\"Temkin86\">{{cite book | last = Temkin | first = Jennifer | chapter = Defining and redefining rape | editor-last = Temkin | editor-first = Jennifer | title = Rape and the legal process | page = 86 | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = Oxford New York | year = 2002 | edition = 2nd | isbn = 9780198763543 }}\n:''Citing'':\n:* {{cite web | title = Criminal Law (Rape) (Amendment) Act, 1990, section 5 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170429001010/http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1990/act/32/section/5/enacted/en/html#sec5 | archive-date = 29 April 2017 | url = http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1990/act/32/section/5/enacted/en/html#sec5 | website = irishstatutebook.ie | publisher = [[Irish Statute Book]] | access-date = 21 December 2017}}</ref> In the US, the criminalization of marital rape started in the mid-1970s and in 1993 North Carolina became the last state to make marital rape illegal.<ref>{{cite news|last =Associated Press|author-link=Associated Press|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1957&dat=19930702&id=_xYxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=UOEFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6288,228462 |title=N.C. the last state to outlaw marital rape |work=[[The Daily Gazette]]| location = New York |date=2 July 1993 |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref>\nIn [[England and Wales]], marital rape was made illegal in 1991. The views of Sir Matthew Hale, a 17th-century jurist, published in ''The History of the Pleas of the Crown'' (1736), stated that a husband cannot be guilty of the rape of his wife because the wife \"hath given up herself in this kind to her husband, which she cannot retract\"; in England and Wales this would remain law for more than 250 years, until it was abolished by the [[Appellate Committee of the House of Lords]], in the case of ''R v R'' in 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bailii.org/uk/cases/UKHL/1991/12.html |title=R v R [1991&#93; UKHL 12 (23 October 1991) |publisher=British and Irish Legal Information Institute |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> In the [[Netherlands]] marital rape was also made illegal in 1991.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Zeegers | first = Nicolle | title = What epistemology would serve criminal law best in finding the truth about rape? | journal = Law and Method | volume = 2 | issue = 1 | pages = 60&ndash;71 | date = January 2012 | ref = harv | doi = 10.5553/ReM/221225082012002001005 }} [https://www.bjutijdschriften.nl/tijdschrift/lawandmethod/2012/1/ReM_2212-2508_2012_002_001_005.pdf Pdf.]</ref> One of the last Western countries to criminalize marital rape was [[Germany]], in 1997.<ref>{{cite thesis|last=Kieler|first=Marita|date=2003|title=Tatbestandsprobleme der sexuellen N\u00f6tigung, Vergewaltigung sowie des sexuellen Mi\u00dfbrauchs widerstandsunf\u00e4higer Personen|publisher=[[University of Osnabr\u00fcck]] via Tenea|url=http://www.jurawelt.com/dissertationen/werke/8821|oclc=758907108}} [http://www.jurawelt.com/sunrise/media/mediafiles/13792/tenea_juraweltbd52_kieler.pdf Pdf.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020164804/http://www.jurawelt.com/sunrise/media/mediafiles/13792/tenea_juraweltbd52_kieler.pdf |date=20 October 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe relation between some religions ([[Christianity]] and [[Islam]]) and marital rape is controversial. The [[Bible]] at 1 Corinthians 7:3-5 explains that one has a \"conjugal duty\" to have sexual relations with one's spouse (in sharp opposition to [[sex outside marriage]], which is considered a [[sin]]) and states, \"The wife does not have authority over her own body, but the husband does. And likewise the husband does not have authority over his own body, but the wife does. Do not deprive one another...\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=1+corinthians%207:3-7:5&version=NKJV |title=1 corinthians 7:3-7:5 NKJV | website = biblegateway.com |publisher=[[BibleGateway.com|Bible Gateway]] |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> Some conservative religious figures interpret this as rejecting to possibility of marital rape.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adn.com/2011/07/22/1980301/readers-blast-valley-paper-over.html |title=Valley paper criticized over pastor's column on spousal rape |work=[[Alaska Dispatch]] |date=22 July 2011 |accessdate=6 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029203959/http://www.adn.com/2011/07/22/1980301/readers-blast-valley-paper-over.html |archivedate=29 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Islam makes reference to sexual relations in marriage too, notably: \"Allah's Apostle said, 'If a husband calls his wife to his bed (i.e. to have sexual relation) and she refuses and causes him to sleep in anger, the angels will curse her till morning';\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/isl/bukhari/bh4/bh4_464.htm |title=Hadith 4:460 | website = Sacred-texts.com |publisher=[[Internet Sacred Text Archive]] |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> and several comments on the issue of marital rape made by Muslim religious leaders have been criticized.<ref>{{cite news| last = Halliday | first =Josh |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/nov/08/islam-channel-ofcom |title=Islam Channel censured by Ofcom |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=8 November 2010 |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/7843909.stm | work=[[BBC News]] | title=Cleric 'must deny' views on rape | date=22 January 2009 | access-date = 11 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Domestic violence===\n[[File:Anti-domestic violence sign in Liberia panoramio (193).jpg|thumb|Anti-domestic violence sign in [[Liberia]]]]\n{{main|Domestic violence|Intimate partner violence}}\nWomen are more likely to be [[victimized]] by someone that they are intimate with, commonly called \"[[intimate partner violence]]\" (IPV). Instances of IPV tend not to be reported to police and thus many experts find it hard to estimate the true magnitude of the problem.<ref>{{cite web | title = Intimate partner violence: fact sheet | url = https://www.cdc.gov/ncipc/factsheets/ipvfacts.htm | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070211183916/http://www.cdc.gov/ncipc/factsheets/ipvfacts.htm | archive-date = 11 February 2007 | website = cdc.gov/ncipc | publisher = National Center for Injury Prevention and Control, [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] | date = 2006 | accessdate = 4 September 2007}}</ref> Though this form of violence is often considered as an issue within the context of heterosexual relationships, it also occurs in lesbian relationships,<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Girshick | first = Lori B. | title = No sugar, no spice: reflections on research on woman-to-woman sexual violence | journal = [[Violence Against Women (journal)|Violence Against Women]] | volume = 8 | issue = 12 | pages = 1500\u20131520 | publisher = [[Sage Publications|Sage]] | doi = 10.1177/107780102237967 | date = December 2002 | ref = harv }}</ref> daughter-mother relationships, [[roommate]] relationships and other domestic relationships involving two women. Violence against women in lesbian relationships is about as common as violence against women in heterosexual relationships.<ref>{{cite web | last = Rose | first = Suzana | title = Lesbian partner violence fact sheet | url = http://www.musc.edu/vawprevention/lesbianrx/factsheet.shtml | publisher = [[Medical University of South Carolina]] }}</ref>\n\nWomen are much more likely than men to be [[murdered]] by an intimate partner. In the United States, in 2005, 1181 women were killed by their intimate partners, compared to 329 men.<ref>{{cite web | title = Intimate partner violence: consequences | url = https://www.cdc.gov/violencePrevention/intimatepartnerviolence/consequences.html | website = cdc.gov/ncipc | publisher = National Center for Injury Prevention and Control, [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] | accessdate = 9 February 2010 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100129161946/http://www.cdc.gov/violencePrevention/intimatepartnerviolence/consequences.html | archive-date = 29 January 2010 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Wheel gallery | url = http://www.theduluthmodel.org/wheelgallery.php | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110728093413/http://www.theduluthmodel.org/wheelgallery.php | archive-date = 28 July 2011 | publisher=The Duluth Model | accessdate = 9 February 2010}}</ref> In [[England and Wales]] about 100 women are killed by partners or former partners each year while 21 men were killed in 2010.<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-13058300 |title=All domestic abuse deaths to have multi-agency review |date=13 April 2011 | work = BBC news |accessdate=14 April 2011}}</ref> In 2008, in [[France]], 156 women were killed by their intimate partner, compared to 27 men.<ref>{{cite book | title = L'action du minist\u00e8re dans le cadre des violences au sein du couple / Aide aux victimes: pr\u00e9sentation des diff\u00e9rents dispositifs | url = http://www.interieur.gouv.fr/sections/a_votre_service/aide_aux_victimes/violence-couple/downloadFile/attachedFile/morts_violentes_au_sein_couples.pdf | language = French | publisher = [[Minister of the Interior (France)|Minist\u00e8re de l'Int\u00e9rieur]] | accessdate = 6 August 2014 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120320014223/http://www.interieur.gouv.fr/sections/a_votre_service/aide_aux_victimes/violence-couple/downloadFile/attachedFile/morts_violentes_au_sein_couples.pdf | archivedate = 20 March 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> According to the WHO, globally, as many as 38% of murders of women are committed by an intimate partner.<ref name=\"WHO VAM Factsheet\" /> A UN report compiled from a number of different studies conducted in at least 71 countries found domestic violence against women to be most prevalent in [[Ethiopia]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Ethiopian women are most abused | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/6040180.stm | work = BBC News | date = 11 October 2006 }}</ref> A study by [[Pan American Health Organization]] conducted in 12 [[Latin American]] countries found the highest prevalence of domestic violence against women to be in [[Bolivia]].<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Bott | first1 = Sarah | last2 = Guedes | first2 = Alessandra | last3 = Goodwin | first3 = Mary | last4 = Mendoza | first4 = Jennifer Adams | title = Violence against women in Latin America and the Caribbean: a comparative analysis of population-based data from 12 countries | url = http://www.paho.org/Hq/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=8175%3A2013-violence-against-women-latin-america-caribbean-comparative-analysis&catid=1505%3Aabout-us&lang=en | publisher = [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] and the [[Pan American Health Organization]] | date = 2012 }} [http://www1.paho.org/hq/dmdocuments/violence-against-women-lac.pdf English pdf.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204013306/http://www1.paho.org/hq/dmdocuments/violence-against-women-lac.pdf |date=4 February 2016 }} [http://www.paho.org/Hq/index.php?option=com_docman&task=doc_download&gid=24353&Itemid=270&lang=en Spanish pdf.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150408155433/http://www.paho.org/Hq/index.php?option=com_docman&task=doc_download&gid=24353&Itemid=270&lang=en |date=8 April 2015 }}</ref> In Western Europe, a country that has received major international criticism for the way it has dealt legally with the issue of violence against women is [[Finland]]; with authors pointing out that a high level of equality for women in the public sphere (as in Finland) should never be equated with equality in all other aspects of women's lives.<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Clarke | first = Kris | title = The paradoxical approach to intimate partner violence in Finland | journal = [[Tokiwa University#Publications|International Perspectives in Victimology]] | volume = 6 | issue = 1 | pages = 9\u201319 | publisher = [[Tokiwa University]] via [[California State University|The Press at California State University]] | doi = 10.5364/ipiv.6.1.19 | date = August 2011 | ref = harv | doi-broken-date = 2020-03-13 }} [https://www.academia.edu/992154/The_Paradoxical_Approach_to_Intimate_Partner_Violence_in_Finland Available through academia.edu.]</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=McKie |first1=Linda |last2=Hearn |first2=Jeff |title=Gender-neutrality and gender equality: comparing and contrasting policy responses to 'domestic violence' in Finland and Scotland |journal=[[Scottish Affairs]] |volume=48 |issue=1 |pages=85\u2013107 |publisher=[[Edinburgh University Press]] |doi=10.3366/scot.2004.0043 |date=August 2004 |ref=harv }} [https://web.archive.org/web/20131021023708/http://www.scottishaffairs.org/backiss/pdfs/sa48/sa48_McKie_and_Hearn.pdf Pdf.]</ref><ref>{{cite report |date=September 2008 |title=Case Closed: Rape and Human Rights in the Nordic Countries |publisher=Amnesty International |url=https://amnesty.dk/media/1557/case-closed.pdf | pages = 89\u201391 | quote = Finland is repeatedly reminded of its widespread problem of violence against women and recommended to take more efficient measures to deal with the situation. International criticism concentrates on the lack of measures to combat violence against women in general and in particular on the lack of a national action plan to combat such violence and on the lack of legislation on domestic violence. (...) Compared to Sweden, Finland has been slower to reform legislation on violence against women. In Sweden, domestic violence was already illegal in 1864, while in Finland such violence was not outlawed until 1970, over a hundred years later. In Sweden the punishment of victims of incest was abolished in 1937, but not until 1971 in Finland. Rape within marriage was criminalised in Sweden in 1962, but the equivalent Finnish legislation only came into force in 1994 \u2013 making Finland one of the last European countries to criminalise marital rape. In addition, assaults taking place on private property did not become impeachable offences in Finland until 1995. Only in 1997 did victims of sexual offences and domestic violence in Finland become entitled to government-funded counselling and support services for the duration of their court cases. | ref = harv | postscript = .}}</ref>\n\n====Diagnosis planning====\nThe [[American Psychiatric Association]] planning and research committees for the forthcoming [[DSM-5]] (2013) have canvassed a series of new [[Relational disorder]]s, which include ''Marital Conflict Disorder Without Violence'' or ''Marital Abuse Disorder (Marital Conflict Disorder With Violence)''.<ref name=\"Personality\">{{cite book| last1 = First | first1 = Michael B. | last2 = Bell | first2 = Carl C. | last3 = Cuthbert | first3 = Bruce | last4 = Krystal | first4 = John H. | last5 = Malison | first5 = Robert | last6 = Offord | first6 = David R. | last7 = Reiss | first7 = David | last8 = Shea | first8 = M. Tracie | last9 = Widger | first9 = Tom | last10 = Wisner | first10 = Katherine L. | chapter = Personality disorders and relational disorders: a research agenda for addressing crucial gaps in DSM | chapterurl = https://contextualscience.org/system/files/Kupfer,2002.pdf | editor-last1 = Kupfer | editor-first1 = David J. | editor-last2 = First | editor-first2 = Michael B. | editor-last3 = Regier | editor-first3 = Darrel A. | title = A research agenda for DSM-V | publisher = [[American Psychiatric Association]] | location = Washington, D.C. | year = 2002 | isbn = 9780890422922 | ref = harv }}</ref>{{rp|164, 166}} Couples with marital disorders sometimes come to clinical attention because the couple recognize long-standing dissatisfaction with their marriage and come to the [[clinician]] on their own initiative or are referred by an astute health care professional. Secondly, there is serious violence in the marriage that is -\"usually the husband battering the wife\".<ref name=\"Personality\" />{{rp|163}} In these cases the emergency room or a legal authority often is the first to notify the [[clinician]]. Most importantly, marital violence \"is a major risk factor for serious injury and even death and women in violent marriages are at much greater risk of being seriously injured or killed ([[National Advisory Council on Violence Against Women]] 2000)\".<ref name=\"Personality\" />{{rp|166}} The authors of this study add, \"There is current considerable controversy over whether male-to-female marital violence is best regarded as a reflection of male [[psychopathology]] and control or whether there is an empirical base and clinical utility for conceptualizing these patterns as relational.\"<ref name=\"Personality\" />{{rp|166}}\n\nRecommendations for clinicians making a diagnosis of ''Marital Relational Disorder'' should include the assessment of actual or \"potential\" male violence as regularly as they assess the potential for suicide in depressed patients. Further, \"clinicians should not relax their vigilance after a battered wife leaves her husband, because some data suggest that the period immediately following a marital separation is the period of greatest risk for the women. Many men will [[stalking|stalk]] and [[battery (crime)|batter]] their wives in an effort to get them to return or punish them for leaving. Initial assessments of the potential for violence in a marriage can be supplemented by standardized interviews and questionnaires, which have been reliable and valid aids in exploring marital violence more systematically.\"<ref name=\"Personality\" />{{rp|166}}\n \nThe authors conclude with what they call \"very recent information\"<ref name=\"Personality\" />{{rp|167, 168}} on the course of violent marriages, which suggests that \"over time a husband's battering may abate somewhat, but perhaps because he has successfully [[intimidate]]d his wife. The risk of violence remains strong in a marriage in which it has been a feature in the past. Thus, treatment is essential here; the clinician cannot just wait and watch.\"<ref name=\"Personality\" />{{rp|167, 168}} The most urgent clinical priority is the protection of the wife because she is the one most frequently at risk, and clinicians must be aware that supporting assertiveness by a battered wife may lead to more beatings or even death.<ref name=\"Personality\" />{{rp|167, 168}}\n\n====Honor killings====\n[[Honor killings]] are a common form of violence against women in certain parts of the world. Honor killings are perpetrated by family members (usually husbands, fathers, uncles or brothers) against women in the family who are believed to have placed dishonor to the family. The death of the dishonorable woman is believed to restore honor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.stanford.edu/group/womenscourage/communitybasedsolutions/the_role_of_community_in_combating_honor_killings.html|title=the role of community in combating honor killings|website=web.stanford.edu|access-date=2018-12-08}}</ref>  These killings are a traditional practice,{{where?|date=January 2019}} believed to have originated from tribal customs where an allegation against a woman can be enough to defile a family's reputation.<ref name=\"BBC_ethics\">{{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Ethics guide \u2013 Honour crimes | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/ethics/honourcrimes/crimesofhonour_1.shtml | work = [[BBC]] | date = | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = Staff writer | title = Definition of honor killing | url = http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/honor%20killing | website = merriam-webster.com | publisher = [[Merriam-Webster]] | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref> Women are killed for reasons such as refusing to enter an [[arranged marriage]], being in a relationship that is disapproved by their relatives, attempting to leave a marriage, having sex outside marriage, becoming the victim of rape, dressing in ways that are deemed inappropriate.<ref name=\"BBC_ethics\" /><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news | last = Harter | first = Pascale | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-13760895 | work= BBC News | title=Libya rape victims 'face honour killings' | date=14 June 2011| access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nHonor killings are common in countries such as Afghanistan, Egypt, Iraq, Jordan, Lebanon, Libya, Morocco, Pakistan, Saudi Arabia, Syria, Turkey, Yemen.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/><ref>{{cite web | last = UN Women | author-link = UN Women | title = Violence against women: work of the General Assembly on violence against women | url = https://www.un.org/womenwatch/daw/vaw/v-work-ga.htm | website = un.org/womenwatch | publisher = [[UN Women]], Violence Against Women | access-date = 18 November 2013}}\n:''Listing for'':\n:* {{cite book | last = UN Secretary-General | author-link = Secretary-General of the United Nations | title = Working towards the elimination of crimes against women committed in the name of honour | url = http://daccess-ods.un.org/access.nsf/Get?Open&DS=A/57/169&Lang=E | id = A/57/169 | publisher = [[United Nations General Assembly]] | language = English | date = 2 July 2002 }} [http://daccess-ods.un.org/access.nsf/Get?Open&DS=A/57/169&Lang=A Arabic pdf.] [http://daccess-ods.un.org/access.nsf/Get?Open&DS=A/57/169&Lang=C Chinese pdf.] [http://daccess-ods.un.org/access.nsf/Get?Open&DS=A/57/169&Lang=F French pdf.] [http://daccess-ods.un.org/access.nsf/Get?Open&DS=A/57/169&Lang=R Russian pdf.] [http://daccess-ods.un.org/access.nsf/Get?Open&DS=A/57/169&Lang=S Spanish pdf.]</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Ghanizada | title = 240 cases of honor killing recorded in Afghanistan, AIHRC | url = http://www.khaama.com/240-cases-of-honor-killing-recorded-in-afghanistan-aihrc-2177 | publisher = [[Khaama Press]] | location = Afghanistan | date = 9 June 2013 | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = UPI |author-link=United Press International | title = AIHRC: 400 rape, honor killings registered in Afghanistan in 2 years | url = http://latinbusinesstoday.com/2013/06/aihrc-400-rape-honor-killings-registered-in-afghanistan-in-2-years/ | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150214224858/http://latinbusinesstoday.com/2013/06/aihrc-400-rape-honor-killings-registered-in-afghanistan-in-2-years/ | archive-date = 14 February 2015 | work = Latin Business Today | location = Kabul, Afghanistan | date = 10 June 2013 | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last1 = Bayoumy | first1 = Yara | last2 = Kami | first2 = Aseel | title=\"Honor killings\" require tougher laws, say Iraqi women | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/03/06/us-iraq-women-idUSTRE82510920120306 | work = Reuters | date=6 March 2012 | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref> Honor killings also occur in immigrant communities in Europe, the United States and Canada. Although honor killings are most often associated with the Middle East and South Asia, they occur in other parts of the world too.<ref name=\"BBC_ethics\" /><ref>{{cite web | title = International Domestic Violence Issues | url = http://www.sanctuaryforfamilies.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=252&Itemid=259 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141016194204/http://www.sanctuaryforfamilies.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=252&Itemid=259 | archive-date = 16 October 2014 | website = sanctuaryforfamilies.org | publisher = Sanctuary for Families }}</ref> In India, honor killings occur in the northern regions of the country, especially in the states of Punjab, Haryana, Bihar, Uttar Pradesh, Rajasthan, Jharkhand, Himachal Pradesh and Madhya Pradesh.<ref>{{cite news | last1 = Donald | first1 = Alice | last2 = Bishop | first2 = Hilary | title = World agenda: what justice? | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/specials/1817_wawryw/page4.shtml | publisher = [[BBC World Service]]  | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = India court seeks 'honour killing' response | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10364986 | work = BBC News |date = 21 June 2010  | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref> In Turkey, honor killings are a serious problem in Southeastern Anatolia.<ref>{{cite news | last = Rainsford | first = Sarah | title = 'Honour' crime defiance in Turkey | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4357158.stm | work = BBC News | date = 19 October 2005 | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = Kardam | first = Filiz | editor-last = Murray | editor-first = Genevra | title = The dynamics of honor killings in Turkey: prospects for action | url = http://www.unfpa.org/publications/dynamics-honour-killings-turkey | publisher = [[United Nations Development Programme]], Population Association (Turkey) and [[United Nations Population Fund]] | date = 2005 | access-date = 18 November 2013}} [http://www.unfpa.org/upload/lib_pub_file/676_filename_honourkillings.pdf Pdf.]</ref>\n\n====Dowry violence====\n[[File:Say no to dowry.jpg|thumb|upright|Anti-dowry poster in [[Bangalore, India]]]]\n\nThe custom of [[dowry]], which is common in South Asia, especially in India, is the trigger of many forms of violence against women. [[Bride burning]] is a form of violence against women in which a bride is killed at home by her husband or husband's family due to his dissatisfaction over the dowry provided by her family. [[Dowry death]] refers to the phenomenon of women and girls being killed or committing [[suicide]] due to disputes regarding dowry. Dowry violence is common in India, Pakistan, Bangladesh and Nepal. In India, in 2011 alone, the National Crime Records Bureau reported 8,618 dowry deaths, while unofficial figures suggest the numbers to be at least three times higher.<ref>{{cite book | last = UN Women | author-link = UN Women | title = Confronting dowry-related violence in India: women at the center of justice | url = http://www.unwomen.org/en/news/stories/2012/12/confronting-dowry-related-violence-in-india-women-at-the-center-of-justice | publisher = [[UN Women]] | date = 24 December 2012 | access-date = 18 November 2013 }}</ref>\n\n====Forced marriage====\n{{main|Forced marriage}}\n[[File:Oskar Shmerling. Free love (Forced marriage). Molla Nasreddin.jpg|thumb|220px|left|Criticism of the [[Azerbaijani people|Azeri]] custom of [[forced marriage]], as depicted in the early 20th-century satirical periodical [[Molla Nasraddin (magazine)|Molla Nasraddin]]]]\nA [[forced marriage]] is a marriage in which one or both of the parties is married against their will. Forced marriages are common in South Asia, the Middle East and Africa. The customs of [[bride price]] and [[dowry]], that exist in many parts of the world, contribute to this practice. A forced marriage is also often the result of a dispute between families, where the dispute is 'resolved' by giving a female from one family to the other.<ref>''Citations'':\n* {{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Ethics guide \u2013 Slavery: Modern slavery | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/ethics/slavery/modern/modern_1.shtml#section_2 | work = [[BBC]] | date = | access-date = 5 September 2013}}\n* {{cite book | last = Shahinian | first = Gulnara | title = Report of the Special Rapporteur on contemporary forms of slavery, including its causes and consequences, Gulnara Shahinian: Thematic report on servile marriage (A/HRC/21/41) | url = http://www.ohchr.org/Documents/HRBodies/HRCouncil/RegularSession/Session21/A-HRC-21-41_en.pdf | publisher =  United Nations. Human Rights Council Twenty-first session | date = 10 July 2012}}\n* {{cite book | last = UNIFEM | author-link = United Nations Development Fund for Women | title = Ending violence against women & girls \u2013 Evidence, data and knowledge in the Pacific Island Countries: literature review and annotated bibliography |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708174234/http://www.undp.org.fj/pdf/unp/evaw.pdf | url = http://www.undp.org.fj/pdf/unp/evaw.pdf |url-status=dead |archivedate=8 July 2011 | publisher = [[United Nations Development Fund for Women|UNIFEM]] | date = August 2010 | accessdate = 8 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe custom of [[bride kidnapping]] continues to exist in some Central Asian countries such as Kyrgyzstan, Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, and the Caucasus, or parts of Africa, especially Ethiopia. A girl or a woman is abducted by the would be groom, who is often helped by his friends. The victim is often raped by the would be groom, after which he may try to negotiate a bride price with the village elders to legitimize the marriage.<ref>''News articles'':\n* {{cite news | last = Staff writer | title=World: Africa, Ethiopia: Revenge of the abducted bride | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/371944.stm | work =[[BBC News]] | date=18 June 1999 | access-date = 19 November 2013}}\n* {{cite news| last = Gena | first = Alem | title = Ethiopia: Surviving forced marriage | url = http://www.irinnews.org/report/69993/ethiopia-surviving-forced-marriage | work = [[IRIN]] | date = 23 February 2007 | accessdate = 3 April 2016}}\n* {{cite book | last = PI | author-link = Pathfinder International | title = Report on causes and consequences of early marriage in Amhara Region |publisher=[[Pathfinder International]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130323124732/http://www.pathfinder.org/publications-tools/pdfs/Causes-and-Consequesnces-of-Early-Marriage-in-the-Amhara-Region-of-Ethiopia.pdf |archivedate=23 March 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all |url=http://www.pathfinder.org/publications-tools/pdfs/Causes-and-Consequesnces-of-Early-Marriage-in-the-Amhara-Region-of-Ethiopia.pdf | date = July 2006 |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nForced and child marriages are practiced by some inhabitants In Tanzania. Girls are sold by their families to older men for financial benefits and often girls are married off as soon as they hit puberty, which can be as young as seven years old.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2014/10/29/tanzania-child-marriage-harms-girls|title=Tanzania: Child Marriage Harms Girls|date=2014-10-29|work=Human Rights Watch|access-date=2018-11-30|language=en}}</ref> To the older men, these young brides act as symbols of masculinity and accomplishment. Child brides endure forced sex, causing health risks and growth impediments.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ezer|first=T|last2=et|first2=al.|date=2006|title=Child marriage and guardianship in tanzania: Robbing girls of their childhood and infantilizing women|url=https://heinonline.org/HOL/P?h=hein.journals/grggenl7&i=367&a=c3VueWJ1ZmZhbG8uZWR1|journal=Georgetown Journal of Gender and the Law|volume=Special Issue|pages=357\u2013450|via=Hein}}</ref> Primary education is usually not completed for young girls in forced marriages. Married and pregnant students are often discriminated against, and expelled and excluded from school.<ref name=\":0\" /> The Law of Marriage Act currently does not address issues with guardianship and child marriage. The issue of child marriage is not addressed enough in this law, and only establishes a minimum age of 18 for the boys of Tanzania. A minimum age needs to be enforced for girls to stop these practices and provide them with equal rights and a less harmful life.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://heinonline.org/HOL/P?h=hein.journals/frdint38&i=660&a=c3VueWJ1ZmZhbG8uZWR1|title=- HeinOnline.org|website=heinonline.org|language=en|access-date=2018-11-30}}</ref>\n\n====Force-feeding====\nIn some countries, notably Mauritania, young girls are forcibly fattened to prepare them for marriage, because obesity is seen as desirable. This practice of [[force-feeding]] is known as ''[[leblouh]]'' or ''gavage''.<ref>''Citations'':\n* {{cite book | last = Popenoe | first = Rebecca | chapter = Getting fat | editor-last = Popenoe | editor-first = Rebecca | chapterurl = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=25H0_G9MG10C&pg=PA39 | title = Feeding desire: fatness, beauty, and sexuality among a Saharan people | pages = 33&ndash;50 | publisher = Routledge | location = London New York | year = 2004 | isbn = 9780415280969 | ref = harv }}\n::''Book review'': {{cite web | last = Fan | title = Space and body modification: Rebecca Popenoe's ''Feeding Desire'' (blog) | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304231342/http://www.savagemind.org/tag/body/ | archive-date = 4 March 2016 | url = http://www.savagemind.org/tag/body/ |publisher= Savage Mind via [[WordPress]] |date=3 August 2012 |accessdate=3 April 2016}}\n* {{cite news | last = LaFraniere | first = Sharon | title = In Mauritania, seeking to end an overfed ideal | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/04/world/africa/04mauritania.html | work = [[The New York Times]] | quote = Girls as young as 5 and as old as 19 had to drink up to five gallons of fat-rich camel's or cow's milk daily, aiming for silvery stretch marks on their upper arms. If a girl refused or vomited, the village weight-gain specialist might squeeze her foot between sticks, pull her ear, pinch her inner thigh, bend her finger backward or force her to drink her own vomit. In extreme cases, girls die, due to a burst stomach. The practice was known as gavage, a French term for force-feeding geese to obtain foie gras. | date = 4 July 2007 | access-date = 30 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe practice goes back to the 11th century, and has been reported to have made a significant comeback after a [[2008 Mauritanian coup d'\u00e9tat|military junta took over the country in 2008]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Smith | first = Alex Duval | title = Girls being force-fed for marriage as junta revives fattening farms | url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/mar/01/mauritania-force-feeding-marriage | work = [[The Observer]] | date = 1 March 2009 | access-date = 22 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Abuse related to son-preference====\n[[File:2011 Census sex ratio map for the states and Union Territories of India Boys to Girls 0 to 1 age group.svg|thumb|250px|left|A map of [[India]]'s child sex ratio, 2011.]]\n[[File:2012 Birth Sex Ratio World Map.jpg|thumb|250px|World map of birth sex ratios, 2012]]\n[[File:Chinese anti infanticide tract from 1800.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Chinese anti-infanticide tract circa 1800. China has a long history of son preference, which was aggravated after the enforcement of the [[one child policy]].]]\n''Son preference'' is a custom rooted in gender inequality that is prevalent in many countries and found across religions and classes.<ref name=\"StopVAW_son\">{{cite web | last = Staff writer | title = Son preference | url =http://www.stopvaw.org/harmful_practices_son_preference | website = stopvaw.org | publisher = Stop Violence Against Women | date = June 2010 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}</ref> Although preference for a specific sex of the child may be common in an abstract way in many cultures, when such preference is so strong as to lead to the rejection of the child or to violence against the mother, this crosses the line into [[domestic violence]], [[child abuse]] and violence against women. Such forms of son preference are common especially in parts of [[South Asia]], [[East Asia]] and the [[Caucasus]]. Manifestations of such practices include [[sex selective abortion]], [[female infanticide]], [[child abandonment|female child abandonment]], as well as favoring sons with regard to allocating of family resources.<ref name=\"StopVAW_son\" />\n\n[[China]] and [[India]] have a very strong son preference. In China, the [[one child policy]] was largely responsible for an unbalanced sex ratio. Sex-selective abortion, as well as rejection of girl children is common. [[The Dying Rooms]] is a 1995 [[television]] [[documentary film]] about Chinese state orphanages, which documented how parents abandoned their newborn girls into [[orphanages]], where the staff would leave the children in rooms to die of thirst, or starvation.\nAnother manifestation of son preference is the violence inflicted against mothers who give birth to girls.<ref>''News articles'':\n* {{cite news | last = Sarwary | first = Bilal | title = Afghan woman is killed 'for giving birth to a girl' | url = https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-16787534 | work = [[BBC News]] | location = Kabul, Afghanistan | date = 30 January 2012 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}\n* {{cite news | last = Agarwal | first = Keshav | title = 23-year-old woman killed for giving birth to twin daughters | url = http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bareilly/23-year-old-woman-killed-for-giving-birth-to-twin-daughters/articleshow/57785767.cms | work = [[The Times of India]] | date = 23 March 2017 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}\n* {{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = 56 killed for giving birth to girl child in Pakistan | url = http://www.deccanchronicle.com/131127/news-world/article/56-killed-giving-birth-girl-child-pakistan | work = [[Deccan Chronicle]] | location = Hyderabad, Telangana, India | date = 27 November 2013 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Acid throwing===\n{{main|Acid throwing}}\n[[File:Acid attack victim.jpg|left|Acid attack victim in [[Cambodia]]|thumb|250px]]\n[[Acid throwing]], also called acid attack, or vitriolage, is defined as the act of throwing acid onto the body of a person \"with the intention of injuring or disfiguring [them] out of jealousy or revenge\".<ref>{{Cite book | last =Vig |first= Krishan| chapter = Corrosive poisons: vitriolage | chapterurl = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Ip1rAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA462 | editor-last =Vig |editor-first=Krishan | title=Textbook of forensic medicine and toxicology: principles and practice | page=462 |publisher=Elsevier | location = India | year=2014 |edition=5th | isbn=9788131226841 }}</ref> The most common types of acid used in these attacks are sulfuric, nitric, or hydrochloric acid.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Welsh | first = Jane | title = \"It was like burning in hell\": A comprehensive exploration of acid attack violence | journal = Carolina Papers on International Health | volume = 32 |publisher=Center for Global Initiatives, [[University of North Carolina]] |accessdate=3 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130123191359/http://cgi.unc.edu/uploads/media_items/it-was-like-burning-in-hell-a-comparative-exploration-of-acid-attack-violence.original.pdf|url=http://cgi.unc.edu/uploads/media_items/it-was-like-burning-in-hell-a-comparative-exploration-of-acid-attack-violence.original.pdf |archivedate=23 January 2013 |df=dmy-all | date = Fall 2006}}</ref> Perpetrators of these attacks throw [[acid]] at their victims, usually at their faces, burning them, and damaging [[skin]] tissue, often exposing and sometimes dissolving the bones.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Swanson | first = Jordan | title = Acid attacks: Bangladesh's efforts to stop the violence | journal = Harvard Health Policy Review | volume = 3 | issue = 1 | page = 3 | publisher = Harvard Internfaculty Initiative in Health Policy | date = Spring 2002 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20060117184047/http://hcs.harvard.edu/~epihc/currentissue/spring2002/swanson-3.php | archive-date = 17 January 2006 | url = http://hcs.harvard.edu:80/~epihc/currentissue/spring2002/swanson-3.php | ref = harv | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> The long term consequences of these attacks include [[blindness]] and permanent [[scarring]] of the face and body.<ref>{{cite news | last = AP | author-link = Associated Press |url=http://archives.cnn.com/2000/ASIANOW/south/11/11/bangladesh.acid.ap/index.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070922210725/http://archives.cnn.com/2000/ASIANOW/south/11/11/bangladesh.acid.ap/index.html |archivedate=22 September 2007 |title= Bangladesh combats an acid onslaught against women |work=[[CNN]]|date= 12 November 2000 |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | last1 = Bahl | first1 = Taur | last2 = Syed | first2 = M. H. | title = Encyclopaedia of Muslim world | publisher = Anmol Publications | location = New Delhi | year = 2003 | isbn = 9788126114191}}</ref> Women and girls are the victims in 75-80% of cases.<ref>{{cite news | last = de Castella | first = Tom | title=How many acid attacks are there? | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-23631395 | work=[[BBC News]] | date=9 August 2013 |accessdate= 18 November 2013}}</ref> Acid attacks are often connected to domestic disputes, including dowry disputes, and refusal of a proposition for marriage, or of sexual advances. Such attacks are common in South Asia, in countries such as Bangladesh, Pakistan, India; and in Southeast Asia, especially in Cambodia.<ref>''Articles'':\n* {{cite news | last = Shackle | first = Samira | title = Acid attacks in Pakistan: A sorry litany of male egotism | url = http://www.newstatesman.com/world-affairs/2012/11/acid-attacks-pakistan-sorry-litany-male-egotism | work = [[New Statesman]] | date = 9 November 2012 |accessdate= 8 September 2013}} ''Interview with [[Sharmeen Obaid-Chinoy]] one of the directors the documentary \"[[Saving Face (2012 film)|Saving Face]]\".''\n* {{cite news | last = CBC | title = Longueuil woman burned and in coma after acid attack|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2012/08/28/nikolas-stefanatos-quebec-acid-attack_n_1838232.html |work=[[HuffPost]] | date = 28 October 2012 |accessdate=8 September 2013}}\n* {{cite news |last = Ungaro | first = Cosima | title = Nurbanu, Bangladeshi woman, forced to return to husband after acid attack | url = https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/11/28/nurbanu-acid-attack_n_2206621.html |work=[[HuffPost]] |accessdate= 8 September 2013  |date=28 November 2012}}\n* {{cite news | last =Scholte| first =Marianne| title =Acid attacks in Bangladesh: a voice for the victims| work = [[Spiegel Online]]| url =http://www.spiegel.de/international/0,1518,406485,00.html | date = 17 March 2006 | accessdate = 21 March 2008}}\n* {{cite book | last = Various |title=Combating acid violence in Bangladesh, India, and Cambodia |url= http://www.lawschool.cornell.edu/womenandjustice/upload/Combating-Acid-Violence-Report.pdf |publisher= [[Cornell Law School#Institutes and Programs|Avon Global Center for Women and Justice at Cornell Law School]], [[New York City Bar Association|Committee on International Human Rights of the, New York City Bar Association]], [[Cornell Law School#Campus|Cornell Law School International Human Rights Clinic]] and the Virtue Foundation | location = New York |accessdate=3 April 2016}}\n* {{cite book | last = CASC | title = Breaking the silence: addressing acid attacks in Cambodia | url = http://www.cambodianacidsurvivorscharity.org/docs/breaking_the_silence.pdf |publisher=Cambodian Acid Survivors Charity (CASC) |accessdate=3 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219010314/http://www.cambodianacidsurvivorscharity.org/docs/breaking_the_silence.pdf |archivedate=19 December 2013 |df=dmy-all | date = May 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Reproductive coercion===\n[[File:Mauricio rugendas - el malon.jpg|thumb|The painting depicts a Chilean woman being kidnapped during a [[mal\u00f3n]]. [[Bride kidnapping]] for the purpose of [[forced marriage]] and [[forced pregnancy]] was common through the history in many countries.]]\n{{Main|Reproductive coercion|Forced pregnancy|Bride kidnapping}}\nReproductive coercion is a form of [[domestic violence|domestic]] or [[intimate partner violence]], that involves violent, manipulative or deceptive behavior against [[reproductive health]] or [[reproductive rights]] within an intimate relation and includes a collection of behaviors intended to lead to [[forced pregnancy]].<ref name=\"ACOG\">{{cite journal | last = Committee on Health Care for Underserved Women | title = Committee Opinion No. 554: Reproductive and Sexual Coercion | journal = [[Obstetrics & Gynecology (journal)|Obstetrics and Gynecology]] | volume = 121 | issue = 2 Pt 1 | pages = 411&ndash;415 | publisher = [[Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|LWW]] | pmid = 23344307 | doi = 10.1097/01.AOG.0000426427.79586.3b | date = February 2013 | url = https://www.acog.org/Resources-And-Publications/Committee-Opinions/Committee-on-Health-Care-for-Underserved-Women/Reproductive-and-Sexual-Coercion | ref = harv }}</ref> Reproductive coercion is used to maintain power, control, and domination within a relationship and over a partner through an unwanted pregnancy. It is considered a serious public health issue.<ref name=\"ACOG\"/><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Chamberlain | first1 = Linda | last2 = Levenson | first2 = Rebecca | title = Reproductive health and partner violence guidelines: an integrated response to intimate partner Violence and reproductive coercion | url = http://www.futureswithoutviolence.org/userfiles/file/HealthCare/Repro_Guide.pdf | publisher = Family Violence Prevention Fund | location = San Francisco | date = 2010 }}</ref> This reproductive control is highly correlated to [[unintended pregnancy]].<ref>{{cite journal | last = Coker | first = Ann L. | title = Does physical intimate partner violence affect sexual health? A systematic review | journal = [[Trauma, Violence, & Abuse]] | volume = 8 | issue = 2| pages = 149&ndash;177 | publisher = [[SAGE Publications|Sage]] | pmid = 17545572 | doi = 10.1177/1524838007301162 | date = April 2007 | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\nForced pregnancy is the practice of forcing a woman or girl to become [[pregnant]], often as part of a [[forced marriage]], including by means of [[bride kidnapping]], through rape (including [[marital rape]], [[war rape]] and [[genocidal rape]]) or as part of a program of breeding [[slave]]s (see [[Slave breeding in the United States]]). In the 20th century, state mandated forced marriage with the aim of increasing the population was practiced by some authoritarian governments, notably during the [[Khmer Rouge]] regime in [[Cambodia]], which systematically forced people into marriages ordering them to have children, in order to increase the population and continue the revolution.<ref>{{cite book | last = Anderson | first = Natalae | title = Memorandum: Charging forced marriage as a crime against humanity | url = http://www.d.dccam.org/Abouts/Intern/Natalae_Forced_marriage.pdf | publisher = Documentation Center of Cambodia | date = 22 September 2010 | access-date = 8 October 2017 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171020153617/http://www.d.dccam.org/Abouts/Intern/Natalae_Forced_marriage.pdf | archive-date = 20 October 2017 | url-status = dead }}</ref> Forced pregnancy is strongly connected to the custom of [[bride price]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Bawah | first1 = Ayaga Agula | last2 = Akweongo | first2 = Patricia | last3 = Simmons | first3 = Ruth | last4 = Phillips | first4 = James F. | title = Women's fears and men's anxieties: the impact of family planning on gender relations in Northern Ghana | journal = [[Studies in Family Planning]] | volume = 30 | issue = 1 | pages = 54&ndash;66 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] on behalf of the [[Population Council]] | date = 1999 | url = https://www.popcouncil.org/research/womens-fears-and-mens-anxieties-the-impact-of-family-planning-on-gender-rel | ref = harv | doi=10.1111/j.1728-4465.1999.00054.x| pmid = 10216896 | hdl = 2027.42/73927 }} [http://www.popcouncil.org/uploads/pdfs/councilarticles/sfp/SFP301Bawah.pdf Pdf.]</ref>\n\nWithin the discourse on reproductive rights, the issue of [[abortion]] is often debated. [[Abortion law]] falls within the jurisdiction of each country, although [[forced abortion]] is prohibited by international law. The [[Convention on preventing and combating violence against women and domestic violence|Istanbul Convention]] prohibits forced abortion and [[forced sterilization]] (Article 39).<ref>{{cite book | last = CoE | author-link = Council of Europe | title = Convention on preventing and combating violence against women and domestic violence | url = https://rm.coe.int/168046031c | publisher = [[Council of Europe]] | date = 12 April 2011 }}</ref> The issue of ''forced continuation of pregnancy'' (i.e. denying a woman safe and legal abortion) is also seen by some organizations as a violation of women's rights, although there are no binding international obligations on this issue. However, the [[Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination against Women]] considers the criminalization of abortion a \"violations of women's sexual and reproductive health and rights\" and a form of \"gender based violence\"; paragraph 18 of its ''General recommendation No. 35 on gender based violence against women, updating general recommendation No. 19'' states, \"Violations of women\u2019s sexual and reproductive health and rights, such as forced sterilizations, forced abortion, forced pregnancy, ''criminalisation of abortion'', ''denial or delay of safe abortion and post abortion care'', ''forced continuation of pregnancy'', abuse and mistreatment of women and girls seeking sexual and reproductive health information, goods and services, are forms of gender based violence that, depending on the circumstances, may amount to torture or cruel, inhuman or degrading treatment.\"<ref>{{cite book | last = Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination Against Women | author-link = Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women#Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination Against Women | title = General recommendation No. 35 on gender-based violence against women, updating general recommendation No. 19 | url = http://tbinternet.ohchr.org/Treaties/CEDAW/Shared%20Documents/1_Global/CEDAW_C_GC_35_8267_E.pdf | publisher = [[Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women]] (CEDAW) | id = CEDAW/C/GC/35 | date = 14 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Mob violence===\nThere have been [[Hassi Messaoud mob attacks against women|mob attacks against single women]] in [[Hassi Messaoud]], [[Algeria]] in 2001.<ref name=\"Amnesty\">{{cite web|title=Algerian authorities must investigate and stop attacks against women |url=https://www.amnesty.org.au/news/comments/22931/ |publisher=Amnesty International|accessdate=13 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903140432/http://www.amnesty.org.au/news/comments/22931/|archivedate=3 September 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> 95 women had been attacked by mobs of men, with at least six fatalities, although the authorities denied this.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Grozelle|first=Renee S.|date=2015|title=Mob Violence Against Women in Algeria: A Historical Case Analysis|url=http://www.inquiriesjournal.com/articles/1016/mob-violence-against-women-in-algeria-a-historical-case-analysis|journal=Inquiries Journal|language=en|volume=7|issue=03}}</ref> As of 2011, similar mob attacks against women were continuing in [[Hassi Messaoud]] and elsewhere in Algeria, notably [[M'Sila, Algeria|M'sila]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Stop renewed attacks on women |url=http://www.wluml.org/node/7420|publisher=Women Living Under Muslim Laws|accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Algerian authorities must investigate and stop attacks against women|url=https://www.amnesty.org.au/news/comments/22931/|publisher=Amnesty International|accessdate=13 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903140432/http://www.amnesty.org.au/news/comments/22931/|archivedate=3 September 2011}}</ref> However, mob violence against women in the country dates back decades, and increased specifically after gaining independence from France in 1962, which was followed by return to stricter religious norms.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nAccording to [[Amnesty International]], \"some women have been sexually abused\" and were targeted \"not just because they are women, but because they are living alone and are economically independent\".<ref name=\"Amnesty\" />\n\n=== Dating abuse ===\n{{See|Dating abuse|Teen dating violence}}\nDating abuse or dating violence is the perpetration of coercion, intimidation or assault in the context of [[dating]] or [[courtship]]. It is also when one partner tries to maintain [[abusive power and control]]. Dating violence is defined by the CDC as \"the physical, sexual, psychological, or emotional violence within a dating relationship, including stalking\".<ref>{{cite web | title = Intimate partner violence: teen dating violence | url = https://www.cdc.gov/violenceprevention/intimatepartnerviolence/teen_dating_violence.html | website = cdc.gov | publisher = [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] | date = 2016 | accessdate = 21 October 2017 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181230230859/https://www.cdc.gov/ViolencePrevention/intimatepartnerviolence/teen_dating_violence.html | archive-date = 30 December 2018 | url-status = dead }} [https://www.cdc.gov/violenceprevention/pdf/teen-dating-violence-factsheet-a.pdf Fact sheet pdf.] </ref> In some countries it is common for older men to engage in \"compensated dating\" with underage girls. Such relationships are called [[enjo k\u014dsai]] in Japan, and are also common in Asian countries such as Taiwan, South Korea, Hong Kong. The WHO condemned \"economically coerced sex (e.g. school girls having sex with \u201csugar daddies\u201d ([[Sugar baby]] in return for school fees)\" as a form of violence against women.<ref name=\"WHO_VAW\" />\n\n===Sexual violence on college campuses===\n{{See|Campus sexual assault}}\nSexual violence on college campuses is considered a major problem in the United States. According to the conclusion of a major Campus Sexual Assault (CSA) Study: \"The CSA Study data suggest women at universities are at considerable risk for experiencing sexual assault.\"<ref>{{cite book  | last1 = Krebs | first1 = Christopher P. | last2 =Lindquist | first2 = Christine H. | last3 =Warner | first3 = Tara D. | last4 =Fisher | first4 = Bonnie S. | last5 =Martin | first5 = Sandra L. | title = Campus sexual assault (CSA) study: final report | publisher = [[RTI International]] | url = https://www.ncjrs.gov/App/Publications/abstract.aspx?ID=243011 | date = October 2007 }} {{NCJ|243011}} [https://www.ncjrs.gov/pdffiles1/nij/grants/221153.pdf Pdf.]</ref> Sexual violence on campus has been researched in other countries too, such as Canada,<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = DeKeseredy | first1 = Walter | last2 = Kelly|  first2 = Katharine | title = The incidence and prevalence of woman abuse in Canadian university and college dating relationships | journal = [[Canadian Journal of Sociology]] | volume = 18 | issue = 2 | pages = 137&ndash;159 | publisher = [[University of Alberta]] | jstor = 3341255 | doi = 10.2307/3341255 | date = 1993 | ref = harv }}</ref> the UK,<ref>{{cite book | last = NUS | author-link = National Union of Students (United Kingdom) |title=Hidden Marks: A study of women student's experiences of harassment, stalking, violence, and sexual assault | url = http://www.nus.org.uk/Global/NUS_hidden_marks_report_2nd_edition_web.pdf | publisher = [[National Union of Students (United Kingdom)|National Union of Students]] | location = London, UK | date = 2011| edition = 2nd|accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref> and New Zealand.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Gavey | authorlink=Nicola Gavey|first = Nicola | title = Sexual victimization prevalence among New Zealand university students | journal = [[Journal of Consulting and Clinical Psychology]] | volume = 59 | issue = 3 | pages = 464&ndash;466 | publisher = [[American Psychological Association]] via [[PsycINFO|PsycNET]] | doi = 10.1037/0022-006X.59.3.464 | date = June 1991 | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\n===Restrictions on freedom of movement===\nWomen are, in many parts of the world, severely restricted in their [[freedom of movement]].\nFreedom of movement is an essential right, recognized by international instruments, including Article 15 (4) of [[CEDAW]].<ref>{{cite book | last =  UN General Assembly | author-link =  UN General Assembly | title = The convention on the elimination of all forms of discrimination against women (CEDAW) | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140326154350/http://www.un.org/womenwatch/daw/cedaw/text/econvention.htm | archive-date = 26 March 2014 | url = http://www.un.org/womenwatch/daw/cedaw/text/econvention.htm | publisher = [[UN Women|UN Women, Division for the Advancement of Women]] | date = 1979 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}</ref> Nevertheless, in some countries, women are not legally allowed to leave home without a [[Wali (Islamic legal guardian)|male guardian]] (male relative or husband).<ref>{{cite news | last = Lee | first = Dave | title = Saudi Arabian woman challenges male guardianship laws | url = https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-13932287 | work = [[BBC World Service]] | date = 29 June 2011 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}</ref> Even in countries where there are no laws against women traveling alone, there are strong social norms, such as [[purdah]] - a religious and social practice of female [[seclusion]] prevalent especially among some [[Muslim]] and [[Hindu]] communities in [[South Asia]]. Many countries have laws on what type of clothing women may or may not wear in public (see [[Hijab by country]]). Women in some cultures are forced into [[social isolation]] during their [[menstruation|menstrual period]]s. In parts of Nepal for instance, they are forced to live in sheds, are forbidden to touch men or even to enter the courtyard of their own homes, and are barred from consuming milk, yogurt, butter, meat, and various other foods, for fear they will contaminate those goods. (see [[Chhaupadi]]). Women have died during this period because of starvation, bad weather, or bites by snakes.<ref>''Articles'':\n* {{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = PM concerned over death of woman in Chaupadi | url = http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2016-11-19/pm-concerned-over-death-of-woman-in-chaupadi.html | work = [[The Kathmandu Post]] | date = 19 November 2016 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}\n* {{cite news| last = Pokharel | first = Sugam | title = Nepali 'mensuration hut' ritual claims life of teenage girl | url = http://edition.cnn.com/2017/07/10/asia/nepal-menstruation-hut-deaths-outrage/index.html | work = [[CNN]] | date = 10 July 2017 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}\n* {{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Nepal criminalises banishing menstruating women to huts | url = https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-40885748 | work = [[BBC News]] | date = 10 August 2017 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}\n* {{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Nepali girl dies due to banned mensuration practice | url = http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/12/nepali-girl-dies-menstruation-chhaupadi-161219090727200.html | work = [[Al Jazeera]] | date = December 2016 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}</ref> In cultures where women are restricted from being in public places, by law or custom, women who break such restrictions often face violence.<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Freedom of movement and women's economic empowerment | url = https://www.empowerwomen.org/en/who-we-are/news/2016/2/freedom-of-movement-and-womens-economic-empowerment | work = Empower Women | date = February 2016 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Denial of medical care===\n[[File:Maternal mortality rate worldwide.jpg|thumb|300px|[[Maternal Mortality Rate]] worldwide, as defined by the number of maternal deaths per 100,000 live births from any cause related to or aggravated by pregnancy or its management, excluding accidental or incidental causes.<ref name=CIA2010>[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2223rank.html?countryName=Australia&countryCode=as&regionCode=aus&rank=156#as Country Comparison: Maternal Mortality Rate] in [[:en:The World Factbook|The CIA World Factbook]]. Date of Information: 2010</ref>]]\nWomen in many parts of the world are often denied medical care. Denial of access to \nhealth assistance, along with denial of access to other services, is a form of socioeconomic violence against women.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.womensrefugeecommission.org/images/zdocs/gl_sgbv03_01.pdf|title=chapter1: Overview of sexual and gender-based violence|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> According to the WHO, \"Discrimination in health care settings takes many forms and is often manifested when an individual or group is denied access to health care services that are otherwise available to others. It can also occur through denial of services that are only needed by certain groups, such as women.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/27-06-2017-joint-united-nations-statement-on-ending-discrimination-in-health-care-settings|title=Joint United Nations statement on ending discrimination in health care settings|website=www.who.int}}</ref> \n\nWomen may be denied medical care for numerous reasons, including lack of necessary [[freedom of movement]] allowing women to leave home so they can go to a medical facility, lack of financial resources, the need (in law or in practice) for a male relative or husband to consent to the medical care of the woman. A common consequence of denial of women's medical care is [[maternal mortality]]. Globally, there are more than 300.000 cases of maternal mortality yearly, with 99% of all maternal deaths occurring in developing countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs348/en/|title=Maternal mortality|website=World Health Organization}}</ref> \n\nDenial of medical care often occurs with regard to reproductive and sexual health. Sometimes women themselves avoid the medical system  for fear of being reported to the police or facing family violence due to having [[premarital sex]] or being the victims of [[sexual violence]]. In some parts of Latin America, with very strict anti-abortion laws, pregnant women avoid the medical system due to fear of being investigated by the authorities if they have a miscarriage, or a stillbirth, or other problems with the pregnancy. Prosecuting such women is quite common in places such as [[El Salvador]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2017/07/el-salvador-rape-survivor-sentenced-to-30-years-in-jail-under-extreme-anti-abortion-law/|title=El Salvador: Rape survivor sentenced to 30 years in jail under extreme anti-abortion law|website=www.amnesty.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/world-latin-america-32491838/el-salvador-women-jailed-for-miscarriages|title=Jailed for a miscarriage|website=BBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceB\">Pr\u00fcgl, E. (Lecturer) (2 December 2013). Gender and International Affairs 2013. INTERNATIONAL FEMINIST MOVEMENTS. Lecture conducted from The Graduate Institute of International and Development Studies (IHEID), Geneva, Switzerland.</ref><ref name=\"reuters.com\">{{cite news|last=Hosenball |first=Mark |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/06/06/us-usa-wiretaps-verizon-idUSBRE95502920130606 |title=Obama administration defends massive phone record collection |work=Reuters |date=6 June 2013 |accessdate=6 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn developed societies, women face medial discrimination in that female health concerns are often dismissed or downplayed, especially when reproductive health is concerned. Research since 2001 has consistently shown that medical practitioners have been \"dismissing, misdiagnosing, or cluelessly shrugging\" at women seeking medical assistance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2018/08/womens-health-care-gaslighting/567149/|title=The Doctor Doesn\u2019t Listen to Her. But the Media Is Starting To.|last=Fetters|first=Ashley|date=2018-08-10|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Pag\u00e1n|first=Camille Noe|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/03/well/live/when-doctors-downplay-womens-health-concerns.html|title=When Doctors Downplay Women\u2019s Health Concerns|date=2018-05-03|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> \n\nDenial of medical care for women has led to the exclusion of female needs in medical research and diagnosis, leading to a male bias in medical trials at the expense of women's health.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jackson|first=Gabrielle|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2019/nov/13/the-female-problem-male-bias-in-medical-trials|title=The female problem: how male bias in medical trials ruined women's health|date=2019-11-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-24|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n===Stalking===\n{{Main|Stalking}}\nStalking is unwanted or obsessive attention by an individual or group toward another person, often manifested through persistent [[harassment]], [[intimidation]], or following/monitoring of the victim. Stalking is often understood as \"course of conduct directed at a specific person that would cause a reasonable person to feel fear\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.victimsofcrime.org/our-programs/stalking-resource-center/stalking-information |title=Stalking information |website =victimsofcrime.org | publisher = Stalking Resource Center |date= |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> Although stalkers are frequently portrayed as being strangers, they are most often known people, such as former or current partners, friends, colleagues or acquaintances. In the U.S., a survey by NVAW found that only 23% of female victims were stalked by strangers.<ref name=\"victimsofcrime.org\">{{cite journal | last1 = McFarlane | first1 = Judith M. | last2 = Campbell | first2 = Jacquelyn C. | last3 = Wilt | first3 = Susan | last4 = Sachs | first4 = Carolyn J. | last5 = Ulrich | first5 = Yvonne | last6 = Xu | first6 = Xiao | title = Stalking and intimate partner femicide | journal = [[Homicide Studies]] | volume = 3 | issue = 4 | pages = 300&ndash;316 | publisher = [[Sage Publications|Sage]] | doi = 10.1177/1088767999003004003 | date = November 1999 | ref = harv }} [http://victimsofcrime.org/docs/src/mcfarlane-j-m-campbell-j-c-wilt-s-sachs-c-j-ulrich-y-xu-x-1999.pdf Pdf.]</ref> Stalking by partners can be very dangerous, as sometimes it can escalate into severe violence, including murder.<ref name=\"victimsofcrime.org\"/> Police statistics from the 1990s in Australia indicated that 87.7% of stalking offenders were male and 82.4% of stalking victims were female.<ref>{{cite book |last=Dussuyer |first=Inez |url=http://www.aic.gov.au/media_library/conferences/stalking/dussuyer.pdf |title=Is stalking legislation effective in protecting victims? |publisher=[[Australian Institute of Criminology]] |location=Sydney |date=December 2000 |accessdate=3 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304052637/http://www.aic.gov.au/media_library/conferences/stalking/dussuyer.pdf |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }} Paper presented at the ''Stalking: Criminal Justice Responses Conference'' convened by the [[Australian Institute of Criminology]] and held in Sydney 7\u20138 December 2000.</ref>\n\n===Sexual harassment===\n{{Main|Sexual harassment}}\nSexual harassment is abusive, uninvited and unwelcome behavior of a sexual nature, typically in the work/studying place, which may include [[intimidation]], [[bullying]] or [[coercion]] of a sexual nature, or the inappropriate promise of rewards in exchange for sexual favors. It can be verbal or physical, and it is often perpetrated by a person in a position of authority against a subordinate.<ref>{{cite web | last = UN Women | author-link = UN Women|url=https://www.un.org/womenwatch/osagi/pdf/whatissh.pdf |title=What is sexual harassment |publisher=[[UN Women]] |accessdate=3 April 2016}}\n:''Citing'':\n:* {{cite book | last = BNA | author-link = Bureau of national affairs  | title = Preventing workplace harassment: a factsheet for employees | publisher = [[Bureau of national affairs|BNA Communications, Inc.]] | location = Washington, DC | issn = 1544-7820 | year = 1992 }} [https://www.bna.com/uploadedFiles/BNA_V2/Legal/Products/Books/Legal_Reference/shfsSample.pdf Sample of 2016 edition.]</ref> In the United States, sexual harassment is a form of discrimination that violates Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964. The [[Council of Europe Convention on preventing and combating violence against women and domestic violence]] defines sexual harassment as: \"any form of unwanted verbal, non-verbal or physical conduct of a sexual nature with the purpose or effect of violating the dignity of a person, in particular when creating an intimidating, hostile, degrading, humiliating or offensive environment\".<ref name=\"COE 210\" />\n\n===Human trafficking and forced prostitution===\n[[File:Map3.3Trafficking compressed.jpg|thumb|230px|right|A world map showing countries by prevalence of female trafficking]]\n{{Main|Human trafficking|Forced prostitution}}\nHuman trafficking refers to the acquisition of persons by improper means such as force, fraud or deception, with the aim of [[Exploitation of labour|exploiting]] them.<ref>{{cite web| last = UNODC| author-link =United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime|url=http://www.unodc.org/unodc/human-trafficking/index.html?ref=menuside |title=UNODC on human trafficking and migrant smuggling (index) |publisher=[[United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime]] |date= |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> The [[Protocol to Prevent, Suppress and Punish Trafficking in Persons, especially Women and Children]] states,<ref>{{cite web | last = OSCE | author-link = OSCE|url=http://www.osce.org/odihr/19223 |title=U.N. protocol to prevent, suppress and punish trafficking in persons, especially women and children, supplementing the United Nations convention against transnational organized crime |publisher=[[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]] |date=15 November 2000 |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n: \"Trafficking in persons\" shall mean the recruitment, transportation, transfer, harbouring or receipt of persons, by means of the threat or use of force or other forms of coercion, of abduction, of fraud, of deception, of the abuse of power or of a position of vulnerability or of the giving or receiving of payments or benefits to achieve the consent of a person having control over another person, for the purpose of exploitation. Exploitation shall include, at a minimum, the exploitation of the prostitution of others or other forms of sexual exploitation, forced labour or services, slavery or practices similar to slavery, servitude or the removal of organs.\n\nBecause of the illegal nature of trafficking, reliable data on its extent is very limited.<ref name=\"apps.who.int\">{{cite book | last = WHO | author-link = World Health Organization|title=Understanding and addressing violence against women: Human trafficking |url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/77394/1/WHO_RHR_12.42_eng.pdf | id = WHO/RHR/12.42 |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] | date = 2012 |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> The [[World Health Organization|WHO]] states \"Current evidence strongly suggests that those who are trafficked into the [[sex industry]] and as domestic servants are more likely to be women and children.\"<ref name=\"apps.who.int\"/>\nA 2006 study in Europe on trafficked women found that the women were subjected to serious forms of abuse, such as physical or sexual violence, that affected their physical and mental health.<ref name=\"apps.who.int\"/>\n\n[[Forced prostitution]] is [[prostitution]] that takes place as a result of [[coercion]] by a third party. In forced prostitution, the party/parties who force the victim to be subjected to unwanted sexual acts exercise control over the victim.<ref>{{cite web | last = McDougall | first = Gay J. | author-link = Gay McDougall|url=http://www.unhchr.ch/huridocda/huridoca.nsf/0/3d25270b5fa3ea998025665f0032f220?OpenDocument#Bsl |title=Report of the Special Rapporteur on systematic rape, sexual slavery and slavery-like practices during armed conflict | id = E/CN.4/Sub.2/1998/13 | publisher = [[United Nations Economic and Social Council]] (ECOSOC) |accessdate=25 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130112211407/http://www.unhchr.ch/huridocda/huridoca.nsf/0/3d25270b5fa3ea998025665f0032f220?OpenDocument |archivedate=12 January 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Mistreatment of widows===\n[[File:Balinese rite of Suttee in Houtman 1597 Verhael vande Reyse ... Naer Oost Indien.jpg|thumb|200px|Description of the [[Bali]]nese rite of ''Suttee'', in Houtman's 1597 ''Verhael vande Reyse ... Naer Oost Indien'']]\n{{Main|Widow}}\n{{See also|Widow inheritance|Sexual cleansing#Widow cleansing|l2=Sexual cleansing}}\nA widow is a woman whose spouse has died. In some parts of the world, widows are subjected to serious forms of abuse, often fueled by traditional practices such as [[widow inheritance]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Owen | first = Margaret | chapter = Human rights, equality and legal protection | chapterurl = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Bh8sGfNKUTEC&pg=PA181 | editor-last = Owen | editor-first = Margaret | title = A world of widows | publisher = Zed Books | location = London Atlantic Highlands, New Jersey | year = 1996 | isbn = 9781856494205 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/worldofwidows0000owen }}</ref> The sacrifice of widows (such as [[Sati (practice)|sati]]) has been prevalent historically in various cultures (especially in [[India]]). Although sati in India is today an almost defunct practice, isolated incidents have occurred in recent years, such as the 1987 sati of [[Roop Kanwar]], as well as several incidents in rural areas in 2002,<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/2178102.stm | work=[[BBC News]] | title=Arrests in Indian ritual burning | date=7 August 2002 | access-date = 25 January 2014}}</ref> and 2006.<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/5366506.stm | work=[[BBC News]] | title=Sons arrested in sati death probe | date=21 September 2006 | access-date = 25 January 2014}}</ref> Those likely to be accused and killed as [[Modern witch-hunts|witche]]s are often widows.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/asia/21725040-law-criminalising-sorcery-was-only-repealed-2013-gruesome-fate-witches-papua-new|title=The gruesome fate of \"witches\" in Papua New Guinea|newspaper=economist.com |date=13 July 2017 |accessdate=23 July 2017}}</ref> In parts of Africa, such as in Kenya, widows are viewed as impure and need to be 'cleansed'. This often requires having sex with someone. Those refusing to be cleansed risk getting beaten by superstitious villagers, who may also harm the woman's children. It is argued that this notion arose from the idea that if a husband dies, the woman may have performed witchcraft against him.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2018-10-23/these-kenyan-widows-are-fighting-against-sexual-cleansing|title=These Kenyan widows are fighting against sexual 'cleansing'|publisher=pri.org|accessdate=7 November 2018|date=23 October 2018}}</ref> Widow inheritance (also known as bride inheritance) is a cultural and social practice whereby a widow is required to marry a male relative of her late husband, often his brother.\n\n===Accusations of witchcraft===\n[[File:Schiltach Flugblatt.JPG|thumb|left|upright|A 1533 account of the execution of a witch charged with burning the [[Germany|German]] town of [[Schiltach]] in 1531]]\n[[Witch trials in the early modern period]] (between the 15th and 18th centuries) were common in Europe and in the European colonies in North America. Today, there remain regions of the world (such as parts of [[Sub-Saharan Africa]], rural [[North India]], and [[Papua New Guinea]]) where belief in [[witchcraft]] is held by many people, and women accused of being witches are subjected to serious violence.<ref>''Citations'':\n* {{cite journal | last = Diwan | first = Mohammed A. | title = Conflict between state legal norms and norms underlying popular beliefs: witchcraft in Africa as a case study | journal = [[Duke Journal of Comparative & International Law]] | volume = 14 | issue = 2 | pages = 351&ndash;388 | publisher = [[Duke University School of Law|Duke Law School]] | date = Summer 2004 | url = https://scholarship.law.duke.edu/djcil/vol14/iss2/5/ | ref = harv }} [https://scholarship.law.duke.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=&httpsredir=1&article=1129&context=djcil#H2N1 Pdf.]\n* {{cite book |last=Ally |first=Yaseen |title=Witch hunts in modern South Africa: an under-represented facet of gender-based violence (fact sheet) |url=http://www.mrc.ac.za/crime/witchhunts.pdf |publisher=[[South African Medical Research Council]] |date=June 2009 |accessdate=12 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425074549/http://www.mrc.ac.za/crime/witchhunts.pdf |archive-date=25 April 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}\n*{{cite news | last=Staff writer | title=Woman burned alive for 'sorcery' in Papua New Guinea | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-21363894 | work=[[BBC News]] | date=7 February 2013 | access-date=12 December 2013 }}</ref> In addition, there are also countries that have criminal legislation against the practice of witchcraft. In [[Saudi Arabia]], witchcraft remains a crime [[punishable by death]].<ref>{{cite web | last = Staff writer |url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/news/saudi-arabia-beheading-sorcery-shocking-2011-12-12 |title=Saudi Arabia: Beheading for 'sorcery' shocking | website = amnesty.org |publisher=[[Amnesty International]] |date=12 December 2011 |accessdate=12 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n===State violence===\n\n====War rape and sexual slavery during military conflict====\n[[File:Paul Jamin - Le Brenn et sa part de butin 1893.jpg|thumb|200 px|''[[Brennus (4th century BC)|Brennus]] and His Share of the Spoils'', by [[Paul Jamin]], 1893.]]\n[[File:Chinese girl from one of the Japanese Army's 'comfort battalions'.jpg|thumb|200 px|[[Rangoon]], [[Myanmar|Burma]]. 8 August 1945. A young [[Chinese diaspora|ethnic Chinese]] woman from one of the [[Imperial Japanese Army]]'s \"comfort battalions\" is interviewed by an [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] officer.]]\n\nMilitarism produces special environments that allow for increased violence against women. [[War rapes]] have accompanied warfare in virtually every known historical era.<ref>{{cite book | last = Washington | first = Harold C. | chapter = 'Lest he die in battle and another man take her': violence and the construction of gender in the laws of Deuteronomy 20-22 | chapter-url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2rZnXQwPX8gC&pg=PA203 | editor-last1 = Matthews | editor-first1 = Victor H. | editor-last2 = Levinson | editor-first2 = Bernard M. | editor-last3 = Frymer-Kensky | editor-first3 = Tikva  | title = Gender and law in the Hebrew Bible and the ancient Near East | page = 203 | publisher = T & T Clark | location = London New York | year = 2004 | isbn = 9780567080981 }}</ref> Rape in the course of war is mentioned multiple times in the Bible: \"For I will gather all the nations against Jerusalem to battle, and the city shall be taken and the houses plundered and the women raped...\" {{bibleref|Zechariah|14:2|ESV}} \"Their little children will be dashed to death before their eyes. Their homes will be sacked, and their wives will be raped.\"{{bibleref|Isaiah|13:16|NLT}}\n\nWar rapes are rapes committed by soldiers, other combatants or civilians during armed conflict or war, or during military occupation, distinguished from sexual assaults and rape committed amongst troops in military service. It also covers the situation where women are forced into prostitution or [[sexual slavery]] by an occupying power. During World War II the Japanese military established brothels filled with \"[[comfort women]]\", girls and women who were forced into sexual slavery for soldiers, exploiting women for the purpose of creating access and entitlement for men.<ref>{{cite news|last=Benedict |first=Helen |url=http://www.inthesetimes.com/article/3848/ |title=Why soldiers rape |work=[[In These Times]] |date=14 August 2008 | access-date = 10 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Morris-Suzuki | first = Tessa | title = Japan's 'Comfort Women': It's time for the truth (in the ordinary, everyday sense of the word) | journal = Japan Focus (The Asia-Pacific Journal) | volume = 5 | issue = 3 | date = 1 March 2007 | url = http://www.japanfocus.org/-Tessa-Morris_Suzuki/2373  |accessdate=4 August 2011 | ref = harv }}</ref>\n \nAnother example of violence against women incited by militarism during war took place in the [[Kaunas Ghetto|Kovno Ghetto]]. Jewish male prisoners had access to (and used) Jewish women forced into camp brothels by the Nazis, who also used them.<ref>{{cite book | last = Dworkin | first = Andrea | author-link = Andrea Dworkin | chapter = Palestinians/prostituted women | chapterurl = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Pew3_DPVfnYC&pg=PA316 | editor-last = Dworkin | editor-first = Andrea | editor-link = Andrea Dworkin | title = Scapegoat: the Jews, Israel, and women's liberation | page = 316 | publisher = Free Press | location = New York | year = 2000 | isbn = 9780684836126 }}</ref>\n\nRape was committed during the [[Bangladesh Liberation War]] by members of the [[Pakistan Armed Forces|Pakistani military]] and the [[militia]]s that supported them. Over a period of nine months, hundreds of thousands of women were raped. [[Susan Brownmiller]], in her report on the [[1971 Bangladesh atrocities|atrocities]], said that girls from the age of eight to grandmothers of seventy-five suffered attacks. {{See also|Rape during the Bangladesh Liberation War}}\n\nRape used as a weapon of war was practiced during the [[Bosnian War]] where rape was used as a highly systematized instrument of war by Serb armed forces predominantly targeting women and girls of the Bosniak ethnic group for physical and moral destruction. Estimates of the number of women raped during the war range from 50,000 to 60,000; as of 2010 only 12 cases have been prosecuted.<ref>{{cite book | last = UNSC | author-link = United Nations Security Council | title = Report of the International Tribunal for the Prosecution of Persons Responsible for Serious Violations of International Humanitarian Law Committed in the Territory of the Former Yugoslavia Since 1991 | id = A/52/375{{spaces|2}}S/1997/729 | publisher = [[United Nations Security Council]] |url=http://www.icty.org/x/file/About/Reports%20and%20Publications/AnnualReports/annual_report_1997_en.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120804004034/http://www.icty.org/x/file/About/Reports%20and%20Publications/AnnualReports/annual_report_1997_en.pdf |archivedate=4 August 2012 | date = 18 September 1997 | access-date = 10 November 2012}}</ref> {{See also|Rape during the Bosnian War}}\n\nThe 1998 [[International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda]] recognized rape as a war crime. Presiding judge [[Navanethem Pillay]] said in a statement after the verdict: \"From time immemorial, rape has been regarded as spoils of war. Now it will be considered a war crime. We want to send out a strong message that rape is no longer a trophy of war.\"<ref>{{cite book| last = Pillay | first = Navanethem | author-link = Navi Pillay |title=Honorary doctorate acceptance address by Navanethem Pillay, Rhodes University |url=http://www.ru.ac.za/academic/graduation/addresses_and_citations/2005/Judge_Pillay_citation.doc |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060926231120/http://www.ru.ac.za/academic/graduation/addresses_and_citations/2005/Judge_Pillay_citation.doc |archivedate=26 September 2006 |df=dmy |date = 2005 |accessdate=27 February 2008}}</ref> {{See also|Rwandan Genocide}}\n\nIn 2006, five [[United States Army|U.S. troops]] from a six-man unit [[gang rape]]d and killed a 14-year-old girl in a village near the town of [[Mahmoudiyah, Iraq|Al-Mahmudiyah]], Iraq. After the rape the girl was shot in her head and the lower part of her body, from her stomach down to her feet, was set on fire.<ref>{{cite news | last = Media pool reports |url=http://www.cnn.com/2006/WORLD/meast/08/08/iraq.mahmoudiya/index.html |title=Soldier: 'Death walk' drives troops 'nuts' | work =[[CNN]] | date = 9 August 2006 |accessdate=6 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = US ex-soldier guilty of Iraq rape | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/8039257.stm | work = [[BBC News]] |date=7 May 2009 |accessdate= 10 November 2012}}</ref> {{See also|Mahmudiyah killings}}\n\nA 1995 study of female war veterans found that 90 percent had been sexually harassed. A 2003 survey found that 30 percent of female vets said they were raped in the military and a 2004 study of veterans who were seeking help for post-traumatic stress disorder found that 71 percent of the women said they were sexually assaulted or raped while serving.<ref>{{cite news | last = Benedict | first = Helen | title = The plight of women soldiers |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=103844570 |work=The Nation |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=6 May 2009 |accessdate= 10 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nAccording to one report, the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]]'s capture of Iraqi cities in June 2014 was accompanied by an upsurge in crimes against women, including kidnap and rape.<ref>''Articles'':\n* {{cite news | last1 = Radwan | first1 = Zahra | last2 = Blumenfeld | first2 = Zoe|title=OP-ED: Surging violence against women in Iraq|url=http://www.ipsnews.net/2014/06/op-ed-surging-violence-against-women-in-iraq/|work=[[Inter Press Service]]|date=27 June 2014|accessdate=5 July 2014}}\n* {{cite news|last1=Winterton|first1=Clare|title=Why we must act when women in Iraq document rape |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/clare-winterton/why-we-must-act_b_5528162.html|date=25 June 2014|work=[[HuffPost]] |accessdate=10 July 2014}}\n* {{cite news | last = Ali | first = Esraa Mohamed | title = Kuwaiti media: \"Daash\" demands the people of Mosul to provide unmarried to \"Jihad marriage\"  | url = https://translate.google.co.uk/translate?hl=en&sl=ar&u=http://www.almasryalyoum.com/news/details/466402&prev=search | work = [[Al-Masry Al-Youm|The Egyptian Today]] [Al-Masry Al-Youm] | date = 18 June 2014 |accessdate=10 July 2014}}\n:* ''Original Arabic version'': {{cite news|last=\u0625\u0633\u0631\u0627\u0621 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0639\u0644\u064a|title=\u0625\u0639\u0644\u0627\u0645\u064a \u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a\u064a: \"\u062f\u0627\u0639\u0634\" \u064a\u0637\u0627\u0644\u0628 \u0623\u0647\u0627\u0644\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0648\u0635\u0644 \u0628\u062a\u0642\u062f\u064a\u0645 \u063a\u064a\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062a\u0632\u0648\u062c\u0627\u062a \u0644\u0640\"\u062c\u0647\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0643\u0627\u062d|url=http://www.almasryalyoum.com/news/details/466402|work=\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0635\u0631\u06cc \u0627\u0644\u06cc\u0648\u0645|accessdate=10 July 2014}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' reported that ISIL's extremist agenda extended to women's bodies and that women living under their control were being captured and raped.<ref>{{cite news|last=Susskind|first=Yifat|title=Under Isis, Iraqi women again face an old nightmare: violence and repression|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/poverty-matters/2014/jul/03/isis-iraqi-women-rape-violence-repression|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=3 July 2014|accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> Fighters are told that they are free to have sex and rape non-Muslim captive women.<ref>{{cite news|language=sv|title=Det jag har bevittnat i al-Raqqa kommer alltid f\u00f6rf\u00f6lja mig|url=http://www.dn.se/nyheter/varlden/det-jag-har-bevittnat-i-al-raqqa-kommer-alltid-forfolja-mig/|accessdate=25 September 2014|work=[[Dagens Nyheter]]|date=23 September 2014}}</ref> Yazidi girls in Iraq allegedly [[War rape|raped]] by ISIL fighters committed [[suicide]] by jumping to their death from [[Mount Sinjar]], as described in a witness statement.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ahmed|first=Havidar|title=The Yezidi Exodus, Girls Raped by ISIS Jump to their Death on Mount Shingal|date=14 August 2014|url=http://rudaw.net/english/kurdistan/140820142|publisher=[[Rudaw Media Network]]|accessdate=26 August 2014}}</ref> Haleh Esfandiari from the [[Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars]] has highlighted the abuse of local women by ISIL militants after they have captured an area. \"They usually take the older women to a makeshift slave market and try to sell them. The younger girls ... are raped or married off to fighters\", she said, adding, \"It's based on temporary marriages, and once these fighters have had sex with these young girls, they just pass them on to other fighters.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brekke|first1=Kira|title=ISIS is attacking women, and nobody is talking about it|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/09/08/isis-attacks-on-women_n_5775106.html?cps=gravity |work=[[HuffPost]] |date=8 September 2014 |accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref> Describing the [[Yazidi]] women captured by ISIS, [[Nazand Begikhani]] said \"[t]hese women have been treated like cattle... They have been subjected to physical and sexual violence, including systematic rape and sex slavery. They've been exposed in markets in Mosul and in Raqqa, Syria, carrying price tags.\"<ref>{{cite news | last = Watson | first = Ivan | title = 'Treated like cattle': Yazidi women sold, raped, enslaved by ISIS | url = http://www.cnn.com/2014/10/30/world/meast/isis-female-slaves/ | work = [[CNN]] | date = 30 October 2014 | access-date =23 February 2015 }}</ref> In December 2014 the [[Ministry of Human Rights (Iraq)|Iraqi Ministry of Human Rights]] announced that the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] had killed over 150 women and girls in [[Fallujah]] who refused to participate in [[sexual jihad]].<ref>{{cite news|last = NOW News | author-link = NOW News|title=ISIS just executed more than 150 women in Fallujah|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/isis-just-executed-more-than-150-women-in-fallujah-2014-12|work=[[Business Insider]]|date= 17 December 2014 | access-date =23 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Forced sterilization and forced abortion====\n{{See|Eugenics in the United States|Violence against women in the United States#Forced pregnancy and sterilization}}\n[[File:SOU 1929 14 Bet\u00e4nkande med f\u00f6rslag till steriliseringslag s 57 Laughlin.jpg|200px|thumb|right|A map from a 1929 Swedish royal commission report displays the U.S. states that had implemented sterilization legislation by then]]\n[[Forced sterilization]] and [[forced abortion]] are forms of gender-based violence.<ref>{{cite web | last = EIGE | author-link = European Institute for Gender Equality |title=What is gender-based violence? |url=http://eige.europa.eu/content/what-is-gender-based-violence | website = eige.europa.eu |publisher=[[European Institute for Gender Equality]] |date=24 August 2015 | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref> Forced sterilization has occurred throughout much of the world, both at the hands of the state and from intimate partners. Studies show forced sterilizations often target socially and politically disadvantaged groups such as racial and ethnic minorities, the poor, and indigenous populations.<ref name=\"Volscho, Thomas W 2010\">{{cite journal | last = Volscho | first = Thomas W. | title = Sterilization racism and pan-ethnic disparities of the past decade: the continued encroachment on reproductive rights | journal = [[W\u00ed\u010dazo \u0160a Review]] | volume = 25 | issue = 1 | pages = 17&ndash;31 | publisher = [[Johns Hopkins University Press]] | jstor = 40891307 | date = Spring 2010 | ref = harv | doi=10.1353/wic.0.0053}}</ref> According to the Convention on the Elimination of all forms of Discrimination Against Women, all \"women are guaranteed the right to decide freely and responsibly on the number of and spacing of their children, and to have access to information, education, and means to enable them to exercise these rights.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination against Women |url=http://www.ohchr.org/EN/ProfessionalInterest/Pages/CEDAW.aspx |publisher = [[United Nations General Assembly]] |accessdate=9 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, much of the history of forced sterilization is connected to the legacy of eugenics and [[racism in the United States]].<ref name=\"Volscho, Thomas W 2010\" /> Many doctors thought that they were doing the country a service by sterilizing poor, disabled, and/or minority women, whom they considered a drain on the system.<ref name=\"Volscho, Thomas W 2010\"/><ref name=\"North Carolina Sterilization Program 2011\">{{cite news | last1 = Kessel | first1 = Michelle | last2 = Jessica | first2 = Hopper | title = Victims speak out about North Carolina sterilization program, which targeted women, young girls and Blacks | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20111108182852/http://rockcenter.msnbc.msn.com/_news/2011/11/07/8640744-victims-speak-out-about-north-carolina-sterilization-program-which-targeted-women-young-girls-and-blacks | archive-date = 8 November 2011 | url = http://rockcenter.msnbc.msn.com/_news/2011/11/07/8640744-victims-speak-out-about-north-carolina-sterilization-program-which-targeted-women-young-girls-and-blacks | work =[[Rock Center with Brian Williams]] | publisher = [[NBC News]] | date = 7 November 2011 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref> [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]], [[Mexican Americans|Mexican American]], [[African Americans|African American]] and [[Puerto Rican-American]] women were coerced into sterilization programs, with Native Americans and African Americans especially being targeted.<ref name=\"Volscho, Thomas W 2010\" /> Records have shown that Native American girls as young as eleven years-old had [[hysterectomy]] operations performed.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vincenti Carpio|first=Myla|date=2004|title=The Lost Generation: American Indian Women and Sterilization Abuse|url=|journal=[[Social Justice (journal)|Social Justice]]|volume=31|issue=4|pages=40\u201353|via=}}</ref>\n\nIn Europe, there have been a number of lawsuits and accusations towards the [[Czech Republic]] and [[Slovakia]] of sterilizing Roma women without adequate information and waiting period.<ref>{{Cite book|last=ERRC|title=Coercive and cruel \u2013 a report by the European Roma Rights Centre: Sterilisation and its consequences for Romani women in the Czech Republic (1966\u20132016) |url=http://www.errc.org/cms/upload/file/coercive-and-cruel-28-november-2016.pdf|publisher=European Roma Right Centre| location = Budapest, Hungary|date=November 2016|isbn = 9789638991638}}</ref> In response, both nations have instituted a mandatory seven-day waiting period and written consent. Slovakia has been condemned on the issue of forced sterilization of Roma women several times by the [[European Court for Human Rights]] (see [[V. C. vs. Slovakia]], [[N. B. vs. Slovakia]] and [[I.G. and Others vs. Slovakia]]).\n\nIn [[Peru]], in 1995, [[Alberto Fujimori]] launched a family planning initiative that especially targeted poor and indigenous women. In total, over 215,000 women were sterilized, with over 200,000 believed to have been coerced.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Boesten | first = Jelke | title = Free choice or poverty alleviation? Population politics in Peru under Alberto Fujimori | journal = European Review of Latin American and Caribbean Studies  | volume = 82 | issue = 82 | pages = 3&ndash;20 | publisher = Centre for Latin American Research and Documentation | doi = 10.18352/erlacs.9637 | date = 2007 | ref = harv }}</ref> In 2002, Health Minister [[Fernando carbone|Fernando Carbone]] admitted that the government gave misleading information, offered food incentives, and threatened to fine parents if they had additional children. The procedures have also been found to have been negligent, with less than half using proper anesthetic.<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Mass sterilisation scandal shocks Peru | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/2148793.stm | work = [[BBC News]] | date = 24 July 2002 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn China, the [[one child policy]] included forced abortions and forced sterilization.<ref>''Citations'':\n\n* {{cite news|url=http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/regions/asia-pacific/china/130409/china-mother-dies-after-forced-sterilization-one-child-policy|title=China: Mother of 2 dies after forced sterilization|last=Jackson|first=Allison|date=9 April 2013|work=[[GlobalPost]]|access-date=18 November 2013}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/news-and-updates/thousands-risk-forced-sterilization-china-2010-04-22|title=Thousands at risk of forced sterilization in China|last=AI|author-link=Amnesty International|date=22 April 2010|publisher=[[Amnesty International]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130529125647/https://www.amnesty.org/en/news-and-updates/thousands-risk-forced-sterilization-china-2010-04-22|archive-date=29 May 2013|access-date=18 November 2013}}\n* {{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-18435126|title=China forced abortion photo sparks outrage|last=Staff writer|date=14 June 2012|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=18 November 2013}}\n* {{cite book|url=http://www.hrnk.org/uploads/pdfs/HRNK_HiddenGulag2_Web_5-18.pdf|title=The Hidden Gulag|last=Hawk|first=David|date=2012|publisher=The Committee for Human Rights in North Korea|edition=2nd|location=Washington DC|oclc=793983613|access-date=18 November 2013}}</ref> Forced sterilization is also practiced in Uzbekistan.<ref>{{cite news | last = Antelava | first = Natalia | title=Uzbekistan's policy of secretly sterilising women| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-17612550 | work=[[BBC World Service]] | date=12 April 2012| access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media | people = Natalia Antelava (reporter) and Wesley Stephenson (producer) | access-date = 18 November 2013 |date=16 April 2012 | title= Forced sterilisation in Uzbekistan | medium= Audio | minutes = 20:30 | series = [[Crossing Continents]] | publisher= [[BBC Radio 4]] | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01fjx63}}</ref>\n\n====Violence by the police and other authority figures====\n[[File:Taliban beating woman in public RAWA.jpg|right|thumb|250px|A member of the Taliban's [[Mutaween#Other groups|religious police]] beating an Afghan woman in [[Kabul]] on 26 August 2001.]]\nWhen police officers misuse their power as agents of the state to physically and [[sexual harassment|sexually harass]] and assault victims, the survivors, including women, feel much less able to report the violence.<ref>{{Cite episode\n| title = Covering 'Tainted Justice' and winning a Pulitzer | url = https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=126386819 | series = Fresh Air | serieslink = Fresh Air | credits = Barbara Laker and Wendy Ruderman, hosted by [[Terry Gross]] | network = NPR | station = [[WHYY-FM|WHYY]]| location = Philadelphia | airdate = 3 May 2010 | transcripturl= }}</ref>  It is standard procedure for police to force entry into the victim's home even after the victim's numerous requests for them to go away.<ref>{{cite book | last = Suk | first = Jeannie | author-link = Jeannie Suk | title = At home in the law: how the domestic violence revolution is transforming privacy | publisher = Yale University Press | location = New Haven | year = 2009 | url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=UML8Ke4IpTEC | isbn = 9780300172621 }}</ref> Government agencies often disregard the victim's right to [[Freedom of association#Intimate association|freedom of association]] with their perpetrator.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Hanna | first = Cheryl | title = No right to choose: mandated victim participation in domestic violence prosecutions | journal = [[Harvard Law Review]] | volume = 109 | issue = 8 | pages = 1849&ndash;1910 | publisher = The Harvard Law Review Association | doi = 10.2307/1342079 | jstor = 1342079 | ssrn = 1276830 | date = June 1996 | ref = harv }}</ref> [[Women's shelter|Shelter]] workers are often reduced themselves to contributing to violence against women by exploiting their [[vulnerability]] in exchange for a paying job.<ref>{{cite book | last = Koyama | first = Emi | chapter = Disloyal to feminism: Abuse of survivors within the domestic violence shelter system | chapterurl = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lZmFjwEACAAJ | editor-last = INCITE! Women of Colour Against Violence | title = Color of violence: the INCITE! anthology | publisher = Duke University Press | location = Durham | year = 2016 | isbn = 9780822373445 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/colorofviolencei00unse }}</ref>\n\nHuman rights violations perpetrated by police and military personnel in many countries are correlated with decreased access to public health services and increased practices of risky behavior among members of vulnerable groups, such as women and female sex workers.<ref name=\"Beletsky L, Martinex G, Gaines T, et al. 2012 403\u2013410\">{{cite journal | last1 = Beletsky | first1 = Leo |display-authors=etal | title = Mexico's northern border conflict: collateral damage to health and human rights of vulnerable groups | journal = [[Pan American Journal of Public Health]] | volume = 31 | issue = 5 | pages = 403&ndash;410 | publisher = [[Pan American Health Organization]] | doi = 10.1590/s1020-49892012000500008 | pmc = 3660986 | pmid = 22767041 | date = May 2012 | ref = harv }}</ref> These practices are especially widespread in settings with a weak rule of law and low levels of police and military management and professionalism. Police abuse in this context has been linked to a wide range of risky behaviors and health outcomes, including post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD), and substance abuse.<ref name=\"Beletsky L, Martinex G, Gaines T, et al. 2012 403\u2013410\"/><ref>''Other citations'':   \n* {{cite journal | last1 = Strathdee | first1 = Steffanie A. |display-authors=etal | title = Social and structural factors associated with HIV infection among female sex workers who inject drugs in the Mexico-US border region | journal = [[PLOS One]] | volume = 6 | issue = 4 |page=e19048 | publisher = [[PLOS]] | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0019048 |pmc=3081836 |pmid=21541349 | date = 25 April 2011 | ref = harv | bibcode = 2011PLoSO...619048S }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Ramos | first1 = Rebeca |display-authors=etal | title = A tale of two cities: social and environmental influences shaping risk factors and protective behaviors in two Mexico-US border cities | journal = [[Health & Place]] | volume = 15 | issue = 4 | pages = 999&ndash;1005 | publisher = [[Elsevier]] | doi = 10.1016/j.healthplace.2009.04.004 | pmid = 19464228 | pmc = 2735581 | date = December 2009 | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Pollini | first1 = Robin A. |display-authors=etal | title = Syringe possession arrests are associated with receptive syringe sharing in two Mexico-US border cities | journal = [[Addiction (journal)|Addiction]] | volume = 103 | issue = 1 | pages = 101&ndash;108 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1360-0443.2007.02051.x | pmid = 18028520 | pmc = 2214830 | date = January 2008 | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Pollini | first1 = Robin A. |display-authors=etal | title = High prevalence of abscesses and self-treatment among injection drug users in Tijuana, Mexico | journal = [[International Journal of Infectious Diseases]] | volume = 14 | issue = S3 | pages = e117&ndash;e122 | publisher = [[Elsevier]] | doi = 10.1016/j.ijid.2010.02.2238 | pmid = 20381396 | pmc = 2917477 | date = September 2010 | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Strathdee | first1 = Steffanie A. |display-authors=etal | title = Individual, social, and environmental influences associated with HIV infection among injection drug users in Tijuana, Mexico | journal = [[Journal of Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndromes]] | volume = 47 | issue = 3 | pages = 369&ndash;376 | publisher = [[Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|LWW]] | doi = 10.1097/QAI.0b013e318160d5ae |pmc=2752692 |pmid=18176320 | date = 1 March 2008 | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite book | last1 = Raj | first1 = Anita | last2 = Gupta | first2 = Jhumka  | last3 = Silverman | first3 = Jay G. | chapter = Women, migration, conflict and risk for HIV | chapter-url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JhxwNjWzB6gC&pg=PA107 | editor-last1 = Forbes Martin | editor-first1 = Susan | editor-last2 = Tirman | editor-first2 = John | title = Women, migration, and conflict: breaking a deadly cycle | page = 107 | publisher = Springer | location = Dordrecht | year = 2009 | isbn = 9789048128242 }}</ref> Extortion of sexual services and police sexual abuse have been linked to a decrease in condom use and an elevated risk of STI and HIV infections among vulnerable groups.<ref name=\"Beletsky L, Martinex G, Gaines T, et al. 2012 403\u2013410\"/><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Blankenship | first1 = Kim M. | last2 = Koester | first2 = Stephen | title = Criminal law, policing policy, and HIV risk in female street sex workers and injection drug users | journal = [[The Journal of Law, Medicine & Ethics]] | volume = 30 | issue = 4 | pages = 548&ndash;559 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1748-720X.2002.tb00425.x | pmid = 12561263 | date = December 2002 | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\n====Stoning and flogging====\n[[Stoning]], or lapidation, refers to a form of [[capital punishment]] whereby an organized group throws stones at an individual until the person dies. Stoning is a punishment that is included in the laws of several countries, including Iran, Saudi Arabia, Sudan, Pakistan, Yemen, the United Arab Emirates, and some states in Nigeria, as punishment for [[adultery]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Batha | first = Emma | title = FACTBOX: Stoning - where does it happen? | work = [[Thomson Reuters Foundation News]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160125051613/http://news.trust.org//item/20130927165059-w9g0i | archive-date = 25 January 2016 | url = http://news.trust.org//item/20130927165059-w9g0i | publisher = [[Thomson Reuters Foundation]] | date = 29 September 2013 | access-date = 19 November 2013}}</ref> [[Flogging]] or flagellation is the act of methodically beating or whipping the human body. It is a judicial punishment in various countries for specific crimes, including [[sex outside marriage]]. These punishments employed for sexual relations outside marriage, apart from constituting a form of violence in themselves, can also deter victims of [[sexual violence]] from reporting the crime, because the victims may themselves be punished (if they cannot prove their case, if they are deemed to have been in the company of an unrelated male, or if they were unmarried and not virgins at the time of the rape).<ref>{{cite news | last = Lang | first = Olivia | title=Maldives girl to get 100 lashes for pre-marital sex | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-21595814 | work=[[BBC News]] | date=26 February 2013 | access-date = 19 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jamali |first=Hasan |url=http://www.today.com/id/15836746/ns/today-today_news/t/rape-case-calls-saudi-legal-system-question/#.UolafidedO6 |title=Rape case brings Saudi laws into focus |work=[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]] |publisher=[[NBC]] |accessdate=19 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6JdMstMvl?url=http://www.today.com/id/15836746/ns/today-today_news/t/rape-case-calls-saudi-legal-system-question/ |archivedate=14 September 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Female genital mutilation===\n{{Main|Female genital mutilation}}\n[[File:Fgm map.gif|thumb|250px|Map showing the prevalence of FGM in Africa]]\n[[File:FGM road sign, Bakau, Gambia, 2005.jpg|thumb|250 px|Anti-[[FGM]] road sign, Bakau, Gambia, 2005]]\nFemale genital mutilation (FGM) is defined by the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) as \"all procedures that involve partial or total removal of the external female genitalia, or other injury to the female genital organs for non-medical reasons\".<ref name=\"WHO FGM\">{{cite book | last = WHO | author-link = World Health Organization |title=Female genital mutilation (factsheet) |url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs241/en/ |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] |date= June 2000 |accessdate=18 November 2013}}</ref> According to a 2013 UNICEF report, 125 million women and girls in Africa and the Middle East have experienced FGM.<ref name=\"unicef.org\">{{cite book | last = UNICEF | author-link = UNICEF | title = Female Genital Mutilation/Cutting: A statistical overview and exploration of the dynamics of change | url = http://www.unicef.org/media/files/FGCM_Lo_res.pdf | publisher = [[UNICEF]] | date = 22 July 2013 | accessdate = 18 November 2013}}</ref> The WHO states: \"The procedure has no health benefits for girls and women\" and \"Procedures can cause severe bleeding and problems urinating, and later cysts, infections, infertility as well as complications in childbirth increased risk of newborn deaths\" and \"FGM is recognized internationally as a violation of the human rights of girls and women. It reflects deep-rooted inequality between the sexes, and constitutes an extreme form of discrimination against women.\"<ref name=\"WHO FGM\"/> According to a UNICEF report, the top rates for FGM are in Somalia (with 98 percent of women affected), Guinea (96 percent), Djibouti (93 percent), Egypt (91 percent), Eritrea (89 percent), Mali (89 percent), Sierra Leone (88 percent), Sudan (88 percent), Gambia (76 percent), Burkina Faso (76 percent), Ethiopia (74 percent), Mauritania (69 percent), Liberia (66 percent), and Guinea-Bissau (50 percent).<ref name=\"unicef.org\"/>\n\nAccording to some local practitioners, it is believed that FGM is linked to cultural rites and customs. It is considered to be a traditional practice that continues to take place in different communities/countries of Africa and Middle East, including in places where it is banned by national legislation. FGM is defined as a \"harmful traditional practice\"<ref name=\"Shell-Duncan\">{{cite journal | last = Shell-Duncan | first = Bettina | title = From health to human rights: female genital cutting and the politics of intervention | journal = [[American Anthropologist]] | volume = 110 | issue = 2 | pages = 225&ndash;236 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1548-1433.2008.00028.x | date = June 2008 | ref = harv }}</ref> in accordance to the Inter-African Committee. \n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:UNFPA-UNICEF Joint Programme On FGM 2012.png|thumbnail|alt=map|300 px|right|Prevalence of FGM among African women aged 15-49. For more detailed maps, see [http://www.unfpa.org/webdav/site/global/shared/documents/publications/2013/UNICEF-UNFPA%20Joint%20Programme%20AR_final_v14.pdf] UNFPA-UNICEF Joint Programme on FGM, 2012]] -->\nDue to globalization and immigration, FGM is spreading beyond the borders of Africa and Middle East, to countries such as Australia, Belgium, Canada, France, New Zealand, the U.S., and UK.<ref>{{cite book | last = Nussbaum | first = Martha | author-link = Martha Nussbaum | chapter = Judging other cultures: the case of genital mutilation | chapter-url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=43U8DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA120 | editor-last = Nussbaum | editor-first = Martha | editor-link = Martha Nussbaum | title = Sex & social justice | pages = [https://archive.org/details/sexsocialjustice00nuss/page/120 120\u2013121] | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = New York | year = 1999 | isbn = 978-0195110326 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/sexsocialjustice00nuss/page/120 }}</ref>\n\nAlthough FGM is today associated with developing countries, this practice was common until the 1970s in parts of the Western world, too. FGM was considered a standard medical procedure in the United States for most of the 19th and 20th centuries.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite journal|last=Webber|first=Sara|last2=Schonfeld|first2=Toby L.|date=2003-06-27|title=Cutting History, Cutting Culture: Female Circumcision in the United States|url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/44151|journal=The American Journal of Bioethics|volume=3|issue=2|pages=65\u201366|issn=1536-0075|doi=10.1162/152651603766436324|pmid=12859826}}</ref> Physicians performed surgeries of varying invasiveness to treat a number of diagnoses, including [[hysteria]], [[Depression (mood)|depression]], [[nymphomania]], and [[frigidity]]. The medicalization of FGM in the United States allowed these practices to continue until the second part of the 20th century, with some procedures covered by [[Blue Cross Blue Shield Association|Blue Cross Blue Shield Insurance]] until 1977.<ref name=\":33\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=LViJROLfEGQC&pg=PA106&lpg=PA106&dq=Watson,+M.+(2005).+Female+circumcision+from+Africa+to+the+Americas:+Slavery+to+the+present.+The+Social+Sciences+Journal,+42,+421-437.#v=onepage&q=Watson,%20M.%20(2005).%20Female%20circumcision%20from%20Africa%20to%20the%20Americas:%20Slavery%20to%20the%20present.%20The%20Social%20Sciences%20Journal,%2042,%20421-437.&f=false|title=Women in Developing Countries: A Reference Handbook|last=Kinnear|first=Karen L.|date=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9781598844252|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":20\" />\n\nThe [[Convention on preventing and combating violence against women and domestic violence|Istanbul Convention]] prohibits female genital mutilation (Article 38).<ref>{{cite book | title = Council of Europe Convention on preventing and combating violence against women and domestic violence | url = https://rm.coe.int/168046031c | date = 12 April 2011 | access-date = 8 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2016, in [[Africa]], FGM has been legally banned in Benin, Burkina Faso, Central African Republic, Chad, C\u00f4te d'Ivoire, Djibouti, Egypt, Eritrea, Ethiopia, Gambia, Ghana, Guinea, Guinea Bissau, Kenya, Mauritania, Niger, Nigeria, Senegal, South Africa, Tanzania, Togo, Uganda, and Zambia.<ref>''Citations'':\n* {{cite news | last = Lyons | first = Kate | title = The Gambia bans female genital mutilation | url = https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/nov/24/the-gambia-bans-female-genital-mutilation | work = [[The Guardian]] | date = 24 November 2015 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}\n* {{cite news | last = Richards | first = Kimberly | title = History has been made: female genital mutilation banned in Nigeria | url = http://aplus.com/a/nigeria-bans-genital-mutilation | work = [[A Plus (aplus.com)|A Plus]] | date = 3 June 2015 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}\n* {{cite book | last = UNFPA | author-link = UNFPA | title = Female genital mutilation (FGM) frequently asked questions | url = http://www.unfpa.org/resources/female-genital-mutilation-fgm-frequently-asked-questions | publisher = [[United Nations Population Fund]] | date = December 2015 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nThere exist several approaches that were set up by international health organizations and civil societies (for example, [[Tostan]]) aimed at eliminating the practice of FGM in implemented countries: \n# FGM as a Health issue (also known as health risks approach)\n# FGM as a Human Rights issue (also known as Human Rights-based approach)\n\nSome scholars suggests that, when dealing with FGM, it is necessary to take lessons from history, particularly 19th-century campaign against [[foot-binding]] in China,<ref name=\"Kwame Appiah\">{{cite news | last = Appiah | first = Kwame Anthony | author-link = Kwame Anthony Appiah | title = The art of social change | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/24/magazine/24FOB-Footbinding-t.html?pagewanted=all |work = [[The New York Times]] |date=22 October 2010 |accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> which was successful.\n\n===Breast ironing===\n{{Main|Breast ironing}}\nBreast ironing (also known as \"breast flattening\") is the practice of pounding and massaging the [[breasts]] of a [[puberty|pubescent girl]], using hard or heated objects, in an attempt to try to make them stop developing or disappear.<ref name=\"west-info.eu\">{{cite book | last = Tapscott | first = Rebecca |title=Understanding breast \"ironing\": a study of the methods, motivations, and outcomes of breast flattening practices in Cameroon | url = http://www.west-info.eu/files/Feinstein-International-Center-Understanding-breast-ironing-a-study-of-the-methods-motivations-and-outcomes-of-breast-flattening-practices-in-Cameroon-20121.pdf | publisher= [[Feinstein International Center]] | date = 14 May 2012 | access-date = 25 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC Cameroon Breast Ironing\">{{cite news | last = Sa'ah | first = Randy Joe | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/5107360.stm | work=[[BBC News]] | title=Cameroon girls battle 'breast ironing' | date=23 June 2006 | access-date = 25 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Penney | first = Joe | url= https://widerimage.reuters.com/story/breast-ironing | work=[[Reuters]] |title= Breast ironing | date = 27 January 2014 | access-date = 25 January 2014}}</ref> It is typically carried out by the girl's mother, with the aim of making the girl less sexually attractive to men and boys, so that her virginity is preserved and she can continue her education.<ref name=\"BBC Cameroon Breast Ironing\"/><ref>{{cite book | last = Ngunshi | first = Rosaline | title = Breast ironing: a harmful practice that has been silenced for too long | url = http://www2.ohchr.org/english/bodies/cedaw/docs/cedaw_crc_contributions/GenderEmpowermentandDevelopment.pdf | publisher = Gender Empowerment and Development (GeED) | date = 24 August 2011 }}</ref> It is practiced primarily in [[Cameroon]], but has also been reported across other areas in [[West Africa|West]] and [[Central Africa]].<ref name=\"west-info.eu\"/><ref name=\"BBC Cameroon Breast Ironing\"/><ref>{{cite news| last = Mabuse | first = Nkepile | title = Breast ironing tradition targeted in Cameroon | url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/07/27/cameroon.breast.ironing/ | work=[[CNN]] | date=28 July 2011 | access-date = 25 January 2014}}</ref> Breast ironing is very painful and can have negative emotional and physical consequences.<ref name=\"west-info.eu\"/><ref name=\"BBC Cameroon Breast Ironing\"/>\n\n===Obstetric violence===\n{{See|Abuse during childbirth}}\n\"Obstetric violence\" refers to acts categorized as physically or psychologically violent in the context of labor and birth. In most developed and many [[developing countries]], birth takes place in an increasingly medicalized environment; with numerous surgical interventions that the pregnant woman can sometimes be coerced into accepting, or which are done without her consent, or which are unnecessary.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Habek | first1 = Dubravko | last2 = Vukovi\u0107 Bobi\u0107 | first2 = Mirna | last3 = Hrgovi\u0107 | first3 = Zlatko | title = Possible feto-maternal clinical risk of the Kristeller's expression | journal = [[Central European Journal of Medicine]] | volume = 3 | issue = 2 | pages = 3&ndash;6 | publisher = [[Walter de Gruyter]] | doi = 10.2478/s11536-008-0008-z | date = 2008 | ref = harv }}</ref><ref name=\"WHO_Normal\">{{cite book | last = WHO | author-link = World Health Organization | title = Care in normal birth: a practical guide | id = WHO/FRH/MSM/96.24 | url = http://www.who.int/maternal_child_adolescent/documents/who_frh_msm_9624/en/ | publisher = [[World Health Organization]] | location = Geneva, Switzerland | series = Safe Motherhood Practical Guide | year = 1996 | access-date = 2 December 2013}} [http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/63167/1/WHO_FRH_MSM_96.24.pdf Pdf.]\n:''Also as'':\n:* {{cite journal | last = Technical Working Group, World Health Organization | author-link = World Health Organization | title = Care in normal birth: a practical guide | journal = [[Birth (journal)|Birth]] | volume = 24 | issue = 2 | pages = 121&ndash;123 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1523-536X.1997.00121.pp.x | date = June 1997 | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\nMany such practices originate in patriarchal ideologies. The WHO stated: \"in normal birth, there should be a valid reason to interfere with the natural process. The aim of care is to achieve a healthy mother and child with the least possible level of intervention compatible with safety.\"<ref name=\"doi.org\">{{cite journal | last1 = Dobbeleir | first1 = Julie M.L.C.L. | last2 = Landuyt | first2 = Koenraad Van | last3 = Monstrey | first3 = Stan J. | title = Aesthetic surgery of the female genitalia | journal = Seminars in Plastic Surgery | volume = 25 | issue = 2 | pages = 130&ndash;141 | publisher = [[Thieme Medical Publishers|Thieme]] | doi = 10.1055/s-0031-1281482 | pmc = 3312147 | date = May 2011 | ref = harv | pmid=22547970}}</ref><ref name=\"WHO_Normal\" />\n\nThe term \"obstetric violence\" is particularly used in Latin American countries, where the law prohibits such behavior. Such laws exist in several countries, including Argentina, Puerto Rico and Venezuela.<ref>{{cite web | last = WHO | author-link = World Health Organization | title = Sexual and reproductive health: Prevention and elimination of disrespect and abuse during childbirth | url = http://www.who.int/reproductivehealth/topics/maternal_perinatal/statement-childbirth-govnts-support/en/ | website = who.int | publisher = [[World Health Organization]] | year = 2015 | access-date = 21 October 2017}}\n:''See also'':\n:* {{cite book | last = WHO | author-link = World Health Organization | title = WHO statement: The prevention and elimination of disrespect and abuse during facility-based childbirth | id = WHO/RHR/14.23 | url = http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/134588/1/WHO_RHR_14.23_eng.pdf | publisher = [[World Health Organization]] | location = Geneva, Switzerland | series = Human Reproduction Programme (HRP) | year = 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Violence against indigenous women ===\nIndigenous women around the world are often targets of sexual assault or physical violence. Many indigenous communities are rural, with few resources and little help from the government or non-state actors. These groups also often have strained relationships with law enforcement, making prosecution difficult. Many indigenous societies also find themselves at the center of land disputes between nations and ethnic groups, often resulting in these communities bearing the brunt of national and ethnic conflicts.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = UNFPA | last2 = UNICEF | last3 = UN Women | last4 = ILO | last5 = Office of the Special Representative of the Secretary-General on Violence against Children (OSRSG/VAC) | author-link1 = United Nations Population Fund | author-link2 = UNICEF | author-link3 = UN Women | author-link4 = International Labour Organization | title = Breaking the silence on violence against indigenous girls, adolescents and young women: A call to action based on an overview of existing evidence from Africa, Asia Pacific and Latin America | url = http://www.unfpa.org/resources/breaking-silence-violence-against-indigenous-girls-adolescents-and-young-women | publisher = [[UNICEF]] | date = May 2013 | access-date = 10 May 2016}} [https://www.unfpa.org/sites/default/files/resource-pdf/VAIWG_FINAL.pdf Pdf.]</ref>\n\nViolence against indigenous women is often perpetrated by the state, such as in [[Peru]], in the 1990s. President [[Alberto Fujimori]] (in office from 1990 to 2000) has been accused of [[genocide]] and [[crimes against humanity]] as a result of a [[forced sterilization]] program put in place by his administration.<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Mass sterilization scandal shocks Peru | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/2148793.stm | work = [[BBC News]] | date = 24 July 2002 | access-date = 30 April 2006}}</ref> During his presidency, Fujimori put in place a program of forced sterilizations against indigenous people (mainly the [[Quechua people|Quechuas]] and the [[Aymara people|Aymaras]]), in the name of a \"[[public health]] plan\", presented 28 July 1995.\n\n[[Domestic violence in Bolivia|Bolivia has the highest rate of domestic violence]] in Latin America.<ref>{{cite news | last1 = Dhillon | first1 = Jaskiran | last2 = Allooloo | first2 = Siku | title = Violence against indigenous women is woven into Canada's history | url = https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/dec/14/violence-indigenous-woman-canada-history-inquiry-racism | work = [[The Guardian]] | date = 14 December 2015 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Shiriari | first = Sara | title = Bolivia struggles with gender-based violence | url = http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2015/4/30/bolivia-struggles-with-gender-based-violence.html | work = [[Al Jazeera America]] | date =  30 April 2015 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref> Indigenous women self-report physical or sexual violence from a current or former partner at rates of twenty-nine percent, in comparison to the national average of twenty four percent.<ref>{{cite report | last = UN | author-link = United Nations |title=Thematic paper on the elimination and responses to violence, exploitation and abuse of indigenous girls, adolescents and young women | url = https://www.un.org/en/ga/president/68/pdf/wcip/IASG%20Thematic%20Paper_%20Violence%20against%20Girls%20and%20Women%20-%20rev1.pdf | publisher = Inter-agency Support Group on Indigenous Peoples' Issues | date = June 2014 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref> Bolivia is largely indigenous in its ethnic demographics, and Quechua, Aymara, and Guarani women have been monumental in the nation's fight against violence against women.<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Bolivian women battle against culture of harassment | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-26446066 | work = [[BBC News]] | date = 12 March 2014 | access-date = 10 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Shahriari | first = Sara | title = Combating violence against women in Bolivia | url = https://pulitzercenter.org/reporting/combating-violence-against-women-bolivia | work = [[Pulitzer Center on Crisis Reporting]] | date = 6 March 2015 | access-date = 10 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Guatemala]]n indigenous women have also faced extensive violence. Throughout over three decades of conflict, [[Maya civilization|Maya]] women and girls have continued to be targeted. The Commission for Historical Clarification found that 88% of women affected by state-sponsored rape and sexual violence against women were indigenous.\n\nThe concept of white dominion over indigenous women's bodies has been rooted in American history since the beginning of colonization. The theory of manifest destiny went beyond simple land extension and into the belief that European settlers had the right to exploit Native women's bodies as a method of taming and \"humanizing\" them.<ref name=\"Bubar, Roe 2004\">{{cite journal | last1 = Roe | first1 = Bubar | last2 = Jumper Thurman | first2 = Pamela | title = Violence against native women | journal = Social Justice | volume = 31 | issue = 4 [98] | pages = 70&ndash;86 | jstor = 29768276 | date = 2004 | url = http://www.socialjusticejournal.org/?product=roe-bubar-and-pamela-jumper-thurman-2 | ref = harv }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Ramirez | first = Renya | title = Healing, violence, and Native American women | journal = Social Justice | volume = 31 | issue = 4 [98] | pages = 103&ndash;116 | jstor = 29768279 | date = 2004 | url = http://www.socialjusticejournal.org/?product=renya-ramirez-2 | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\n[[Canada]] has an extensive problem with violence against indigenous women, by both indigenous men and non-aboriginals. \"[I]t has been consistently found that Aboriginal women have a higher likelihood of being victimized compared to the rest of the female population.\"<ref>{{cite book | editor-last = Sinha | editor-first = Maire | title = Measuring violence against women: statistical trends 2006 (85-570-XWE) | page = 19 | publisher = Statistics Canada | location = Ottawa, Ontario | series = Juristat | url = http://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/85-002-x/2013001/article/11766-eng.pdf | year = 2006 }}\n:''Citing'':\n:* {{cite book | last = Brennan | first = Shannon | title = Violent victimization of Aboriginal women in the Canadian provinces, 2009  | publisher = Statistics Canada | location = Ottawa, Ontario | series = Juristat | url = https://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/85-002-x/2011001/article/11439-eng.htm | year = 2011 }} Catalogue no. 85-002.\n:* {{cite book | last = Perreault | first = Samuel | title = Violent victimization of Aboriginal women in the Canadian provinces, 2009  | publisher = Statistics Canada | location = Ottawa, Ontario | series = Juristat | url = http://statcan.gc.ca/pub/85-002-x/2011001/article/11415-eng.htm | year = 2011 }} Catalogue no. 85-002.</ref> While Canadian national averages of violence against women are falling, they have remained the same for aboriginal communities throughout the years. The history of [[Canadian Indian residential school system|residential schools]] and economic inequality of indigenous Canadians has resulted in communities facing violence, unemployment, drug use, alcoholism, political corruption, and high rates of suicide.<ref name=\"Bubar, Roe 2004\"/> In addition, there has been clear and admitted racism towards indigenous people by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]], making victims less likely to report cases of domestic violence.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jackson |first=Kenneth |title=Top Mountie Admits Racism in Ranks towards Indigenous People |work=[[Aboriginal People's Television Network]] |date=9 December 2015 |url=http://aptn.ca/news/2015/12/09/top-mountie-admits-racism-in-ranks-towards-indigenous-people/ | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nMany of the issues facing indigenous women in Canada have been addressed via the Murdered and Missing Indigenous Women (MMIW) initiatives. Thousands of Native Canadian women have gone missing or been killed in the past 30 years, with little representation or attention from the government. Efforts to make the Canadian public aware of these women's disappearances have mostly been led by Aboriginal communities, who often reached across provinces to support one another. In 2015, prime minister [[Stephen Harper]] commented that the issue of murdered and missing indigenous women was \"not high on our radar\",<ref>{{cite news | title = Full Text of Peter Mansbridge's interview with Stephen Harper | work = [[CBC News]] | url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/canada-election-2105-full-text-of-peter-mansbridge-s-interview-with-stephen-harper-1.3218399 | date = 7 September 2015 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref> prompting outrage in already frustrated indigenous communities. A few months later, Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] launched an official inquiry into the Murdered and Missing Indigenous Women.\n\nIn the United States, Native American women are more than twice as likely to experience violence than any other demographic.<ref name=\"Bubar, Roe 2004\"/> One in three Native women is sexually assaulted during her life, and 67% of these assaults are perpetrated by non-Natives,<ref name=\"ncai\">{{cite book |title=Policy Insights - Brief Statistics on Violence Against Native Women |date=2013 |publisher=NCAI Policy Research Center |page=4 |url=http://www.ncai.org/attachments/PolicyPaper_tWAjznFslemhAffZgNGzHUqIWMRPkCDjpFtxeKEUVKjubxfpGYK_Policy%20Insights%20Brief_VAWA_020613.pdf |quote= A previously reported statistic that, \u201cAmong [American Indian and Alaska Native] victims of rape or sexual assault, 86 percent described the offender as non\u2010Indian\u201d is accurate according to Perry\u2019s analysis (2004) in American Indians and Crime: A BJS Statistical Profile, 1992-2002. However, Perry\u2019s analysis includes reports by both Native men and women victims of rape or sexual assault. Given this brief\u2019s focus on violence against Native women, we include the updated rate of 67 percent reported by Native women victims of rape or sexual assault indicated in Bachman, et al., (2008).}}</ref><ref name=\"Bubar, Roe 2004\"/><ref>{{cite news | last = Chekuru | first = Kavitha | title = Sexual violence scars Native American Women | url = http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2013/03/201334111633172507.html | work = [[Al Jazeera]] | date = 6 March 2013 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref> with Native Americans constituting 0.7% of U.S. population in 2015.<ref name=ACS>{{cite web|title=ACS Demographic and Housing Estimates \u2013 2011\u20132015|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/15_5YR/DP05/0100000US|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|accessdate=December 23, 2019|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213004951/https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/15_5YR/DP05/0100000US|archive-date=13 February 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref> The disproportionate rate of assault to indigenous women is due to a variety of causes, including but not limited to the historical legal inability of tribes to prosecute on their own on the reservation. The federal Violence Against Women Act was reauthorized in 2013, which for the first time gave tribes jurisdiction to investigate and prosecute felony domestic violence offenses involving Native American and non-Native offenders on the reservation,<ref name=\"rapidcityjournal\">{{cite news |last1=Cook |first1=Andrea J. |title=Tribal leaders urged to apply Violence Against Women Act |url=https://rapidcityjournal.com/news/local/tribal-leaders-urged-to-apply-violence-against-women-act/article_f030d4ad-dbda-53ff-bb72-5816465f78d4.html |accessdate=January 11, 2020 |newspaper=Rapid City Journal |date=April 1, 2015}}</ref> as 26% of Natives live on reservations.<ref name=\"calgary\">{{cite news |last1=Milke |first1=Mark |title=Increasing number of Aboriginals choose not to live on reserves |url=https://www.fraserinstitute.org/article/increasing-number-aboriginals-choose-not-live-reserves |accessdate=December 23, 2019 |publisher=Calgary Herald and Regina Leader Post |date=January 12, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last1 = Bachman | first1 = Ronet | last2 = Zaykowski| first2 = Heather | last3 = Kallmyer | first3 = Rachel | last4 = Poteyeva | first4 = Margarita | last5 = Lanier | first5 = Christina | title = Violence against American Indian and Alaska Native women and the criminal justice response: what is known | publisher = [[National Institute of Justice]] | url = https://www.ncjrs.gov/pdffiles1/nij/grants/223691.pdf | date=August 2008 |accessdate=May 10, 2016}} {{NCJ|245615}}</ref> In 2019 the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[United States House of Representatives|House]] passed H.R. 1585 (Violence Against Women Reauthorization Act of 2019) by a vote of 263\u2013158, which increases tribes' prosecution rights much further. However in the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[United States Senate|Senate]] its progress has stalled.<ref name=\"gq\">{{cite magazine |last1=Willis |first1=Jay |title=Why Can't the Senate Pass the Violence Against Women Act? |url=https://www.gq.com/story/senate-violence-against-women-act |accessdate=January 11, 2020 |magazine=GQ |date=December 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Violence against immigrant and refugee women===\nImmigrant and refugee women often face violence, both in the private sphere (by partners and other family members) and in the public sphere (by the police and other authorities). These women are often in a vulnerable position: they do not speak the language of the country they are in, they do not know its laws, and sometimes they are in a legal position where they may be deported if they make contact with the authorities. Women who seek protection from armed conflict in their countries of origin often face more violence while travelling to the destination country or when they arrive there.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Freedman | first = Jane | title = Sexual and gender-based violence against refugee women: a hidden aspect of the refugee \"crisis\" | journal = Reproductive Health Matters | volume = 24 | issue = 47 | pages = 18&ndash;26 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] | doi = 10.1016/j.rhm.2016.05.003 | pmid = 27578335 | date = 2017 | ref = harv | url = https://halshs.archives-ouvertes.fr/halshs-01441147/file/Sexual%20and%20gender%20based%20violence%20against%20refugee%20women%20a%20hidden%20aspect%20of%20the%20refugee%20crisis.pdf }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Robbers | first1 = Gianna | last2 = Gunta | first2 = Lazdane | last3 = Dinesh | first3 = Sethi | title = Sexual violence against refugee women on the move to and within Europe | journal = Entre Nous | volume = 84 | pages = 26&ndash;29 | publisher = [[WHO]]/Europe | date = 2016 | url = http://www.euro.who.int/en/health-topics/Life-stages/sexual-and-reproductive-health/publications/entre-nous/entre-nous/together-for-a-better-sexual-and-reproductive-health.-entre-nous-no-84,-2016 | ref = harv }} [http://www.euro.who.int/__data/assets/pdf_file/0017/319301/Entre-Nous-84-full-book.pdf?ua=1 Pdf.]</ref>\n\n===Violence against trans women===\n{{See also|Violence against LGBT people}}\n[[Trans women]], especially [[women of color]], are at higher risk of experiencing violence than [[cisgender women]].<ref>{{Cite report |url=https://www.apa.org/about/policy/psychological-practice-girls-women.pdf |title=APA Guidelines for Psychological Practice with Girls and Women|year=2018 |author=American Psychological Association|page=11|quote=Transgender women are at a notably higher risk of violence than their cisgender counterparts...especially transgender women of color}}</ref> Trans women commonly experience intimate partner violence, with one study finding that 31.1% of trans people experience it, and another finding that half of all trans women experience it.<ref name=\"williams\">{{Cite journal |last=Brown |first=Taylor N.T. |last2=Herman |first2=Jody L. |year=2015 |title=Intimate Partner Violence and Sexual Abuse Among LGBT People: A Review of Existing Research |url=https://williamsinstitute.law.ucla.edu/wp-content/uploads/Intimate-Partner-Violence-and-Sexual-Abuse-among-LGBT-People.pdf |journal=The Williams Institute: UCLA School of Law}}</ref><ref name=\"lang\">{{Cite journal |last=Langenderfer-Magruder |first=Lisa|year=2016 |title=Experiences of Intimate Partner Violence and Subsequent Police Reporting Among Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender, and Queer Adults in Colorado: Comparing Rates of Cisgender and Transgender Victimization |journal=Journal of Interpersonal Violence |volume=31 |issue=5 |pages=855\u2013871 |doi=10.1177/0886260514556767 |issn=1552-6518 |pmid=25392392}}</ref><ref name=\"risser\">{{Cite journal |last=Risser |first=Jan M. H. |date=2005-10-11 |title=Sex, Drugs, Violence, and HIV Status Among Male-to-Female Transgender Persons in Houston, Texas |journal=International Journal of Transgenderism |volume=8 |issue=2\u20133 |pages=67\u201374 |doi=10.1300/J485v08n02_07 |issn=1553-2739}}</ref> Trans women also often face abuse by police, and [[transgender sex workers]] often face violence from clients.<ref name=\"whotrans\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.who.int/hiv/topics/transgender/about/en/ |title=Transgender people |website=World Health Organization |access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> Trans survivors of violence can have a harder time finding [[domestic violence shelter]]s, as some shelters only accept cisgender women.<ref name=\"williams\" /><ref>{{Cite journal |url=https://scholarship.law.berkeley.edu/californialawreview/vol106/iss5/6 |title=Are Women's Spaces Transgender Spaces? Single-Sex Domestic Violence Shelters, Transgender Inclusion, and the Equal Protection Clause |last=Apsani |first=Rishita |date=2018-10-01 |website=California Law Review |pages=1689 |doi=10.15779/Z38125Q91G |access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> In 2018, more than two dozen [[transgender]] people were violently killed in the United States, most of them [[women of color]].<ref name=\"hrc2019\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.hrc.org/resources/violence-against-the-transgender-community-in-2019/ |title=Violence Against the Transgender Community in 2019 |website=Human Rights Campaign |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"cnn\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/16/health/transgender-deaths-2018/index.html |title=Killings of transgender people in the US saw another high year |last=Christensen |first=Jen |website=CNN |access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref>\n\n===Sport-related===\n\nSport-related violence against women refers to any physical, sexual, mental acts that are \"perpetrated by both male athletes and by male fans or consumers of sport and sporting events, as well as by coaches of female athletes\".<ref name=\"Catherine Palmer\">{{cite book|last=Palmer|first=Catherine|title=Violence against women and sport: Literature review|year=2011|publisher=Durham University|location=London|pages=2\u20135|url=http://www.endviolenceagainstwomen.org.uk/resources/22/violence-against-women-and-sport-a-literature-review-by-dr-catherine-palmer|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106162130/http://www.endviolenceagainstwomen.org.uk/resources/22/violence-against-women-and-sport-a-literature-review-by-dr-catherine-palmer|archivedate=6 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe documenting reports and literature suggest that there are obvious connections between contemporary sport and violence against women. Such events as the [[2010 World Cup]], the [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] and [[Commonwealth Games]] \"have highlighted the connections between sports spectatorship and intimate partner violence, and the need for police, authorities and services to be aware of this when planning sporting events\".<ref name=\"Catherine Palmer\" />\n\nSport-related violence can occur in various contexts and places, including homes, pubs, clubs, hotel rooms, the streets.<ref name=\"Catherine Palmer\" />\n\n====Sport-related violence by male college athletes====\n\nViolence against women is a topic of concern in the United States' collegiate athletic community. From the 2010 UVA lacrosse murder, in which a male athlete was charged guilty with second degree murder of his girlfriend, to the 2004 University of Colorado Football Scandal when players were charged with nine alleged sexual assaults,<ref>{{cite news|last=Vaughan|first=Kevin|title=Colorado woman seeks justice in alleged sexual assault Read more: Colorado woman seeks justice in alleged sexual assault|url=http://www.denverpost.com/firstinthepost/ci_12557039|work=[[The Denver Post]]|date=9 June 2009|accessdate=17 April 2012}}</ref> studies suggest that athletes are at higher risk for committing sexual assault against women than the average student.<ref>{{cite web|last=Brady|first=Jeff|author-link=Jeff Brady (reporter)|title=Scandal Returns to University of Colorado Football|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=105381707|work=[[Weekend Edition]]|publisher=[[NPR]]|accessdate=12 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"chandler1999\">{{cite journal|last1=Chandler|first1=Steve B.|last2=Johnson|first2=Dewayne J.|last3=Carroll|first3=Pamela S.|title=Abusive behaviors of college athletes | journal = [[College Student Journal]] | volume = 33 | issue = 4 | pages = 638&ndash;645 | publisher = [[University of South Alabama]] | date = 1 December 1999 | ref = harv |oclc=193500507}}</ref> It is reported that one in three college assaults are committed by athletes.<ref name=\"johnshopkins1\">{{cite journal|last=Mak|first=Stephanie|title=Are athletes more abusive than the rest of the student population?|url=http://web1.johnshopkins.edu/hurj/issue3/spotlight-mak.html|journal=Hopkins Undergraduate Research Journal Online|accessdate=12 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229044851/http://web1.johnshopkins.edu/hurj/issue3/spotlight-mak.html|archivedate=29 February 2012|date=2004|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Surveys suggest that male student athletes who represent 3.3% of the college population, commit 19% of reported sexual assaults and 35% of domestic violence.<ref>{{cite web|last=Staff writer|title=Game stats|publisher=The National Coalition Against Violent Athletes (NCVA)|accessdate=27 December 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161117092517/http://www.ncava.org/statistics.html|archivedate=17 November 2016|url=http://www.ncava.org:80/statistics.html|df=dmy-all}}\n:''Citing'':\n:* {{cite journal | last1 = Crosset | first1 = Todd W. | last2 = Benedict | first2 = Jeffrey R. | last3 = McDonald | first3 = Mark A. | title = Male student-athletes and violence against women: a survey of campus judicial affairs offices | journal = [[Journal of Sport & Social Issues]] | volume = 19 | issue = 2 | pages = 126&ndash;140 | publisher = [[Sage Publications|Sage]] | doi = 10.1177/019372395019002002 | date = May 1995 | ref = harv }}\n:* {{cite journal | last1 = Crosset | first1 = Todd W. | last2 = Ptacek | first2 = James | last3 = McDonald | first3 = Mark A. | last4 = Benedict | first4 = Jeffrey R. | title = Male student-athletes and violence against women: a survey of campus judicial affairs offices | journal = [[Violence Against Women (journal)|Violence Against Women]] | volume = 2 | issue = 2 | pages = 163&ndash;179 | publisher = [[Sage Publications|Sage]] | doi = 10.1177/1077801296002002004 | pmid = 12295457 | date = June 1996 | ref = harv | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/b3e4babb2d254a82585ce0ef51115bd827bca7d1 }}\n\n:''See also'':\n:* {{cite book | last1 = Benedict | first1 = Jeff | last2 = Keteyian | first2 = Armen | title = The system: the glory and scandal of big-time college football | publisher = Doubleday | location = New York | year = 2013 | url = https://archive.org/details/systemgloryscand0000bene | url-access = registration | isbn = 9780345803030 }}</ref> The theories that surround these statistics range from misrepresentation of the student-athlete to an unhealthy mentality towards women within the team itself.<ref name=\"johnshopkins1\"/>\n\n====Controversy over contributing factors====\n\nSociologist Timothy Curry, after conducting an observational analysis of two big time sports' locker room conversations, deduced that the high risk of male student athletes for gender abuse is a result of the team's subculture.<ref name=Curry1991>{{cite journal|last=Curry|first=Timothy Jon|title=Fraternal Bonding in the Locker Room: A Profeminist Analysis Of Talk About Competition And Women|journal=Sociology of Sport Journal|year=1991|volume=8|issue=2|pages=119\u2013135 |url=http://www.umt.edu/sociology/faculty_staff/ellestad/documents/275_Curry1991fraternalbondinginthelockerroom_s10.pdf |accessdate=12 March 2012|doi=10.1123/ssj.8.2.119}}</ref> He states, \"Their locker room talk generally treated women as objects, encouraged sexist attitudes toward women and, in its extreme, promoted rape culture.\"<ref name=Curry1991/> He proposes that this objectification is a way for the male to reaffirm his heterosexual status and hyper-masculinity. Claims have been made that the atmosphere changes when an outsider (especially women) intrude in the locker room. In the wake of the reporter [[Lisa Olson]] being harassed by a Patriots player in the locker room in 1990, she reflected, \"We are taught to think we must have done something wrong and it took me a while to realize I hadn't done anything wrong.\"<ref name=\"Disch\">{{cite journal|last=Disch|first=Lisa|author2=Kane, Mary Jo |title=When a Looker is Really a Bitch: Lisa Olson, Sport, and the Heterosexual Matrix|journal=Signs|date=Winter 1996|volume=21|issue=2|pages=278\u2013308|jstor=3175065|doi=10.1086/495067}}</ref> Other female sports reporters (college and professional) have claimed that they often brush off the players' comments, which leads to further objectification.<ref name=\"Disch\" /> Other sociologists challenge this claim. Steve Chandler notes that because of their celebrity status on campus, \"athletes are more likely to be scrutinized or falsely accused than non-athletes.\"<ref name=\"chandler1999\"/> Another contender, Stephanie Mak, notes that, \"if one considers the 1998 estimates that about three million women were battered and almost one million raped, the proportion of incidences that involve athletes in comparison to the regular population is relatively small.\"<ref name=\"johnshopkins1\"/>\n\n====Response to violence by male college athletes====\n\nIn response to the proposed link between college athletes and gender-based violence, and media coverage holding Universities as responsible for these scandals more universities are requiring athletes to attend workshops that promote awareness. For example, St. John's University holds sexual assault awareness classes in the fall for its incoming student athletes.<ref>{{cite news|last=Newsom|first=John|title=Share on emailShare on redditMore Sharing Services Few Colleges Tackle Issue of Athlete Sex Assaults|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1992-03-22/news/mn-7249_1_sexual-assault|publisher=Los Angeles Times Online |date=22 March 1992 |accessdate=12 March 2012}}</ref> Other groups, such as the National Coalition Against Violent Athletes, have formed to provide support for the victims as their mission statement reads, \"The NCAVA works to eliminate off the field violence by athletes through the implementation of prevention methods that recognize and promote the positive leadership potential of athletes within their communities. In order to eliminate violence, the NCAVA is dedicated to empowering individuals affected by athlete violence through comprehensive services including advocacy, education and counseling.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Mission|url=http://www.ncava.org/Mission.html|publisher=National Coalition Against Violent Athletes|accessdate=12 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120416074831/http://www.ncava.org/Mission.html|archivedate=16 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Cyberbullying===\n[[Cyberbullying]] is a form of intimidation using electronic forms of contact. In the 21st century, cyberbullying has become increasingly common, especially among teenagers in Western countries.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Smith |first1=Peter K. |last2=Mahdavi |first2=Jess |last3=Carvalho |first3=Manuel |last4=Fisher |first4=Sonja |last5=Russell |first5=Shanette |last6=Tippett |first6=Neil | title = Cyberbullying: its nature and impact in secondary school pupils | journal = [[Journal of Child Psychology and Psychiatry]] | volume = 49 | issue = 4 | pages = 376&ndash;385 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1469-7610.2007.01846.x |pmid=18363945 | date = 2008 | ref = harv }}</ref> On 24 September 2015, the [[United Nations Broadband Commission]] released a report that claimed that almost 75% percent of women [[online]] have encountered harassment and threats of violence, otherwise known as [[cyber violence]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unwomen.org/en/news/stories/2015/9/cyber-violence-report-press-release |title=cyber violence report press release |publisher=UN Women |date= |accessdate=2016-04-03}}</ref> Misogynistic rhetoric is prevalent online, and the public debate over gender-based attacks has increased significantly, leading to calls for policy interventions and better responses by social networks like [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]].<ref>{{cite journal |last= Jane |first= Emma Alice | title = 'Back to the kitchen, cunt': speaking the unspeakable about online misogyny  | journal = [[Continuum: Journal of Media & Cultural Studies]] | volume = 28 | issue = 4 | pages = 558&ndash;570 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] | doi = 10.1080/10304312.2014.924479 | date = 2014 | ref = harv }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last= Filipovic |first= Jill | title = Blogging while female: how internet misogyny parallels real-world harassment | journal = [[Yale Journal of Law and Feminism]] | volume = 19 | issue = 2 | pages = 295&ndash;303 | publisher = [[Yale Law School]] | date = 2007 | url = http://digitalcommons.law.yale.edu/yjlf/vol19/iss1/10/ | ref = harv }} [http://digitalcommons.law.yale.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1268&context=yjlf Pdf.]</ref>\n\n==Activism==\n[[File:A Bulgarian poster urging open your eyes - against women being abused.jpg|thumb|250px|A Bulgarian poster urging people to open their eyes about domestic violence against women]]\n[[File:MintoParkMemorial.JPG|thumb|left|Memorial in [[Minto Park]], [[Ottawa]], of the victims of the [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]]]]\n\n===Background and history===\nActivism refers to \"a doctrine or practice that emphasizes direct vigorous action especially in support of or opposition to one side of a controversial issue\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/activism |title=Activism (definition) | website = merriam-webster.com |publisher=[[Merriam-Webster]] |date= |accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref> In the activism for violence against women, the objectives are to address and draw public attention on the issues of VAW as well as seek and recommend measures to prevent and eliminate this violence.<ref name=\"Youngs_368325\">{{cite journal | last = Youngs | first = Gillian | title = Private pain/public peace: women's rights as human rights and Amnesty International's report on violence against women | journal = [[Signs (journal)|Signs]] | volume = 28 | issue = 4 | pages = 1209&ndash;1229 | publisher = [[University of Chicago Press]] | doi = 10.1086/368325 | jstor = 10.1086/368325 | date = Summer 2003 | ref = harv }}</ref> Many scholarly articles suggest that the VAW is considered as a violation of human rights<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\">{{cite journal | last1 = Htun | first1 = Mala | last2 = Weldon | first2 = S. Laurel | title = The civic origins of progressive policy change: combating violence against women in global perspective, 1975\u20132005 | journal = [[American Political Science Review]] | volume = 106 | issue = 3 | pages = 548&ndash;569 | publisher = [[Cambridge University Press]] | doi = 10.1017/S0003055412000226 | jstor = 23275433 | date = August 2012 | ref = harv }} [https://web.archive.org/web/20121030053243/http://polisci.unm.edu/common/documents/htun_apsa-article.pdf Pdf.]</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Carraway | first = G. Chezia | title = Violence against women of color | journal = [[Stanford Law Review]] | volume = 43 | issue = 6 | pages = 1301&ndash;1309 | publisher = [[Stanford Law School]] | doi = 10.2307/1229040 | jstor = 1229040 | date = July 1991 | ref = harv }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Robinson | first = Nancy P. | title = Origins of the International Day for the Elimination of Violence against Women: The Caribbean contribution | journal = [[Caribbean Studies (UPR)|Caribbean Studies]] | volume = 34 | issue = 2 | pages = 141&ndash;161 | publisher = [[University of Puerto Rico, R\u00edo Piedras Campus|UPR, Rio Piedras Campus]] | jstor = 25613539 | date = July\u2013December 2006 | ref = harv }}</ref> as well as \"public health issue\".<ref name=\"Michau, L. 2007 95\u2013109\">{{cite journal | last = Michau | first = Lori | title = Approaching old problems in new ways: community mobilisation as a primary prevention strategy to combat violence against women | journal = [[Gender & Development]] | volume = 15 | issue = 1 | pages = 95&ndash;109 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] | doi = 10.1080/13552070601179144  | jstor = 20461184 | date = March 2007 | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\nIn order to better comprehend the anti-violence movements against VAW, there is a need to also understand the generic historical background of [[feminist movements]] in a holistic manner. Talking about the international women's movement, many feminist scholars have categorized these movements into three waves<ref name=\"Krol\u00f8kke&S\u00f8rensen\">{{cite book | last1 = Krol\u00f8kke | first1 = Charlotte | last2 = S\u00f8rensen | first2 = Ann Scott | chapter = Three waves of feminism: from suffragettes to grrls | chapterurl = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=IEhqiWR1Rt0C&pg=PA1 | editor-last1 = Krol\u00f8kke | editor-first1 = Charlotte | editor-last2 = S\u00f8rensen | editor-first2 = Ann Scott | title = Gender communication theories & analyses: from silence to performance | pages = 1&ndash;23 | publisher = Sage Publications | location = Thousand Oaks, California | year = 2006 | isbn = 9780761929185 | ref = harv }}</ref> according to their different beliefs, strategies and goals.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Rupp | first1 = Leila J. | last2 = Taylor | first2 = Verta | title = Forging feminist identity in an international movement: a collective identity approach to twentieth-century feminism | journal = [[Signs (journal)|Signs]] | volume = 24 | issue = 2 | pages = 363&ndash;386 | publisher = [[University of Chicago Press]] | doi = 10.1086/495344 | jstor = 3175646 | date = Winter 1999 | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\nThe emergence of the first women's movements, or so called the [[First-wave feminism|first wave]] of feminism, dated back in the years the late 19th Century and early 20th Century in the United States and Europe. During this period, feminist movements developed from the context of industrialization and liberal politics that triggered the rise of feminist groups concerned with gaining equal access and opportunity for women.<ref name=\"Krol\u00f8kke&S\u00f8rensen\" />{{rp|1}} This wave marks a period of \"[[Women's suffrage|suffrage]], independence, rights to nationality, work and [[Gender pay gap|equal pay]]\" for women.<ref name=\"Pr\u00fcgl, E. Dec. 2013\">{{cite book | last = Pr\u00fcgl | first = Elisabeth (Lecturer) | title = Violence Against Women. Gender and International Affairs Class 2013 | url = http://graduateinstitute.ch/home/study/courses/courses-2017-2018/masters-interdisciplinaires/mia/ia039---gender-and-international.html | location = Geneva, Switzerland | publisher = Lecture conducted from [[The Graduate Institute of International and Development Studies]] (IHEID) | date = 2 December 2013 | access-date = 27 December 2017 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180721122423/http://graduateinstitute.ch/home/study/courses/courses-2017-2018/masters-interdisciplinaires/mia/ia039---gender-and-international.html | archive-date = 21 July 2018 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Second-wave feminism|second wave]] of feminist movements was the series of movements from the period of the late 1960s to early 1970s. It was noted by feminist scholars that this wave could be characterized as a period of [[Women's liberation movement|women's liberation]] and the rise of a branch of feminism known as [[radical feminism]].<ref name=\"Krol\u00f8kke&S\u00f8rensen\" />{{rp|7\u20138}} This wave of feminism emerged in the context of the postwar period<ref name=\"Krol\u00f8kke&S\u00f8rensen\" />{{rp|8}} in society where other mainstream movements also played a large role; for instance, the [[civil rights movements]],<ref name=\"Pr\u00fcgl, E. Dec. 2013\" /> which meant to condemn [[capitalism]], [[imperialism]] and the oppression of people based on the notions of [[Racism|race]], ethnicity, [[gender identity]] and [[LGBT social movements|sexual orientation]].<ref name=\"Krol\u00f8kke&S\u00f8rensen\" />{{rp|9}} This wave marks a period of equal rights at home and workplace as well as rights to development<ref name=\"Pr\u00fcgl, E. Dec. 2013\" /> for the purposes of people of different races, ethnicities, economic statuses and gender identities.\n\nThe [[Third-wave feminism|third wave]] of feminism is the newest wave of feminism led by young feminists whose understanding and context are of the [[Globalization|globalized]] world order and the technological advances that have come with it. Also, this wave is a transition of the fall communism<ref name=\"Krol\u00f8kke&S\u00f8rensen\" />{{rp|17}} to more complex issues of new kinds of 'warfare'{{Clarify|reason=What does this mean by \"warfare\"?  Also, this whole sentence is oddly worded but I don't understand what it's trying to say well enough to rewrite it.|date=November 2018}}, threats and violence. This new wave also \"embraces ambiguity\"<ref name=\"Krol\u00f8kke&S\u00f8rensen\" />{{rp|16}} and introduced a feminist approach of '[[intersectionality]]' that includes the issues of race, gender, age, and class.<ref name=\"Krol\u00f8kke&S\u00f8rensen\" />{{rp|17}} Other than that, the third wave marks a period of feminism dealing with [[identity politics]], body politics as well as the issues of violence.<ref>{{cite book | last = Lind | first = Amy (Lecturer) | title = Gender and International Affairs 2013: International Feminist Movements | url = http://graduateinstitute.ch/directory?detail=people/faculty/lind | location = Geneva, Switzerland | publisher = Lecture conducted from [[The Graduate Institute of International and Development Studies]] (IHEID) | date = 2 December 2013 | access-date = 29 March 2020 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181113125400/http://graduateinstitute.ch/directory?detail=people%2Ffaculty%2Flind | archive-date = 13 November 2018 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n[[File:Papua New Guinean children, men and women show their support for putting an end to violence against women during a White Ribbon Day march (21614943268).jpg|thumb|[[Papua New Guinean]]s show their support for putting an end to [[Sexual violence in Papua New Guinea|violence against women]] during a [[White Ribbon Campaign|White Ribbon Day]] march]]\n\nNonetheless, the VAW movement was initiated in the 1970s where some feminist movements started to bring the discussion on the issue of violence into the feminist discourse<ref>{{cite book | last = Eng | first = Phoebe | author-link = Phoebe Eng | title = Stopping the violence against women: the movement from intervention to prevention | url = http://www.ncdsv.org/images/Ms_StoppingVAWTheMovementFromInterventionToPrevention_Aug2005.pdf | page = 2 | publisher = [[Ms. Foundation for Women]] | location = New York | date = August 2005 | series = A Safety Program Report | access-date = 3 December 2013 }}</ref> and that many other groups, on the national as well as international levels, had attempted to push for the betterment of women through lobbying of the state officials and delegates, demanding the conferences on 'gender issues'<ref name=\"Pr\u00fcgl, E. Dec. 2013\" /> and thus made the VAW known to a wider range of population. Therefore, to put this into the theoretical context, VAW can be categorized along with the second and third waves of feminism which share a focus on violence.\n\nVAW activist movements come in many forms, operating at international, national, and local levels<ref name=\"Youngs_368325\" /> and utilizing different approaches based on health and human rights frameworks.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Miller | first = Alice M. | title = Sexuality, violence against women, and human rights: women make demands and ladies get protection | journal = [[Health and Human Rights]] | volume = 7 | issue = 2 | pages = 16&ndash;47 | publisher = [[Harvard University Press]] | doi = 10.2307/4065347 | jstor = 4065347 | date = 2004 | ref = harv }}</ref> The movements stemmed mostly from social movements and groups of women who see the need to create organizations to 'lobby' their governments to establish \"sanctuaries, shelters\" and provision of services that help protecting these victims, also called \"battered women\", from acts of violence. The term \"battered women\" was used in a number of VAW movements and had its root in the early stage of organizing efforts to tackle the problem of violence against women in many regions of the world such as Africa, Asia Pacific, Latin American and the Caribbean.<ref name=\"Fried\" />{{rp|94}} The activist organizations against VAW, some with and the others without the support of their governments, attempted to develop \"innovative efforts\" to assist battered women by providing them services such as shelters and centers; drafting and lobbying governments to include the recognition and language of VAW into national legislations and [[international human rights instruments]]; advocating to raise the awareness of people via education and training sessions; forming national, regional as well as international networks to empower the movements; organizing demonstrations and gathering more efforts to end violent acts against women.<ref name=\"Fried\" />{{rp|88\u201389}} In addition, many women's rights activist groups see the issue of violence against women as a central focus of their movements. Many of these groups take a human rights approach as the integral framework of their activism. These VAW movements also employ the idea that \"women's rights are human rights\", transform the concepts and ideas of human rights, which are mostly reckoned to be \"[[Western world|Western]] concepts\" and '[[Vernacularization|vernacularize]] them into the concepts that can be understood in their local institutions.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Merry | first = Sally Engle | title = Transnational human rights and local activism: mapping the middle | journal = [[American Anthropologist]] | volume = 108 | issue = 1 | pages = 38&ndash;51 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1525/aa.2006.108.1.38 | date = March 2006 | ref = harv }}</ref>{{rp|39}}\n\n=== Levels of activist movements ===\n[[File:Girl_Summit_-_22nd_July_in_London_(14498368279).jpg|thumb|250px|Poster against child and forced marriage]]\n[[File:Marcha_Ni_una_menos_1.JPG|thumb|250px|right|Mass protest against violence against women in [[Buenos Aires]] in 2015]]\nOn the local or national level, the VAW movements are diverse and differ in their strategic program of intervention. The strategies used in a number of the movements focus on the individual level with the emphases on individuals, relationships and family. Also, many of them take the 'preventive' as an approach to tackle the issues on the ground by encouraging people to \"reexamine their attitudes and beliefs\" in order to trigger and create fundamental changes in these \"deep-rooted beliefs and behaviors\".<ref name=\"Michau, L. 2007 95\u2013109\"/> Despite the fact that these strategies can be life changing, helpful to those who participate and feasible over a long time frame, the effects on societal level seem to be restricted and of minimal effects. In order to achieve the objectives of the movement, many activists and scholars argue that they have to initiate changes in cultural attitudes and norms on a communal level.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Heise | first1 = L. | last2 = Gottemoeller | first2 = M. | title = Ending violence against women | journal = Population Reports | volume = L | issue = 11 | page = 38 | publisher = Johns Hopkins University School of Public Health, Population and Information Program | url = https://vawnet.org/sites/default/files/assets/files/2016-10/PopulationReports.pdf | date = December 1999 }}</ref> An example of activism on the local level can be seen in South Africa. The movements of VAW in this context employ a strategy that is based on the 'prevention' approach, which is applicable on individual and societal levels: in families and communities. This movement encourages the individuals and small populations to rethink their attitudes and beliefs in order to create a possibility to alter these deep-rooted beliefs and behaviors, which lead to the acts of violence against women.<ref name=\"Michau, L. 2007 pp.96\"/> Another example is the local level movement in East Africa that employs the prevention approach, which is applicable on a communal level. They call this a \"raising voices\" approach. This approach employs an 'ad hoc' framework that can be used alongside the individual approach where the strategy is to aggravate the status quo issues onto the individuals' and communities' perception and establish a common ground of interests for them to push for the movement, all in a short time period.<ref name=\"Michau, L. 2007 pp.96\"/> In addition, on the domestic level, there seems to be many 'autonomous movements.'<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\" /> feminist movements (for VAW) can be understood as \"a form of women's mobilization that is devoted to promoting women's status and well-being independently of political parties and other associations that do not have the status of women as their main concern\".<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\" />\n\nA number of regions of the world have come together to address violence against women. In South America, the Southern Cone Network Against Domestic Violence has worked extensively to address sexual and domestic violence since 1989. The Latin American and Caribbean Network Against Domestic and Sexual Violence, formed in 1990, includes representation from twenty-one different countries and has been instrumental in increasing the visibility of VAW.<ref name=\"Fried\" />{{rp|88}} In September 1999, the Heads of States of the [[Southern African Development Community]] (SADC) met and drafted the \"Prevention and Eradication of Violence Against Women and Children\", a document condemning violence against women and children, and resolved a set of 13 methods of addressing it, reaching into the legal; social, economic, cultural, and political; social service; and education, training, and awareness building sectors.<ref>{{cite journal | last = SADC| title = The prevention and eradication of violence against women and children | journal = Review of African Political Economy | volume = 26 | issue = 81 | pages = 415&ndash;417 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] | doi = 10.1080/03056249908704404 | jstor = 4006468 | date = September 1999 | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\nOn the transnational or regional level, the anti-violence movements also deploy different strategies based on the specificities of their cultures and beliefs in their particular regions. On this level, the activist movements are known as \"transnational feminist networks\" or TFNs.<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\" />{{rp|556}} The TFNs have a significant effect, like the autonomous movements on the national level, in shaping sets of policies as well pushing for the recognition and inclusion of language of VAW in the United Nations human rights mechanisms: the international human rights agreements.<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\" /> Their activities are ranging from lobbying the policy makers; organizing demonstrations on the local and regional levels; to creating institutional pressure that could push for changes in the international institutional measures.<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\" />\n\nOn an international level, the movements that advocate for women's rights and against VAW are the mixture of (civil society) actors from domestic and regional levels. The objectives of these VAW movements focus on \"creating shared expectations\" within the domestic and regional levels as well as \"mobilizing numbers of domestic civil society\" to create \"standards in global civil society\".<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\" />{{rp|556}} The global women's movement works to transform numbers of international conventions and conferences to \"a conference on women's rights\" by pushing for a \"stronger language and clearer recognition\" of the VAW issues. In addition, the United Nations also plays a vital role in promoting and campaigning for the VAW movements on the international level. For instance, in 2008 UN Secretary General [[Ban Ki-moon|Ban Ki-Moon]] initiated and launched a campaign called \"[[UNiTE to End Violence against Women]]\". This campaign \"calls on governments, civil society, women's organizations, young people, the private sector, the media and the entire UN system to join forces in addressing the global pandemic of violence against women and girls\".<ref name=\"UNiTE_Orange\">{{cite web | last = UNiTE | author-link = UNiTE to End Violence against Women | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131220093826/http://www.unwomen.org/en/what-we-do/ending-violence-against-women/take-action | archive-date = 20 December 2013 |url=http://www.unwomen.org/en/what-we-do/ending-violence-against-women/take-action |title=Take action to Orange your day |publisher=[[UN Women]] |date= 2013 | accessdate = 20 December 2013}}</ref> Moreover, this campaign also announces every 25th of the month to be \"Orange Day\" or \"a day to take action to raise awareness and prevent violence against women and girls\".<ref name=\"UNiTE_Orange\" />\n\nIn conclusion, each level of activism is intertwined and has the common purpose to end violence against women. Activism on local levels can significantly affect national, transnational, and international levels as well. In a scholarly article on ''Combating Violence Against Women'', the authors illustrated from their research analysis on how the norms of international society can shape and influence policy making on the domestic or national level and vice versa. They argue that there are three mechanisms which have effects on the making of national policies as well as global agreements and conventions: \"1) the influence of global treaties and documents such as [[CEDAW]] on women's rights\" - on the national policies \"2) the influence of regional agreements on VAW (particularly after certain tipping points are reached)\" - on both domestic policies and international conventions and \"3) regional demonstration effects or pressure for conformity captured as diffusion within regions\" - on the international norms and agreements.<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\" />\n\n=== Achievements of the VAW movements ===\nOn the global level:\n* The first major document that highlights the recognition of violence against women as a human rights violation: the United Nations [[Declaration on the Elimination of Violence Against Women]] in Vienna, 1993.<ref name=\"Brown Thompson 2002\">{{cite book | last = Brown Thompson | first = Karen | chapter = Women's rights are human rights | editor-last1 = Khagram | editor-first1 = Sanjeev | editor-last2 = Riker | editor-first2 = James V. | editor-last3 = Sikkink | editor-first3 = Kathryn | title = Restructuring world politics: transnational social movements, networks, and norms | pages = 96&ndash;122 | publisher = University of Minnesota Press | location = Minneapolis | year = 2002 | isbn = 9780816639076 | ref = harv }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = Elman | first = R. Amy | title = Sexual equality in an integrated Europe: virtual equality | publisher = Palgrave Macmillan | location = Basingstoke, UK | series = Europe in Transition: the NYU European Studies Series | year = 2008 | isbn = 9780230610071 }}</ref><ref name=\"Weldon, S.L 2006\">{{cite journal | last = Weldon | first = S. Laurel | title = Inclusion, solidarity, and social movements: the global movement against gender violence | journal = [[Perspectives on Politics]] | volume = 4 | issue = 1 | pages = 55&ndash;74 | publisher =  [[Cambridge University Press]] | doi = 10.1017/S1537592706060063 | jstor = 3688626 | date = March 2006 | ref = harv }}</ref> It was a result of collective effort of global feminist movement to transform the Vienna conference from a general and mainstream human rights conference into the conference on women's rights. As before the other human rights organizations such as Amnesty International and Human Rights Watch did not focus on the issue of VAW and did not consider rape and domestic violence as violations of human rights despite of the fact that they also have agenda on women's rights.<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\" />\n* The 1995 [[Fourth World Conference on Women]] in Beijing<ref>{{cite book | last = UN | author-link = United Nations |title=Beijing Declaration and Platform for Action |url=https://www.un.org/womenwatch/daw/beijing/pdf/BDPfA%20E.pdf |publisher=United Nations | date = 1995 |accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref> During the 4th Women Conference, VAW was emphasized and named as a critical concern. Also, the spillover effect was that this push highlighted the need for the development of \"new international norms\" that have often been used by activists and governments the proposition of legislation that provide other action to redress the acts of violence.<ref name=\"Brown Thompson 2002\"/><ref name=\"Weldon, S.L 2006\"/><ref>{{cite book | editor-last = F\u00e1bi\u00e1n | editor-first = Katalin | title = Domestic violence in postcommunist states: local activism, national policies, and global forces | publisher = Indiana University Press | location = Bloomington, Indiana| year = 2010 | isbn = 9780253222183 }}</ref>\n* Subsequently, the push from the global feminist movement also push for the fully incorporation of the VAW issues into the \"Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination Against Women\" or [[CEDAW]]<ref>{{cite book | last = CEDAW | author-link = CEDAW |title=Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination against Women |url=https://www.un.org/womenwatch/daw/cedaw/committee.htm |publisher=[[United Nations]] |date=31 December 2003 |accessdate=19 December 2013}}</ref> whereas the \"original text of [[CEDAW]] in 1979 did not explicitly mention violence against women\".<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\" />{{rp|556}}\n\nOn the regional level:\n* ''Americas'': the Inter-American Convention on Violence Against Women, which was formally announced and adopted by the [[Organization of American States]] (OAS) in 1994, immediately after the Vienna Conference<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\" />{{rp|557}}\n* ''Europe'': The [[European Union]] (EU)'s initiatives to combat violence against women after the 1990s: the 1997 resolution calling for a zero tolerance: specifically on UN human rights instruments of [[CEDAW]] and the [[Vienna Declaration and Programme of Action|Vienna Declaration]].\n** The [[Council of Europe]] also developed \"a series of initiatives\" related to the issue of VAW: \"the 2000 resolution on trafficking, the 2003 resolution on domestic violence, and the 2004 resolution on honor crimes\" as well as promoted \"the 2002 recommendation on the protection of women against violence and established its monitoring framework\".<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\" />{{rp|557}}\n* ''Africa'': \n** There emerged a series of regional meetings and agreements, which was triggered by the UN processes on the international level such as Third World Conference on Women in Nairobi, 1985; the 1993 Kampala Prep Com; the 1994 Africa-wide UN women's conference<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Tripp | first1 = Aili Mari | last2 = Casimiro | first2 = Isabel | last3 = Kwesiga | first3 = Joy | last4 = Mungwa | first4 = Alice | title = African women's movements: transforming political landscapes | publisher = Cambridge University Press | location = Cambridge New York | year = 2009 | isbn = 9780511479014 }}</ref> that led to the identification of VAW as a critical issue in the Southern African Women's Charter.<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\" />{{rp|557}}\n\n==Access to justice for female victims of violence==\n\n===International and regional instruments===\nEfforts to fight violence against women can take many forms and access to justice, or lack thereof, for such violence varies greatly depending on the justice system. International and regional instruments are increasingly used as the basis for national legislation and policies to eradicate violence against women.\n\nThe Inter-American Convention to Prevent, Eradicate and Punish Violence Against Women \u2013 also known as the Bel\u00e9m do Par\u00e0 Convention, for instance, has been applied by the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights (IACHR) in its first case of domestic violence to condemn Brazil in the Maria da Penha case. This led the Brazilian government to enact in 2006 the Maria da Penha Law, the country's first law against domestic violence against women.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Spieler | first = Paula | title = The Maria da Penha Case and the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights: contributions to the debate on domestic violence against women in Brazil | journal = [[Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies]] | volume = 18 | issue = 1 | pages = 121&ndash;143 | publisher = [[Indiana University Maurer School of Law]] | date = Winter 2011 | url = https://muse.jhu.edu/article/445824 | ref = harv | doi=10.2979/indjglolegstu.18.1.121}}</ref> There is also, for instance, the South Asian Agreement on Regional Cooperation's (SAARC) Protocol to End Trafficking in Women and Children.<ref name=\"Fried\" />\n\n===Examples of measures put in place===\nAs violence is often committed by a family member, women first started by lobbying their governments to set up shelters for domestic violence survivors. The Julia Burgos Protected House established in Puerto Rico in 1979 was the first shelter in Latin America and the Caribbean for \"battered women\". In 2003, 18 out of the 20 countries in the region had legislation on domestic or family violence, and 11 countries addressed sexual violence in their laws. Legislative measures to protect victims can include restraining orders, which can be found in Colombia, El Salvador, Guatemala, Paraguay, Venezuela, Turkey, the United States and many western European countries for instance.\n\nCourts can also be allowed by law (Germany, 2001) to order the perpetrator to leave the home so that victims do not have to seek shelter. Countries were urged to repeal discriminatory legislation by 2005 following the review of the Beijing Declaration and Platform for Action in 2000. Egypt, for instance, abolished a law that exempted men from rape charges when marrying their victims. However, the goal of antiviolence legislation is often to keep the families together, regardless of the best interests of women, which perpetuate domestic violence.<ref name=\"Fried\" />\n\nInnovative measures have been pioneered in a number of countries to end violence against women. In Brazil and Jordan, [[women's police stations]] have been introduced, and one-stop [[women's shelter]]s were created in Malaysia and Nicaragua.\n\n[[Marital rape]] has been illegal in every American state and the District of Columbia since 1993, but is rarely prosecuted in America.<ref name=\"rainn.org\">{{cite web |title=Marital rape | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131201082952/http://www.rainn.org/public-policy/sexual-assault-issues/marital-rape | archive-date = 1 December 2013 |url=http://www.rainn.org/public-policy/sexual-assault-issues/marital-rape |website=rainn.org | publisher = [[Rape, Abuse and Incest National Network]] (RAINN) |date= |accessdate=8 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 the [[UN General Assembly]] passed its first resolution calling for the protection of defenders of women's human rights.<ref name=\"Norway Post\" /> The resolution urges states to put in place gender-specific laws and policies for the protection of women's human rights defenders and to ensure that defenders themselves are involved in the design and implementation of these measures, and calls on states to protect women's human rights defenders from reprisals for cooperating with the UN and to ensure their unhindered access to and communication with international human rights bodies and mechanisms.<ref name=\"awid.org\"/>\n\n=== Challenges faced by women in accessing justice and limitations of measures ===\nThere can be a de jure or de facto acceptance of violent behaviors and lack of remedies for victims.<ref name=\"Fried\" />\n\n*'''Lack of criminalization:''' in many places, acts of abuse, especially acts such as [[female genital mutilation]], [[marital rape]], [[forced marriage]] and [[child marriage]], are not criminalized, or are illegal but widely tolerated, with the laws against them being rarely enforced. There are instances where crimes against women are also categorized as minor offenses.\n*'''Lack of awareness of the existing laws:''' in many places, although there are laws against violence on the books, many women do not know of their existence. This is especially the case with marital rape - its criminalization being very recent in most countries.<ref>''Citations'':\n* {{cite book | last = AI | author-link = Amnesty International | title = ''Hungary \u2013'' Cries unheard: ''The failure to protect women from rape and sexual violence in the home''|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/documents/eur27/002/2007/en/ |accessdate=12 December 2013 | format = PDF | id = EUR 27/002/2007 | publisher = [[Amnesty International]] }}\n* {{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Hungary law 'fails rape victims' | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/6643727.stm | work=[[BBC News]] | date = 10 May 2007 | accessdate = 12 December 2013}}\n* {{cite news | last = Moy | first = Patsy |url=http://www.scmp.com/article/435610/publicity-urged-law-marital-rape |title=Publicity urged for law on marital rape |work=[[South China Morning Post]] |date= 23 November 2003 |accessdate=12 December 2013}}</ref>\n*'''Challenges in making a case in court:''' the burden of proof can be placed on the victim. For instance in the Philippines, before a change in law in 1997, rape used to be described as a crime against chastity; and virginity played an important role in court. In various countries, such as [[Bangladesh]], a woman's past sexual experience continues to be very important in a case of rape. Bangladesh has received criticism for its employment of the \"two-finger test\" in rape investigations. This test consists in a physical examination of women who report rape during which a doctor inserts two fingers in the woman's vagina to determine whether the woman is \"habituated to sex\". This examination has its origin in the country's British colonial-era laws dating back to 1872. This deters many women from reporting rape. More than 100 experts, including doctors, lawyers, police, and women's rights activists had signed a joint statement in 2013 asking for the test, which they called \"demeaning\", to be abolished, as it \"does not provide any evidence that is relevant to proving the offence\". This test is also performed in several other countries in the region, including India.<ref>''Citations'':\n* {{cite book | last = Press release |title=100 experts demand change in medical evidence laws and justice for rape victims |url= http://www.blast.org.bd/content/pressrelease/press-release-nc-2-2-2013.pdf |publisher=Bangladesh Legal Aid Services Trust | date = 2 February 2013 |accessdate=4 April 2016}}\n* {{cite news | last = Agence France-Presse | author-link = Agence France-Presse | title = Bangladesh activists urge ban on rape victim 'finger test' | url = http://www.ndtv.com/article/world/bangladesh-activists-urge-ban-on-rape-victim-finger-test-326175 | work = [[NDTV]] | date = 4 February 2013 | accessdate = 4 April 2016}}\n* {{cite news|last=Park |first=Madison |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/02/05/world/asia/rape-exam-india/index.html |title=Activists: Get rid of 'degrading' parts of India's sexual assault exam |work=[[CNN]] |date=5 February 2013  |accessdate=4 April 2016}}</ref> It can also be difficult to make a case of sexual assault in court, when members of the judiciary expect evidence of severe struggle and injury as determinative evidence of non-consent. On the other hand, there are measures, such as the 2012 law in Brazil, that allow for cases to be filed even without the representation of the victim.\n*'''Existing laws are insufficient, conflicting, and have no effect in practice:''' some laws on domestic violence, for instance, conflict with other provisions and ultimately contradict their goals. Legal frameworks can also be flawed when laws that integrate protection do so in isolation, notably in relation to immigration laws. Undocumented women in countries where they would have, in theory, access to justice, don't in practice for fear of being denounced and deported. The CEDAW Committee recommends that a State authority's obligation to report undocumented persons be repealed in national legislation.\n*'''The attitude of the police:''' women who report acts of violence most often come into contact first with police workers. Therefore, police attitudes are crucial in facilitating a sense of safety and comfort for women who have been victimized.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Logan | first1 = T. K. | last2 = Shannon | first2 = Lisa | last3 = Walker | first3 = Robert | title = Police attitudes toward domestic violence offenders | journal = [[Journal of Interpersonal Violence]] | volume = 21 | issue = 10 | pages = 1365&ndash;1374 | publisher = [[Sage Publications|Sage]] | doi = 10.1177/0886260506291653 | pmid = 16940401 | date = October 2006 | ref = harv }}</ref> When police officers have hostile attitudes towards victimized women, these women are prevented from obtaining justice.<ref>{{cite news | last = Travis | first = Alan | title = Police treatment of domestic abuse victims to be investigated | url = https://www.theguardian.com/society/2016/may/17/police-treatment-of-domestic-abuse-victims-to-be-investigated | work = [[The Guardian]] | date = 17 May 2016 | access-date = 21 October 2017}}</ref> Recognizing these problems, some countries have enacted [[women's police station]], which are [[police station]]s that specialize in certain crimes, such as [[sexual violence]], [[harassment]], [[domestic violence]] committed against women.\n\nMeasures to address violence against women range from access to legal-aid to the provision of shelters and hotlines for victims. Despite advances in legislation and policies, the lack of implementation of the measures put in place prevents significant progress in eradicating violence against women globally. This failure to apply existing laws and procedures is often due to the persisting issue of gender stereotyping.<ref>{{cite book | last = CEDAW | author-link = CEDAW | title = General discussion on women and access to justice | url = http://wilpf.org/cedaw-general-discussion-on-women-and-access-to-justice/ | publisher = [[United Nations]] | location = Geneva, Switzerland | date = 18 February 2013 | accessdate = 12 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Relation with marriage laws==\n[[File:Marriage_is_no_excuse_for_rape.png|thumb|Sign against justification of violence in marriage]] \n{{Further|Criticism of marriage|Sexism#Coverture_and_other_marriage_regulations}}\nThe relation between violence against women and marriage laws, regulations and traditions has also been discussed.<ref>{{cite book | last = Chambers | first = Clare | title = Recognizing marriage as a symbolic institution |url= http://citation.allacademic.com/meta/p_mla_apa_research_citation/0/4/1/2/5/p41259_index.html |publisher=American Political Science Association | location = Washington, D.C. |date= 1 September 2005 | accessdate = 12 December 2013}} Paper presented at the annual meeting of the American Political Science Association.\n:''For a later version of this paper see'':\n:* {{cite book | last = Chambers | first = Clare | title = Feminism, liberalism and marriage (workshop) | url = https://www.brown.edu/Research/ppw/past_07_08.html | publisher = Political Philosophy Workshop at [[Brown University]] | date = 10 April 2008 }} [https://www.brown.edu/Research/ppw/files/Feminism,%20Liberalism%20and%20Marriage.doc Word document.]</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = Jeffreys | first = Sheila | author-link = Sheila Jeffreys | title = The industrial vagina: the political economy of the global sex trade | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=9mlFgjEBYWYC | publisher = Routledge | location = London New York | year = 2009 | series = RIPE Series in Global Political Economy | isbn = 9780415412322 }}</ref> The US and English law subscribed until the 20th century to the system of [[coverture]], that is, a legal doctrine under which, upon marriage, a woman's legal rights were subsumed by those of her husband.<ref>{{cite book | last = Blackstone | first = William | author-link = William Blackstone | chapter = Husband and wife | chapterurl = http://www.lonang.com/exlibris/blackstone/bla-115.htm | title = Commentaries on the laws of England (1765-1769), vol 1: Of the rights of persons | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = Oxford, United Kingdom New York, NY | year = 2016 | origyear = 1765 | isbn = 9780199600991 }}</ref> Today, outside the West, many countries severely restrict the rights of married women: for example, in [[Yemen]], marriage regulations state that a wife must obey her husband and must not leave home without his permission.<ref>{{cite book | last = AI | author-link = Amnesty International | title = Yemen's dark side: discrimination and violence against women and girls | url = https://www.amnesty.org/en/documents/MDE31/014/2009/en/ |publisher=[[Amnesty International]] | id = MDE 31/014/2009 | date = November 2009 | accessdate = 12 December 2013}}</ref> In [[Iraq]] husbands have a legal right to \"punish\" their wives. The criminal code states at Paragraph 41 that there is no crime if an act is committed while exercising a legal right; examples of legal rights include: \"The punishment of a wife by her husband, the disciplining by parents and teachers of children under their authority within certain limits prescribed by law or by custom\".<ref>{{cite book | title = Statutory notice: The [Iraqi] penal-code with amendments | id = STS 251/88 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121021100954/http://law.case.edu/saddamtrial/documents/Iraqi_Penal_Code_1969.pdf | archive-date = 21 October 2012 | url = http://law.case.edu/saddamtrial/documents/Iraqi_Penal_Code_1969.pdf | publisher = Case Western Reserve University School of Law | date = 1969 | accessdate = 12 December 2013}}</ref> In the West, married women faced discrimination until just a few decades ago: for instance, in [[France]], married women received the right to work without their husband's permission in 1965.<ref>''Citations'':\n* {{cite journal | last = Allwood | first = Gill | title = Women in France |url=http://www.tandf.co.uk/journals/explore/cmcf-vsi-women-in-france.pdf | journal = Modern & Contemporary France |publisher=[[Taylor and Francis]] | accessdate = 12 December 2013}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://marinablue.fr/voicepress/frances-leading-women-show-the-way/ |title=France's leading women show the way | website = marinablue.fr |publisher=Paris Voice |date= November 1997| accessdate = 12 December 2013}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.womeninworldhistory.com/TWR-07.html|title= \"''The Wife is Obliged''\": The French Civil Code (Napoleonic Code) 1800-1820 | website = womeninworldhistory |publisher=Women in World History Curriculum | accessdate = 12 December 2013}}</ref> In [[Spain]], during the Franco era, a married woman required her husband's consent (''permiso marital'') for nearly all economic activities, including employment, ownership of property and traveling away from home; the permiso marital was abolished in 1975.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Solsten | first1 = Eric | last2 = Meditz | first2 = Sandra W. | chapter = Social values and attitudes | chapterurl = http://countrystudies.us/spain/43.htm | editor-last1 = Solsten | editor-first1 = Eric | editor-last2 = Meditz | editor-first2 = Sandra W. | title = Spain: a country study | publisher = Library of Congress, Federal Research Division | location = Washington, DC | year = 1988 | oclc = 712557481}}</ref> Concerns exist about violence related to marriage - both inside marriage (physical abuse, sexual violence, restriction of liberty) and in relation to marriage customs ([[dowry]], [[bride price]], [[forced marriage]], [[child marriage]], [[marriage by abduction]], violence related to female premarital [[virginity]]). Claudia Card, professor of Philosophy at the University of Wisconsin-Madison, writes:<ref>{{cite journal | last = Card | first = Claudia | title = Against marriage and motherhood | journal = [[Hypatia (journal)|Hypatia: A Journal of Feminist Philosophy]] | volume = 11 | issue = 3 | pages = 1&ndash;23 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1527-2001.1996.tb01013.x | jstor = 3810319 | date = August 1996 | ref = harv }} [https://pol285.blog.gustavus.edu/files/2009/08/Card_Against_Marriage.pdf Pdf.]</ref>\n:\"The legal rights of access that married partners have to each other's persons, property, and lives makes it all but impossible for a spouse to defend herself (or himself), or to be protected against torture, rape, battery, stalking, mayhem, or murder by the other spouse... Legal marriage thus enlists state support for conditions conducive to murder and mayhem.\"\n\n==Istanbul Convention==\nThe [[Council of Europe Convention on preventing and combating violence against women and domestic violence]], also known as the Istanbul Convention, is the first legally binding instrument in Europe in the field of domestic violence and violence against women,<ref>https://www.oas.org/es/mesecvi/docs/CSW-SideEvent2014-Flyer-EN.pdf</ref> and came into force in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|author=Bureau des Trait\u00e9s |url=http://www.conventions.coe.int/Treaty/Commun/ChercheSig.asp?NT=210&CM=&DF=&CL=ENG |title=Liste compl\u00e8te |publisher=Conventions.coe.int |date= |accessdate=18 July 2016}}</ref>\nCountries which ratify it must ensure that the forms of violence defined in its text are outlawed. In its Preamble, the Convention states that \"the realisation of ''de jure'' and ''de facto'' equality between women and men is a key element in the prevention of violence against women\". The Convention also provides a definition of [[domestic violence]] as \"all acts of physical, sexual, psychological or economic violence that occur within the family or domestic unit or between former or current spouses or partners, whether or not the perpetrator shares or has shared the same residence with the victim\".<ref name=\"Istanbul\">{{cite web|url=http://www.conventions.coe.int/Treaty/EN/Treaties/Html/210.htm|title=Council of Europe \u2013 Convention on preventing and combating violence against women and domestic violence (CETS No. 210)|work=coe.int|accessdate=8 October 2015}}</ref> Although it is a Convention of the [[Council of Europe]], it is open to accession by any country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coe.int/t/dghl/standardsetting/convention-violence/thematic_factsheets/IC%20Global%20Tool_EN.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=8 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221131635/http://www.coe.int/t/dghl/standardsetting/convention-violence/thematic_factsheets/IC%20Global%20Tool_EN.pdf |archivedate=21 February 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n<!-- New links in alphabetical order please -->\n{{Columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n*[[Bodily integrity]]\n*[[Children's rights]]\n*[[Eve teasing]]\n*[[List of incidents of violence against women]], list of notable incidents of violence against women sorted by country and year\n*[[Men's rights movement]]\n*[[Military sexual trauma]]\n*[[Misogyny in horror films]]\n*[[Rhinotomy]]\n*[[School-related gender-based violence (SRGBV)]]\n*[[Sexism]]\n*[[Sexual assault in the U.S. military]]\n*[[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1325]]\n*[[Violence against LGBT people]]\n*[[Violence against men]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite journal | last = Almosaed | first = Nora | title = Violence against women: a cross\u2010cultural perspective | journal = [[Institute of Muslim Minority Affairs#Journal of Muslim Minority Affairs|Journal of Muslim Minority Affairs]] | volume = 24 | issue = 1 | pages = 67&ndash;88 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] | doi = 10.1080/1360200042000212124 | date = 2004 | ref = harv }}\n* {{Cite news | last = Appiah | first = Kwame Anthony | author-link = Kwame Anthony Appiah | title = Convincing other cultures to change | work = [[Big Think]] | date = 21 September 2010 | url = http://bigthink.com/videos/convincing-other-cultures-to-change | url-status = bot: unknown | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131212131130/http://bigthink.com/videos/convincing-other-cultures-to-change | archivedate = 12 December 2013 | df = dmy-all }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Bellemare | first1 = Marc F. | last2 = Steinmetz | first2 = Tara L. | title = All in the family: explaining the persistence of female genital cutting in the Gambia | journal = [[Social Science Research Network]] | doi = 10.2139/ssrn.2280086 | ssrn = 2280086 | date = 17 June 2013  | url = http://marcfbellemare.com/wordpress/2013/06/explaining-the-persistence-of-female-genital-cutting-in-the-gambia/ | ref = harv }} [http://marcfbellemare.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/BellemareSteinmetzFGCJune2013.pdf Pdf.]\n* {{cite book | last1 = Dobash | first1 = Russell P. | last2 = Dobash | first2 = R. Emerson | title = Women, violence and social change | publisher = Routledge | location = Abingdon, Oxon | year = 2016 | isbn = 9781138174023 }}\n*{{Cite journal | last1 = Durham | first1 = Meenakshi G. | authorlink1 = Meenakshi Gigi Durham | title = \"Vicious Assault Shakes Texas Town\": the politics of gender violence in ''The New York Times''<nowiki>'</nowiki> coverage of a schoolgirl's gang rape | journal = Journalism Studies | volume = 14 | issue = 1 | pages = 1&ndash;12 | publisher = [[Taylor & Francis]] | doi = 10.1080/1461670X.2012.657907 | date = February 2013 | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite book | last = Heise | first = Lori L. | last2 = Pitanguy | first2 = Jacqueline | last3 = Germain | first3 = Adrienne | title = Violence against women: the hidden health burden | journal = World Health Statistics Quarterly. Rapport Trimestriel de Statistiques Sanitaires Mondiales | volume = 46 | issue = 1 | pages = 78\u201385 | publisher = World Bank | location = Washington, D.C | year = 1994 | isbn = 9780821329801 | pmid = 8237054 }} Discussion Paper No. 255\n* {{cite journal | last1 = James | first1 = Stanlie M. | title = Shades of othering: reflections on female circumcision/genital mutilation | journal = [[Signs (journal)|Signs: Journal of Women in Culture and Society]] | volume = 23 | issue = 4 | pages = 1031&ndash;1048 | publisher = [[University of Chicago Press]] | doi = 10.1086/495300 | jstor = 3175202 | date = Summer 1998 | ref = harv }} \n* {{cite journal | last1 = Jones | first1 = Helen | last2 = Diop | first2 = Nafissatou | last3 = Askew | first3 = Ian | last4 = Kabor\u00e9 | first4 = Inoussa | title = Female genital cutting practices in Burkina Faso and Mali and their negative health outcomes | journal = [[Studies in Family Planning]] | volume = 30 | issue = 3 | pages = 219&ndash;230 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1728-4465.1999.00219.x | pmid = 10546313 | date = September 1999 | ref = harv }} \n* {{cite journal | last1 = Jones | first1 = Wanda K. | last2 = Smith | first2 = Jack | last3 = Kieke, Jr. | first3 = Burney | last4 = Wilcox | first4 = Lynne | title = Female genital mutilation/female circumcision: who is at risk in the US? | journal = [[Public Health Reports]] | volume = 112 | issue = 5 | pages = 368&ndash;377  | pmc = 1381943 | date = September 1997 | ref = harv | pmid=9323387}} [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1381943/pdf/pubhealthrep00038-0014.pdf Pdf.]\n* {{Cite journal | last = Kelly | first = Liz | author-link = Liz Kelly | title = Inside outsiders: Mainstreaming violence against women into human rights discourse and practice | journal = International Feminist Journal of Politics | volume = 7 | issue = 4 | pages = 471&ndash;495 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] | doi = 10.1080/14616740500284391 | date = December 2005 | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite journal | last = Mackie | first = Gerry | title = Female genital cutting: a harmless practice? | journal = [[Medical Anthropology Quarterly]] | volume = 17 | issue = 2 | pages = 135&ndash;158 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] on behalf of the [[American Anthropological Association]] | doi = 10.1525/maq.2003.17.2.135 | pmid = 12846114 | jstor = 3655332 | date = June 2003 | ref = harv }} [http://dss.ucsd.edu/~gmackie/documents/FGCHarmlessPractice.pdf Pdf.]\n* {{cite journal | last = Shell-Duncan | first = Bettina | last2 = Herniund | first2 = Yiva | title = Are there \"Stages of Change\" in the practice of female genital cutting?: Qualitative research findings from Senegal and The Gambia | journal = African Journal of Reproductive Health [La Revue Africaine de la Sant\u00e9 Reproductive] | volume = 10 | issue = 2 | pages = 57&ndash;71 | publisher = Women's Health and Action Research Centre (WHARC) | doi = 10.2307/30032459 | jstor = 30032459 | date = August 2006| url = http://www.bioline.org.br/abstract?id=rh06027&lang=en | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite book | last = Skaine | first = Rosemarie | title = Female genital mutilation: legal, cultural, and medical issues | publisher = McFarland & Company, Inc. | location = Jefferson, North Caroline | year = 2005 | isbn = 9780786421671 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Wagner | first = Natascha | title = Why female genital cutting persist? | series = Working Paper | publisher = University of Rotterdam | url = http://www.natascha-wagner.com/uploads/9/0/1/5/9015445/fgc_march2013.pdf | date = March 2013 }}\n* {{cite book | last = True | first = Jacqui | title = The political economy of violence against women | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = New York, NY | year = 2012 | isbn = 9780199755912 }}\n* {{cite journal | last = Wakabi | first = Wairagala | title = Africa battles to make female genital mutilation history | journal = [[The Lancet]] | volume = 369 | issue = 9567| pages = 1069&ndash;1070 | publisher = [[Elsevier]] | pmid = 17405200 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(07)60508-X | date = 31 March 2007 | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Williams | first1 = Lindy | last2 = Sobieszczyk | first2 = Teresa | title = Attitudes surrounding the continuation of female circumcision in the Sudan: passing the tradition to the next generation | journal = [[Journal of Marriage and Family]] | volume = 59 | issue = 4 | pages = 966&ndash;981 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.2307/353796 | jstor = 353796 | date = November 1997 | ref = harv }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{dmoz|Society/People/Women/Issues/Violence_and_Abuse}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110516094651/http://www.echr.coe.int/NR/rdonlyres/39C38938-2E29-4151-9280-D5AC063DD02E/0/FICHES_Violence_femmes_EN.pdf Violence against women], a factsheet on [[ECtHR]] case law\n* [http://www.endvawnow.org/ Virtual Knowledge Centre to End Violence against Women and Girls] (in English, French, and Spanish)\n* [http://www.ohchr.org/EN/Issues/Women/SRWomen/Pages/SRWomenIndex.aspx UN Special Rapporteur on violence against women, its causes and consequences]\n* [http://www.who.int/reproductivehealth/publications/fgm/en/index.html World Health Organization's reports on FGM], Health complications of female genital mutilation\n\n{{abuse}}\n{{Domestic violence}}\n{{Violence against women by country}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Violence Against Women}}\n[[Category:Violence against women| ]]\n[[Category:Sex industry]]\n[[Category:Feminism and health]]\n[[Category:Gender-related violence|Against Women]]\n[[Category:Misogyny]]\n[[Category:Crimes against women]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Violent acts committed primarily against women and girls}}\n[[File:MURDER-SCALE-4-2019.jpg|thumb|A map of the world showing Murders per 100,000 population committed against women, 2019]]\n{{For|the journal|Violence Against Women (journal)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2012}}\n{{pp-semi-sock|small=yes}}\n{{Violence against women}}\n{{Feminism sidebar}}\n{{Discrimination sidebar|state=collapsed}}\n'''Violence against women''' ('''VAW'''), also known as '''gender-based violence'''<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Russo | first1 = Nancy Felipe | last2 = Pirlott | first2 = Angela | title = Gender-based violence: concepts, methods, and findings | journal = [[Annals of the New York Academy of Sciences]] |issue=Violence and Exploitation Against Women and Girls | volume = 1087 | pages = 178&ndash;205 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] and [[Oxfam]] | doi = 10.1196/annals.1385.024 | pmid = 17189506 | date = November 2006 | ref = harv | bibcode = 2006NYASA1087..178R }}</ref> and '''sexual and gender-based violence''' ('''SGBV'''),<ref>[http://www.who.int/hac/techguidance/pht/SGBV/en/ Sexual and Gender-based Violence] (WHO)</ref> are violent acts the victims of which are primarily or exclusively [[woman|women]] or girls. Such violence is often considered a form of [[hate crime]],<ref>''Citations'':\n* {{cite book | last = Angelari | first = Marguerite | chapter = Hate crime statutes: a promising tool for fighting violence against women | chapterurl = https://books.google.com/books?id=2YdCbgXjr-EC&pg=PA405 | editor-last = Maschke | editor-first = Karen J. | title = Pornography, sex work, and hate speech | pages = 405&ndash;448 | publisher = Taylor and Francis | location = New York | year = 1997 | isbn = 9780815325208 }} \n* {{cite book | last = Gerstenfeld | first = Phyllis B. | chapter = The hate debate: constitutional and policy problems | chapterurl = https://books.google.com/books?id=DiBIZcx1nPcC&pg=PA58 | editor-last = Gerstenfeld | editor-first = Phyllis B. | title = Hate crimes: causes, controls, and controversies | page = 58 | publisher = Sage | location = Thousand Oaks, California | year = 2013 | isbn = 9781452256627 }}\n* {{cite book | last = McPhail | first = Beverly | chapter = Gender-bias hate crimes: a review | chapterurl = https://books.google.com/books?id=2ZNnXj_SbOsC&pg=PA271 | editor-last = Perry | editor-first = Barbara | title = Hate and bias crime: a reader | page = 271 | publisher = Routledge | location = New York | year = 2003 | isbn = 9780415944076 }}</ref> committed against women or girls specifically because they are female, and can take many forms. \n\nVAW has a very long history, though the incidents and intensity of such violence has varied over time and even today varies between societies. Such violence is often seen as a mechanism for the subjugation of women, whether in society in general or in an [[interpersonal relationship]]. Such violence may arise from a sense of [[entitlement]], [[superior (hierarchy)|superior]]ity, [[misogyny]] or similar attitudes in the perpetrator, or because of his violent nature, especially against women. \n\nThe UN [[Declaration on the Elimination of Violence Against Women]] states, \"violence against women is a manifestation of historically unequal power relations between men and women\" and \"violence against women is one of the crucial social mechanisms by which women are forced into a subordinate position compared with men.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.un-documents.net/a48r104.htm |title=A/RES/48/104 - Declaration on the Elimination of Violence against Women |publisher=United Nations General Assembly |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n[[Kofi Annan]], [[Secretary-General of the United Nations]], declared in a 2006 report posted on the [[United Nations Development Fund for Women]] (UNIFEM) website:<blockquote>Violence against women and girls is a problem of [[pandemic]] proportions. At least one out of every three women around the world has been beaten, coerced into sex, or otherwise abused in her lifetime with the abuser usually someone known to her.<ref name=\"Moradian\">{{cite web |url=http://en.tolerancy.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=176:2009-09-15-08-37-55&catid=43:events-a-reports&Itemid=90 |title=Domestic Violence against Single and Married Women in Iranian Society |last=Moradian |first=Azad |work=Tolerancy.org |publisher=[[The Chicago School of Professional Psychology]] |date=10 September 2010 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425230632/http://en.tolerancy.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=176%3A2009-09-15-08-37-55&catid=43%3Aevents-a-reports&Itemid=90 |archivedate=25 April 2012 |accessdate=1 March 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref></blockquote>\n{{TOC limit|3}}\n\n==Types of violence==\nViolence against women can fit into several broad categories. These include violence carried out by individuals as well as states. Some of the forms of violence perpetrated by individuals are: [[rape]], [[domestic violence]], [[sexual harassment]], [[acid throwing]], [[reproductive coercion]], [[female infanticide]], [[sex selective abortion|prenatal sex selection]], [[obstetric violence]], and [[mob violence]]; as well as harmful customary or traditional practices such as [[honor killings]], [[dowry death|dowry violence]], [[female genital mutilation]], [[marriage by abduction]] and [[forced marriage]]. There are forms of violence which may be perpetrated or condoned by the government, such as [[war rape]]; [[sexual violence]] and [[sexual slavery]] during conflict; [[forced sterilization]]; [[forced abortion]]; violence by the police and authoritative personnel; [[stoning]] and [[flogging]]. Many forms of VAW, such as [[trafficking in women]] and [[forced prostitution]] are often perpetrated by organized criminal networks.<ref name=\"Pr\u00fcgl, E. 2013\">{{cite book | last = Pr\u00fcgl | first = Elisabeth (Director) | title = Violence Against Women. Gender and International Affairs Class 2013. Lecture conducted from The Graduate Institute of International and Development Studies (IHEID) | location = Geneva, Switzerland | date = 25 November 2013 }}</ref> Histrorically, there have been forms of organized WAV, such as the [[Witch trials in the early modern period]] or the [[sexual slavery]] of the [[Comfort women]].\n\nThe [[World Health Organization]] (WHO), in its research on VAW, has analyzed and categorized the different forms of VAW occurring through all stages of life from before birth to old age.<ref name=\"WHO_VAW\">{{cite book | last = WHO | author-link = World Health Organization | title = Violence against women: Definition and scope of the problem, 1, 1-3 | url = http://www.who.int/gender/violence/v4.pdf | publisher = [[World Health Organization]] | date = July 1997 | access-date = 30 November 2013 }}</ref>\n\nIn recent years, there has been a trend of approaching VAW at an international level  through means such as conventions or, in the [[European Union]], through [[Directive (European Union)|directive]]s (such as the directive against [[sexual harassment]], and the directive against [[human trafficking]]).<ref>{{cite web | title = Directive 2002/73/EC - equal treatment of 23 September 2002 amending Council Directive 76/207/EEC on the implementation of the principle of equal treatment for men and women as regards access to employment, vocational training and promotion, and working conditions | url = http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=CONSLEG:1976L0207:20021005:EN:PDF |format=PDF | date = September 2002}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/LexUriServ/LexUriServ.do?uri=OJ:L:2011:101:0001:0011:EN:PDF |format=PDF |title= Directive 2011/36/EU of the European Parliament and of the Council of 5 April 2011 on preventing and combating trafficking in human beings and protecting its victims, and replacing Council Framework Decision 2002/629/JH |work=Official Journal of the European Union |accessdate=4 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Definition==\nA number of international instruments that aim to eliminate violence against women and domestic violence have been enacted by various international bodies. These generally start with a definition of what such violence is, with a view to combating such practices. The Istanbul Convention ([[Council of Europe Convention on preventing and combating violence against women and domestic violence]]) of the [[Council of Europe]] describes VAW \"as a violation of human rights and a form of discrimination against women\" and defines VAW as \"all acts of gender-based violence that result in, or are likely to result in, physical, sexual, psychological or economic harm or suffering to women, including threats of such acts, coercion or arbitrary deprivation of liberty, whether occurring in public or in private life.<ref name=\"COE 210\">{{cite web |url=https://www.coe.int/en/web/conventions/full-list/-/conventions/treaty/210 |title=Details of Treaty No.210: Council of Europe Convention on preventing and combating violence against women and domestic violence |publisher=Council of Europe |date= |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe 1979 [[Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women]] (CEDAW) of the [[United Nations General Assembly]] makes recommendations relating to VAW,<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |title=General recommendations made by the Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination against Women |url=https://www.un.org/womenwatch/daw/cedaw/recommendations/recomm.htm#recom1 |website=www.un.org |accessdate=2015-05-08 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150510132556/http://www.un.org/womenwatch/daw/cedaw/recommendations/recomm.htm#recom1 |archivedate=10 May 2015 |df=dmy-all }}, General Recommendations 12 and 19</ref> and the [[Vienna Declaration and Programme of Action]] mentions VAW.<ref>{{cite web |date=12 July 1993 |url=http://www.refworld.org/cgi-bin/texis/vtx/rwmain?page=topic&tocid=459d17822&toid=459b17a82&docid=3ae6b39ec&skip=O |title=Vienna Declaration and Programme of Action |publisher=UN General Assembly |accessdate=3 April 2016}}, paragraph 18</ref> However, the 1993 [[United Nations General Assembly]] resolution on the [[Declaration on the Elimination of Violence Against Women]] was the first international instrument to explicitly define VAW and elaborate on the subject.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unwomen.org/en/what-we-do/ending-violence-against-women/global-norms-and-standards |title=What We Do: Ending Violence against Women: Global Norms and Standards |publisher=UN Women |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> Other definitions of VAW are set out in the 1994 ''Inter-American Convention on the Prevention, Punishment, and Eradication of Violence against Women''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oas.org/juridico/english/treaties/a-61.html |title=Inter-American Convention On The Prevention, Punishment And Eradication Of Violence Against Women \"Convention Of Belem Do Para\" |publisher=Organization of American States |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> and by the 2003 [[Maputo Protocol]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.achpr.org/files/instruments/women-protocol/achpr_instr_proto_women_eng.pdf |title=Protocol to the African Charter on Human and Peoples' Rights on the Rights of Women in Africa |publisher=African Commission on Human and Peoples' Rights |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, the term ''gender-based violence'' refers to \"any acts or threats of acts intended to hurt or make women suffer physically, sexually or psychologically, and which affect women because they are women or affect women disproportionately\".<ref>{{cite book | last = Richters | first = J.M. Annemiek | title = Women, culture and violence: a development, health and human rights issue | publisher = Women and Autonomy Centre (VENA), Leiden University | location = Leiden, The Netherlands | year = 1994 | url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KvbtAAAAMAAJ | oclc = 905570045 | isbn = 9789072631374 }}</ref> The definition of gender-based violence is most often \"used interchangeably with violence against women\",<ref name=\"Krantz\">{{cite journal | last1 = Krantz | first1 = Gunilla | last2 = Garcia-Moreno | first2 = Claudia | title = Violence against women | journal = [[Journal of Epidemiology and Community Health]] | volume = 59 | issue = 10 | pages = 818&ndash;821 | publisher = [[BMJ Group]] | doi = 10.1136/jech.2004.022756 | jstor = 25570854 | pmid = 16166351 | pmc = 1732916 | date = October 2005 | ref = harv }}</ref> and some articles on VAW reiterate these conceptions by suggesting that men are the main perpetrators of this violence.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Sen | first = Purna | title = Development practice and violence against women | journal = Gender & Development | volume = 6 | issue = 3 | pages = 7&ndash;16 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] and [[Oxfam]] | doi = 10.1080/741922827 | pmid = 12294415 | jstor = 4030497 | date = November 1998 | ref = harv }}</ref> Moreover, the definition stated by the 1993 Declaration on the Elimination of Violence Against Women also supported the notion that violence is rooted in the inequality between men and women when the term violence is used together with the term 'gender-based.'<ref name=\"Krantz\"/>\n\nIn ''Recommendation Rec(2002)5 of the Committee of Ministers to member states on the protection of women against violence'', the Council of Europe stipulated that VAW \"includes, but is not limited to, the following\":<ref>{{cite web |date=30 April 2002 |url=https://wcd.coe.int/ViewDoc.jsp?id=280915&Site=CM&BackColorInternet=C3C3C3&BackColorIntranet=EDB021&BackColorLogged=F5D383 |format=PDF |title=Recommendations of the Committee of Ministers to member states on the protection of women against violence |publisher=Council of Europe Committee of Ministers |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n:a. violence occurring in the family or domestic unit, including, ''inter alia'', physical and mental aggression, emotional and psychological abuse, rape and sexual abuse, incest, rape between spouses, regular or occasional partners and cohabitants, crimes committed in the name of honour, female genital and sexual mutilation and other traditional practices harmful to women, such as forced marriages;\n\n:b. violence occurring within the general community, including, ''inter alia'', rape, sexual abuse, sexual harassment and intimidation at work, in institutions or elsewhere trafficking in women for the purposes of sexual exploitation and economic exploitation and sex tourism;\n\n:c. violence perpetrated or condoned by the state or its officials;\n\n:d. violation of the human rights of women in situations of armed conflict, in particular the taking of hostages, forced displacement, systematic rape, sexual slavery, forced pregnancy, and trafficking for the purposes of sexual exploitation and economic exploitation.\n\nThese definitions of VAW as being gender-based are seen by some to be unsatisfactory and problematic. These definitions are conceptualized in an understanding of society as patriarchal, signifying unequal relations between men and women.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Ert\u00fcrk | first = Yakin | title = Towards a post-patriarchal gender order: confronting the universality and the particularity of violence against women | journal = Sociologisk Forskning | volume = 46 | issue = 4 | pages = 61&ndash;70 | publisher = Sveriges Sociologf\u00f6rbund [Swedish Sociological Association] | jstor = 20853687 | date = 2009 | ref = harv }}</ref> Opponents of such definitions argue that the definitions disregard violence against men and that the term ''[[gender]]'', as used in ''gender based violence'', only refers to women. Other critics argue that employing the term ''gender'' in this particular way may introduce notions of inferiority and subordination for femininity and superiority for masculinity.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Visaria | first = Leela | title = Violence against women: a field study | journal = [[Economic and Political Weekly]] | volume = 35 | issue = 20 | pages = 1742&ndash;1751 | publisher = Sameeksha Trust, Mumbai, India | jstor = 4409296 | date = 13 May 2000 | ref = harv }}</ref><ref name=\"Michau, L. 2007 pp.96\">{{cite journal | last = Michau | first = Lori | title = Approaching old problems in new ways: community mobilisation as a primary prevention strategy to combat violence against women | journal = Gender & Development | volume = 15 | issue = 1 | pages = 95&ndash;109 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] and [[Oxfam]] | doi = 10.1080/13552070601179144 | jstor = 20461184 | date = March 2007 | ref = harv }}</ref> There is no widely accepted current definition that covers all the dimensions of gender-based violence rather than the one for women that tends to reproduce the concept of binary oppositions: masculinity versus femininity.<ref name=\"Pr\u00fcgl, E. 2013\"/>\n\n==History==\n\n===Overview===\n[[File:Grandville Cent Proverbes page69.png|thumb|right|An illustration from [[Jean Ignace Isidore G\u00e9rard|JJ Grandville]]'s ''Cent Proverbes'' (1845) captioned \"Qui aime bien ch\u00e2tie bien\" (''Who loves well, punishes well''). A man beating a woman is shown in the back.]]\n[[File:Torturing and execution of witches in medieval miniature.jpg|thumb|Burning witches, with others held in Stocks]]\n[[File:Sati ceremony.jpg|thumb|[[Sati (practice)|Sati]] (a Hindu practice whereby a [[widow]] immolates herself on the funeral pyre of her husband) ceremony.]]\n[[File:Bound feet (X-ray).jpg|thumb|X-ray of [[bound feet]], China]]\nThe history of violence against women remains vague in scientific literature. This is in part because many kinds of violence against women (specifically rape, sexual assault, and domestic violence) are under-reported, often due to societal norms, taboos, stigma, and the sensitive nature of the subject.<ref name=\"WHO World Report on violence and health\" /><ref name=\"VAM: Global scope & magnitude\">{{cite journal | last1 = Watts | first1 = Charlotte | last2 = Zimmerman | first2 = Cathy | title = Violence against women: global scope and magnitude | journal = [[The Lancet]] | volume = 359 | issue = 9313 | pages = 1232&ndash;1237 | publisher = [[Elsevier]] | pmid = 11955557 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(02)08221-1 | date = 6 April 2002 | ref = harv }}</ref> It is widely recognized that even today, a lack of reliable and continuous data is an obstacle to forming a clear picture of violence against women.<ref name=\"UN In-depth Study on all Forms of Violence Against Women\">{{cite book | last = UN | author-link = United Nations |title=In-depth study on all forms of violence against women. Report of the Secretary-General.|url=http://www.un.org/womenwatch/daw/vaw/violenceagainstwomenstudydoc.pdf1|publisher=United Nations General Assembly | id = A/61/122/Add | date = 2006 |accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nAlthough the history of violence against women is difficult to track, it is clear that much of the violence was accepted, condoned and even legally sanctioned.<ref name=\"Film script\">{{cite book|last=Ireland|first=Patricia | title=No Safe Place: Violence Against Women (script) |url=https://www.pbs.org/kued/nosafeplace/script/script.html|publisher=[[PBS]] documentary |date =1996|accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> Examples include that Roman law gave men the right to chastise their wives, even to the point of death,<ref name=\"Roman Law\">{{cite journal | last = Stedman | first = Berne | title = Right of husband to chastise wife | journal = [[Virginia Law Review|The Virginia Law Register]] | volume = 3 | issue = 4 | pages = 241&ndash;248 | publisher = [[University of Virginia School of Law]] | doi = 10.2307/1106112 | jstor = 1106112 | date = August 1917 | ref = harv }} Also available at [http://heinonline.org/HOL/LandingPage?handle=hein.journals/valrgn3&div=35&id=&page= HeinOnline]. Full text available here [https://archive.org/stream/jstor-1106112/1106112_djvu.txt].</ref> and the burning of witches, which was condoned by both the church and the state (although this was not a practice exclusively against women).<ref name=\"Film script\" />\n\nThe history of violence against women is closely related to the historical view of women as property and a gender role of subservience.<ref>{{cite book| last = Toren | first = Christina | chapter = Transforming love: representing Fijian hierarchy | chapterurl = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=KGXezlZnjF8C&pg=PA36 | editor-last1 = Harvey | editor-first1 = Penelope | editor-last2= Gow | editor-first2 = Peter  | title = Sex and violence: issues in representation and experience | pages = 18&ndash;39 | publisher = Routledge | location = London New York | year = 1994 | isbn = 9780415057349 }}</ref> Explanations of [[patriarchy]] and an overall world system or status quo in which gender inequalities exist and are perpetuated are cited to explain the scope and history of violence against women.<ref name=\"VAM: Global scope & magnitude\" /><ref name=\"UN In-depth Study on all Forms of Violence Against Women\" /> The UN Declaration on the Elimination of Violence against Women (1993) states, \"violence against women is a manifestation of historically unequal power relations between men and women, which have led to domination over and discrimination against women by men and to the prevention of the full advancement of women, and that violence against women is one of the crucial social mechanisms by which women are forced into a subordinate position compared with men.\"<ref>{{cite book | last = UN | author-link = United Nations | title = Declaration on the Elimination of Violence against Women | id = A/RES/48/104 | url = https://www.un.org/documents/ga/res/48/a48r104.htm | publisher = United Nations }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = UNFPA | author-link = United Nations Population Fund | title = Addressing gender-based violence: advancing human rights | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141021001255/http://www.unfpa.org/rights/violence.htm | archive-date = 21 October 2014 | url = http://www.unfpa.org/rights/violence.htm | publisher = [[United Nations Population Fund]] (UNFPA) }}</ref>\n\nAccording to the UN, \"there is no region of the world, no country and no culture in which women's freedom from violence has been secured.\"<ref name=\"UN In-depth Study on all Forms of Violence Against Women\" /> Several forms of violence are more prevalent in certain parts of the world, often in [[developing countries]]. For example, [[dowry death|dowry violence]] and [[bride burning]] is associated with [[India]], [[Bangladesh]], [[Sri Lanka]], and [[Nepal]]. [[Acid throwing]] is also associated with these countries, as well as in [[Southeast Asia]], including [[Cambodia]]. [[Honor killing]] is associated with the [[Middle East]] and [[South Asia]]. [[Female genital mutilation]] is found mostly in [[Africa]], and to a lesser extent in the Middle East and some other parts of Asia. [[Marriage by abduction]] is found in [[Ethiopia]], [[Central Asia]] and the [[Caucasus]]. Abuse related to payment of [[bride price]] (such as violence, trafficking and forced marriage) is linked to parts of Sub-Saharan Africa and Oceania. (Also see [[lobolo]].)<ref>{{cite news | title = Papua New Guinea: police cite bride price major factor in marital violence | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150218182845/http://www.violenceisnotourculture.org/News-and-Views/papua-new-guinea-police-cite-bride-price-major-factor-marital-violence | archive-date = 18 February 2015 |url= http://www.violenceisnotourculture.org/News-and-Views/papua-new-guinea-police-cite-bride-price-major-factor-marital-violence | work = Island Business |via=Violence is not our Culture |date=21 November 2011 |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=An exploratory study of bride price and domestic violence in Bundibugyo District, Uganda |url=http://www.mrc.ac.za/gender/Bridepricedomesticviolence.pdf |publisher=Centre for Human Rights Advancement (CEHURA) and [[South African Medical Research Council]] |date=April 2012 |accessdate=6 August 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130717105205/http://www.mrc.ac.za/gender/Bridepricedomesticviolence.pdf |archive-date=17 July 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nCertain regions are no longer associated with a specific form of violence, but such violence was common until quite recently in those places; this is true of honor-based crimes in Southern/Mediterranean Europe.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Kirti | first1 = Anand | last2 = Kumar | first2 = Prateek | last3 = Yadav | first3 = Rachana | title = The face of honour based crimes: global concerns and solutions | journal = International Journal of Criminal Justice Sciences | volume = 6 | issue = 1&ndash;2 | pages = 343&ndash;357 | publisher = South Asian Society of Criminology & Victimology (SASCV) | date = 2011 | url = http://www.sascv.org/ijcjs/pdfs/kirtietalicjs2011i&iind.pdf | ref = harv }}</ref> For instance, in [[Italy]], before 1981, the Criminal Code provided for mitigating circumstances in case of a killing of a woman or her sexual partner for reasons related to honor, providing for a reduced sentence.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Barazzetti | first1 = Donatella | last2 = Garreffa | first2 = Franca | last3 = Marsico | first3 = Rosaria | title = Daphne Project \"Proposing new indicators: measuring violence's effects, GVEI (Gender Violence Effects Indicators)\" | url = http://www.surt.org/gvei/docs/national_report_italy.pdf | publisher = Centre Women\u2019s Studies \"Milly Villa\", [[University of Calabria]] | location = Rende, Italy | date = July 2007 | quote = Before 1981, Art. 587 read: He who causes the death of a spouse, daughter, or sister upon discovering her in illegitimate carnal relations and in the heat of passion caused by the offence to his honour or that of his family will be sentenced to three to seven years. The same sentence shall apply to whom, in the above circumstances, causes the death of the person involved in illegitimate carnal relations with his spouse, daughter, or sister.}}</ref>\n\nInvoking culture to explain particular forms of violence against women risks appearing to legitimize them. There is also debate and controversy about the ways in which cultural traditions, local customs and social expectations, as well as various interpretations of religion, interact with abusive practices.<ref name=\"UN In-depth Study on all Forms of Violence Against Women\" /><ref>{{cite book | last = Narayan | first = Uma | chapter = Cross\u2010cultural connections, border\u2010crossings, and \"Death by Culture\": thinking about dowry-murders in India and domestic\u2010violence murders in the United States | chapterurl = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lzQ49LnmL_cC&pg=PA81 | editor-last = Narayan | editor-first = Uma | title = Dislocating cultures: identities, traditions, and Third-World feminism | pages = 81&ndash;118 | publisher = Routledge | location = New York | year = 1997 | isbn = 9780415914192 | ref = harv }}</ref> Specifically, cultural justifications for certain violent acts against women are asserted by some states and social groups within many countries claiming to defend their traditions. These justifications are questionable precisely because the defenses are generally voiced by political leaders or traditional authorities, not by those actually affected.<ref name=\"UN In-depth Study on all Forms of Violence Against Women\" /> The need for sensitivity and respect of culture is an element that cannot be ignored either; thus a sensitive debate has ensued and is ongoing.\n\nThere has also been a history of recognizing the harmful effects of this violence. In the 1870s, courts in the United States stopped recognizing the common-law principle that a husband had the right to \"physically chastise an errant wife\".<ref>{{cite book | last = Calvert | first = Robert | chapter = Criminal and civil liability in husband-wife assaults | chapterurl = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=fCpHAAAAMAAJ | editor-last1 = Steinmetz | editor-first1 = Suzanne | editor-last2 = Straus | editor-first2 = Murray A. | author-link2 = Murray A. Straus | title = Violence in the family | pages = 88&ndash;91 | publisher = Harper & Row | location = New York | year = 1974 | isbn = 9780060464196 | ref = harv }}</ref> The first state to rescind this right was Alabama in 1871.<ref name=\"USDOJ-History of VAWA\" /> In the UK the right of a husband to inflict moderate [[corporal punishment]] on his wife to keep her \"within the bounds of duty\" was removed in 1891.<ref>R. v. Jackson [1891]. 1 Q.B. 671</ref><ref>{{cite book | chapter = Corporal punishment | title = Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Eleventh Edition | edition = 11th | year = 1911 | title-link = Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica Eleventh Edition }}</ref>\n\nIn the 20th and 21st centuries, and in particular since the 1990s, there has been increased activity on both the national and international levels to research, raise awareness and advocate for the prevention of all kinds of violence against women.<ref name=\"UN In-depth Study on all Forms of Violence Against Women\" /> Most often, violence against women has been framed as a health issue, and also as a violation of human rights. A study in 2002 estimated that at least one in five women in the world had been physically or sexually abused by a man sometime in their lives, and \"gender-based violence accounts for as much death and ill-health in women aged 15\u201344 years as cancer, and is a greater cause of ill-health than malaria and traffic accidents combined.\"<ref name=\"VAW: A Global Burden\" />\n\nCertain characteristics of violence against women have emerged from the research. For example, acts of violence against women are often not unique episodes, but are ongoing over time. More often than not, the violence is perpetrated by someone the woman knows, not by a stranger.<ref name=\"VAM: Global scope & magnitude\" /> The research seems to provide convincing evidence that violence against women is a severe and pervasive problem the world over, with devastating effects on the health and well-being of women and children.<ref name=\"UN In-depth Study on all Forms of Violence Against Women\" />\n\n===Milestones===\nSome of the most important milestones on the international level for the prevention of violence against women include:\n\n*The 1979 [[Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination against Women]] (CEDAW), which recognizes violence as a part of discrimination against women in recommendations 12 and 19.<ref name=\"UN Women: Global Norms & Standards\">{{cite web|title=Global norms and standards: Ending violence against women|url=http://www.unwomen.org/en/what-we-do/ending-violence-against-women/global-norms-and-standards|publisher=[[UN Women]]|accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref>\n*The 1993 [[World Conference on Human Rights]], which recognized violence against women as a human rights violation, and which contributed to the following UN declaration.<ref name=\"UN Women: Global Norms & Standards\" />\n*The 1993 UN [[Declaration on the Elimination of Violence against Women]] was the first international instrument explicitly defining and addressing violence against women. This document specifically refers to the historically forever-present nature of gender inequalities in understanding violence against women.<ref name=\"UN Women: Global Norms & Standards\"/> (Include current 2nd paragraph here). This Declaration, as well as the World Conference of the same year, is often viewed as a \"turning point\" at which the consideration of violence against women by the international community began to be taken much more seriously, and after which more countries mobilized around this problem.<ref name=\"VAW: A Global Burden\">{{cite journal | last1 = Venis | first1 = Sarah | last2 = Horton | first2 = Richard | title = Violence against women: a global burden | journal = [[The Lancet]] | volume = 359 | issue = 9313 | page = 1172 | publisher = [[Elsevier]] | pmid = 11955533 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(02)08251-X | date = 6 April 2002 | ref = harv }}</ref><ref name=\"WHO Multicountry Study\">{{cite book | last = Garcia-Moreno | first = Claudia | title = WHO multi-country study on women's health and domestic violence against women: initial results on prevalence, health outcomes and women's responses | publisher = [[World Health Organization]] | location = Geneva, Switzerland | year = 2005 | url = https://www.who.int/reproductivehealth/publications/violence/24159358X/en/ | isbn = 9789241593588 }}</ref>\n*The 1994 [[International Conference on Population and Development]], linking violence against women to reproductive health and rights, and also providing recommendations to governments on how to prevent and respond to violence against women and girls.<ref name=\"UN Women: Global Norms & Standards\"/>\n*In 1996, the [[World Health Assembly]] (WHA) declared violence a major public health issue, and included in the subtypes recognized were intimate partner violence and sexual violence, two kinds of violence often perpetrated as violence against women. This was followed by a WHO report in 2002 (see below).<ref name=\"WHO World Report on violence and health\">{{cite book | last1 = Krug | first1 = Etienne G. | last2 = Dahlberg | first2 = Linda L. | last3 = Mercy | first3 = James A. | last4 = Zwi | first4 = Anthony B. | last5 = Lozano | first5 = Rafael | title = World report on violence and health | publisher = [[World Health Organization]] | location = Geneva, Switzerland | year = 2002 | url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=db9OHpk-TksC&printsec=frontcover | isbn = 9789241545617 }}\n:''Also available as'':\n:* {{cite journal | last1 = Krug | first1 = Etienne G. | last2 = Dahlberg | first2 = Linda L. | last3 = Mercy | first3 = James A. | last4 = Zwi | first4 = Anthony B. | last5 = Lozano | first5 = Rafael | title = The world report on violence and health | journal = [[The Lancet]] | volume = 360 | issue = 9339 | pages = 1083&ndash;1088 | publisher = [[Elsevier]] | pmid = 12384003 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(02)11133-0 | date = 5 October 2002 | ref = harv | url = http://www.revistabiomedica.org/index.php/biomedica/article/view/1182 }}</ref> The UN also created the Trust Fund to Support Actions to Eliminate Violence Against Women.<ref name=\"Fried\">{{cite journal | last =Fried | first = Susana T. | title = Violence against women | journal = [[Health and Human Rights|Health and Human Rights Journal]] | volume = 6 | issue = 2 | pages = 88&ndash;111 | publisher = [[Harvard University Press]] | doi = 10.2307/4065431 | jstor = 4065431 | date = 2003 | ref = harv }} [https://cdn2.sph.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/125/2014/04/6-Fried.pdf Pdf.]</ref> \n*In 1999, the UN adopted the [[Optional Protocol to the Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination against Women]] and designated 25 November as the [[International Day for the Elimination of Violence against Women]].<ref name=\"VAW: A Global Burden\" /> \n*In 2002, as a follow-up of the WHA declaration in 1996 of violence as a major public health issue, the [[World Health Organization]] published the first World Report on Violence and Health, which addressed many types of violence and their effect on public health, including forms of violence affecting women particularly strongly. The report specifically noted the sharp rise in civil society organizations and activities directed at responding to gender-based violence against women from the 1970s to the 1990s.<ref name=\"WHO World Report on violence and health\" /> \n*In 2004, the [[World Health Organization]] published its \"Multi-country study on Women's Health and Domestic Violence against Women\", a study of women's health and [[domestic violence]] by surveying over 24,000 women in 10 countries from all regions of the world, which assessed the prevalence and extent of violence against women, particularly violence by intimate partners, and linked this with health outcomes to women as well as documenting strategies and services that women use to cope with intimate-partner violence.<ref name=\"WHO Multicountry Study\" />\n*The 2006 UN Secretary General's \"In-depth study on all forms of violence against women\", the first comprehensive international document on the issue.<ref name=\"UN In-depth Study on all Forms of Violence Against Women\" />\n*The 2011 Council of Europe [[Convention on preventing and combating violence against women and domestic violence]], which is the second regional legally-binding instrument on violence against women and girls.<ref name=\"UN Women: Global Norms & Standards\"/> \n*In 2013, the [[United Nations Commission on the Status of Women]] (CSW) adopted, by consensus, Agreed Conclusions on the elimination and prevention of all forms of violence against women and girls (formerly, there were no agreed-upon conclusions).<ref name=\"UN Women: Global Norms & Standards\"/>\n*Also in 2013, the [[UN General Assembly]] passed its first resolution calling for the protection of [[human rights defender|defenders]] of women's human rights.<ref name=\"Norway Post\">{{cite news | last = NRK |title=Protection of women human rights defenders | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131213142536/http://www.norwaypost.no/index.php/news/latest-news/29260-protection-of-women-human-rights-defenders | archive-date = 13 December 2013 |url=http://www.norwaypost.no/index.php/news/latest-news/29260-protection-of-women-human-rights-defenders |work=The Norway Post |date=30 November 2013 |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> The resolution urges states to put in place gender-specific laws and policies for the protection of women's [[human rights defender]]s and to ensure that defenders themselves are involved in the design and implementation of these measures, and calls on states to protect women's human rights defenders from reprisals for cooperating with the UN and to ensure their unhindered access to and communication with international human rights bodies and mechanisms.<ref name=\"awid.org\">{{cite web |url=http://www.awid.org/Library/UN-adopts-landmark-resolution-on-Protecting-Women-Human-Rights-Defenders |title=UN adopts landmark resolution on Protecting Women Human Rights Defenders |publisher=[[Association for Women's Rights in Development]] (AWID) |date=28 November 2013 |accessdate=6 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140819203819/http://www.awid.org/Library/UN-adopts-landmark-resolution-on-Protecting-Women-Human-Rights-Defenders |archivedate=19 August 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, on the national level, individual countries have also organized efforts (legally, politically, socially) to prevent, reduce and punish violence against women. As a particular case study, here are some developments since the 1960s in the United States to oppose and treat violence against women:<ref name=\"USDOJ-History of VAWA\">{{cite web|last=U.S. Department of Justice, Office of Violence Against Women (OVM)|title=The History of the Violence Against Women Act|url=http://www.ovw.usdoj.gov/docs/history-vawa.pdf|publisher=U.S. Department of Justice|accessdate=2 December 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111017204719/http://www.ovw.usdoj.gov/docs/history-vawa.pdf|archivedate=17 October 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \n*1967: One of the country's first domestic violence shelters opened in Maine.\n*1972: The country's first rape help hotline opened in Washington, D.C.\n*1978: Two national coalitions, the National Coalition Against Sexual Assault and the [[National Coalition Against Domestic Violence]], were formed, to raise awareness of these two forms of violence against women.\n*1984: The U.S. Attorney General created the Department of Justice Task Force on Family Violence, to address ways in which the criminal justice system and community response to domestic violence should be improved.\n*1994: Passage of the [[Violence Against Women Act]] or VAWA, legislation included in the [[Violent Crime Control and Law Enforcement Act]] of 1994, sponsored by then-Senator Joseph Biden, which required a strengthened community response to crimes of domestic violence and sexual assault, strengthened federal penalties for repeat sex offenders and strengthened legislative protection of victims, among many other provisions.\n*2000: President Clinton signed into law the VAWA of 2000, further strengthening federal laws, and emphasizing assistance of immigrant victims, elderly victims, victims with disabilities, and victims of dating violence.\n*2006: President Bush signed into law the VAWA of 2006, with an emphasis on programs to address violence against youth victims, and establishing programs for Engaging Men and Youth, and Culturally and Linguistically Specific Services.\n*2007: The National Teen Dating Abuse Hotline opened.\n*2009: President Obama declared April as Sexual Assault Awareness Month.\n*2013: President Obama signed into law the VAWA of 2015, which granted Native American tribes the ability to prosecute non-Native offenders, and regulated reports of sexual assault on college campuses.<ref>{{cite book | last = Kohlman | first = Cindy | title = Violence Against Women Act (VAWA) New Reporting Requirements Effective July 1, 2015 \u2013 Are You Ready? | url = https://www.inceptia.org | publisher = Inceptia Institute | date = 9 June 2015 }}\n:''See also'':\n:* {{cite book | last = ACE | author-link = American Council on Education | title = New requirements imposed by the Violence Against Women Reauthorization Act | url = http://www.acenet.edu/news-room/Documents/VAWA-Summary.pdf | publisher = [[American Council on Education]] | date = 1 April 2014 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Fee|first1=Stephen |display-authors=etal | title=Tribal Justice: Prosecuting Non-Natives for Sexual Assault on Reservations (transcript) |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/show/tribal-justice-prosecuting-non-natives-sexual-assault-indian-reservations|publisher=[[PBS]] documentary |date =5 September 2015}}</ref>\n\nOther countries have also enacted comparable legislative, political and social instruments to address violence against women. Experts in the international community generally believe, however, that solely enacting punitive legislation for prevention and punishment of violence against women is not sufficient to address the problem. For example, although much stricter laws on violence against women have been passed in Bangladesh, violence against women is still rising.<ref name=\"VAW: A Global Burden\" /> Instead, it is thought that wide societal changes to address gender inequalities and women's empowerment will be the way to reduce violence against women.<ref name=\"UN In-depth Study on all Forms of Violence Against Women\" /><ref name=\"VAW: A Global Burden\" /><ref name=\"Nigeria-Female Hawkers-Interventions\">{{cite journal | last1 = Fawole | first1 = Olufunmilayo I. | last2 = Ajuwon | first2 = Ademola J. | last3 = Osungbade | first3 = Kayode O. | last4 = Faweya | first4 = Olufemi C. | title = Interventions for violence prevention among young female hawkers in motor parks in South-Western Nigeria: a review of effectiveness | journal = African Journal of Reproductive Health [La Revue Africaine de la Sant\u00e9 Reproductive] | volume = 7 | issue = 1 | pages = 71&ndash;82 | publisher = Women's Health and Action Research Centre (WHARC) | doi = 10.2307/3583347 | jstor = 3583347 | date = April 2003 | ref = harv | hdl = 1807/2587 }}</ref><ref name=\"WHO VAM Factsheet\">{{cite book | last = WHO | author-link = World Health Organization |title=Violence against women|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs239/en/|publisher=[[World Health Organization]]| date = 1 September 2011|accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Effect on society==\nAccording to an article in the [[Health and Human Rights (journal)|Health and Human Rights Journal]],<ref name=\"Fried\" /> regardless of many years of advocacy and involvement of many feminist activist organizations, the issue of violence against women still \"remains one of the most pervasive forms of human rights violations worldwide\".<ref name=\"Fried\" />{{rp|91}} The violence against women can occur in both public and private spheres of life and at any time of their life span. Violence against women often keeps women from wholly contributing to social, economic, and political development of their communities.<ref name=\"Fried\"/> Many women are terrified by these threats of violence and this essentially influences their lives so that they are impeded to exercise their human rights; for instance, they fear contributing to the development of their communities socially, economically and politically. Apart from that, the causes that trigger VAW or gender-based violence can go beyond just the issue of gender and into the issues of age, class, culture, ethnicity, religion, sexual orientation and specific geographical area of their origins.\n\nImportantly, other than the issue of social divisions, violence can also extend into the realm of health issues and become a direct concern of the public health sector.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Colarossi | first = Lisa | title = A response to Danis & Lockhart: What guides social work knowledge about violence against women? | journal = Journal of Social Work Education | volume = 41 | issue = 1 | pages = 147&ndash;159 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] on behalf of the [[Council on Social Work Education]] (CSWE) |doi=10.5175/JSWE.2005.200400418 | jstor = 23044038 | date = Winter 2005 | ref = harv}}\n:''See also'':\n:* {{cite journal | last1 = Danis | first1 = Fran S. | last2 = Lockhart | first2 = Lettie | title = Guest Editorial &ndash; Domestic violence and social work education: what do we know, what do we need to know? | journal = Journal of Social Work Education, Special Section: Domestic Violence and Social Work Education | volume = 39 | issue = 2 | pages = 215&ndash;224 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] on behalf of the [[Council on Social Work Education]] (CSWE) | doi = 10.1080/10437797.2003.10779132 | jstor = 23044061 | date = Spring\u2013Summer 2003 | ref = harv }}</ref> A health issue such as [[HIV/AIDS]] is another cause that also leads to violence. Women who have HIV/AIDS infection are also among the targets of the violence.<ref name=\"Fried\" />{{rp|91}} The [[World Health Organization]] reports that violence against women puts an undue burden on health care services, as women who have suffered violence are more likely to need health services and at higher cost, compared to women who have not suffered violence.<ref name=\"WHO VAM Factsheet\" /> Another statement that confirms an understanding of VAW as being a significant health issue is apparent in the recommendation adopted by the Council of Europe, violence against women in private sphere, at home or [[domestic violence]], is the main reason of \"death and disability\" among the women who encountered violence.<ref name=\"Fried\" />{{rp|91}}\n\nIn addition, several studies have shown a link between poor treatment of women and international violence. These studies show that one of the best predictors of inter- and intranational violence is the maltreatment of women in the society.<ref>{{cite news | last = Maffly | first = Brian | title = BYU study links women's safety, nation's peace | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100202080318/http://www.sltrib.com/ci_11967564 | archive-date = 2 February 2010 | url = http://www.sltrib.com/ci_11967564 | work = [[The Salt Lake Tribune]] | date = 21 March 2009 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last1 = Strearmer | first1 = Matthew | last2 = Emmett | first2 = Chad F.|url=http://www.womanstats.org/images/StearmerEmmettAPSA07.pdf |title=The great divide: Revealing differences in the Islamic world regarding the status of women and its impact on international peace |publisher= [[WomanStats Project]] |date=2007 |accessdate=6 August 2014}} Paper prepared for presentation at the annual meeting of the [[American Political Science Association]], Chicago, Illinois, 29 August \u2013 1 September 2007.</ref>\n\n== Typology ==\nViolence against women may be classified according to different approaches. \n\n=== WHO's life cycle typology ===\nThe [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) has developed a typology of violence against women based on their cultural life cycles. \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| '''Phase''' || '''Type of violence'''\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n| Pre-birth || Sex-selective abortion; effects of battering during pregnancy on birth outcomes\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n| Infancy || Female infanticide; physical, sexual and psychological abuse\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n| Girlhood || Child marriage; female genital mutilation; physical, sexual and psychological abuse; incest; child prostitution and pornography\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n| Adolescence and adulthood || Dating and courtship violence (e.g. acid throwing and date rape); economically coerced sex (e.g. school girls having sex with \"sugar daddies\" in return for school fees); incest; sexual abuse in the workplace; rape; sexual harassment; forced prostitution and pornography; trafficking in women; partner violence; marital rape; dowry abuse and murders; partner homicide; psychological abuse; abuse of women with disabilities; forced pregnancy\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top;\"\n| Elderly || Forced \"suicide\" or homicide of widows for economic reasons; sexual, physical and psychological abuse<ref name=\"WHO_VAW\" />\n|}\n\nSignificant progress towards the protection of women from violence has been made on international level as a product of collective effort of lobbying by many women's rights movements; international organizations to civil society groups. As a result, worldwide governments and international as well as civil society organizations actively work to combat violence against women through a variety of programs. Among the major achievements of the women's rights movements against violence on girls and women, the landmark accomplishments are the \"[[Declaration on the Elimination of Violence Against Women]]\" that implies \"political will towards addressing VAW \" and the legal binding agreement, \"the Convention on Elimination of all forms of Discrimination Against Women ([[CEDAW]])\".<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Rosche | first1 = Daniela | last2 = Dawe | first2 = Alexandra | title = Oxfam Briefing Note: Ending violence against women the case for a comprehensive international action plan | page = 2 | publisher = [[Oxfam|Oxfam GB]] | location = Oxford | year = 2013 | url = http://www.oxfam.org/sites/www.oxfam.org/files/bn-ending-violence-against-women-action-plan-220213-en.pdf | isbn = 9781780772639 | access-date = 2 December 2013 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170925212852/https://www.oxfam.org/sites/www.oxfam.org/files/bn-ending-violence-against-women-action-plan-220213-en.pdf | archive-date = 25 September 2017 | url-status = dead }}</ref> In addition, the UN General Assembly resolution also designated 25 November as [[International Day for the Elimination of Violence against Women]].<ref>{{cite book | last = UN | author-link = United Nations | title = International Day for the Elimination of Violence against Women | url = https://www.un.org/womenwatch/daw/news/vawd.html | website = un.org | publisher = [[United Nations]] |date= 17 December 1999|accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== ''The Lancet'''s over time typology ===\n[[File:Typology of Violence Against Women over Time.png|thumbnail|300 px|A diagram of typology of violence against women over time, as conceived by authors [[Charlotte Watts]] & Cathy Zimmerman.]]\n\nA typology similar to the WHO's from an article on violence against women published in the academic journal ''[[The Lancet]]'' shows the different types of violence perpetrated against women according to what time period in a women's life the violence takes place.<ref name=\"VAM: Global scope & magnitude\" /> However, it also classifies the types of violence according to the perpetrator. One important point to note is that more of the types of violence inflicted on women are perpetrated by someone the woman knows, either a family member or intimate partner, rather than a stranger.\n\n=== Council of Europe's nine forms of violence ===\nThe Gender Equality Commission of the [[Council of Europe]] identifies nine forms of violence against women based on subject and context rather than life cycle or time period:<ref name=\"Hagemann-White\">{{Cite web |url=https://rm.coe.int/16805915e9 |title=Analytical study of the results of the 4th round of monitoring the implementation of Recommendation Rec(2002)5 on the protection of women against violence in Council of Europe member states |author=Carol Hagemann-White |page=7, 8, 11 |publisher=Council of Europe Equality Division |date=February 2014 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://edoc.coe.int/en/fundamental-freedoms/5949-state-of-democracy-human-rights-and-the-rule-of-law-in-europe.html |title=State of democracy, human rights and the rule of law in Europe (2014) |author=[[Thorbj\u00f8rn Jagland]] |work=Report by the Secretary General of the Council of Europe |page=48 |publisher=Council of Europe |date=May 2014 |accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref>\n*'Violence within the family or domestic violence'\n*'Rape and sexual violence'\n*'Sexual harassment'\n*'Violence in institutional environments'\n*'Female genital mutilation'\n*'Forced marriages'\n*'Violence in conflict and post-conflict situations'\n*'Killings in the name of honour'\n*'Failure to respect freedom of choice with regard to reproduction'\n\n==Forms of violence==\nViolence against women can take a number of forms and arise in a number of situations:\n\n===Rape===\n{{main|Rape}}\nWomen are most often the victims of rape, which is usually perpetrated by men known to them.<ref>''Relevant citations'':\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Abbey | first1 = Antonia | last2 = BeShears | first2 = Renee | last3 = Clinton-Sherrod | first3 = A. Monique | last4 = McAuslan | first4 = Pam  | title = Similarities and differences in women's sexual assault experiences based on tactics used by the perpetrator | journal = [[Psychology of Women Quarterly]] | volume = 28 | issue = 4 | pages = 323&ndash;332 | publisher = [[Sage Publications|Sage]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1471-6402.2004.00149.x | pmid = 26257466 | pmc = 4527559 | date = December 2004 | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20130108020408/http://www.hawaii.edu/hivandaids/Similarities_And_Differences_In_Women_s_Sexual_Assault_Experiences_Based_On_Tactics.pdf | url-status = dead | archivedate = 8 January 2013 | df = dmy-all | url = http://www.hawaii.edu/hivandaids/Similarities_And_Differences_In_Women_s_Sexual_Assault_Experiences_Based_On_Tactics.pdf | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.rainn.org/statistics/|title=Statistics | website = rainn.org |publisher= [[Rape, Abuse & Incest National Network]] (RAINN) |accessdate=1 January 2008}}\n* {{cite book | last = Tjaden | first1 = Patricia | last2 = Thoennes | first2 = Nancy | title = Extent, nature, and consequences of rape victimization: findings From the national violence against women survey | url = https://www.ncjrs.gov/App/Publications/abstract.aspx?ID=210346 | publisher = [[National Criminal Justice Reference Service]], U.S. Department of Justice Office of Justice Programs | date = January 2006 }} [http://www.ncjrs.gov/pdffiles1/nij/210346.pdf Pdf.]\n* {{cite web | last = ABS | author-link = Australian Bureau of Statistics | title = Sexual assault in Australia: a statistical overview, 2004 |url=http://www.abs.gov.au/ausstats/abs@.nsf/mf/4523.0 |website =abs.gov.au | publisher = [[Australian Bureau of Statistics]] |date=7 September 2004 |accessdate=31 December 2010}}\n* {{cite book | last = Myhill | first1 = Andy | last2 = Allen | first2 = Jonathan | title = Rape and sexual assault of women: findings from the British Crime Survey | url = http://rds.homeoffice.gov.uk/rds/pdfs2/r159.pdf | accessdate = 31 December 2010 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20110218135832/http://rds.homeoffice.gov.uk/rds/pdfs2/r159.pdf | archivedate = 18 February 2011 | df=dmy-all | publisher = [[Home Office]] | location = London | year = 2002 | series = [[Home Office]] Findings No. 159 }}</ref> The rate of reporting, prosecution and convictions for rape varies considerably in different jurisdictions, and reflects to some extent the society's attitudes to such crimes. It is considered the most underreported violent crime.<ref>{{cite book | last = AMA | author-link = American Medical Association | title = Strategies for the treatment and prevention of sexual assault | publisher = [[American Medical Association]] | location = Chicago, Illinois | year = 1995 | oclc = 33901581 }}</ref><ref name=\"rds.homeoffice.gov.uk\">{{cite book | last1 = Kelly | first1 = Liz | last2 = Regan | first2 = Linda | last3 = Lovett | first3 = Jo | author-link = Liz Kelly | title = A gap or a chasm?: Attrition in reported rape cases | publisher = Home Office Research, Development and Statistics Directorate | location = London | id = 293 | year = 2005 | isbn = 9781844735556 | archiveurl = http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20110218135832/rds.homeoffice.gov.uk/rds/pdfs05/hors293.pdf | archivedate = 18 February 2011 | url = http://rds.homeoffice.gov.uk/rds/pdfs05/hors293.pdf | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all | accessdate = 31 December 2010 }}</ref> Following a rape, a victim may face violence or threats of violence from the rapist, and, in many cultures, from the victim's own family and relatives. Violence or intimidation of the victim may be perpetrated by the rapist or by friends and relatives of the rapist, as a way of preventing the victims from reporting the rape, of punishing them for reporting it, or of forcing them to withdraw the complaint; or it may be perpetrated by the relatives of the victim as a punishment for \"bringing shame\" to the family. This is especially the case in cultures where female [[virginity]] is highly valued and considered mandatory before marriage; in extreme cases, rape victims are killed in [[honor killings]]. Victims may also be forced by their families to marry the rapist in order to restore the family's \"honor\".<ref>''Relevant articles'':\n* {{cite news | last = PTI | author-link =Press Trust of India | title = Rape victim threatened to withdraw case in UP | url = http://zeenews.india.com/news/uttar-pradesh/rape-victim-threatened-to-withdraw-case-in-up_694364.html | work = [[Zee News]] | publisher = [[Essel Group]] | location = Mumbai, India | date = 19 March 2011 | accessdate = 3 February 2013 }}\n* {{cite news | last = Staff writer | title =Stigmatization of rape & honor killings |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121108041415/http://www.wisemuslimwomen.org/currentissues/stigmitizationofrape/ | archive-date = 8 November 2012 | url = http://www.wisemuslimwomen.org/currentissues/stigmitizationofrape/ | work = WISE Muslim Women | publisher = [[Women's Islamic Initiative in Spirituality and Equality]] | date = 31 January 2002 | accessdate = 3 February 2013 }}\n* {{cite news | last = Harter | first = Pascale | title = Libya rape victims 'face honour killings' | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-13760895 | work = [[BBC News]] | date=14 June 2011 |accessdate= 3 February 2013 }}\n* {{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Morocco protest after raped Amina Filali kills herself | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-17379721 | work = [[BBC News]] | date = 15 March 2012 | accessdate = 19 November 2013}}</ref> In Lebanon, the [[Campaign Against Lebanese Rape Law - Article 522]] was launched in December 2016 to abolish the article that permitted a rapist to escape prison by marrying his victim.\n\nInternationally, the incidence of rapes recorded by police during 2008 varied between 0.1 per 100,000 people in [[Egypt]] and 91.6 per 100,000 people in [[Lesotho]] with 4.9 per 100,000 people in [[Lithuania]] as the [[median]].<ref name=\"unodc1\">{{cite book | last = UNODC | author-link = United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime | title = Rape at the National Level, number of police recorded offenses | url = http://www.unodc.org/documents/data-and-analysis/Crime-statistics/Sexual_violence_sv_against_children_and_rape.xls | format = spreadsheet | publisher = [[United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime]] }}</ref> In some countries, rape is not reported or properly recorded by police because of the consequences on the victim and the stigma attached to it.\n\n===Marital rape===\n{{Main|Marital rape|domestic violence}}\nMarital or spousal rape was once widely condoned or ignored by law, and is now widely considered an unacceptable violence against women and repudiated by international conventions and increasingly criminalized. Still, in many countries, spousal rape either remains legal, or is illegal but widely tolerated and accepted as a husband's prerogative. The criminalization of spousal rape is recent, having occurred during the past few decades. Traditional understanding and views of [[marriage]], [[rape]], [[sexuality]], [[gender roles]] and [[self determination]] have started to be challenged in most Western countries during the 1960s and 1970s, which has led to the subsequent criminalization of marital rape during the following decades. With a few notable exceptions, it was during the past 30 years when most laws against marital rape have been enacted. Some countries in Scandinavia and in the former Communist Bloc of Europe made spousal rape illegal before 1970, but most Western countries criminalized it only in the 1980s and 1990s. In many parts of the world the laws against marital rape are very new, having been enacted in the 2000s.\n\nIn [[Canada]], marital rape was made illegal in 1983, when several legal changes were made, including changing the rape statute to ''sexual assault'', and making the laws gender neutral.<ref name=grady>{{cite book | last = Grady | first = William | title = Crime in Canadian context: debates and controversies | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = Don Mills, Ontario | year = 2011 | isbn = 9780195433784 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last1 = Brennan | first1 = Shannon| last2 = Taylor-Butts | first2 = Andrea | title = Sexual assault in Canada, 2004 | publisher = Canadian Centre for Justice Statistics | location = Ottawa | year = 2008 |url=http://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/85f0033m/85f0033m2008019-eng.pdf | isbn = 9781100111636 |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = SIECCAN |title=Sexual assault in Canada: what do we know? |publisher=The Sex Information and Education Council of Canada (SIECCAN) | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140722071229/http://sexualityandu.ca/uploads/files/SexualAssault-OCT2011-ENG.pdf | archive-date = 22 July 2014 |url=http://sexualityandu.ca/uploads/files/SexualAssault-OCT2011-ENG.pdf | date = October 2011 |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> In [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]] spousal rape was outlawed in 1990.<ref name=\"Temkin86\">{{cite book | last = Temkin | first = Jennifer | chapter = Defining and redefining rape | editor-last = Temkin | editor-first = Jennifer | title = Rape and the legal process | page = 86 | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = Oxford New York | year = 2002 | edition = 2nd | isbn = 9780198763543 }}\n:''Citing'':\n:* {{cite web | title = Criminal Law (Rape) (Amendment) Act, 1990, section 5 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20170429001010/http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1990/act/32/section/5/enacted/en/html#sec5 | archive-date = 29 April 2017 | url = http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/eli/1990/act/32/section/5/enacted/en/html#sec5 | website = irishstatutebook.ie | publisher = [[Irish Statute Book]] | access-date = 21 December 2017}}</ref> In the US, the criminalization of marital rape started in the mid-1970s and in 1993 North Carolina became the last state to make marital rape illegal.<ref>{{cite news|last =Associated Press|author-link=Associated Press|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1957&dat=19930702&id=_xYxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=UOEFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6288,228462 |title=N.C. the last state to outlaw marital rape |work=[[The Daily Gazette]]| location = New York |date=2 July 1993 |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref>\nIn [[England and Wales]], marital rape was made illegal in 1991. The views of Sir Matthew Hale, a 17th-century jurist, published in ''The History of the Pleas of the Crown'' (1736), stated that a husband cannot be guilty of the rape of his wife because the wife \"hath given up herself in this kind to her husband, which she cannot retract\"; in England and Wales this would remain law for more than 250 years, until it was abolished by the [[Appellate Committee of the House of Lords]], in the case of ''R v R'' in 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bailii.org/uk/cases/UKHL/1991/12.html |title=R v R [1991&#93; UKHL 12 (23 October 1991) |publisher=British and Irish Legal Information Institute |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> In the [[Netherlands]] marital rape was also made illegal in 1991.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Zeegers | first = Nicolle | title = What epistemology would serve criminal law best in finding the truth about rape? | journal = Law and Method | volume = 2 | issue = 1 | pages = 60&ndash;71 | date = January 2012 | ref = harv | doi = 10.5553/ReM/221225082012002001005 }} [https://www.bjutijdschriften.nl/tijdschrift/lawandmethod/2012/1/ReM_2212-2508_2012_002_001_005.pdf Pdf.]</ref> One of the last Western countries to criminalize marital rape was [[Germany]], in 1997.<ref>{{cite thesis|last=Kieler|first=Marita|date=2003|title=Tatbestandsprobleme der sexuellen N\u00f6tigung, Vergewaltigung sowie des sexuellen Mi\u00dfbrauchs widerstandsunf\u00e4higer Personen|publisher=[[University of Osnabr\u00fcck]] via Tenea|url=http://www.jurawelt.com/dissertationen/werke/8821|oclc=758907108}} [http://www.jurawelt.com/sunrise/media/mediafiles/13792/tenea_juraweltbd52_kieler.pdf Pdf.] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131020164804/http://www.jurawelt.com/sunrise/media/mediafiles/13792/tenea_juraweltbd52_kieler.pdf |date=20 October 2013 }}</ref>\n\nThe relation between some religions ([[Christianity]] and [[Islam]]) and marital rape is controversial. The [[Bible]] at 1 Corinthians 7:3-5 explains that one has a \"conjugal duty\" to have sexual relations with one's spouse (in sharp opposition to [[sex outside marriage]], which is considered a [[sin]]) and states, \"The wife does not have authority over her own body, but the husband does. And likewise the husband does not have authority over his own body, but the wife does. Do not deprive one another...\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=1+corinthians%207:3-7:5&version=NKJV |title=1 corinthians 7:3-7:5 NKJV | website = biblegateway.com |publisher=[[BibleGateway.com|Bible Gateway]] |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> Some conservative religious figures interpret this as rejecting to possibility of marital rape.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.adn.com/2011/07/22/1980301/readers-blast-valley-paper-over.html |title=Valley paper criticized over pastor's column on spousal rape |work=[[Alaska Dispatch]] |date=22 July 2011 |accessdate=6 August 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029203959/http://www.adn.com/2011/07/22/1980301/readers-blast-valley-paper-over.html |archivedate=29 October 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Islam makes reference to sexual relations in marriage too, notably: \"Allah's Apostle said, 'If a husband calls his wife to his bed (i.e. to have sexual relation) and she refuses and causes him to sleep in anger, the angels will curse her till morning';\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sacred-texts.com/isl/bukhari/bh4/bh4_464.htm |title=Hadith 4:460 | website = Sacred-texts.com |publisher=[[Internet Sacred Text Archive]] |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref> and several comments on the issue of marital rape made by Muslim religious leaders have been criticized.<ref>{{cite news| last = Halliday | first =Josh |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2010/nov/08/islam-channel-ofcom |title=Islam Channel censured by Ofcom |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=8 November 2010 |accessdate=6 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/7843909.stm | work=[[BBC News]] | title=Cleric 'must deny' views on rape | date=22 January 2009 | access-date = 11 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Domestic violence===\n[[File:Anti-domestic violence sign in Liberia panoramio (193).jpg|thumb|Anti-domestic violence sign in [[Liberia]]]]\n{{main|Domestic violence|Intimate partner violence}}\nWomen are more likely to be [[victimized]] by someone that they are intimate with, commonly called \"[[intimate partner violence]]\" (IPV). Instances of IPV tend not to be reported to police and thus many experts find it hard to estimate the true magnitude of the problem.<ref>{{cite web | title = Intimate partner violence: fact sheet | url = https://www.cdc.gov/ncipc/factsheets/ipvfacts.htm | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070211183916/http://www.cdc.gov/ncipc/factsheets/ipvfacts.htm | archive-date = 11 February 2007 | website = cdc.gov/ncipc | publisher = National Center for Injury Prevention and Control, [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] | date = 2006 | accessdate = 4 September 2007}}</ref> Though this form of violence is often considered as an issue within the context of heterosexual relationships, it also occurs in lesbian relationships,<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Girshick | first = Lori B. | title = No sugar, no spice: reflections on research on woman-to-woman sexual violence | journal = [[Violence Against Women (journal)|Violence Against Women]] | volume = 8 | issue = 12 | pages = 1500\u20131520 | publisher = [[Sage Publications|Sage]] | doi = 10.1177/107780102237967 | date = December 2002 | ref = harv }}</ref> daughter-mother relationships, [[roommate]] relationships and other domestic relationships involving two women. Violence against women in lesbian relationships is about as common as violence against women in heterosexual relationships.<ref>{{cite web | last = Rose | first = Suzana | title = Lesbian partner violence fact sheet | url = http://www.musc.edu/vawprevention/lesbianrx/factsheet.shtml | publisher = [[Medical University of South Carolina]] }}</ref>\n\nWomen are much more likely than men to be [[murdered]] by an intimate partner. In the United States, in 2005, 1181 women were killed by their intimate partners, compared to 329 men.<ref>{{cite web | title = Intimate partner violence: consequences | url = https://www.cdc.gov/violencePrevention/intimatepartnerviolence/consequences.html | website = cdc.gov/ncipc | publisher = National Center for Injury Prevention and Control, [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] | accessdate = 9 February 2010 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20100129161946/http://www.cdc.gov/violencePrevention/intimatepartnerviolence/consequences.html | archive-date = 29 January 2010 | url-status = dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title = Wheel gallery | url = http://www.theduluthmodel.org/wheelgallery.php | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110728093413/http://www.theduluthmodel.org/wheelgallery.php | archive-date = 28 July 2011 | publisher=The Duluth Model | accessdate = 9 February 2010}}</ref> In [[England and Wales]] about 100 women are killed by partners or former partners each year while 21 men were killed in 2010.<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-13058300 |title=All domestic abuse deaths to have multi-agency review |date=13 April 2011 | work = BBC news |accessdate=14 April 2011}}</ref> In 2008, in [[France]], 156 women were killed by their intimate partner, compared to 27 men.<ref>{{cite book | title = L'action du minist\u00e8re dans le cadre des violences au sein du couple / Aide aux victimes: pr\u00e9sentation des diff\u00e9rents dispositifs | url = http://www.interieur.gouv.fr/sections/a_votre_service/aide_aux_victimes/violence-couple/downloadFile/attachedFile/morts_violentes_au_sein_couples.pdf | language = French | publisher = [[Minister of the Interior (France)|Minist\u00e8re de l'Int\u00e9rieur]] | accessdate = 6 August 2014 | url-status = dead | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20120320014223/http://www.interieur.gouv.fr/sections/a_votre_service/aide_aux_victimes/violence-couple/downloadFile/attachedFile/morts_violentes_au_sein_couples.pdf | archivedate = 20 March 2012 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> According to the WHO, globally, as many as 38% of murders of women are committed by an intimate partner.<ref name=\"WHO VAM Factsheet\" /> A UN report compiled from a number of different studies conducted in at least 71 countries found domestic violence against women to be most prevalent in [[Ethiopia]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Ethiopian women are most abused | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/6040180.stm | work = BBC News | date = 11 October 2006 }}</ref> A study by [[Pan American Health Organization]] conducted in 12 [[Latin American]] countries found the highest prevalence of domestic violence against women to be in [[Bolivia]].<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Bott | first1 = Sarah | last2 = Guedes | first2 = Alessandra | last3 = Goodwin | first3 = Mary | last4 = Mendoza | first4 = Jennifer Adams | title = Violence against women in Latin America and the Caribbean: a comparative analysis of population-based data from 12 countries | url = http://www.paho.org/Hq/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=8175%3A2013-violence-against-women-latin-america-caribbean-comparative-analysis&catid=1505%3Aabout-us&lang=en | publisher = [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] and the [[Pan American Health Organization]] | date = 2012 }} [http://www1.paho.org/hq/dmdocuments/violence-against-women-lac.pdf English pdf.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160204013306/http://www1.paho.org/hq/dmdocuments/violence-against-women-lac.pdf |date=4 February 2016 }} [http://www.paho.org/Hq/index.php?option=com_docman&task=doc_download&gid=24353&Itemid=270&lang=en Spanish pdf.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150408155433/http://www.paho.org/Hq/index.php?option=com_docman&task=doc_download&gid=24353&Itemid=270&lang=en |date=8 April 2015 }}</ref> In Western Europe, a country that has received major international criticism for the way it has dealt legally with the issue of violence against women is [[Finland]]; with authors pointing out that a high level of equality for women in the public sphere (as in Finland) should never be equated with equality in all other aspects of women's lives.<ref>{{Cite journal | last = Clarke | first = Kris | title = The paradoxical approach to intimate partner violence in Finland | journal = [[Tokiwa University#Publications|International Perspectives in Victimology]] | volume = 6 | issue = 1 | pages = 9\u201319 | publisher = [[Tokiwa University]] via [[California State University|The Press at California State University]] | doi = 10.5364/ipiv.6.1.19 | date = August 2011 | ref = harv | doi-broken-date = 2020-03-13 }} [https://www.academia.edu/992154/The_Paradoxical_Approach_to_Intimate_Partner_Violence_in_Finland Available through academia.edu.]</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=McKie |first1=Linda |last2=Hearn |first2=Jeff |title=Gender-neutrality and gender equality: comparing and contrasting policy responses to 'domestic violence' in Finland and Scotland |journal=[[Scottish Affairs]] |volume=48 |issue=1 |pages=85\u2013107 |publisher=[[Edinburgh University Press]] |doi=10.3366/scot.2004.0043 |date=August 2004 |ref=harv }} [https://web.archive.org/web/20131021023708/http://www.scottishaffairs.org/backiss/pdfs/sa48/sa48_McKie_and_Hearn.pdf Pdf.]</ref><ref>{{cite report |date=September 2008 |title=Case Closed: Rape and Human Rights in the Nordic Countries |publisher=Amnesty International |url=https://amnesty.dk/media/1557/case-closed.pdf | pages = 89\u201391 | quote = Finland is repeatedly reminded of its widespread problem of violence against women and recommended to take more efficient measures to deal with the situation. International criticism concentrates on the lack of measures to combat violence against women in general and in particular on the lack of a national action plan to combat such violence and on the lack of legislation on domestic violence. (...) Compared to Sweden, Finland has been slower to reform legislation on violence against women. In Sweden, domestic violence was already illegal in 1864, while in Finland such violence was not outlawed until 1970, over a hundred years later. In Sweden the punishment of victims of incest was abolished in 1937, but not until 1971 in Finland. Rape within marriage was criminalised in Sweden in 1962, but the equivalent Finnish legislation only came into force in 1994 \u2013 making Finland one of the last European countries to criminalise marital rape. In addition, assaults taking place on private property did not become impeachable offences in Finland until 1995. Only in 1997 did victims of sexual offences and domestic violence in Finland become entitled to government-funded counselling and support services for the duration of their court cases. | ref = harv | postscript = .}}</ref>\n\n====Diagnosis planning====\nThe [[American Psychiatric Association]] planning and research committees for the forthcoming [[DSM-5]] (2013) have canvassed a series of new [[Relational disorder]]s, which include ''Marital Conflict Disorder Without Violence'' or ''Marital Abuse Disorder (Marital Conflict Disorder With Violence)''.<ref name=\"Personality\">{{cite book| last1 = First | first1 = Michael B. | last2 = Bell | first2 = Carl C. | last3 = Cuthbert | first3 = Bruce | last4 = Krystal | first4 = John H. | last5 = Malison | first5 = Robert | last6 = Offord | first6 = David R. | last7 = Reiss | first7 = David | last8 = Shea | first8 = M. Tracie | last9 = Widger | first9 = Tom | last10 = Wisner | first10 = Katherine L. | chapter = Personality disorders and relational disorders: a research agenda for addressing crucial gaps in DSM | chapterurl = https://contextualscience.org/system/files/Kupfer,2002.pdf | editor-last1 = Kupfer | editor-first1 = David J. | editor-last2 = First | editor-first2 = Michael B. | editor-last3 = Regier | editor-first3 = Darrel A. | title = A research agenda for DSM-V | publisher = [[American Psychiatric Association]] | location = Washington, D.C. | year = 2002 | isbn = 9780890422922 | ref = harv }}</ref>{{rp|164, 166}} Couples with marital disorders sometimes come to clinical attention because the couple recognize long-standing dissatisfaction with their marriage and come to the [[clinician]] on their own initiative or are referred by an astute health care professional. Secondly, there is serious violence in the marriage that is -\"usually the husband battering the wife\".<ref name=\"Personality\" />{{rp|163}} In these cases the emergency room or a legal authority often is the first to notify the [[clinician]]. Most importantly, marital violence \"is a major risk factor for serious injury and even death and women in violent marriages are at much greater risk of being seriously injured or killed ([[National Advisory Council on Violence Against Women]] 2000)\".<ref name=\"Personality\" />{{rp|166}} The authors of this study add, \"There is current considerable controversy over whether male-to-female marital violence is best regarded as a reflection of male [[psychopathology]] and control or whether there is an empirical base and clinical utility for conceptualizing these patterns as relational.\"<ref name=\"Personality\" />{{rp|166}}\n\nRecommendations for clinicians making a diagnosis of ''Marital Relational Disorder'' should include the assessment of actual or \"potential\" male violence as regularly as they assess the potential for suicide in depressed patients. Further, \"clinicians should not relax their vigilance after a battered wife leaves her husband, because some data suggest that the period immediately following a marital separation is the period of greatest risk for the women. Many men will [[stalking|stalk]] and [[battery (crime)|batter]] their wives in an effort to get them to return or punish them for leaving. Initial assessments of the potential for violence in a marriage can be supplemented by standardized interviews and questionnaires, which have been reliable and valid aids in exploring marital violence more systematically.\"<ref name=\"Personality\" />{{rp|166}}\n \nThe authors conclude with what they call \"very recent information\"<ref name=\"Personality\" />{{rp|167, 168}} on the course of violent marriages, which suggests that \"over time a husband's battering may abate somewhat, but perhaps because he has successfully [[intimidate]]d his wife. The risk of violence remains strong in a marriage in which it has been a feature in the past. Thus, treatment is essential here; the clinician cannot just wait and watch.\"<ref name=\"Personality\" />{{rp|167, 168}} The most urgent clinical priority is the protection of the wife because she is the one most frequently at risk, and clinicians must be aware that supporting assertiveness by a battered wife may lead to more beatings or even death.<ref name=\"Personality\" />{{rp|167, 168}}\n\n====Honor killings====\n[[Honor killings]] are a common form of violence against women in certain parts of the world. Honor killings are perpetrated by family members (usually husbands, fathers, uncles or brothers) against women in the family who are believed to have placed dishonor to the family. The death of the dishonorable woman is believed to restore honor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.stanford.edu/group/womenscourage/communitybasedsolutions/the_role_of_community_in_combating_honor_killings.html|title=the role of community in combating honor killings|website=web.stanford.edu|access-date=2018-12-08}}</ref>  These killings are a traditional practice,{{where?|date=January 2019}} believed to have originated from tribal customs where an allegation against a woman can be enough to defile a family's reputation.<ref name=\"BBC_ethics\">{{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Ethics guide \u2013 Honour crimes | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/ethics/honourcrimes/crimesofhonour_1.shtml | work = [[BBC]] | date = | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last = Staff writer | title = Definition of honor killing | url = http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/honor%20killing | website = merriam-webster.com | publisher = [[Merriam-Webster]] | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref> Women are killed for reasons such as refusing to enter an [[arranged marriage]], being in a relationship that is disapproved by their relatives, attempting to leave a marriage, having sex outside marriage, becoming the victim of rape, dressing in ways that are deemed inappropriate.<ref name=\"BBC_ethics\" /><ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\">{{cite news | last = Harter | first = Pascale | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-13760895 | work= BBC News | title=Libya rape victims 'face honour killings' | date=14 June 2011| access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref>\n\nHonor killings are common in countries such as Afghanistan, Egypt, Iraq, Jordan, Lebanon, Libya, Morocco, Pakistan, Saudi Arabia, Syria, Turkey, Yemen.<ref name=\"bbc.co.uk\"/><ref>{{cite web | last = UN Women | author-link = UN Women | title = Violence against women: work of the General Assembly on violence against women | url = https://www.un.org/womenwatch/daw/vaw/v-work-ga.htm | website = un.org/womenwatch | publisher = [[UN Women]], Violence Against Women | access-date = 18 November 2013}}\n:''Listing for'':\n:* {{cite book | last = UN Secretary-General | author-link = Secretary-General of the United Nations | title = Working towards the elimination of crimes against women committed in the name of honour | url = http://daccess-ods.un.org/access.nsf/Get?Open&DS=A/57/169&Lang=E | id = A/57/169 | publisher = [[United Nations General Assembly]] | language = English | date = 2 July 2002 }} [http://daccess-ods.un.org/access.nsf/Get?Open&DS=A/57/169&Lang=A Arabic pdf.] [http://daccess-ods.un.org/access.nsf/Get?Open&DS=A/57/169&Lang=C Chinese pdf.] [http://daccess-ods.un.org/access.nsf/Get?Open&DS=A/57/169&Lang=F French pdf.] [http://daccess-ods.un.org/access.nsf/Get?Open&DS=A/57/169&Lang=R Russian pdf.] [http://daccess-ods.un.org/access.nsf/Get?Open&DS=A/57/169&Lang=S Spanish pdf.]</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Ghanizada | title = 240 cases of honor killing recorded in Afghanistan, AIHRC | url = http://www.khaama.com/240-cases-of-honor-killing-recorded-in-afghanistan-aihrc-2177 | publisher = [[Khaama Press]] | location = Afghanistan | date = 9 June 2013 | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = UPI |author-link=United Press International | title = AIHRC: 400 rape, honor killings registered in Afghanistan in 2 years | url = http://latinbusinesstoday.com/2013/06/aihrc-400-rape-honor-killings-registered-in-afghanistan-in-2-years/ | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150214224858/http://latinbusinesstoday.com/2013/06/aihrc-400-rape-honor-killings-registered-in-afghanistan-in-2-years/ | archive-date = 14 February 2015 | work = Latin Business Today | location = Kabul, Afghanistan | date = 10 June 2013 | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last1 = Bayoumy | first1 = Yara | last2 = Kami | first2 = Aseel | title=\"Honor killings\" require tougher laws, say Iraqi women | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/03/06/us-iraq-women-idUSTRE82510920120306 | work = Reuters | date=6 March 2012 | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref> Honor killings also occur in immigrant communities in Europe, the United States and Canada. Although honor killings are most often associated with the Middle East and South Asia, they occur in other parts of the world too.<ref name=\"BBC_ethics\" /><ref>{{cite web | title = International Domestic Violence Issues | url = http://www.sanctuaryforfamilies.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=252&Itemid=259 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141016194204/http://www.sanctuaryforfamilies.org/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=252&Itemid=259 | archive-date = 16 October 2014 | website = sanctuaryforfamilies.org | publisher = Sanctuary for Families }}</ref> In India, honor killings occur in the northern regions of the country, especially in the states of Punjab, Haryana, Bihar, Uttar Pradesh, Rajasthan, Jharkhand, Himachal Pradesh and Madhya Pradesh.<ref>{{cite news | last1 = Donald | first1 = Alice | last2 = Bishop | first2 = Hilary | title = World agenda: what justice? | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/worldservice/specials/1817_wawryw/page4.shtml | publisher = [[BBC World Service]]  | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = India court seeks 'honour killing' response | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/10364986 | work = BBC News |date = 21 June 2010  | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref> In Turkey, honor killings are a serious problem in Southeastern Anatolia.<ref>{{cite news | last = Rainsford | first = Sarah | title = 'Honour' crime defiance in Turkey | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/4357158.stm | work = BBC News | date = 19 October 2005 | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = Kardam | first = Filiz | editor-last = Murray | editor-first = Genevra | title = The dynamics of honor killings in Turkey: prospects for action | url = http://www.unfpa.org/publications/dynamics-honour-killings-turkey | publisher = [[United Nations Development Programme]], Population Association (Turkey) and [[United Nations Population Fund]] | date = 2005 | access-date = 18 November 2013}} [http://www.unfpa.org/upload/lib_pub_file/676_filename_honourkillings.pdf Pdf.]</ref>\n\n====Dowry violence====\n[[File:Say no to dowry.jpg|thumb|upright|Anti-dowry poster in [[Bangalore, India]]]]\n\nThe custom of [[dowry]], which is common in South Asia, especially in India, is the trigger of many forms of violence against women. [[Bride burning]] is a form of violence against women in which a bride is killed at home by her husband or husband's family due to his dissatisfaction over the dowry provided by her family. [[Dowry death]] refers to the phenomenon of women and girls being killed or committing [[suicide]] due to disputes regarding dowry. Dowry violence is common in India, Pakistan, Bangladesh and Nepal. In India, in 2011 alone, the National Crime Records Bureau reported 8,618 dowry deaths, while unofficial figures suggest the numbers to be at least three times higher.<ref>{{cite book | last = UN Women | author-link = UN Women | title = Confronting dowry-related violence in India: women at the center of justice | url = http://www.unwomen.org/en/news/stories/2012/12/confronting-dowry-related-violence-in-india-women-at-the-center-of-justice | publisher = [[UN Women]] | date = 24 December 2012 | access-date = 18 November 2013 }}</ref>\n\n====Forced marriage====\n{{main|Forced marriage}}\n[[File:Oskar Shmerling. Free love (Forced marriage). Molla Nasreddin.jpg|thumb|220px|left|Criticism of the [[Azerbaijani people|Azeri]] custom of [[forced marriage]], as depicted in the early 20th-century satirical periodical [[Molla Nasraddin (magazine)|Molla Nasraddin]]]]\nA [[forced marriage]] is a marriage in which one or both of the parties is married against their will. Forced marriages are common in South Asia, the Middle East and Africa. The customs of [[bride price]] and [[dowry]], that exist in many parts of the world, contribute to this practice. A forced marriage is also often the result of a dispute between families, where the dispute is 'resolved' by giving a female from one family to the other.<ref>''Citations'':\n* {{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Ethics guide \u2013 Slavery: Modern slavery | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/ethics/slavery/modern/modern_1.shtml#section_2 | work = [[BBC]] | date = | access-date = 5 September 2013}}\n* {{cite book | last = Shahinian | first = Gulnara | title = Report of the Special Rapporteur on contemporary forms of slavery, including its causes and consequences, Gulnara Shahinian: Thematic report on servile marriage (A/HRC/21/41) | url = http://www.ohchr.org/Documents/HRBodies/HRCouncil/RegularSession/Session21/A-HRC-21-41_en.pdf | publisher =  United Nations. Human Rights Council Twenty-first session | date = 10 July 2012}}\n* {{cite book | last = UNIFEM | author-link = United Nations Development Fund for Women | title = Ending violence against women & girls \u2013 Evidence, data and knowledge in the Pacific Island Countries: literature review and annotated bibliography |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110708174234/http://www.undp.org.fj/pdf/unp/evaw.pdf | url = http://www.undp.org.fj/pdf/unp/evaw.pdf |url-status=dead |archivedate=8 July 2011 | publisher = [[United Nations Development Fund for Women|UNIFEM]] | date = August 2010 | accessdate = 8 July 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe custom of [[bride kidnapping]] continues to exist in some Central Asian countries such as Kyrgyzstan, Kazakhstan, Uzbekistan, and the Caucasus, or parts of Africa, especially Ethiopia. A girl or a woman is abducted by the would be groom, who is often helped by his friends. The victim is often raped by the would be groom, after which he may try to negotiate a bride price with the village elders to legitimize the marriage.<ref>''News articles'':\n* {{cite news | last = Staff writer | title=World: Africa, Ethiopia: Revenge of the abducted bride | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/371944.stm | work =[[BBC News]] | date=18 June 1999 | access-date = 19 November 2013}}\n* {{cite news| last = Gena | first = Alem | title = Ethiopia: Surviving forced marriage | url = http://www.irinnews.org/report/69993/ethiopia-surviving-forced-marriage | work = [[IRIN]] | date = 23 February 2007 | accessdate = 3 April 2016}}\n* {{cite book | last = PI | author-link = Pathfinder International | title = Report on causes and consequences of early marriage in Amhara Region |publisher=[[Pathfinder International]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130323124732/http://www.pathfinder.org/publications-tools/pdfs/Causes-and-Consequesnces-of-Early-Marriage-in-the-Amhara-Region-of-Ethiopia.pdf |archivedate=23 March 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all |url=http://www.pathfinder.org/publications-tools/pdfs/Causes-and-Consequesnces-of-Early-Marriage-in-the-Amhara-Region-of-Ethiopia.pdf | date = July 2006 |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nForced and child marriages are practiced by some inhabitants In Tanzania. Girls are sold by their families to older men for financial benefits and often girls are married off as soon as they hit puberty, which can be as young as seven years old.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.hrw.org/news/2014/10/29/tanzania-child-marriage-harms-girls|title=Tanzania: Child Marriage Harms Girls|date=2014-10-29|work=Human Rights Watch|access-date=2018-11-30|language=en}}</ref> To the older men, these young brides act as symbols of masculinity and accomplishment. Child brides endure forced sex, causing health risks and growth impediments.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ezer|first=T|last2=et|first2=al.|date=2006|title=Child marriage and guardianship in tanzania: Robbing girls of their childhood and infantilizing women|url=https://heinonline.org/HOL/P?h=hein.journals/grggenl7&i=367&a=c3VueWJ1ZmZhbG8uZWR1|journal=Georgetown Journal of Gender and the Law|volume=Special Issue|pages=357\u2013450|via=Hein}}</ref> Primary education is usually not completed for young girls in forced marriages. Married and pregnant students are often discriminated against, and expelled and excluded from school.<ref name=\":0\" /> The Law of Marriage Act currently does not address issues with guardianship and child marriage. The issue of child marriage is not addressed enough in this law, and only establishes a minimum age of 18 for the boys of Tanzania. A minimum age needs to be enforced for girls to stop these practices and provide them with equal rights and a less harmful life.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://heinonline.org/HOL/P?h=hein.journals/frdint38&i=660&a=c3VueWJ1ZmZhbG8uZWR1|title=- HeinOnline.org|website=heinonline.org|language=en|access-date=2018-11-30}}</ref>\n\n====Force-feeding====\nIn some countries, notably Mauritania, young girls are forcibly fattened to prepare them for marriage, because obesity is seen as desirable. This practice of [[force-feeding]] is known as ''[[leblouh]]'' or ''gavage''.<ref>''Citations'':\n* {{cite book | last = Popenoe | first = Rebecca | chapter = Getting fat | editor-last = Popenoe | editor-first = Rebecca | chapterurl = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=25H0_G9MG10C&pg=PA39 | title = Feeding desire: fatness, beauty, and sexuality among a Saharan people | pages = 33&ndash;50 | publisher = Routledge | location = London New York | year = 2004 | isbn = 9780415280969 | ref = harv }}\n::''Book review'': {{cite web | last = Fan | title = Space and body modification: Rebecca Popenoe's ''Feeding Desire'' (blog) | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160304231342/http://www.savagemind.org/tag/body/ | archive-date = 4 March 2016 | url = http://www.savagemind.org/tag/body/ |publisher= Savage Mind via [[WordPress]] |date=3 August 2012 |accessdate=3 April 2016}}\n* {{cite news | last = LaFraniere | first = Sharon | title = In Mauritania, seeking to end an overfed ideal | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/04/world/africa/04mauritania.html | work = [[The New York Times]] | quote = Girls as young as 5 and as old as 19 had to drink up to five gallons of fat-rich camel's or cow's milk daily, aiming for silvery stretch marks on their upper arms. If a girl refused or vomited, the village weight-gain specialist might squeeze her foot between sticks, pull her ear, pinch her inner thigh, bend her finger backward or force her to drink her own vomit. In extreme cases, girls die, due to a burst stomach. The practice was known as gavage, a French term for force-feeding geese to obtain foie gras. | date = 4 July 2007 | access-date = 30 June 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe practice goes back to the 11th century, and has been reported to have made a significant comeback after a [[2008 Mauritanian coup d'\u00e9tat|military junta took over the country in 2008]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Smith | first = Alex Duval | title = Girls being force-fed for marriage as junta revives fattening farms | url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/mar/01/mauritania-force-feeding-marriage | work = [[The Observer]] | date = 1 March 2009 | access-date = 22 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Abuse related to son-preference====\n[[File:2011 Census sex ratio map for the states and Union Territories of India Boys to Girls 0 to 1 age group.svg|thumb|250px|left|A map of [[India]]'s child sex ratio, 2011.]]\n[[File:2012 Birth Sex Ratio World Map.jpg|thumb|250px|World map of birth sex ratios, 2012]]\n[[File:Chinese anti infanticide tract from 1800.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Chinese anti-infanticide tract circa 1800. China has a long history of son preference, which was aggravated after the enforcement of the [[one child policy]].]]\n''Son preference'' is a custom rooted in gender inequality that is prevalent in many countries and found across religions and classes.<ref name=\"StopVAW_son\">{{cite web | last = Staff writer | title = Son preference | url =http://www.stopvaw.org/harmful_practices_son_preference | website = stopvaw.org | publisher = Stop Violence Against Women | date = June 2010 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}</ref> Although preference for a specific sex of the child may be common in an abstract way in many cultures, when such preference is so strong as to lead to the rejection of the child or to violence against the mother, this crosses the line into [[domestic violence]], [[child abuse]] and violence against women. Such forms of son preference are common especially in parts of [[South Asia]], [[East Asia]] and the [[Caucasus]]. Manifestations of such practices include [[sex selective abortion]], [[female infanticide]], [[child abandonment|female child abandonment]], as well as favoring sons with regard to allocating of family resources.<ref name=\"StopVAW_son\" />\n\n[[China]] and [[India]] have a very strong son preference. In China, the [[one child policy]] was largely responsible for an unbalanced sex ratio. Sex-selective abortion, as well as rejection of girl children is common. [[The Dying Rooms]] is a 1995 [[television]] [[documentary film]] about Chinese state orphanages, which documented how parents abandoned their newborn girls into [[orphanages]], where the staff would leave the children in rooms to die of thirst, or starvation.\nAnother manifestation of son preference is the violence inflicted against mothers who give birth to girls.<ref>''News articles'':\n* {{cite news | last = Sarwary | first = Bilal | title = Afghan woman is killed 'for giving birth to a girl' | url = https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-16787534 | work = [[BBC News]] | location = Kabul, Afghanistan | date = 30 January 2012 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}\n* {{cite news | last = Agarwal | first = Keshav | title = 23-year-old woman killed for giving birth to twin daughters | url = http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bareilly/23-year-old-woman-killed-for-giving-birth-to-twin-daughters/articleshow/57785767.cms | work = [[The Times of India]] | date = 23 March 2017 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}\n* {{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = 56 killed for giving birth to girl child in Pakistan | url = http://www.deccanchronicle.com/131127/news-world/article/56-killed-giving-birth-girl-child-pakistan | work = [[Deccan Chronicle]] | location = Hyderabad, Telangana, India | date = 27 November 2013 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Acid throwing===\n{{main|Acid throwing}}\n[[File:Acid attack victim.jpg|left|Acid attack victim in [[Cambodia]]|thumb|250px]]\n[[Acid throwing]], also called acid attack, or vitriolage, is defined as the act of throwing acid onto the body of a person \"with the intention of injuring or disfiguring [them] out of jealousy or revenge\".<ref>{{Cite book | last =Vig |first= Krishan| chapter = Corrosive poisons: vitriolage | chapterurl = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Ip1rAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA462 | editor-last =Vig |editor-first=Krishan | title=Textbook of forensic medicine and toxicology: principles and practice | page=462 |publisher=Elsevier | location = India | year=2014 |edition=5th | isbn=9788131226841 }}</ref> The most common types of acid used in these attacks are sulfuric, nitric, or hydrochloric acid.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Welsh | first = Jane | title = \"It was like burning in hell\": A comprehensive exploration of acid attack violence | journal = Carolina Papers on International Health | volume = 32 |publisher=Center for Global Initiatives, [[University of North Carolina]] |accessdate=3 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130123191359/http://cgi.unc.edu/uploads/media_items/it-was-like-burning-in-hell-a-comparative-exploration-of-acid-attack-violence.original.pdf|url=http://cgi.unc.edu/uploads/media_items/it-was-like-burning-in-hell-a-comparative-exploration-of-acid-attack-violence.original.pdf |archivedate=23 January 2013 |df=dmy-all | date = Fall 2006}}</ref> Perpetrators of these attacks throw [[acid]] at their victims, usually at their faces, burning them, and damaging [[skin]] tissue, often exposing and sometimes dissolving the bones.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Swanson | first = Jordan | title = Acid attacks: Bangladesh's efforts to stop the violence | journal = Harvard Health Policy Review | volume = 3 | issue = 1 | page = 3 | publisher = Harvard Internfaculty Initiative in Health Policy | date = Spring 2002 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20060117184047/http://hcs.harvard.edu/~epihc/currentissue/spring2002/swanson-3.php | archive-date = 17 January 2006 | url = http://hcs.harvard.edu:80/~epihc/currentissue/spring2002/swanson-3.php | ref = harv | url-status = dead | df = dmy-all }}</ref> The long term consequences of these attacks include [[blindness]] and permanent [[scarring]] of the face and body.<ref>{{cite news | last = AP | author-link = Associated Press |url=http://archives.cnn.com/2000/ASIANOW/south/11/11/bangladesh.acid.ap/index.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070922210725/http://archives.cnn.com/2000/ASIANOW/south/11/11/bangladesh.acid.ap/index.html |archivedate=22 September 2007 |title= Bangladesh combats an acid onslaught against women |work=[[CNN]]|date= 12 November 2000 |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book | last1 = Bahl | first1 = Taur | last2 = Syed | first2 = M. H. | title = Encyclopaedia of Muslim world | publisher = Anmol Publications | location = New Delhi | year = 2003 | isbn = 9788126114191}}</ref> Women and girls are the victims in 75-80% of cases.<ref>{{cite news | last = de Castella | first = Tom | title=How many acid attacks are there? | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-23631395 | work=[[BBC News]] | date=9 August 2013 |accessdate= 18 November 2013}}</ref> Acid attacks are often connected to domestic disputes, including dowry disputes, and refusal of a proposition for marriage, or of sexual advances. Such attacks are common in South Asia, in countries such as Bangladesh, Pakistan, India; and in Southeast Asia, especially in Cambodia.<ref>''Articles'':\n* {{cite news | last = Shackle | first = Samira | title = Acid attacks in Pakistan: A sorry litany of male egotism | url = http://www.newstatesman.com/world-affairs/2012/11/acid-attacks-pakistan-sorry-litany-male-egotism | work = [[New Statesman]] | date = 9 November 2012 |accessdate= 8 September 2013}} ''Interview with [[Sharmeen Obaid-Chinoy]] one of the directors the documentary \"[[Saving Face (2012 film)|Saving Face]]\".''\n* {{cite news | last = CBC | title = Longueuil woman burned and in coma after acid attack|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.ca/2012/08/28/nikolas-stefanatos-quebec-acid-attack_n_1838232.html |work=[[HuffPost]] | date = 28 October 2012 |accessdate=8 September 2013}}\n* {{cite news |last = Ungaro | first = Cosima | title = Nurbanu, Bangladeshi woman, forced to return to husband after acid attack | url = https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/11/28/nurbanu-acid-attack_n_2206621.html |work=[[HuffPost]] |accessdate= 8 September 2013  |date=28 November 2012}}\n* {{cite news | last =Scholte| first =Marianne| title =Acid attacks in Bangladesh: a voice for the victims| work = [[Spiegel Online]]| url =http://www.spiegel.de/international/0,1518,406485,00.html | date = 17 March 2006 | accessdate = 21 March 2008}}\n* {{cite book | last = Various |title=Combating acid violence in Bangladesh, India, and Cambodia |url= http://www.lawschool.cornell.edu/womenandjustice/upload/Combating-Acid-Violence-Report.pdf |publisher= [[Cornell Law School#Institutes and Programs|Avon Global Center for Women and Justice at Cornell Law School]], [[New York City Bar Association|Committee on International Human Rights of the, New York City Bar Association]], [[Cornell Law School#Campus|Cornell Law School International Human Rights Clinic]] and the Virtue Foundation | location = New York |accessdate=3 April 2016}}\n* {{cite book | last = CASC | title = Breaking the silence: addressing acid attacks in Cambodia | url = http://www.cambodianacidsurvivorscharity.org/docs/breaking_the_silence.pdf |publisher=Cambodian Acid Survivors Charity (CASC) |accessdate=3 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219010314/http://www.cambodianacidsurvivorscharity.org/docs/breaking_the_silence.pdf |archivedate=19 December 2013 |df=dmy-all | date = May 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Reproductive coercion===\n[[File:Mauricio rugendas - el malon.jpg|thumb|The painting depicts a Chilean woman being kidnapped during a [[mal\u00f3n]]. [[Bride kidnapping]] for the purpose of [[forced marriage]] and [[forced pregnancy]] was common through the history in many countries.]]\n{{Main|Reproductive coercion|Forced pregnancy|Bride kidnapping}}\nReproductive coercion is a form of [[domestic violence|domestic]] or [[intimate partner violence]], that involves violent, manipulative or deceptive behavior against [[reproductive health]] or [[reproductive rights]] within an intimate relation and includes a collection of behaviors intended to lead to [[forced pregnancy]].<ref name=\"ACOG\">{{cite journal | last = Committee on Health Care for Underserved Women | title = Committee Opinion No. 554: Reproductive and Sexual Coercion | journal = [[Obstetrics & Gynecology (journal)|Obstetrics and Gynecology]] | volume = 121 | issue = 2 Pt 1 | pages = 411&ndash;415 | publisher = [[Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|LWW]] | pmid = 23344307 | doi = 10.1097/01.AOG.0000426427.79586.3b | date = February 2013 | url = https://www.acog.org/Resources-And-Publications/Committee-Opinions/Committee-on-Health-Care-for-Underserved-Women/Reproductive-and-Sexual-Coercion | ref = harv }}</ref> Reproductive coercion is used to maintain power, control, and domination within a relationship and over a partner through an unwanted pregnancy. It is considered a serious public health issue.<ref name=\"ACOG\"/><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Chamberlain | first1 = Linda | last2 = Levenson | first2 = Rebecca | title = Reproductive health and partner violence guidelines: an integrated response to intimate partner Violence and reproductive coercion | url = http://www.futureswithoutviolence.org/userfiles/file/HealthCare/Repro_Guide.pdf | publisher = Family Violence Prevention Fund | location = San Francisco | date = 2010 }}</ref> This reproductive control is highly correlated to [[unintended pregnancy]].<ref>{{cite journal | last = Coker | first = Ann L. | title = Does physical intimate partner violence affect sexual health? A systematic review | journal = [[Trauma, Violence, & Abuse]] | volume = 8 | issue = 2| pages = 149&ndash;177 | publisher = [[SAGE Publications|Sage]] | pmid = 17545572 | doi = 10.1177/1524838007301162 | date = April 2007 | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\nForced pregnancy is the practice of forcing a woman or girl to become [[pregnant]], often as part of a [[forced marriage]], including by means of [[bride kidnapping]], through rape (including [[marital rape]], [[war rape]] and [[genocidal rape]]) or as part of a program of breeding [[slave]]s (see [[Slave breeding in the United States]]). In the 20th century, state mandated forced marriage with the aim of increasing the population was practiced by some authoritarian governments, notably during the [[Khmer Rouge]] regime in [[Cambodia]], which systematically forced people into marriages ordering them to have children, in order to increase the population and continue the revolution.<ref>{{cite book | last = Anderson | first = Natalae | title = Memorandum: Charging forced marriage as a crime against humanity | url = http://www.d.dccam.org/Abouts/Intern/Natalae_Forced_marriage.pdf | publisher = Documentation Center of Cambodia | date = 22 September 2010 | access-date = 8 October 2017 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20171020153617/http://www.d.dccam.org/Abouts/Intern/Natalae_Forced_marriage.pdf | archive-date = 20 October 2017 | url-status = dead }}</ref> Forced pregnancy is strongly connected to the custom of [[bride price]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Bawah | first1 = Ayaga Agula | last2 = Akweongo | first2 = Patricia | last3 = Simmons | first3 = Ruth | last4 = Phillips | first4 = James F. | title = Women's fears and men's anxieties: the impact of family planning on gender relations in Northern Ghana | journal = [[Studies in Family Planning]] | volume = 30 | issue = 1 | pages = 54&ndash;66 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] on behalf of the [[Population Council]] | date = 1999 | url = https://www.popcouncil.org/research/womens-fears-and-mens-anxieties-the-impact-of-family-planning-on-gender-rel | ref = harv | doi=10.1111/j.1728-4465.1999.00054.x| pmid = 10216896 | hdl = 2027.42/73927 }} [http://www.popcouncil.org/uploads/pdfs/councilarticles/sfp/SFP301Bawah.pdf Pdf.]</ref>\n\nWithin the discourse on reproductive rights, the issue of [[abortion]] is often debated. [[Abortion law]] falls within the jurisdiction of each country, although [[forced abortion]] is prohibited by international law. The [[Convention on preventing and combating violence against women and domestic violence|Istanbul Convention]] prohibits forced abortion and [[forced sterilization]] (Article 39).<ref>{{cite book | last = CoE | author-link = Council of Europe | title = Convention on preventing and combating violence against women and domestic violence | url = https://rm.coe.int/168046031c | publisher = [[Council of Europe]] | date = 12 April 2011 }}</ref> The issue of ''forced continuation of pregnancy'' (i.e. denying a woman safe and legal abortion) is also seen by some organizations as a violation of women's rights, although there are no binding international obligations on this issue. However, the [[Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination against Women]] considers the criminalization of abortion a \"violations of women's sexual and reproductive health and rights\" and a form of \"gender based violence\"; paragraph 18 of its ''General recommendation No. 35 on gender based violence against women, updating general recommendation No. 19'' states, \"Violations of women\u2019s sexual and reproductive health and rights, such as forced sterilizations, forced abortion, forced pregnancy, ''criminalisation of abortion'', ''denial or delay of safe abortion and post abortion care'', ''forced continuation of pregnancy'', abuse and mistreatment of women and girls seeking sexual and reproductive health information, goods and services, are forms of gender based violence that, depending on the circumstances, may amount to torture or cruel, inhuman or degrading treatment.\"<ref>{{cite book | last = Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination Against Women | author-link = Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women#Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination Against Women | title = General recommendation No. 35 on gender-based violence against women, updating general recommendation No. 19 | url = http://tbinternet.ohchr.org/Treaties/CEDAW/Shared%20Documents/1_Global/CEDAW_C_GC_35_8267_E.pdf | publisher = [[Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination Against Women]] (CEDAW) | id = CEDAW/C/GC/35 | date = 14 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Mob violence===\nThere have been [[Hassi Messaoud mob attacks against women|mob attacks against single women]] in [[Hassi Messaoud]], [[Algeria]] in 2001.<ref name=\"Amnesty\">{{cite web|title=Algerian authorities must investigate and stop attacks against women |url=https://www.amnesty.org.au/news/comments/22931/ |publisher=Amnesty International|accessdate=13 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903140432/http://www.amnesty.org.au/news/comments/22931/|archivedate=3 September 2011|df=dmy-all}}</ref> 95 women had been attacked by mobs of men, with at least six fatalities, although the authorities denied this.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Grozelle|first=Renee S.|date=2015|title=Mob Violence Against Women in Algeria: A Historical Case Analysis|url=http://www.inquiriesjournal.com/articles/1016/mob-violence-against-women-in-algeria-a-historical-case-analysis|journal=Inquiries Journal|language=en|volume=7|issue=03}}</ref> As of 2011, similar mob attacks against women were continuing in [[Hassi Messaoud]] and elsewhere in Algeria, notably [[M'Sila, Algeria|M'sila]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Stop renewed attacks on women |url=http://www.wluml.org/node/7420|publisher=Women Living Under Muslim Laws|accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Algerian authorities must investigate and stop attacks against women|url=https://www.amnesty.org.au/news/comments/22931/|publisher=Amnesty International|accessdate=13 August 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110903140432/http://www.amnesty.org.au/news/comments/22931/|archivedate=3 September 2011}}</ref> However, mob violence against women in the country dates back decades, and increased specifically after gaining independence from France in 1962, which was followed by return to stricter religious norms.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nAccording to [[Amnesty International]], \"some women have been sexually abused\" and were targeted \"not just because they are women, but because they are living alone and are economically independent\".<ref name=\"Amnesty\" />\n\n=== Dating abuse ===\n{{See|Dating abuse|Teen dating violence}}\nDating abuse or dating violence is the perpetration of coercion, intimidation or assault in the context of [[dating]] or [[courtship]]. It is also when one partner tries to maintain [[abusive power and control]]. Dating violence is defined by the CDC as \"the physical, sexual, psychological, or emotional violence within a dating relationship, including stalking\".<ref>{{cite web | title = Intimate partner violence: teen dating violence | url = https://www.cdc.gov/violenceprevention/intimatepartnerviolence/teen_dating_violence.html | website = cdc.gov | publisher = [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] | date = 2016 | accessdate = 21 October 2017 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181230230859/https://www.cdc.gov/ViolencePrevention/intimatepartnerviolence/teen_dating_violence.html | archive-date = 30 December 2018 | url-status = dead }} [https://www.cdc.gov/violenceprevention/pdf/teen-dating-violence-factsheet-a.pdf Fact sheet pdf.] </ref> In some countries it is common for older men to engage in \"compensated dating\" with underage girls. Such relationships are called [[enjo k\u014dsai]] in Japan, and are also common in Asian countries such as Taiwan, South Korea, Hong Kong. The WHO condemned \"economically coerced sex (e.g. school girls having sex with \u201csugar daddies\u201d ([[Sugar baby]] in return for school fees)\" as a form of violence against women.<ref name=\"WHO_VAW\" />\n\n===Sexual violence on college campuses===\n{{See|Campus sexual assault}}\nSexual violence on college campuses is considered a major problem in the United States. According to the conclusion of a major Campus Sexual Assault (CSA) Study: \"The CSA Study data suggest women at universities are at considerable risk for experiencing sexual assault.\"<ref>{{cite book  | last1 = Krebs | first1 = Christopher P. | last2 =Lindquist | first2 = Christine H. | last3 =Warner | first3 = Tara D. | last4 =Fisher | first4 = Bonnie S. | last5 =Martin | first5 = Sandra L. | title = Campus sexual assault (CSA) study: final report | publisher = [[RTI International]] | url = https://www.ncjrs.gov/App/Publications/abstract.aspx?ID=243011 | date = October 2007 }} {{NCJ|243011}} [https://www.ncjrs.gov/pdffiles1/nij/grants/221153.pdf Pdf.]</ref> Sexual violence on campus has been researched in other countries too, such as Canada,<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = DeKeseredy | first1 = Walter | last2 = Kelly|  first2 = Katharine | title = The incidence and prevalence of woman abuse in Canadian university and college dating relationships | journal = [[Canadian Journal of Sociology]] | volume = 18 | issue = 2 | pages = 137&ndash;159 | publisher = [[University of Alberta]] | jstor = 3341255 | doi = 10.2307/3341255 | date = 1993 | ref = harv }}</ref> the UK,<ref>{{cite book | last = NUS | author-link = National Union of Students (United Kingdom) |title=Hidden Marks: A study of women student's experiences of harassment, stalking, violence, and sexual assault | url = http://www.nus.org.uk/Global/NUS_hidden_marks_report_2nd_edition_web.pdf | publisher = [[National Union of Students (United Kingdom)|National Union of Students]] | location = London, UK | date = 2011| edition = 2nd|accessdate=10 January 2015}}</ref> and New Zealand.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Gavey | authorlink=Nicola Gavey|first = Nicola | title = Sexual victimization prevalence among New Zealand university students | journal = [[Journal of Consulting and Clinical Psychology]] | volume = 59 | issue = 3 | pages = 464&ndash;466 | publisher = [[American Psychological Association]] via [[PsycINFO|PsycNET]] | doi = 10.1037/0022-006X.59.3.464 | date = June 1991 | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\n===Restrictions on freedom of movement===\nWomen are, in many parts of the world, severely restricted in their [[freedom of movement]].\nFreedom of movement is an essential right, recognized by international instruments, including Article 15 (4) of [[CEDAW]].<ref>{{cite book | last =  UN General Assembly | author-link =  UN General Assembly | title = The convention on the elimination of all forms of discrimination against women (CEDAW) | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140326154350/http://www.un.org/womenwatch/daw/cedaw/text/econvention.htm | archive-date = 26 March 2014 | url = http://www.un.org/womenwatch/daw/cedaw/text/econvention.htm | publisher = [[UN Women|UN Women, Division for the Advancement of Women]] | date = 1979 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}</ref> Nevertheless, in some countries, women are not legally allowed to leave home without a [[Wali (Islamic legal guardian)|male guardian]] (male relative or husband).<ref>{{cite news | last = Lee | first = Dave | title = Saudi Arabian woman challenges male guardianship laws | url = https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-13932287 | work = [[BBC World Service]] | date = 29 June 2011 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}</ref> Even in countries where there are no laws against women traveling alone, there are strong social norms, such as [[purdah]] - a religious and social practice of female [[seclusion]] prevalent especially among some [[Muslim]] and [[Hindu]] communities in [[South Asia]]. Many countries have laws on what type of clothing women may or may not wear in public (see [[Hijab by country]]). Women in some cultures are forced into [[social isolation]] during their [[menstruation|menstrual period]]s. In parts of Nepal for instance, they are forced to live in sheds, are forbidden to touch men or even to enter the courtyard of their own homes, and are barred from consuming milk, yogurt, butter, meat, and various other foods, for fear they will contaminate those goods. (see [[Chhaupadi]]). Women have died during this period because of starvation, bad weather, or bites by snakes.<ref>''Articles'':\n* {{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = PM concerned over death of woman in Chaupadi | url = http://kathmandupost.ekantipur.com/news/2016-11-19/pm-concerned-over-death-of-woman-in-chaupadi.html | work = [[The Kathmandu Post]] | date = 19 November 2016 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}\n* {{cite news| last = Pokharel | first = Sugam | title = Nepali 'mensuration hut' ritual claims life of teenage girl | url = http://edition.cnn.com/2017/07/10/asia/nepal-menstruation-hut-deaths-outrage/index.html | work = [[CNN]] | date = 10 July 2017 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}\n* {{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Nepal criminalises banishing menstruating women to huts | url = https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-40885748 | work = [[BBC News]] | date = 10 August 2017 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}\n* {{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Nepali girl dies due to banned mensuration practice | url = http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/12/nepali-girl-dies-menstruation-chhaupadi-161219090727200.html | work = [[Al Jazeera]] | date = December 2016 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}</ref> In cultures where women are restricted from being in public places, by law or custom, women who break such restrictions often face violence.<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Freedom of movement and women's economic empowerment | url = https://www.empowerwomen.org/en/who-we-are/news/2016/2/freedom-of-movement-and-womens-economic-empowerment | work = Empower Women | date = February 2016 | access-date = 3 October 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Denial of medical care===\n[[File:Maternal mortality rate worldwide.jpg|thumb|300px|[[Maternal Mortality Rate]] worldwide, as defined by the number of maternal deaths per 100,000 live births from any cause related to or aggravated by pregnancy or its management, excluding accidental or incidental causes.<ref name=CIA2010>[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2223rank.html?countryName=Australia&countryCode=as&regionCode=aus&rank=156#as Country Comparison: Maternal Mortality Rate] in [[:en:The World Factbook|The CIA World Factbook]]. Date of Information: 2010</ref>]]\nWomen in many parts of the world are often denied medical care. Denial of access to \nhealth assistance, along with denial of access to other services, is a form of socioeconomic violence against women.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.womensrefugeecommission.org/images/zdocs/gl_sgbv03_01.pdf|title=chapter1: Overview of sexual and gender-based violence|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref> According to the WHO, \"Discrimination in health care settings takes many forms and is often manifested when an individual or group is denied access to health care services that are otherwise available to others. It can also occur through denial of services that are only needed by certain groups, such as women.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.who.int/news-room/detail/27-06-2017-joint-united-nations-statement-on-ending-discrimination-in-health-care-settings|title=Joint United Nations statement on ending discrimination in health care settings|website=www.who.int}}</ref> \n\nWomen may be denied medical care for numerous reasons, including lack of necessary [[freedom of movement]] allowing women to leave home so they can go to a medical facility, lack of financial resources, the need (in law or in practice) for a male relative or husband to consent to the medical care of the woman. A common consequence of denial of women's medical care is [[maternal mortality]]. Globally, there are more than 300.000 cases of maternal mortality yearly, with 99% of all maternal deaths occurring in developing countries.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs348/en/|title=Maternal mortality|website=World Health Organization}}</ref> \n\nDenial of medical care often occurs with regard to reproductive and sexual health. Sometimes women themselves avoid the medical system  for fear of being reported to the police or facing family violence due to having [[premarital sex]] or being the victims of [[sexual violence]]. In some parts of Latin America, with very strict anti-abortion laws, pregnant women avoid the medical system due to fear of being investigated by the authorities if they have a miscarriage, or a stillbirth, or other problems with the pregnancy. Prosecuting such women is quite common in places such as [[El Salvador]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/latest/news/2017/07/el-salvador-rape-survivor-sentenced-to-30-years-in-jail-under-extreme-anti-abortion-law/|title=El Salvador: Rape survivor sentenced to 30 years in jail under extreme anti-abortion law|website=www.amnesty.org}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/av/world-latin-america-32491838/el-salvador-women-jailed-for-miscarriages|title=Jailed for a miscarriage|website=BBC News}}</ref><ref name=\"ReferenceB\">Pr\u00fcgl, E. (Lecturer) (2 December 2013). Gender and International Affairs 2013. INTERNATIONAL FEMINIST MOVEMENTS. Lecture conducted from The Graduate Institute of International and Development Studies (IHEID), Geneva, Switzerland.</ref><ref name=\"reuters.com\">{{cite news|last=Hosenball |first=Mark |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/06/06/us-usa-wiretaps-verizon-idUSBRE95502920130606 |title=Obama administration defends massive phone record collection |work=Reuters |date=6 June 2013 |accessdate=6 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn developed societies, women face medial discrimination in that female health concerns are often dismissed or downplayed, especially when reproductive health is concerned. Research since 2001 has consistently shown that medical practitioners have been \"dismissing, misdiagnosing, or cluelessly shrugging\" at women seeking medical assistance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/family/archive/2018/08/womens-health-care-gaslighting/567149/|title=The Doctor Doesn\u2019t Listen to Her. But the Media Is Starting To.|last=Fetters|first=Ashley|date=2018-08-10|website=The Atlantic|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Pag\u00e1n|first=Camille Noe|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/05/03/well/live/when-doctors-downplay-womens-health-concerns.html|title=When Doctors Downplay Women\u2019s Health Concerns|date=2018-05-03|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-24|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> \n\nDenial of medical care for women has led to the exclusion of female needs in medical research and diagnosis, leading to a male bias in medical trials at the expense of women's health.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Jackson|first=Gabrielle|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2019/nov/13/the-female-problem-male-bias-in-medical-trials|title=The female problem: how male bias in medical trials ruined women's health|date=2019-11-13|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-24|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n===Stalking===\n{{Main|Stalking}}\nStalking is unwanted or obsessive attention by an individual or group toward another person, often manifested through persistent [[harassment]], [[intimidation]], or following/monitoring of the victim. Stalking is often understood as \"course of conduct directed at a specific person that would cause a reasonable person to feel fear\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.victimsofcrime.org/our-programs/stalking-resource-center/stalking-information |title=Stalking information |website =victimsofcrime.org | publisher = Stalking Resource Center |date= |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> Although stalkers are frequently portrayed as being strangers, they are most often known people, such as former or current partners, friends, colleagues or acquaintances. In the U.S., a survey by NVAW found that only 23% of female victims were stalked by strangers.<ref name=\"victimsofcrime.org\">{{cite journal | last1 = McFarlane | first1 = Judith M. | last2 = Campbell | first2 = Jacquelyn C. | last3 = Wilt | first3 = Susan | last4 = Sachs | first4 = Carolyn J. | last5 = Ulrich | first5 = Yvonne | last6 = Xu | first6 = Xiao | title = Stalking and intimate partner femicide | journal = [[Homicide Studies]] | volume = 3 | issue = 4 | pages = 300&ndash;316 | publisher = [[Sage Publications|Sage]] | doi = 10.1177/1088767999003004003 | date = November 1999 | ref = harv }} [http://victimsofcrime.org/docs/src/mcfarlane-j-m-campbell-j-c-wilt-s-sachs-c-j-ulrich-y-xu-x-1999.pdf Pdf.]</ref> Stalking by partners can be very dangerous, as sometimes it can escalate into severe violence, including murder.<ref name=\"victimsofcrime.org\"/> Police statistics from the 1990s in Australia indicated that 87.7% of stalking offenders were male and 82.4% of stalking victims were female.<ref>{{cite book |last=Dussuyer |first=Inez |url=http://www.aic.gov.au/media_library/conferences/stalking/dussuyer.pdf |title=Is stalking legislation effective in protecting victims? |publisher=[[Australian Institute of Criminology]] |location=Sydney |date=December 2000 |accessdate=3 April 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304052637/http://www.aic.gov.au/media_library/conferences/stalking/dussuyer.pdf |archive-date=4 March 2016 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }} Paper presented at the ''Stalking: Criminal Justice Responses Conference'' convened by the [[Australian Institute of Criminology]] and held in Sydney 7\u20138 December 2000.</ref>\n\n===Sexual harassment===\n{{Main|Sexual harassment}}\nSexual harassment is abusive, uninvited and unwelcome behavior of a sexual nature, typically in the work/studying place, which may include [[intimidation]], [[bullying]] or [[coercion]] of a sexual nature, or the inappropriate promise of rewards in exchange for sexual favors. It can be verbal or physical, and it is often perpetrated by a person in a position of authority against a subordinate.<ref>{{cite web | last = UN Women | author-link = UN Women|url=https://www.un.org/womenwatch/osagi/pdf/whatissh.pdf |title=What is sexual harassment |publisher=[[UN Women]] |accessdate=3 April 2016}}\n:''Citing'':\n:* {{cite book | last = BNA | author-link = Bureau of national affairs  | title = Preventing workplace harassment: a factsheet for employees | publisher = [[Bureau of national affairs|BNA Communications, Inc.]] | location = Washington, DC | issn = 1544-7820 | year = 1992 }} [https://www.bna.com/uploadedFiles/BNA_V2/Legal/Products/Books/Legal_Reference/shfsSample.pdf Sample of 2016 edition.]</ref> In the United States, sexual harassment is a form of discrimination that violates Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964. The [[Council of Europe Convention on preventing and combating violence against women and domestic violence]] defines sexual harassment as: \"any form of unwanted verbal, non-verbal or physical conduct of a sexual nature with the purpose or effect of violating the dignity of a person, in particular when creating an intimidating, hostile, degrading, humiliating or offensive environment\".<ref name=\"COE 210\" />\n\n===Human trafficking and forced prostitution===\n[[File:Map3.3Trafficking compressed.jpg|thumb|230px|right|A world map showing countries by prevalence of female trafficking]]\n{{Main|Human trafficking|Forced prostitution}}\nHuman trafficking refers to the acquisition of persons by improper means such as force, fraud or deception, with the aim of [[Exploitation of labour|exploiting]] them.<ref>{{cite web| last = UNODC| author-link =United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime|url=http://www.unodc.org/unodc/human-trafficking/index.html?ref=menuside |title=UNODC on human trafficking and migrant smuggling (index) |publisher=[[United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime]] |date= |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> The [[Protocol to Prevent, Suppress and Punish Trafficking in Persons, especially Women and Children]] states,<ref>{{cite web | last = OSCE | author-link = OSCE|url=http://www.osce.org/odihr/19223 |title=U.N. protocol to prevent, suppress and punish trafficking in persons, especially women and children, supplementing the United Nations convention against transnational organized crime |publisher=[[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]] |date=15 November 2000 |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n: \"Trafficking in persons\" shall mean the recruitment, transportation, transfer, harbouring or receipt of persons, by means of the threat or use of force or other forms of coercion, of abduction, of fraud, of deception, of the abuse of power or of a position of vulnerability or of the giving or receiving of payments or benefits to achieve the consent of a person having control over another person, for the purpose of exploitation. Exploitation shall include, at a minimum, the exploitation of the prostitution of others or other forms of sexual exploitation, forced labour or services, slavery or practices similar to slavery, servitude or the removal of organs.\n\nBecause of the illegal nature of trafficking, reliable data on its extent is very limited.<ref name=\"apps.who.int\">{{cite book | last = WHO | author-link = World Health Organization|title=Understanding and addressing violence against women: Human trafficking |url=http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/77394/1/WHO_RHR_12.42_eng.pdf | id = WHO/RHR/12.42 |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] | date = 2012 |accessdate=3 April 2016}}</ref> The [[World Health Organization|WHO]] states \"Current evidence strongly suggests that those who are trafficked into the [[sex industry]] and as domestic servants are more likely to be women and children.\"<ref name=\"apps.who.int\"/>\nA 2006 study in Europe on trafficked women found that the women were subjected to serious forms of abuse, such as physical or sexual violence, that affected their physical and mental health.<ref name=\"apps.who.int\"/>\n\n[[Forced prostitution]] is [[prostitution]] that takes place as a result of [[coercion]] by a third party. In forced prostitution, the party/parties who force the victim to be subjected to unwanted sexual acts exercise control over the victim.<ref>{{cite web | last = McDougall | first = Gay J. | author-link = Gay McDougall|url=http://www.unhchr.ch/huridocda/huridoca.nsf/0/3d25270b5fa3ea998025665f0032f220?OpenDocument#Bsl |title=Report of the Special Rapporteur on systematic rape, sexual slavery and slavery-like practices during armed conflict | id = E/CN.4/Sub.2/1998/13 | publisher = [[United Nations Economic and Social Council]] (ECOSOC) |accessdate=25 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130112211407/http://www.unhchr.ch/huridocda/huridoca.nsf/0/3d25270b5fa3ea998025665f0032f220?OpenDocument |archivedate=12 January 2013 }}</ref>\n\n===Mistreatment of widows===\n[[File:Balinese rite of Suttee in Houtman 1597 Verhael vande Reyse ... Naer Oost Indien.jpg|thumb|200px|Description of the [[Bali]]nese rite of ''Suttee'', in Houtman's 1597 ''Verhael vande Reyse ... Naer Oost Indien'']]\n{{Main|Widow}}\n{{See also|Widow inheritance|Sexual cleansing#Widow cleansing|l2=Sexual cleansing}}\nA widow is a woman whose spouse has died. In some parts of the world, widows are subjected to serious forms of abuse, often fueled by traditional practices such as [[widow inheritance]].<ref>{{cite book | last = Owen | first = Margaret | chapter = Human rights, equality and legal protection | chapterurl = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Bh8sGfNKUTEC&pg=PA181 | editor-last = Owen | editor-first = Margaret | title = A world of widows | publisher = Zed Books | location = London Atlantic Highlands, New Jersey | year = 1996 | isbn = 9781856494205 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/worldofwidows0000owen }}</ref> The sacrifice of widows (such as [[Sati (practice)|sati]]) has been prevalent historically in various cultures (especially in [[India]]). Although sati in India is today an almost defunct practice, isolated incidents have occurred in recent years, such as the 1987 sati of [[Roop Kanwar]], as well as several incidents in rural areas in 2002,<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/2178102.stm | work=[[BBC News]] | title=Arrests in Indian ritual burning | date=7 August 2002 | access-date = 25 January 2014}}</ref> and 2006.<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | url= http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/south_asia/5366506.stm | work=[[BBC News]] | title=Sons arrested in sati death probe | date=21 September 2006 | access-date = 25 January 2014}}</ref> Those likely to be accused and killed as [[Modern witch-hunts|witche]]s are often widows.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/asia/21725040-law-criminalising-sorcery-was-only-repealed-2013-gruesome-fate-witches-papua-new|title=The gruesome fate of \"witches\" in Papua New Guinea|newspaper=economist.com |date=13 July 2017 |accessdate=23 July 2017}}</ref> In parts of Africa, such as in Kenya, widows are viewed as impure and need to be 'cleansed'. This often requires having sex with someone. Those refusing to be cleansed risk getting beaten by superstitious villagers, who may also harm the woman's children. It is argued that this notion arose from the idea that if a husband dies, the woman may have performed witchcraft against him.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2018-10-23/these-kenyan-widows-are-fighting-against-sexual-cleansing|title=These Kenyan widows are fighting against sexual 'cleansing'|publisher=pri.org|accessdate=7 November 2018|date=23 October 2018}}</ref> Widow inheritance (also known as bride inheritance) is a cultural and social practice whereby a widow is required to marry a male relative of her late husband, often his brother.\n\n===Accusations of witchcraft===\n[[File:Schiltach Flugblatt.JPG|thumb|left|upright|A 1533 account of the execution of a witch charged with burning the [[Germany|German]] town of [[Schiltach]] in 1531]]\n[[Witch trials in the early modern period]] (between the 15th and 18th centuries) were common in Europe and in the European colonies in North America. Today, there remain regions of the world (such as parts of [[Sub-Saharan Africa]], rural [[North India]], and [[Papua New Guinea]]) where belief in [[witchcraft]] is held by many people, and women accused of being witches are subjected to serious violence.<ref>''Citations'':\n* {{cite journal | last = Diwan | first = Mohammed A. | title = Conflict between state legal norms and norms underlying popular beliefs: witchcraft in Africa as a case study | journal = [[Duke Journal of Comparative & International Law]] | volume = 14 | issue = 2 | pages = 351&ndash;388 | publisher = [[Duke University School of Law|Duke Law School]] | date = Summer 2004 | url = https://scholarship.law.duke.edu/djcil/vol14/iss2/5/ | ref = harv }} [https://scholarship.law.duke.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?referer=&httpsredir=1&article=1129&context=djcil#H2N1 Pdf.]\n* {{cite book |last=Ally |first=Yaseen |title=Witch hunts in modern South Africa: an under-represented facet of gender-based violence (fact sheet) |url=http://www.mrc.ac.za/crime/witchhunts.pdf |publisher=[[South African Medical Research Council]] |date=June 2009 |accessdate=12 December 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120425074549/http://www.mrc.ac.za/crime/witchhunts.pdf |archive-date=25 April 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}\n*{{cite news | last=Staff writer | title=Woman burned alive for 'sorcery' in Papua New Guinea | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-21363894 | work=[[BBC News]] | date=7 February 2013 | access-date=12 December 2013 }}</ref> In addition, there are also countries that have criminal legislation against the practice of witchcraft. In [[Saudi Arabia]], witchcraft remains a crime [[punishable by death]].<ref>{{cite web | last = Staff writer |url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/news/saudi-arabia-beheading-sorcery-shocking-2011-12-12 |title=Saudi Arabia: Beheading for 'sorcery' shocking | website = amnesty.org |publisher=[[Amnesty International]] |date=12 December 2011 |accessdate=12 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n===State violence===\n\n====War rape and sexual slavery during military conflict====\n[[File:Paul Jamin - Le Brenn et sa part de butin 1893.jpg|thumb|200 px|''[[Brennus (4th century BC)|Brennus]] and His Share of the Spoils'', by [[Paul Jamin]], 1893.]]\n[[File:Chinese girl from one of the Japanese Army's 'comfort battalions'.jpg|thumb|200 px|[[Rangoon]], [[Myanmar|Burma]]. 8 August 1945. A young [[Chinese diaspora|ethnic Chinese]] woman from one of the [[Imperial Japanese Army]]'s \"comfort battalions\" is interviewed by an [[Allies of World War II|Allied]] officer.]]\n\nMilitarism produces special environments that allow for increased violence against women. [[War rapes]] have accompanied warfare in virtually every known historical era.<ref>{{cite book | last = Washington | first = Harold C. | chapter = 'Lest he die in battle and another man take her': violence and the construction of gender in the laws of Deuteronomy 20-22 | chapter-url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2rZnXQwPX8gC&pg=PA203 | editor-last1 = Matthews | editor-first1 = Victor H. | editor-last2 = Levinson | editor-first2 = Bernard M. | editor-last3 = Frymer-Kensky | editor-first3 = Tikva  | title = Gender and law in the Hebrew Bible and the ancient Near East | page = 203 | publisher = T & T Clark | location = London New York | year = 2004 | isbn = 9780567080981 }}</ref> Rape in the course of war is mentioned multiple times in the Bible: \"For I will gather all the nations against Jerusalem to battle, and the city shall be taken and the houses plundered and the women raped...\" {{bibleref|Zechariah|14:2|ESV}} \"Their little children will be dashed to death before their eyes. Their homes will be sacked, and their wives will be raped.\"{{bibleref|Isaiah|13:16|NLT}}\n\nWar rapes are rapes committed by soldiers, other combatants or civilians during armed conflict or war, or during military occupation, distinguished from sexual assaults and rape committed amongst troops in military service. It also covers the situation where women are forced into prostitution or [[sexual slavery]] by an occupying power. During World War II the Japanese military established brothels filled with \"[[comfort women]]\", girls and women who were forced into sexual slavery for soldiers, exploiting women for the purpose of creating access and entitlement for men.<ref>{{cite news|last=Benedict |first=Helen |url=http://www.inthesetimes.com/article/3848/ |title=Why soldiers rape |work=[[In These Times]] |date=14 August 2008 | access-date = 10 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Morris-Suzuki | first = Tessa | title = Japan's 'Comfort Women': It's time for the truth (in the ordinary, everyday sense of the word) | journal = Japan Focus (The Asia-Pacific Journal) | volume = 5 | issue = 3 | date = 1 March 2007 | url = http://www.japanfocus.org/-Tessa-Morris_Suzuki/2373  |accessdate=4 August 2011 | ref = harv }}</ref>\n \nAnother example of violence against women incited by militarism during war took place in the [[Kaunas Ghetto|Kovno Ghetto]]. Jewish male prisoners had access to (and used) Jewish women forced into camp brothels by the Nazis, who also used them.<ref>{{cite book | last = Dworkin | first = Andrea | author-link = Andrea Dworkin | chapter = Palestinians/prostituted women | chapterurl = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Pew3_DPVfnYC&pg=PA316 | editor-last = Dworkin | editor-first = Andrea | editor-link = Andrea Dworkin | title = Scapegoat: the Jews, Israel, and women's liberation | page = 316 | publisher = Free Press | location = New York | year = 2000 | isbn = 9780684836126 }}</ref>\n\nRape was committed during the [[Bangladesh Liberation War]] by members of the [[Pakistan Armed Forces|Pakistani military]] and the [[militia]]s that supported them. Over a period of nine months, hundreds of thousands of women were raped. [[Susan Brownmiller]], in her report on the [[1971 Bangladesh atrocities|atrocities]], said that girls from the age of eight to grandmothers of seventy-five suffered attacks. {{See also|Rape during the Bangladesh Liberation War}}\n\nRape used as a weapon of war was practiced during the [[Bosnian War]] where rape was used as a highly systematized instrument of war by Serb armed forces predominantly targeting women and girls of the Bosniak ethnic group for physical and moral destruction. Estimates of the number of women raped during the war range from 50,000 to 60,000; as of 2010 only 12 cases have been prosecuted.<ref>{{cite book | last = UNSC | author-link = United Nations Security Council | title = Report of the International Tribunal for the Prosecution of Persons Responsible for Serious Violations of International Humanitarian Law Committed in the Territory of the Former Yugoslavia Since 1991 | id = A/52/375{{spaces|2}}S/1997/729 | publisher = [[United Nations Security Council]] |url=http://www.icty.org/x/file/About/Reports%20and%20Publications/AnnualReports/annual_report_1997_en.pdf |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120804004034/http://www.icty.org/x/file/About/Reports%20and%20Publications/AnnualReports/annual_report_1997_en.pdf |archivedate=4 August 2012 | date = 18 September 1997 | access-date = 10 November 2012}}</ref> {{See also|Rape during the Bosnian War}}\n\nThe 1998 [[International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda]] recognized rape as a war crime. Presiding judge [[Navanethem Pillay]] said in a statement after the verdict: \"From time immemorial, rape has been regarded as spoils of war. Now it will be considered a war crime. We want to send out a strong message that rape is no longer a trophy of war.\"<ref>{{cite book| last = Pillay | first = Navanethem | author-link = Navi Pillay |title=Honorary doctorate acceptance address by Navanethem Pillay, Rhodes University |url=http://www.ru.ac.za/academic/graduation/addresses_and_citations/2005/Judge_Pillay_citation.doc |url-status=dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20060926231120/http://www.ru.ac.za/academic/graduation/addresses_and_citations/2005/Judge_Pillay_citation.doc |archivedate=26 September 2006 |df=dmy |date = 2005 |accessdate=27 February 2008}}</ref> {{See also|Rwandan Genocide}}\n\nIn 2006, five [[United States Army|U.S. troops]] from a six-man unit [[gang rape]]d and killed a 14-year-old girl in a village near the town of [[Mahmoudiyah, Iraq|Al-Mahmudiyah]], Iraq. After the rape the girl was shot in her head and the lower part of her body, from her stomach down to her feet, was set on fire.<ref>{{cite news | last = Media pool reports |url=http://www.cnn.com/2006/WORLD/meast/08/08/iraq.mahmoudiya/index.html |title=Soldier: 'Death walk' drives troops 'nuts' | work =[[CNN]] | date = 9 August 2006 |accessdate=6 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = US ex-soldier guilty of Iraq rape | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/8039257.stm | work = [[BBC News]] |date=7 May 2009 |accessdate= 10 November 2012}}</ref> {{See also|Mahmudiyah killings}}\n\nA 1995 study of female war veterans found that 90 percent had been sexually harassed. A 2003 survey found that 30 percent of female vets said they were raped in the military and a 2004 study of veterans who were seeking help for post-traumatic stress disorder found that 71 percent of the women said they were sexually assaulted or raped while serving.<ref>{{cite news | last = Benedict | first = Helen | title = The plight of women soldiers |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=103844570 |work=The Nation |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=6 May 2009 |accessdate= 10 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nAccording to one report, the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]]'s capture of Iraqi cities in June 2014 was accompanied by an upsurge in crimes against women, including kidnap and rape.<ref>''Articles'':\n* {{cite news | last1 = Radwan | first1 = Zahra | last2 = Blumenfeld | first2 = Zoe|title=OP-ED: Surging violence against women in Iraq|url=http://www.ipsnews.net/2014/06/op-ed-surging-violence-against-women-in-iraq/|work=[[Inter Press Service]]|date=27 June 2014|accessdate=5 July 2014}}\n* {{cite news|last1=Winterton|first1=Clare|title=Why we must act when women in Iraq document rape |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/clare-winterton/why-we-must-act_b_5528162.html|date=25 June 2014|work=[[HuffPost]] |accessdate=10 July 2014}}\n* {{cite news | last = Ali | first = Esraa Mohamed | title = Kuwaiti media: \"Daash\" demands the people of Mosul to provide unmarried to \"Jihad marriage\"  | url = https://translate.google.co.uk/translate?hl=en&sl=ar&u=http://www.almasryalyoum.com/news/details/466402&prev=search | work = [[Al-Masry Al-Youm|The Egyptian Today]] [Al-Masry Al-Youm] | date = 18 June 2014 |accessdate=10 July 2014}}\n:* ''Original Arabic version'': {{cite news|last=\u0625\u0633\u0631\u0627\u0621 \u0645\u062d\u0645\u062f \u0639\u0644\u064a|title=\u0625\u0639\u0644\u0627\u0645\u064a \u0643\u0648\u064a\u062a\u064a: \"\u062f\u0627\u0639\u0634\" \u064a\u0637\u0627\u0644\u0628 \u0623\u0647\u0627\u0644\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u0648\u0635\u0644 \u0628\u062a\u0642\u062f\u064a\u0645 \u063a\u064a\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062a\u0632\u0648\u062c\u0627\u062a \u0644\u0640\"\u062c\u0647\u0627\u062f \u0627\u0644\u0646\u0643\u0627\u062d|url=http://www.almasryalyoum.com/news/details/466402|work=\u0627\u0644\u0645\u0635\u0631\u06cc \u0627\u0644\u06cc\u0648\u0645|accessdate=10 July 2014}}</ref> ''[[The Guardian]]'' reported that ISIL's extremist agenda extended to women's bodies and that women living under their control were being captured and raped.<ref>{{cite news|last=Susskind|first=Yifat|title=Under Isis, Iraqi women again face an old nightmare: violence and repression|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global-development/poverty-matters/2014/jul/03/isis-iraqi-women-rape-violence-repression|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=3 July 2014|accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> Fighters are told that they are free to have sex and rape non-Muslim captive women.<ref>{{cite news|language=sv|title=Det jag har bevittnat i al-Raqqa kommer alltid f\u00f6rf\u00f6lja mig|url=http://www.dn.se/nyheter/varlden/det-jag-har-bevittnat-i-al-raqqa-kommer-alltid-forfolja-mig/|accessdate=25 September 2014|work=[[Dagens Nyheter]]|date=23 September 2014}}</ref> Yazidi girls in Iraq allegedly [[War rape|raped]] by ISIL fighters committed [[suicide]] by jumping to their death from [[Mount Sinjar]], as described in a witness statement.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ahmed|first=Havidar|title=The Yezidi Exodus, Girls Raped by ISIS Jump to their Death on Mount Shingal|date=14 August 2014|url=http://rudaw.net/english/kurdistan/140820142|publisher=[[Rudaw Media Network]]|accessdate=26 August 2014}}</ref> Haleh Esfandiari from the [[Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars]] has highlighted the abuse of local women by ISIL militants after they have captured an area. \"They usually take the older women to a makeshift slave market and try to sell them. The younger girls ... are raped or married off to fighters\", she said, adding, \"It's based on temporary marriages, and once these fighters have had sex with these young girls, they just pass them on to other fighters.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Brekke|first1=Kira|title=ISIS is attacking women, and nobody is talking about it|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/09/08/isis-attacks-on-women_n_5775106.html?cps=gravity |work=[[HuffPost]] |date=8 September 2014 |accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref> Describing the [[Yazidi]] women captured by ISIS, [[Nazand Begikhani]] said \"[t]hese women have been treated like cattle... They have been subjected to physical and sexual violence, including systematic rape and sex slavery. They've been exposed in markets in Mosul and in Raqqa, Syria, carrying price tags.\"<ref>{{cite news | last = Watson | first = Ivan | title = 'Treated like cattle': Yazidi women sold, raped, enslaved by ISIS | url = http://www.cnn.com/2014/10/30/world/meast/isis-female-slaves/ | work = [[CNN]] | date = 30 October 2014 | access-date =23 February 2015 }}</ref> In December 2014 the [[Ministry of Human Rights (Iraq)|Iraqi Ministry of Human Rights]] announced that the [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]] had killed over 150 women and girls in [[Fallujah]] who refused to participate in [[sexual jihad]].<ref>{{cite news|last = NOW News | author-link = NOW News|title=ISIS just executed more than 150 women in Fallujah|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/isis-just-executed-more-than-150-women-in-fallujah-2014-12|work=[[Business Insider]]|date= 17 December 2014 | access-date =23 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Forced sterilization and forced abortion====\n{{See|Eugenics in the United States|Violence against women in the United States#Forced pregnancy and sterilization}}\n[[File:SOU 1929 14 Bet\u00e4nkande med f\u00f6rslag till steriliseringslag s 57 Laughlin.jpg|200px|thumb|right|A map from a 1929 Swedish royal commission report displays the U.S. states that had implemented sterilization legislation by then]]\n[[Forced sterilization]] and [[forced abortion]] are forms of gender-based violence.<ref>{{cite web | last = EIGE | author-link = European Institute for Gender Equality |title=What is gender-based violence? |url=http://eige.europa.eu/content/what-is-gender-based-violence | website = eige.europa.eu |publisher=[[European Institute for Gender Equality]] |date=24 August 2015 | access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref> Forced sterilization has occurred throughout much of the world, both at the hands of the state and from intimate partners. Studies show forced sterilizations often target socially and politically disadvantaged groups such as racial and ethnic minorities, the poor, and indigenous populations.<ref name=\"Volscho, Thomas W 2010\">{{cite journal | last = Volscho | first = Thomas W. | title = Sterilization racism and pan-ethnic disparities of the past decade: the continued encroachment on reproductive rights | journal = [[W\u00ed\u010dazo \u0160a Review]] | volume = 25 | issue = 1 | pages = 17&ndash;31 | publisher = [[Johns Hopkins University Press]] | jstor = 40891307 | date = Spring 2010 | ref = harv | doi=10.1353/wic.0.0053}}</ref> According to the Convention on the Elimination of all forms of Discrimination Against Women, all \"women are guaranteed the right to decide freely and responsibly on the number of and spacing of their children, and to have access to information, education, and means to enable them to exercise these rights.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Convention on the Elimination of All Forms of Discrimination against Women |url=http://www.ohchr.org/EN/ProfessionalInterest/Pages/CEDAW.aspx |publisher = [[United Nations General Assembly]] |accessdate=9 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, much of the history of forced sterilization is connected to the legacy of eugenics and [[racism in the United States]].<ref name=\"Volscho, Thomas W 2010\" /> Many doctors thought that they were doing the country a service by sterilizing poor, disabled, and/or minority women, whom they considered a drain on the system.<ref name=\"Volscho, Thomas W 2010\"/><ref name=\"North Carolina Sterilization Program 2011\">{{cite news | last1 = Kessel | first1 = Michelle | last2 = Jessica | first2 = Hopper | title = Victims speak out about North Carolina sterilization program, which targeted women, young girls and Blacks | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20111108182852/http://rockcenter.msnbc.msn.com/_news/2011/11/07/8640744-victims-speak-out-about-north-carolina-sterilization-program-which-targeted-women-young-girls-and-blacks | archive-date = 8 November 2011 | url = http://rockcenter.msnbc.msn.com/_news/2011/11/07/8640744-victims-speak-out-about-north-carolina-sterilization-program-which-targeted-women-young-girls-and-blacks | work =[[Rock Center with Brian Williams]] | publisher = [[NBC News]] | date = 7 November 2011 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref> [[Native Americans in the United States|Native American]], [[Mexican Americans|Mexican American]], [[African Americans|African American]] and [[Puerto Rican-American]] women were coerced into sterilization programs, with Native Americans and African Americans especially being targeted.<ref name=\"Volscho, Thomas W 2010\" /> Records have shown that Native American girls as young as eleven years-old had [[hysterectomy]] operations performed.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Vincenti Carpio|first=Myla|date=2004|title=The Lost Generation: American Indian Women and Sterilization Abuse|url=|journal=[[Social Justice (journal)|Social Justice]]|volume=31|issue=4|pages=40\u201353|via=}}</ref>\n\nIn Europe, there have been a number of lawsuits and accusations towards the [[Czech Republic]] and [[Slovakia]] of sterilizing Roma women without adequate information and waiting period.<ref>{{Cite book|last=ERRC|title=Coercive and cruel \u2013 a report by the European Roma Rights Centre: Sterilisation and its consequences for Romani women in the Czech Republic (1966\u20132016) |url=http://www.errc.org/cms/upload/file/coercive-and-cruel-28-november-2016.pdf|publisher=European Roma Right Centre| location = Budapest, Hungary|date=November 2016|isbn = 9789638991638}}</ref> In response, both nations have instituted a mandatory seven-day waiting period and written consent. Slovakia has been condemned on the issue of forced sterilization of Roma women several times by the [[European Court for Human Rights]] (see [[V. C. vs. Slovakia]], [[N. B. vs. Slovakia]] and [[I.G. and Others vs. Slovakia]]).\n\nIn [[Peru]], in 1995, [[Alberto Fujimori]] launched a family planning initiative that especially targeted poor and indigenous women. In total, over 215,000 women were sterilized, with over 200,000 believed to have been coerced.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Boesten | first = Jelke | title = Free choice or poverty alleviation? Population politics in Peru under Alberto Fujimori | journal = European Review of Latin American and Caribbean Studies  | volume = 82 | issue = 82 | pages = 3&ndash;20 | publisher = Centre for Latin American Research and Documentation | doi = 10.18352/erlacs.9637 | date = 2007 | ref = harv }}</ref> In 2002, Health Minister [[Fernando carbone|Fernando Carbone]] admitted that the government gave misleading information, offered food incentives, and threatened to fine parents if they had additional children. The procedures have also been found to have been negligent, with less than half using proper anesthetic.<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Mass sterilisation scandal shocks Peru | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/2148793.stm | work = [[BBC News]] | date = 24 July 2002 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn China, the [[one child policy]] included forced abortions and forced sterilization.<ref>''Citations'':\n\n* {{cite news|url=http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/news/regions/asia-pacific/china/130409/china-mother-dies-after-forced-sterilization-one-child-policy|title=China: Mother of 2 dies after forced sterilization|last=Jackson|first=Allison|date=9 April 2013|work=[[GlobalPost]]|access-date=18 November 2013}}\n* {{cite web|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/news-and-updates/thousands-risk-forced-sterilization-china-2010-04-22|title=Thousands at risk of forced sterilization in China|last=AI|author-link=Amnesty International|date=22 April 2010|publisher=[[Amnesty International]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130529125647/https://www.amnesty.org/en/news-and-updates/thousands-risk-forced-sterilization-china-2010-04-22|archive-date=29 May 2013|access-date=18 November 2013}}\n* {{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-china-18435126|title=China forced abortion photo sparks outrage|last=Staff writer|date=14 June 2012|work=[[BBC News]]|access-date=18 November 2013}}\n* {{cite book|url=http://www.hrnk.org/uploads/pdfs/HRNK_HiddenGulag2_Web_5-18.pdf|title=The Hidden Gulag|last=Hawk|first=David|date=2012|publisher=The Committee for Human Rights in North Korea|edition=2nd|location=Washington DC|oclc=793983613|access-date=18 November 2013}}</ref> Forced sterilization is also practiced in Uzbekistan.<ref>{{cite news | last = Antelava | first = Natalia | title=Uzbekistan's policy of secretly sterilising women| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-17612550 | work=[[BBC World Service]] | date=12 April 2012| access-date = 18 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite AV media | people = Natalia Antelava (reporter) and Wesley Stephenson (producer) | access-date = 18 November 2013 |date=16 April 2012 | title= Forced sterilisation in Uzbekistan | medium= Audio | minutes = 20:30 | series = [[Crossing Continents]] | publisher= [[BBC Radio 4]] | url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01fjx63}}</ref>\n\n====Violence by the police and other authority figures====\n[[File:Taliban beating woman in public RAWA.jpg|right|thumb|250px|A member of the Taliban's [[Mutaween#Other groups|religious police]] beating an Afghan woman in [[Kabul]] on 26 August 2001.]]\nWhen police officers misuse their power as agents of the state to physically and [[sexual harassment|sexually harass]] and assault victims, the survivors, including women, feel much less able to report the violence.<ref>{{Cite episode\n| title = Covering 'Tainted Justice' and winning a Pulitzer | url = https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=126386819 | series = Fresh Air | serieslink = Fresh Air | credits = Barbara Laker and Wendy Ruderman, hosted by [[Terry Gross]] | network = NPR | station = [[WHYY-FM|WHYY]]| location = Philadelphia | airdate = 3 May 2010 | transcripturl= }}</ref>  It is standard procedure for police to force entry into the victim's home even after the victim's numerous requests for them to go away.<ref>{{cite book | last = Suk | first = Jeannie | author-link = Jeannie Suk | title = At home in the law: how the domestic violence revolution is transforming privacy | publisher = Yale University Press | location = New Haven | year = 2009 | url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=UML8Ke4IpTEC | isbn = 9780300172621 }}</ref> Government agencies often disregard the victim's right to [[Freedom of association#Intimate association|freedom of association]] with their perpetrator.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Hanna | first = Cheryl | title = No right to choose: mandated victim participation in domestic violence prosecutions | journal = [[Harvard Law Review]] | volume = 109 | issue = 8 | pages = 1849&ndash;1910 | publisher = The Harvard Law Review Association | doi = 10.2307/1342079 | jstor = 1342079 | ssrn = 1276830 | date = June 1996 | ref = harv }}</ref> [[Women's shelter|Shelter]] workers are often reduced themselves to contributing to violence against women by exploiting their [[vulnerability]] in exchange for a paying job.<ref>{{cite book | last = Koyama | first = Emi | chapter = Disloyal to feminism: Abuse of survivors within the domestic violence shelter system | chapterurl = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=lZmFjwEACAAJ | editor-last = INCITE! Women of Colour Against Violence | title = Color of violence: the INCITE! anthology | publisher = Duke University Press | location = Durham | year = 2016 | isbn = 9780822373445 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/colorofviolencei00unse }}</ref>\n\nHuman rights violations perpetrated by police and military personnel in many countries are correlated with decreased access to public health services and increased practices of risky behavior among members of vulnerable groups, such as women and female sex workers.<ref name=\"Beletsky L, Martinex G, Gaines T, et al. 2012 403\u2013410\">{{cite journal | last1 = Beletsky | first1 = Leo |display-authors=etal | title = Mexico's northern border conflict: collateral damage to health and human rights of vulnerable groups | journal = [[Pan American Journal of Public Health]] | volume = 31 | issue = 5 | pages = 403&ndash;410 | publisher = [[Pan American Health Organization]] | doi = 10.1590/s1020-49892012000500008 | pmc = 3660986 | pmid = 22767041 | date = May 2012 | ref = harv }}</ref> These practices are especially widespread in settings with a weak rule of law and low levels of police and military management and professionalism. Police abuse in this context has been linked to a wide range of risky behaviors and health outcomes, including post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD), and substance abuse.<ref name=\"Beletsky L, Martinex G, Gaines T, et al. 2012 403\u2013410\"/><ref>''Other citations'':   \n* {{cite journal | last1 = Strathdee | first1 = Steffanie A. |display-authors=etal | title = Social and structural factors associated with HIV infection among female sex workers who inject drugs in the Mexico-US border region | journal = [[PLOS One]] | volume = 6 | issue = 4 |page=e19048 | publisher = [[PLOS]] | doi = 10.1371/journal.pone.0019048 |pmc=3081836 |pmid=21541349 | date = 25 April 2011 | ref = harv | bibcode = 2011PLoSO...619048S }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Ramos | first1 = Rebeca |display-authors=etal | title = A tale of two cities: social and environmental influences shaping risk factors and protective behaviors in two Mexico-US border cities | journal = [[Health & Place]] | volume = 15 | issue = 4 | pages = 999&ndash;1005 | publisher = [[Elsevier]] | doi = 10.1016/j.healthplace.2009.04.004 | pmid = 19464228 | pmc = 2735581 | date = December 2009 | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Pollini | first1 = Robin A. |display-authors=etal | title = Syringe possession arrests are associated with receptive syringe sharing in two Mexico-US border cities | journal = [[Addiction (journal)|Addiction]] | volume = 103 | issue = 1 | pages = 101&ndash;108 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1360-0443.2007.02051.x | pmid = 18028520 | pmc = 2214830 | date = January 2008 | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Pollini | first1 = Robin A. |display-authors=etal | title = High prevalence of abscesses and self-treatment among injection drug users in Tijuana, Mexico | journal = [[International Journal of Infectious Diseases]] | volume = 14 | issue = S3 | pages = e117&ndash;e122 | publisher = [[Elsevier]] | doi = 10.1016/j.ijid.2010.02.2238 | pmid = 20381396 | pmc = 2917477 | date = September 2010 | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Strathdee | first1 = Steffanie A. |display-authors=etal | title = Individual, social, and environmental influences associated with HIV infection among injection drug users in Tijuana, Mexico | journal = [[Journal of Acquired Immune Deficiency Syndromes]] | volume = 47 | issue = 3 | pages = 369&ndash;376 | publisher = [[Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|LWW]] | doi = 10.1097/QAI.0b013e318160d5ae |pmc=2752692 |pmid=18176320 | date = 1 March 2008 | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite book | last1 = Raj | first1 = Anita | last2 = Gupta | first2 = Jhumka  | last3 = Silverman | first3 = Jay G. | chapter = Women, migration, conflict and risk for HIV | chapter-url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=JhxwNjWzB6gC&pg=PA107 | editor-last1 = Forbes Martin | editor-first1 = Susan | editor-last2 = Tirman | editor-first2 = John | title = Women, migration, and conflict: breaking a deadly cycle | page = 107 | publisher = Springer | location = Dordrecht | year = 2009 | isbn = 9789048128242 }}</ref> Extortion of sexual services and police sexual abuse have been linked to a decrease in condom use and an elevated risk of STI and HIV infections among vulnerable groups.<ref name=\"Beletsky L, Martinex G, Gaines T, et al. 2012 403\u2013410\"/><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Blankenship | first1 = Kim M. | last2 = Koester | first2 = Stephen | title = Criminal law, policing policy, and HIV risk in female street sex workers and injection drug users | journal = [[The Journal of Law, Medicine & Ethics]] | volume = 30 | issue = 4 | pages = 548&ndash;559 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1748-720X.2002.tb00425.x | pmid = 12561263 | date = December 2002 | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\n====Stoning and flogging====\n[[Stoning]], or lapidation, refers to a form of [[capital punishment]] whereby an organized group throws stones at an individual until the person dies. Stoning is a punishment that is included in the laws of several countries, including Iran, Saudi Arabia, Sudan, Pakistan, Yemen, the United Arab Emirates, and some states in Nigeria, as punishment for [[adultery]].<ref>{{cite news | last = Batha | first = Emma | title = FACTBOX: Stoning - where does it happen? | work = [[Thomson Reuters Foundation News]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160125051613/http://news.trust.org//item/20130927165059-w9g0i | archive-date = 25 January 2016 | url = http://news.trust.org//item/20130927165059-w9g0i | publisher = [[Thomson Reuters Foundation]] | date = 29 September 2013 | access-date = 19 November 2013}}</ref> [[Flogging]] or flagellation is the act of methodically beating or whipping the human body. It is a judicial punishment in various countries for specific crimes, including [[sex outside marriage]]. These punishments employed for sexual relations outside marriage, apart from constituting a form of violence in themselves, can also deter victims of [[sexual violence]] from reporting the crime, because the victims may themselves be punished (if they cannot prove their case, if they are deemed to have been in the company of an unrelated male, or if they were unmarried and not virgins at the time of the rape).<ref>{{cite news | last = Lang | first = Olivia | title=Maldives girl to get 100 lashes for pre-marital sex | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-21595814 | work=[[BBC News]] | date=26 February 2013 | access-date = 19 November 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Jamali |first=Hasan |url=http://www.today.com/id/15836746/ns/today-today_news/t/rape-case-calls-saudi-legal-system-question/#.UolafidedO6 |title=Rape case brings Saudi laws into focus |work=[[Today (U.S. TV program)|Today]] |publisher=[[NBC]] |accessdate=19 November 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6JdMstMvl?url=http://www.today.com/id/15836746/ns/today-today_news/t/rape-case-calls-saudi-legal-system-question/ |archivedate=14 September 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===Female genital mutilation===\n{{Main|Female genital mutilation}}\n[[File:Fgm map.gif|thumb|250px|Map showing the prevalence of FGM in Africa]]\n[[File:FGM road sign, Bakau, Gambia, 2005.jpg|thumb|250 px|Anti-[[FGM]] road sign, Bakau, Gambia, 2005]]\nFemale genital mutilation (FGM) is defined by the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) as \"all procedures that involve partial or total removal of the external female genitalia, or other injury to the female genital organs for non-medical reasons\".<ref name=\"WHO FGM\">{{cite book | last = WHO | author-link = World Health Organization |title=Female genital mutilation (factsheet) |url=http://www.who.int/mediacentre/factsheets/fs241/en/ |publisher=[[World Health Organization]] |date= June 2000 |accessdate=18 November 2013}}</ref> According to a 2013 UNICEF report, 125 million women and girls in Africa and the Middle East have experienced FGM.<ref name=\"unicef.org\">{{cite book | last = UNICEF | author-link = UNICEF | title = Female Genital Mutilation/Cutting: A statistical overview and exploration of the dynamics of change | url = http://www.unicef.org/media/files/FGCM_Lo_res.pdf | publisher = [[UNICEF]] | date = 22 July 2013 | accessdate = 18 November 2013}}</ref> The WHO states: \"The procedure has no health benefits for girls and women\" and \"Procedures can cause severe bleeding and problems urinating, and later cysts, infections, infertility as well as complications in childbirth increased risk of newborn deaths\" and \"FGM is recognized internationally as a violation of the human rights of girls and women. It reflects deep-rooted inequality between the sexes, and constitutes an extreme form of discrimination against women.\"<ref name=\"WHO FGM\"/> According to a UNICEF report, the top rates for FGM are in Somalia (with 98 percent of women affected), Guinea (96 percent), Djibouti (93 percent), Egypt (91 percent), Eritrea (89 percent), Mali (89 percent), Sierra Leone (88 percent), Sudan (88 percent), Gambia (76 percent), Burkina Faso (76 percent), Ethiopia (74 percent), Mauritania (69 percent), Liberia (66 percent), and Guinea-Bissau (50 percent).<ref name=\"unicef.org\"/>\n\nAccording to some local practitioners, it is believed that FGM is linked to cultural rites and customs. It is considered to be a traditional practice that continues to take place in different communities/countries of Africa and Middle East, including in places where it is banned by national legislation. FGM is defined as a \"harmful traditional practice\"<ref name=\"Shell-Duncan\">{{cite journal | last = Shell-Duncan | first = Bettina | title = From health to human rights: female genital cutting and the politics of intervention | journal = [[American Anthropologist]] | volume = 110 | issue = 2 | pages = 225&ndash;236 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1548-1433.2008.00028.x | date = June 2008 | ref = harv }}</ref> in accordance to the Inter-African Committee. \n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:UNFPA-UNICEF Joint Programme On FGM 2012.png|thumbnail|alt=map|300 px|right|Prevalence of FGM among African women aged 15-49. For more detailed maps, see [http://www.unfpa.org/webdav/site/global/shared/documents/publications/2013/UNICEF-UNFPA%20Joint%20Programme%20AR_final_v14.pdf] UNFPA-UNICEF Joint Programme on FGM, 2012]] -->\nDue to globalization and immigration, FGM is spreading beyond the borders of Africa and Middle East, to countries such as Australia, Belgium, Canada, France, New Zealand, the U.S., and UK.<ref>{{cite book | last = Nussbaum | first = Martha | author-link = Martha Nussbaum | chapter = Judging other cultures: the case of genital mutilation | chapter-url = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=43U8DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA120 | editor-last = Nussbaum | editor-first = Martha | editor-link = Martha Nussbaum | title = Sex & social justice | pages = [https://archive.org/details/sexsocialjustice00nuss/page/120 120\u2013121] | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = New York | year = 1999 | isbn = 978-0195110326 | url-access = registration | url = https://archive.org/details/sexsocialjustice00nuss/page/120 }}</ref>\n\nAlthough FGM is today associated with developing countries, this practice was common until the 1970s in parts of the Western world, too. FGM was considered a standard medical procedure in the United States for most of the 19th and 20th centuries.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite journal|last=Webber|first=Sara|last2=Schonfeld|first2=Toby L.|date=2003-06-27|title=Cutting History, Cutting Culture: Female Circumcision in the United States|url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/44151|journal=The American Journal of Bioethics|volume=3|issue=2|pages=65\u201366|issn=1536-0075|doi=10.1162/152651603766436324|pmid=12859826}}</ref> Physicians performed surgeries of varying invasiveness to treat a number of diagnoses, including [[hysteria]], [[Depression (mood)|depression]], [[nymphomania]], and [[frigidity]]. The medicalization of FGM in the United States allowed these practices to continue until the second part of the 20th century, with some procedures covered by [[Blue Cross Blue Shield Association|Blue Cross Blue Shield Insurance]] until 1977.<ref name=\":33\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=LViJROLfEGQC&pg=PA106&lpg=PA106&dq=Watson,+M.+(2005).+Female+circumcision+from+Africa+to+the+Americas:+Slavery+to+the+present.+The+Social+Sciences+Journal,+42,+421-437.#v=onepage&q=Watson,%20M.%20(2005).%20Female%20circumcision%20from%20Africa%20to%20the%20Americas:%20Slavery%20to%20the%20present.%20The%20Social%20Sciences%20Journal,%2042,%20421-437.&f=false|title=Women in Developing Countries: A Reference Handbook|last=Kinnear|first=Karen L.|date=2011|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9781598844252|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":20\" />\n\nThe [[Convention on preventing and combating violence against women and domestic violence|Istanbul Convention]] prohibits female genital mutilation (Article 38).<ref>{{cite book | title = Council of Europe Convention on preventing and combating violence against women and domestic violence | url = https://rm.coe.int/168046031c | date = 12 April 2011 | access-date = 8 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2016, in [[Africa]], FGM has been legally banned in Benin, Burkina Faso, Central African Republic, Chad, C\u00f4te d'Ivoire, Djibouti, Egypt, Eritrea, Ethiopia, Gambia, Ghana, Guinea, Guinea Bissau, Kenya, Mauritania, Niger, Nigeria, Senegal, South Africa, Tanzania, Togo, Uganda, and Zambia.<ref>''Citations'':\n* {{cite news | last = Lyons | first = Kate | title = The Gambia bans female genital mutilation | url = https://www.theguardian.com/society/2015/nov/24/the-gambia-bans-female-genital-mutilation | work = [[The Guardian]] | date = 24 November 2015 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}\n* {{cite news | last = Richards | first = Kimberly | title = History has been made: female genital mutilation banned in Nigeria | url = http://aplus.com/a/nigeria-bans-genital-mutilation | work = [[A Plus (aplus.com)|A Plus]] | date = 3 June 2015 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}\n* {{cite book | last = UNFPA | author-link = UNFPA | title = Female genital mutilation (FGM) frequently asked questions | url = http://www.unfpa.org/resources/female-genital-mutilation-fgm-frequently-asked-questions | publisher = [[United Nations Population Fund]] | date = December 2015 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nThere exist several approaches that were set up by international health organizations and civil societies (for example, [[Tostan]]) aimed at eliminating the practice of FGM in implemented countries: \n# FGM as a Health issue (also known as health risks approach)\n# FGM as a Human Rights issue (also known as Human Rights-based approach)\n\nSome scholars suggests that, when dealing with FGM, it is necessary to take lessons from history, particularly 19th-century campaign against [[foot-binding]] in China,<ref name=\"Kwame Appiah\">{{cite news | last = Appiah | first = Kwame Anthony | author-link = Kwame Anthony Appiah | title = The art of social change | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2010/10/24/magazine/24FOB-Footbinding-t.html?pagewanted=all |work = [[The New York Times]] |date=22 October 2010 |accessdate=2 December 2013}}</ref> which was successful.\n\n===Breast ironing===\n{{Main|Breast ironing}}\nBreast ironing (also known as \"breast flattening\") is the practice of pounding and massaging the [[breasts]] of a [[puberty|pubescent girl]], using hard or heated objects, in an attempt to try to make them stop developing or disappear.<ref name=\"west-info.eu\">{{cite book | last = Tapscott | first = Rebecca |title=Understanding breast \"ironing\": a study of the methods, motivations, and outcomes of breast flattening practices in Cameroon | url = http://www.west-info.eu/files/Feinstein-International-Center-Understanding-breast-ironing-a-study-of-the-methods-motivations-and-outcomes-of-breast-flattening-practices-in-Cameroon-20121.pdf | publisher= [[Feinstein International Center]] | date = 14 May 2012 | access-date = 25 January 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"BBC Cameroon Breast Ironing\">{{cite news | last = Sa'ah | first = Randy Joe | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/africa/5107360.stm | work=[[BBC News]] | title=Cameroon girls battle 'breast ironing' | date=23 June 2006 | access-date = 25 January 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Penney | first = Joe | url= https://widerimage.reuters.com/story/breast-ironing | work=[[Reuters]] |title= Breast ironing | date = 27 January 2014 | access-date = 25 January 2014}}</ref> It is typically carried out by the girl's mother, with the aim of making the girl less sexually attractive to men and boys, so that her virginity is preserved and she can continue her education.<ref name=\"BBC Cameroon Breast Ironing\"/><ref>{{cite book | last = Ngunshi | first = Rosaline | title = Breast ironing: a harmful practice that has been silenced for too long | url = http://www2.ohchr.org/english/bodies/cedaw/docs/cedaw_crc_contributions/GenderEmpowermentandDevelopment.pdf | publisher = Gender Empowerment and Development (GeED) | date = 24 August 2011 }}</ref> It is practiced primarily in [[Cameroon]], but has also been reported across other areas in [[West Africa|West]] and [[Central Africa]].<ref name=\"west-info.eu\"/><ref name=\"BBC Cameroon Breast Ironing\"/><ref>{{cite news| last = Mabuse | first = Nkepile | title = Breast ironing tradition targeted in Cameroon | url=http://edition.cnn.com/2011/WORLD/africa/07/27/cameroon.breast.ironing/ | work=[[CNN]] | date=28 July 2011 | access-date = 25 January 2014}}</ref> Breast ironing is very painful and can have negative emotional and physical consequences.<ref name=\"west-info.eu\"/><ref name=\"BBC Cameroon Breast Ironing\"/>\n\n===Obstetric violence===\n{{See|Abuse during childbirth}}\n\"Obstetric violence\" refers to acts categorized as physically or psychologically violent in the context of labor and birth. In most developed and many [[developing countries]], birth takes place in an increasingly medicalized environment; with numerous surgical interventions that the pregnant woman can sometimes be coerced into accepting, or which are done without her consent, or which are unnecessary.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Habek | first1 = Dubravko | last2 = Vukovi\u0107 Bobi\u0107 | first2 = Mirna | last3 = Hrgovi\u0107 | first3 = Zlatko | title = Possible feto-maternal clinical risk of the Kristeller's expression | journal = [[Central European Journal of Medicine]] | volume = 3 | issue = 2 | pages = 3&ndash;6 | publisher = [[Walter de Gruyter]] | doi = 10.2478/s11536-008-0008-z | date = 2008 | ref = harv }}</ref><ref name=\"WHO_Normal\">{{cite book | last = WHO | author-link = World Health Organization | title = Care in normal birth: a practical guide | id = WHO/FRH/MSM/96.24 | url = http://www.who.int/maternal_child_adolescent/documents/who_frh_msm_9624/en/ | publisher = [[World Health Organization]] | location = Geneva, Switzerland | series = Safe Motherhood Practical Guide | year = 1996 | access-date = 2 December 2013}} [http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/63167/1/WHO_FRH_MSM_96.24.pdf Pdf.]\n:''Also as'':\n:* {{cite journal | last = Technical Working Group, World Health Organization | author-link = World Health Organization | title = Care in normal birth: a practical guide | journal = [[Birth (journal)|Birth]] | volume = 24 | issue = 2 | pages = 121&ndash;123 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1523-536X.1997.00121.pp.x | date = June 1997 | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\nMany such practices originate in patriarchal ideologies. The WHO stated: \"in normal birth, there should be a valid reason to interfere with the natural process. The aim of care is to achieve a healthy mother and child with the least possible level of intervention compatible with safety.\"<ref name=\"doi.org\">{{cite journal | last1 = Dobbeleir | first1 = Julie M.L.C.L. | last2 = Landuyt | first2 = Koenraad Van | last3 = Monstrey | first3 = Stan J. | title = Aesthetic surgery of the female genitalia | journal = Seminars in Plastic Surgery | volume = 25 | issue = 2 | pages = 130&ndash;141 | publisher = [[Thieme Medical Publishers|Thieme]] | doi = 10.1055/s-0031-1281482 | pmc = 3312147 | date = May 2011 | ref = harv | pmid=22547970}}</ref><ref name=\"WHO_Normal\" />\n\nThe term \"obstetric violence\" is particularly used in Latin American countries, where the law prohibits such behavior. Such laws exist in several countries, including Argentina, Puerto Rico and Venezuela.<ref>{{cite web | last = WHO | author-link = World Health Organization | title = Sexual and reproductive health: Prevention and elimination of disrespect and abuse during childbirth | url = http://www.who.int/reproductivehealth/topics/maternal_perinatal/statement-childbirth-govnts-support/en/ | website = who.int | publisher = [[World Health Organization]] | year = 2015 | access-date = 21 October 2017}}\n:''See also'':\n:* {{cite book | last = WHO | author-link = World Health Organization | title = WHO statement: The prevention and elimination of disrespect and abuse during facility-based childbirth | id = WHO/RHR/14.23 | url = http://apps.who.int/iris/bitstream/10665/134588/1/WHO_RHR_14.23_eng.pdf | publisher = [[World Health Organization]] | location = Geneva, Switzerland | series = Human Reproduction Programme (HRP) | year = 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Violence against indigenous women ===\nIndigenous women around the world are often targets of sexual assault or physical violence. Many indigenous communities are rural, with few resources and little help from the government or non-state actors. These groups also often have strained relationships with law enforcement, making prosecution difficult. Many indigenous societies also find themselves at the center of land disputes between nations and ethnic groups, often resulting in these communities bearing the brunt of national and ethnic conflicts.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = UNFPA | last2 = UNICEF | last3 = UN Women | last4 = ILO | last5 = Office of the Special Representative of the Secretary-General on Violence against Children (OSRSG/VAC) | author-link1 = United Nations Population Fund | author-link2 = UNICEF | author-link3 = UN Women | author-link4 = International Labour Organization | title = Breaking the silence on violence against indigenous girls, adolescents and young women: A call to action based on an overview of existing evidence from Africa, Asia Pacific and Latin America | url = http://www.unfpa.org/resources/breaking-silence-violence-against-indigenous-girls-adolescents-and-young-women | publisher = [[UNICEF]] | date = May 2013 | access-date = 10 May 2016}} [https://www.unfpa.org/sites/default/files/resource-pdf/VAIWG_FINAL.pdf Pdf.]</ref>\n\nViolence against indigenous women is often perpetrated by the state, such as in [[Peru]], in the 1990s. President [[Alberto Fujimori]] (in office from 1990 to 2000) has been accused of [[genocide]] and [[crimes against humanity]] as a result of a [[forced sterilization]] program put in place by his administration.<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Mass sterilization scandal shocks Peru | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/americas/2148793.stm | work = [[BBC News]] | date = 24 July 2002 | access-date = 30 April 2006}}</ref> During his presidency, Fujimori put in place a program of forced sterilizations against indigenous people (mainly the [[Quechua people|Quechuas]] and the [[Aymara people|Aymaras]]), in the name of a \"[[public health]] plan\", presented 28 July 1995.\n\n[[Domestic violence in Bolivia|Bolivia has the highest rate of domestic violence]] in Latin America.<ref>{{cite news | last1 = Dhillon | first1 = Jaskiran | last2 = Allooloo | first2 = Siku | title = Violence against indigenous women is woven into Canada's history | url = https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/dec/14/violence-indigenous-woman-canada-history-inquiry-racism | work = [[The Guardian]] | date = 14 December 2015 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Shiriari | first = Sara | title = Bolivia struggles with gender-based violence | url = http://america.aljazeera.com/articles/2015/4/30/bolivia-struggles-with-gender-based-violence.html | work = [[Al Jazeera America]] | date =  30 April 2015 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref> Indigenous women self-report physical or sexual violence from a current or former partner at rates of twenty-nine percent, in comparison to the national average of twenty four percent.<ref>{{cite report | last = UN | author-link = United Nations |title=Thematic paper on the elimination and responses to violence, exploitation and abuse of indigenous girls, adolescents and young women | url = https://www.un.org/en/ga/president/68/pdf/wcip/IASG%20Thematic%20Paper_%20Violence%20against%20Girls%20and%20Women%20-%20rev1.pdf | publisher = Inter-agency Support Group on Indigenous Peoples' Issues | date = June 2014 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref> Bolivia is largely indigenous in its ethnic demographics, and Quechua, Aymara, and Guarani women have been monumental in the nation's fight against violence against women.<ref>{{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Bolivian women battle against culture of harassment | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-latin-america-26446066 | work = [[BBC News]] | date = 12 March 2014 | access-date = 10 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | last = Shahriari | first = Sara | title = Combating violence against women in Bolivia | url = https://pulitzercenter.org/reporting/combating-violence-against-women-bolivia | work = [[Pulitzer Center on Crisis Reporting]] | date = 6 March 2015 | access-date = 10 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[Guatemala]]n indigenous women have also faced extensive violence. Throughout over three decades of conflict, [[Maya civilization|Maya]] women and girls have continued to be targeted. The Commission for Historical Clarification found that 88% of women affected by state-sponsored rape and sexual violence against women were indigenous.\n\nThe concept of white dominion over indigenous women's bodies has been rooted in American history since the beginning of colonization. The theory of manifest destiny went beyond simple land extension and into the belief that European settlers had the right to exploit Native women's bodies as a method of taming and \"humanizing\" them.<ref name=\"Bubar, Roe 2004\">{{cite journal | last1 = Roe | first1 = Bubar | last2 = Jumper Thurman | first2 = Pamela | title = Violence against native women | journal = Social Justice | volume = 31 | issue = 4 [98] | pages = 70&ndash;86 | jstor = 29768276 | date = 2004 | url = http://www.socialjusticejournal.org/?product=roe-bubar-and-pamela-jumper-thurman-2 | ref = harv }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Ramirez | first = Renya | title = Healing, violence, and Native American women | journal = Social Justice | volume = 31 | issue = 4 [98] | pages = 103&ndash;116 | jstor = 29768279 | date = 2004 | url = http://www.socialjusticejournal.org/?product=renya-ramirez-2 | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\n[[Canada]] has an extensive problem with violence against indigenous women, by both indigenous men and non-aboriginals. \"[I]t has been consistently found that Aboriginal women have a higher likelihood of being victimized compared to the rest of the female population.\"<ref>{{cite book | editor-last = Sinha | editor-first = Maire | title = Measuring violence against women: statistical trends 2006 (85-570-XWE) | page = 19 | publisher = Statistics Canada | location = Ottawa, Ontario | series = Juristat | url = http://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/85-002-x/2013001/article/11766-eng.pdf | year = 2006 }}\n:''Citing'':\n:* {{cite book | last = Brennan | first = Shannon | title = Violent victimization of Aboriginal women in the Canadian provinces, 2009  | publisher = Statistics Canada | location = Ottawa, Ontario | series = Juristat | url = https://www.statcan.gc.ca/pub/85-002-x/2011001/article/11439-eng.htm | year = 2011 }} Catalogue no. 85-002.\n:* {{cite book | last = Perreault | first = Samuel | title = Violent victimization of Aboriginal women in the Canadian provinces, 2009  | publisher = Statistics Canada | location = Ottawa, Ontario | series = Juristat | url = http://statcan.gc.ca/pub/85-002-x/2011001/article/11415-eng.htm | year = 2011 }} Catalogue no. 85-002.</ref> While Canadian national averages of violence against women are falling, they have remained the same for aboriginal communities throughout the years. The history of [[Canadian Indian residential school system|residential schools]] and economic inequality of indigenous Canadians has resulted in communities facing violence, unemployment, drug use, alcoholism, political corruption, and high rates of suicide.<ref name=\"Bubar, Roe 2004\"/> In addition, there has been clear and admitted racism towards indigenous people by the [[Royal Canadian Mounted Police]], making victims less likely to report cases of domestic violence.<ref>{{cite news |last=Jackson |first=Kenneth |title=Top Mountie Admits Racism in Ranks towards Indigenous People |work=[[Aboriginal People's Television Network]] |date=9 December 2015 |url=http://aptn.ca/news/2015/12/09/top-mountie-admits-racism-in-ranks-towards-indigenous-people/ | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nMany of the issues facing indigenous women in Canada have been addressed via the Murdered and Missing Indigenous Women (MMIW) initiatives. Thousands of Native Canadian women have gone missing or been killed in the past 30 years, with little representation or attention from the government. Efforts to make the Canadian public aware of these women's disappearances have mostly been led by Aboriginal communities, who often reached across provinces to support one another. In 2015, prime minister [[Stephen Harper]] commented that the issue of murdered and missing indigenous women was \"not high on our radar\",<ref>{{cite news | title = Full Text of Peter Mansbridge's interview with Stephen Harper | work = [[CBC News]] | url = http://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/canada-election-2105-full-text-of-peter-mansbridge-s-interview-with-stephen-harper-1.3218399 | date = 7 September 2015 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref> prompting outrage in already frustrated indigenous communities. A few months later, Prime Minister [[Justin Trudeau]] launched an official inquiry into the Murdered and Missing Indigenous Women.\n\nIn the United States, Native American women are more than twice as likely to experience violence than any other demographic.<ref name=\"Bubar, Roe 2004\"/> One in three Native women is sexually assaulted during her life, and 67% of these assaults are perpetrated by non-Natives,<ref name=\"ncai\">{{cite book |title=Policy Insights - Brief Statistics on Violence Against Native Women |date=2013 |publisher=NCAI Policy Research Center |page=4 |url=http://www.ncai.org/attachments/PolicyPaper_tWAjznFslemhAffZgNGzHUqIWMRPkCDjpFtxeKEUVKjubxfpGYK_Policy%20Insights%20Brief_VAWA_020613.pdf |quote= A previously reported statistic that, \u201cAmong [American Indian and Alaska Native] victims of rape or sexual assault, 86 percent described the offender as non\u2010Indian\u201d is accurate according to Perry\u2019s analysis (2004) in American Indians and Crime: A BJS Statistical Profile, 1992-2002. However, Perry\u2019s analysis includes reports by both Native men and women victims of rape or sexual assault. Given this brief\u2019s focus on violence against Native women, we include the updated rate of 67 percent reported by Native women victims of rape or sexual assault indicated in Bachman, et al., (2008).}}</ref><ref name=\"Bubar, Roe 2004\"/><ref>{{cite news | last = Chekuru | first = Kavitha | title = Sexual violence scars Native American Women | url = http://www.aljazeera.com/indepth/features/2013/03/201334111633172507.html | work = [[Al Jazeera]] | date = 6 March 2013 | access-date = 9 May 2016}}</ref> with Native Americans constituting 0.7% of U.S. population in 2015.<ref name=ACS>{{cite web|title=ACS Demographic and Housing Estimates \u2013 2011\u20132015|url=https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/15_5YR/DP05/0100000US|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|accessdate=December 23, 2019|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200213004951/https://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/ACS/15_5YR/DP05/0100000US|archive-date=13 February 2020|url-status=dead}}</ref> The disproportionate rate of assault to indigenous women is due to a variety of causes, including but not limited to the historical legal inability of tribes to prosecute on their own on the reservation. The federal Violence Against Women Act was reauthorized in 2013, which for the first time gave tribes jurisdiction to investigate and prosecute felony domestic violence offenses involving Native American and non-Native offenders on the reservation,<ref name=\"rapidcityjournal\">{{cite news |last1=Cook |first1=Andrea J. |title=Tribal leaders urged to apply Violence Against Women Act |url=https://rapidcityjournal.com/news/local/tribal-leaders-urged-to-apply-violence-against-women-act/article_f030d4ad-dbda-53ff-bb72-5816465f78d4.html |accessdate=January 11, 2020 |newspaper=Rapid City Journal |date=April 1, 2015}}</ref> as 26% of Natives live on reservations.<ref name=\"calgary\">{{cite news |last1=Milke |first1=Mark |title=Increasing number of Aboriginals choose not to live on reserves |url=https://www.fraserinstitute.org/article/increasing-number-aboriginals-choose-not-live-reserves |accessdate=December 23, 2019 |publisher=Calgary Herald and Regina Leader Post |date=January 12, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last1 = Bachman | first1 = Ronet | last2 = Zaykowski| first2 = Heather | last3 = Kallmyer | first3 = Rachel | last4 = Poteyeva | first4 = Margarita | last5 = Lanier | first5 = Christina | title = Violence against American Indian and Alaska Native women and the criminal justice response: what is known | publisher = [[National Institute of Justice]] | url = https://www.ncjrs.gov/pdffiles1/nij/grants/223691.pdf | date=August 2008 |accessdate=May 10, 2016}} {{NCJ|245615}}</ref> In 2019 the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] [[United States House of Representatives|House]] passed H.R. 1585 (Violence Against Women Reauthorization Act of 2019) by a vote of 263\u2013158, which increases tribes' prosecution rights much further. However in the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[United States Senate|Senate]] its progress has stalled.<ref name=\"gq\">{{cite magazine |last1=Willis |first1=Jay |title=Why Can't the Senate Pass the Violence Against Women Act? |url=https://www.gq.com/story/senate-violence-against-women-act |accessdate=January 11, 2020 |magazine=GQ |date=December 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Violence against immigrant and refugee women===\nImmigrant and refugee women often face violence, both in the private sphere (by partners and other family members) and in the public sphere (by the police and other authorities). These women are often in a vulnerable position: they do not speak the language of the country they are in, they do not know its laws, and sometimes they are in a legal position where they may be deported if they make contact with the authorities. Women who seek protection from armed conflict in their countries of origin often face more violence while travelling to the destination country or when they arrive there.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Freedman | first = Jane | title = Sexual and gender-based violence against refugee women: a hidden aspect of the refugee \"crisis\" | journal = Reproductive Health Matters | volume = 24 | issue = 47 | pages = 18&ndash;26 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] | doi = 10.1016/j.rhm.2016.05.003 | pmid = 27578335 | date = 2017 | ref = harv | url = https://halshs.archives-ouvertes.fr/halshs-01441147/file/Sexual%20and%20gender%20based%20violence%20against%20refugee%20women%20a%20hidden%20aspect%20of%20the%20refugee%20crisis.pdf }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Robbers | first1 = Gianna | last2 = Gunta | first2 = Lazdane | last3 = Dinesh | first3 = Sethi | title = Sexual violence against refugee women on the move to and within Europe | journal = Entre Nous | volume = 84 | pages = 26&ndash;29 | publisher = [[WHO]]/Europe | date = 2016 | url = http://www.euro.who.int/en/health-topics/Life-stages/sexual-and-reproductive-health/publications/entre-nous/entre-nous/together-for-a-better-sexual-and-reproductive-health.-entre-nous-no-84,-2016 | ref = harv }} [http://www.euro.who.int/__data/assets/pdf_file/0017/319301/Entre-Nous-84-full-book.pdf?ua=1 Pdf.]</ref>\n\n===Violence against trans women===\n{{See also|Violence against LGBT people}}\n[[Trans women]], especially [[women of color]], are at higher risk of experiencing violence than [[cisgender women]].<ref>{{Cite report |url=https://www.apa.org/about/policy/psychological-practice-girls-women.pdf |title=APA Guidelines for Psychological Practice with Girls and Women|year=2018 |author=American Psychological Association|page=11|quote=Transgender women are at a notably higher risk of violence than their cisgender counterparts...especially transgender women of color}}</ref> Trans women commonly experience intimate partner violence, with one study finding that 31.1% of trans people experience it, and another finding that half of all trans women experience it.<ref name=\"williams\">{{Cite journal |last=Brown |first=Taylor N.T. |last2=Herman |first2=Jody L. |year=2015 |title=Intimate Partner Violence and Sexual Abuse Among LGBT People: A Review of Existing Research |url=https://williamsinstitute.law.ucla.edu/wp-content/uploads/Intimate-Partner-Violence-and-Sexual-Abuse-among-LGBT-People.pdf |journal=The Williams Institute: UCLA School of Law}}</ref><ref name=\"lang\">{{Cite journal |last=Langenderfer-Magruder |first=Lisa|year=2016 |title=Experiences of Intimate Partner Violence and Subsequent Police Reporting Among Lesbian, Gay, Bisexual, Transgender, and Queer Adults in Colorado: Comparing Rates of Cisgender and Transgender Victimization |journal=Journal of Interpersonal Violence |volume=31 |issue=5 |pages=855\u2013871 |doi=10.1177/0886260514556767 |issn=1552-6518 |pmid=25392392}}</ref><ref name=\"risser\">{{Cite journal |last=Risser |first=Jan M. H. |date=2005-10-11 |title=Sex, Drugs, Violence, and HIV Status Among Male-to-Female Transgender Persons in Houston, Texas |journal=International Journal of Transgenderism |volume=8 |issue=2\u20133 |pages=67\u201374 |doi=10.1300/J485v08n02_07 |issn=1553-2739}}</ref> Trans women also often face abuse by police, and [[transgender sex workers]] often face violence from clients.<ref name=\"whotrans\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.who.int/hiv/topics/transgender/about/en/ |title=Transgender people |website=World Health Organization |access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> Trans survivors of violence can have a harder time finding [[domestic violence shelter]]s, as some shelters only accept cisgender women.<ref name=\"williams\" /><ref>{{Cite journal |url=https://scholarship.law.berkeley.edu/californialawreview/vol106/iss5/6 |title=Are Women's Spaces Transgender Spaces? Single-Sex Domestic Violence Shelters, Transgender Inclusion, and the Equal Protection Clause |last=Apsani |first=Rishita |date=2018-10-01 |website=California Law Review |pages=1689 |doi=10.15779/Z38125Q91G |access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref> In 2018, more than two dozen [[transgender]] people were violently killed in the United States, most of them [[women of color]].<ref name=\"hrc2019\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.hrc.org/resources/violence-against-the-transgender-community-in-2019/ |title=Violence Against the Transgender Community in 2019 |website=Human Rights Campaign |language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"cnn\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/01/16/health/transgender-deaths-2018/index.html |title=Killings of transgender people in the US saw another high year |last=Christensen |first=Jen |website=CNN |access-date=2019-08-10}}</ref>\n\n===Sport-related===\n\nSport-related violence against women refers to any physical, sexual, mental acts that are \"perpetrated by both male athletes and by male fans or consumers of sport and sporting events, as well as by coaches of female athletes\".<ref name=\"Catherine Palmer\">{{cite book|last=Palmer|first=Catherine|title=Violence against women and sport: Literature review|year=2011|publisher=Durham University|location=London|pages=2\u20135|url=http://www.endviolenceagainstwomen.org.uk/resources/22/violence-against-women-and-sport-a-literature-review-by-dr-catherine-palmer|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141106162130/http://www.endviolenceagainstwomen.org.uk/resources/22/violence-against-women-and-sport-a-literature-review-by-dr-catherine-palmer|archivedate=6 November 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nThe documenting reports and literature suggest that there are obvious connections between contemporary sport and violence against women. Such events as the [[2010 World Cup]], the [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] and [[Commonwealth Games]] \"have highlighted the connections between sports spectatorship and intimate partner violence, and the need for police, authorities and services to be aware of this when planning sporting events\".<ref name=\"Catherine Palmer\" />\n\nSport-related violence can occur in various contexts and places, including homes, pubs, clubs, hotel rooms, the streets.<ref name=\"Catherine Palmer\" />\n\n====Sport-related violence by male college athletes====\n\nViolence against women is a topic of concern in the United States' collegiate athletic community. From the 2010 UVA lacrosse murder, in which a male athlete was charged guilty with second degree murder of his girlfriend, to the 2004 University of Colorado Football Scandal when players were charged with nine alleged sexual assaults,<ref>{{cite news|last=Vaughan|first=Kevin|title=Colorado woman seeks justice in alleged sexual assault Read more: Colorado woman seeks justice in alleged sexual assault|url=http://www.denverpost.com/firstinthepost/ci_12557039|work=[[The Denver Post]]|date=9 June 2009|accessdate=17 April 2012}}</ref> studies suggest that athletes are at higher risk for committing sexual assault against women than the average student.<ref>{{cite web|last=Brady|first=Jeff|author-link=Jeff Brady (reporter)|title=Scandal Returns to University of Colorado Football|url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=105381707|work=[[Weekend Edition]]|publisher=[[NPR]]|accessdate=12 March 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"chandler1999\">{{cite journal|last1=Chandler|first1=Steve B.|last2=Johnson|first2=Dewayne J.|last3=Carroll|first3=Pamela S.|title=Abusive behaviors of college athletes | journal = [[College Student Journal]] | volume = 33 | issue = 4 | pages = 638&ndash;645 | publisher = [[University of South Alabama]] | date = 1 December 1999 | ref = harv |oclc=193500507}}</ref> It is reported that one in three college assaults are committed by athletes.<ref name=\"johnshopkins1\">{{cite journal|last=Mak|first=Stephanie|title=Are athletes more abusive than the rest of the student population?|url=http://web1.johnshopkins.edu/hurj/issue3/spotlight-mak.html|journal=Hopkins Undergraduate Research Journal Online|accessdate=12 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120229044851/http://web1.johnshopkins.edu/hurj/issue3/spotlight-mak.html|archivedate=29 February 2012|date=2004|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Surveys suggest that male student athletes who represent 3.3% of the college population, commit 19% of reported sexual assaults and 35% of domestic violence.<ref>{{cite web|last=Staff writer|title=Game stats|publisher=The National Coalition Against Violent Athletes (NCVA)|accessdate=27 December 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161117092517/http://www.ncava.org/statistics.html|archivedate=17 November 2016|url=http://www.ncava.org:80/statistics.html|df=dmy-all}}\n:''Citing'':\n:* {{cite journal | last1 = Crosset | first1 = Todd W. | last2 = Benedict | first2 = Jeffrey R. | last3 = McDonald | first3 = Mark A. | title = Male student-athletes and violence against women: a survey of campus judicial affairs offices | journal = [[Journal of Sport & Social Issues]] | volume = 19 | issue = 2 | pages = 126&ndash;140 | publisher = [[Sage Publications|Sage]] | doi = 10.1177/019372395019002002 | date = May 1995 | ref = harv }}\n:* {{cite journal | last1 = Crosset | first1 = Todd W. | last2 = Ptacek | first2 = James | last3 = McDonald | first3 = Mark A. | last4 = Benedict | first4 = Jeffrey R. | title = Male student-athletes and violence against women: a survey of campus judicial affairs offices | journal = [[Violence Against Women (journal)|Violence Against Women]] | volume = 2 | issue = 2 | pages = 163&ndash;179 | publisher = [[Sage Publications|Sage]] | doi = 10.1177/1077801296002002004 | pmid = 12295457 | date = June 1996 | ref = harv | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/b3e4babb2d254a82585ce0ef51115bd827bca7d1 }}\n\n:''See also'':\n:* {{cite book | last1 = Benedict | first1 = Jeff | last2 = Keteyian | first2 = Armen | title = The system: the glory and scandal of big-time college football | publisher = Doubleday | location = New York | year = 2013 | url = https://archive.org/details/systemgloryscand0000bene | url-access = registration | isbn = 9780345803030 }}</ref> The theories that surround these statistics range from misrepresentation of the student-athlete to an unhealthy mentality towards women within the team itself.<ref name=\"johnshopkins1\"/>\n\n====Controversy over contributing factors====\n\nSociologist Timothy Curry, after conducting an observational analysis of two big time sports' locker room conversations, deduced that the high risk of male student athletes for gender abuse is a result of the team's subculture.<ref name=Curry1991>{{cite journal|last=Curry|first=Timothy Jon|title=Fraternal Bonding in the Locker Room: A Profeminist Analysis Of Talk About Competition And Women|journal=Sociology of Sport Journal|year=1991|volume=8|issue=2|pages=119\u2013135 |url=http://www.umt.edu/sociology/faculty_staff/ellestad/documents/275_Curry1991fraternalbondinginthelockerroom_s10.pdf |accessdate=12 March 2012|doi=10.1123/ssj.8.2.119}}</ref> He states, \"Their locker room talk generally treated women as objects, encouraged sexist attitudes toward women and, in its extreme, promoted rape culture.\"<ref name=Curry1991/> He proposes that this objectification is a way for the male to reaffirm his heterosexual status and hyper-masculinity. Claims have been made that the atmosphere changes when an outsider (especially women) intrude in the locker room. In the wake of the reporter [[Lisa Olson]] being harassed by a Patriots player in the locker room in 1990, she reflected, \"We are taught to think we must have done something wrong and it took me a while to realize I hadn't done anything wrong.\"<ref name=\"Disch\">{{cite journal|last=Disch|first=Lisa|author2=Kane, Mary Jo |title=When a Looker is Really a Bitch: Lisa Olson, Sport, and the Heterosexual Matrix|journal=Signs|date=Winter 1996|volume=21|issue=2|pages=278\u2013308|jstor=3175065|doi=10.1086/495067}}</ref> Other female sports reporters (college and professional) have claimed that they often brush off the players' comments, which leads to further objectification.<ref name=\"Disch\" /> Other sociologists challenge this claim. Steve Chandler notes that because of their celebrity status on campus, \"athletes are more likely to be scrutinized or falsely accused than non-athletes.\"<ref name=\"chandler1999\"/> Another contender, Stephanie Mak, notes that, \"if one considers the 1998 estimates that about three million women were battered and almost one million raped, the proportion of incidences that involve athletes in comparison to the regular population is relatively small.\"<ref name=\"johnshopkins1\"/>\n\n====Response to violence by male college athletes====\n\nIn response to the proposed link between college athletes and gender-based violence, and media coverage holding Universities as responsible for these scandals more universities are requiring athletes to attend workshops that promote awareness. For example, St. John's University holds sexual assault awareness classes in the fall for its incoming student athletes.<ref>{{cite news|last=Newsom|first=John|title=Share on emailShare on redditMore Sharing Services Few Colleges Tackle Issue of Athlete Sex Assaults|url=https://articles.latimes.com/1992-03-22/news/mn-7249_1_sexual-assault|publisher=Los Angeles Times Online |date=22 March 1992 |accessdate=12 March 2012}}</ref> Other groups, such as the National Coalition Against Violent Athletes, have formed to provide support for the victims as their mission statement reads, \"The NCAVA works to eliminate off the field violence by athletes through the implementation of prevention methods that recognize and promote the positive leadership potential of athletes within their communities. In order to eliminate violence, the NCAVA is dedicated to empowering individuals affected by athlete violence through comprehensive services including advocacy, education and counseling.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Mission|url=http://www.ncava.org/Mission.html|publisher=National Coalition Against Violent Athletes|accessdate=12 March 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120416074831/http://www.ncava.org/Mission.html|archivedate=16 April 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n===Cyberbullying===\n[[Cyberbullying]] is a form of intimidation using electronic forms of contact. In the 21st century, cyberbullying has become increasingly common, especially among teenagers in Western countries.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Smith |first1=Peter K. |last2=Mahdavi |first2=Jess |last3=Carvalho |first3=Manuel |last4=Fisher |first4=Sonja |last5=Russell |first5=Shanette |last6=Tippett |first6=Neil | title = Cyberbullying: its nature and impact in secondary school pupils | journal = [[Journal of Child Psychology and Psychiatry]] | volume = 49 | issue = 4 | pages = 376&ndash;385 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1469-7610.2007.01846.x |pmid=18363945 | date = 2008 | ref = harv }}</ref> On 24 September 2015, the [[United Nations Broadband Commission]] released a report that claimed that almost 75% percent of women [[online]] have encountered harassment and threats of violence, otherwise known as [[cyber violence]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unwomen.org/en/news/stories/2015/9/cyber-violence-report-press-release |title=cyber violence report press release |publisher=UN Women |date= |accessdate=2016-04-03}}</ref> Misogynistic rhetoric is prevalent online, and the public debate over gender-based attacks has increased significantly, leading to calls for policy interventions and better responses by social networks like [[Facebook]] and [[Twitter]].<ref>{{cite journal |last= Jane |first= Emma Alice | title = 'Back to the kitchen, cunt': speaking the unspeakable about online misogyny  | journal = [[Continuum: Journal of Media & Cultural Studies]] | volume = 28 | issue = 4 | pages = 558&ndash;570 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] | doi = 10.1080/10304312.2014.924479 | date = 2014 | ref = harv }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last= Filipovic |first= Jill | title = Blogging while female: how internet misogyny parallels real-world harassment | journal = [[Yale Journal of Law and Feminism]] | volume = 19 | issue = 2 | pages = 295&ndash;303 | publisher = [[Yale Law School]] | date = 2007 | url = http://digitalcommons.law.yale.edu/yjlf/vol19/iss1/10/ | ref = harv }} [http://digitalcommons.law.yale.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1268&context=yjlf Pdf.]</ref>\n\n==Activism==\n[[File:A Bulgarian poster urging open your eyes - against women being abused.jpg|thumb|250px|A Bulgarian poster urging people to open their eyes about domestic violence against women]]\n[[File:MintoParkMemorial.JPG|thumb|left|Memorial in [[Minto Park]], [[Ottawa]], of the victims of the [[\u00c9cole Polytechnique massacre]]]]\n\n===Background and history===\nActivism refers to \"a doctrine or practice that emphasizes direct vigorous action especially in support of or opposition to one side of a controversial issue\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/activism |title=Activism (definition) | website = merriam-webster.com |publisher=[[Merriam-Webster]] |date= |accessdate=1 December 2013}}</ref> In the activism for violence against women, the objectives are to address and draw public attention on the issues of VAW as well as seek and recommend measures to prevent and eliminate this violence.<ref name=\"Youngs_368325\">{{cite journal | last = Youngs | first = Gillian | title = Private pain/public peace: women's rights as human rights and Amnesty International's report on violence against women | journal = [[Signs (journal)|Signs]] | volume = 28 | issue = 4 | pages = 1209&ndash;1229 | publisher = [[University of Chicago Press]] | doi = 10.1086/368325 | jstor = 10.1086/368325 | date = Summer 2003 | ref = harv }}</ref> Many scholarly articles suggest that the VAW is considered as a violation of human rights<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\">{{cite journal | last1 = Htun | first1 = Mala | last2 = Weldon | first2 = S. Laurel | title = The civic origins of progressive policy change: combating violence against women in global perspective, 1975\u20132005 | journal = [[American Political Science Review]] | volume = 106 | issue = 3 | pages = 548&ndash;569 | publisher = [[Cambridge University Press]] | doi = 10.1017/S0003055412000226 | jstor = 23275433 | date = August 2012 | ref = harv }} [https://web.archive.org/web/20121030053243/http://polisci.unm.edu/common/documents/htun_apsa-article.pdf Pdf.]</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Carraway | first = G. Chezia | title = Violence against women of color | journal = [[Stanford Law Review]] | volume = 43 | issue = 6 | pages = 1301&ndash;1309 | publisher = [[Stanford Law School]] | doi = 10.2307/1229040 | jstor = 1229040 | date = July 1991 | ref = harv }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Robinson | first = Nancy P. | title = Origins of the International Day for the Elimination of Violence against Women: The Caribbean contribution | journal = [[Caribbean Studies (UPR)|Caribbean Studies]] | volume = 34 | issue = 2 | pages = 141&ndash;161 | publisher = [[University of Puerto Rico, R\u00edo Piedras Campus|UPR, Rio Piedras Campus]] | jstor = 25613539 | date = July\u2013December 2006 | ref = harv }}</ref> as well as \"public health issue\".<ref name=\"Michau, L. 2007 95\u2013109\">{{cite journal | last = Michau | first = Lori | title = Approaching old problems in new ways: community mobilisation as a primary prevention strategy to combat violence against women | journal = [[Gender & Development]] | volume = 15 | issue = 1 | pages = 95&ndash;109 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] | doi = 10.1080/13552070601179144  | jstor = 20461184 | date = March 2007 | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\nIn order to better comprehend the anti-violence movements against VAW, there is a need to also understand the generic historical background of [[feminist movements]] in a holistic manner. Talking about the international women's movement, many feminist scholars have categorized these movements into three waves<ref name=\"Krol\u00f8kke&S\u00f8rensen\">{{cite book | last1 = Krol\u00f8kke | first1 = Charlotte | last2 = S\u00f8rensen | first2 = Ann Scott | chapter = Three waves of feminism: from suffragettes to grrls | chapterurl = https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=IEhqiWR1Rt0C&pg=PA1 | editor-last1 = Krol\u00f8kke | editor-first1 = Charlotte | editor-last2 = S\u00f8rensen | editor-first2 = Ann Scott | title = Gender communication theories & analyses: from silence to performance | pages = 1&ndash;23 | publisher = Sage Publications | location = Thousand Oaks, California | year = 2006 | isbn = 9780761929185 | ref = harv }}</ref> according to their different beliefs, strategies and goals.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Rupp | first1 = Leila J. | last2 = Taylor | first2 = Verta | title = Forging feminist identity in an international movement: a collective identity approach to twentieth-century feminism | journal = [[Signs (journal)|Signs]] | volume = 24 | issue = 2 | pages = 363&ndash;386 | publisher = [[University of Chicago Press]] | doi = 10.1086/495344 | jstor = 3175646 | date = Winter 1999 | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\nThe emergence of the first women's movements, or so called the [[First-wave feminism|first wave]] of feminism, dated back in the years the late 19th Century and early 20th Century in the United States and Europe. During this period, feminist movements developed from the context of industrialization and liberal politics that triggered the rise of feminist groups concerned with gaining equal access and opportunity for women.<ref name=\"Krol\u00f8kke&S\u00f8rensen\" />{{rp|1}} This wave marks a period of \"[[Women's suffrage|suffrage]], independence, rights to nationality, work and [[Gender pay gap|equal pay]]\" for women.<ref name=\"Pr\u00fcgl, E. Dec. 2013\">{{cite book | last = Pr\u00fcgl | first = Elisabeth (Lecturer) | title = Violence Against Women. Gender and International Affairs Class 2013 | url = http://graduateinstitute.ch/home/study/courses/courses-2017-2018/masters-interdisciplinaires/mia/ia039---gender-and-international.html | location = Geneva, Switzerland | publisher = Lecture conducted from [[The Graduate Institute of International and Development Studies]] (IHEID) | date = 2 December 2013 | access-date = 27 December 2017 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20180721122423/http://graduateinstitute.ch/home/study/courses/courses-2017-2018/masters-interdisciplinaires/mia/ia039---gender-and-international.html | archive-date = 21 July 2018 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\nThe [[Second-wave feminism|second wave]] of feminist movements was the series of movements from the period of the late 1960s to early 1970s. It was noted by feminist scholars that this wave could be characterized as a period of [[Women's liberation movement|women's liberation]] and the rise of a branch of feminism known as [[radical feminism]].<ref name=\"Krol\u00f8kke&S\u00f8rensen\" />{{rp|7\u20138}} This wave of feminism emerged in the context of the postwar period<ref name=\"Krol\u00f8kke&S\u00f8rensen\" />{{rp|8}} in society where other mainstream movements also played a large role; for instance, the [[civil rights movements]],<ref name=\"Pr\u00fcgl, E. Dec. 2013\" /> which meant to condemn [[capitalism]], [[imperialism]] and the oppression of people based on the notions of [[Racism|race]], ethnicity, [[gender identity]] and [[LGBT social movements|sexual orientation]].<ref name=\"Krol\u00f8kke&S\u00f8rensen\" />{{rp|9}} This wave marks a period of equal rights at home and workplace as well as rights to development<ref name=\"Pr\u00fcgl, E. Dec. 2013\" /> for the purposes of people of different races, ethnicities, economic statuses and gender identities.\n\nThe [[Third-wave feminism|third wave]] of feminism is the newest wave of feminism led by young feminists whose understanding and context are of the [[Globalization|globalized]] world order and the technological advances that have come with it. Also, this wave is a transition of the fall communism<ref name=\"Krol\u00f8kke&S\u00f8rensen\" />{{rp|17}} to more complex issues of new kinds of 'warfare'{{Clarify|reason=What does this mean by \"warfare\"?  Also, this whole sentence is oddly worded but I don't understand what it's trying to say well enough to rewrite it.|date=November 2018}}, threats and violence. This new wave also \"embraces ambiguity\"<ref name=\"Krol\u00f8kke&S\u00f8rensen\" />{{rp|16}} and introduced a feminist approach of '[[intersectionality]]' that includes the issues of race, gender, age, and class.<ref name=\"Krol\u00f8kke&S\u00f8rensen\" />{{rp|17}} Other than that, the third wave marks a period of feminism dealing with [[identity politics]], body politics as well as the issues of violence.<ref>{{cite book | last = Lind | first = Amy (Lecturer) | title = Gender and International Affairs 2013: International Feminist Movements | url = http://graduateinstitute.ch/directory?detail=people/faculty/lind | location = Geneva, Switzerland | publisher = Lecture conducted from [[The Graduate Institute of International and Development Studies]] (IHEID) | date = 2 December 2013 | access-date = 29 March 2020 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20181113125400/http://graduateinstitute.ch/directory?detail=people%2Ffaculty%2Flind | archive-date = 13 November 2018 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n[[File:Papua New Guinean children, men and women show their support for putting an end to violence against women during a White Ribbon Day march (21614943268).jpg|thumb|[[Papua New Guinean]]s show their support for putting an end to [[Sexual violence in Papua New Guinea|violence against women]] during a [[White Ribbon Campaign|White Ribbon Day]] march]]\n\nNonetheless, the VAW movement was initiated in the 1970s where some feminist movements started to bring the discussion on the issue of violence into the feminist discourse<ref>{{cite book | last = Eng | first = Phoebe | author-link = Phoebe Eng | title = Stopping the violence against women: the movement from intervention to prevention | url = http://www.ncdsv.org/images/Ms_StoppingVAWTheMovementFromInterventionToPrevention_Aug2005.pdf | page = 2 | publisher = [[Ms. Foundation for Women]] | location = New York | date = August 2005 | series = A Safety Program Report | access-date = 3 December 2013 }}</ref> and that many other groups, on the national as well as international levels, had attempted to push for the betterment of women through lobbying of the state officials and delegates, demanding the conferences on 'gender issues'<ref name=\"Pr\u00fcgl, E. Dec. 2013\" /> and thus made the VAW known to a wider range of population. Therefore, to put this into the theoretical context, VAW can be categorized along with the second and third waves of feminism which share a focus on violence.\n\nVAW activist movements come in many forms, operating at international, national, and local levels<ref name=\"Youngs_368325\" /> and utilizing different approaches based on health and human rights frameworks.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Miller | first = Alice M. | title = Sexuality, violence against women, and human rights: women make demands and ladies get protection | journal = [[Health and Human Rights]] | volume = 7 | issue = 2 | pages = 16&ndash;47 | publisher = [[Harvard University Press]] | doi = 10.2307/4065347 | jstor = 4065347 | date = 2004 | ref = harv }}</ref> The movements stemmed mostly from social movements and groups of women who see the need to create organizations to 'lobby' their governments to establish \"sanctuaries, shelters\" and provision of services that help protecting these victims, also called \"battered women\", from acts of violence. The term \"battered women\" was used in a number of VAW movements and had its root in the early stage of organizing efforts to tackle the problem of violence against women in many regions of the world such as Africa, Asia Pacific, Latin American and the Caribbean.<ref name=\"Fried\" />{{rp|94}} The activist organizations against VAW, some with and the others without the support of their governments, attempted to develop \"innovative efforts\" to assist battered women by providing them services such as shelters and centers; drafting and lobbying governments to include the recognition and language of VAW into national legislations and [[international human rights instruments]]; advocating to raise the awareness of people via education and training sessions; forming national, regional as well as international networks to empower the movements; organizing demonstrations and gathering more efforts to end violent acts against women.<ref name=\"Fried\" />{{rp|88\u201389}} In addition, many women's rights activist groups see the issue of violence against women as a central focus of their movements. Many of these groups take a human rights approach as the integral framework of their activism. These VAW movements also employ the idea that \"women's rights are human rights\", transform the concepts and ideas of human rights, which are mostly reckoned to be \"[[Western world|Western]] concepts\" and '[[Vernacularization|vernacularize]] them into the concepts that can be understood in their local institutions.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Merry | first = Sally Engle | title = Transnational human rights and local activism: mapping the middle | journal = [[American Anthropologist]] | volume = 108 | issue = 1 | pages = 38&ndash;51 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1525/aa.2006.108.1.38 | date = March 2006 | ref = harv }}</ref>{{rp|39}}\n\n=== Levels of activist movements ===\n[[File:Girl_Summit_-_22nd_July_in_London_(14498368279).jpg|thumb|250px|Poster against child and forced marriage]]\n[[File:Marcha_Ni_una_menos_1.JPG|thumb|250px|right|Mass protest against violence against women in [[Buenos Aires]] in 2015]]\nOn the local or national level, the VAW movements are diverse and differ in their strategic program of intervention. The strategies used in a number of the movements focus on the individual level with the emphases on individuals, relationships and family. Also, many of them take the 'preventive' as an approach to tackle the issues on the ground by encouraging people to \"reexamine their attitudes and beliefs\" in order to trigger and create fundamental changes in these \"deep-rooted beliefs and behaviors\".<ref name=\"Michau, L. 2007 95\u2013109\"/> Despite the fact that these strategies can be life changing, helpful to those who participate and feasible over a long time frame, the effects on societal level seem to be restricted and of minimal effects. In order to achieve the objectives of the movement, many activists and scholars argue that they have to initiate changes in cultural attitudes and norms on a communal level.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Heise | first1 = L. | last2 = Gottemoeller | first2 = M. | title = Ending violence against women | journal = Population Reports | volume = L | issue = 11 | page = 38 | publisher = Johns Hopkins University School of Public Health, Population and Information Program | url = https://vawnet.org/sites/default/files/assets/files/2016-10/PopulationReports.pdf | date = December 1999 }}</ref> An example of activism on the local level can be seen in South Africa. The movements of VAW in this context employ a strategy that is based on the 'prevention' approach, which is applicable on individual and societal levels: in families and communities. This movement encourages the individuals and small populations to rethink their attitudes and beliefs in order to create a possibility to alter these deep-rooted beliefs and behaviors, which lead to the acts of violence against women.<ref name=\"Michau, L. 2007 pp.96\"/> Another example is the local level movement in East Africa that employs the prevention approach, which is applicable on a communal level. They call this a \"raising voices\" approach. This approach employs an 'ad hoc' framework that can be used alongside the individual approach where the strategy is to aggravate the status quo issues onto the individuals' and communities' perception and establish a common ground of interests for them to push for the movement, all in a short time period.<ref name=\"Michau, L. 2007 pp.96\"/> In addition, on the domestic level, there seems to be many 'autonomous movements.'<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\" /> feminist movements (for VAW) can be understood as \"a form of women's mobilization that is devoted to promoting women's status and well-being independently of political parties and other associations that do not have the status of women as their main concern\".<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\" />\n\nA number of regions of the world have come together to address violence against women. In South America, the Southern Cone Network Against Domestic Violence has worked extensively to address sexual and domestic violence since 1989. The Latin American and Caribbean Network Against Domestic and Sexual Violence, formed in 1990, includes representation from twenty-one different countries and has been instrumental in increasing the visibility of VAW.<ref name=\"Fried\" />{{rp|88}} In September 1999, the Heads of States of the [[Southern African Development Community]] (SADC) met and drafted the \"Prevention and Eradication of Violence Against Women and Children\", a document condemning violence against women and children, and resolved a set of 13 methods of addressing it, reaching into the legal; social, economic, cultural, and political; social service; and education, training, and awareness building sectors.<ref>{{cite journal | last = SADC| title = The prevention and eradication of violence against women and children | journal = Review of African Political Economy | volume = 26 | issue = 81 | pages = 415&ndash;417 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] | doi = 10.1080/03056249908704404 | jstor = 4006468 | date = September 1999 | ref = harv }}</ref>\n\nOn the transnational or regional level, the anti-violence movements also deploy different strategies based on the specificities of their cultures and beliefs in their particular regions. On this level, the activist movements are known as \"transnational feminist networks\" or TFNs.<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\" />{{rp|556}} The TFNs have a significant effect, like the autonomous movements on the national level, in shaping sets of policies as well pushing for the recognition and inclusion of language of VAW in the United Nations human rights mechanisms: the international human rights agreements.<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\" /> Their activities are ranging from lobbying the policy makers; organizing demonstrations on the local and regional levels; to creating institutional pressure that could push for changes in the international institutional measures.<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\" />\n\nOn an international level, the movements that advocate for women's rights and against VAW are the mixture of (civil society) actors from domestic and regional levels. The objectives of these VAW movements focus on \"creating shared expectations\" within the domestic and regional levels as well as \"mobilizing numbers of domestic civil society\" to create \"standards in global civil society\".<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\" />{{rp|556}} The global women's movement works to transform numbers of international conventions and conferences to \"a conference on women's rights\" by pushing for a \"stronger language and clearer recognition\" of the VAW issues. In addition, the United Nations also plays a vital role in promoting and campaigning for the VAW movements on the international level. For instance, in 2008 UN Secretary General [[Ban Ki-moon|Ban Ki-Moon]] initiated and launched a campaign called \"[[UNiTE to End Violence against Women]]\". This campaign \"calls on governments, civil society, women's organizations, young people, the private sector, the media and the entire UN system to join forces in addressing the global pandemic of violence against women and girls\".<ref name=\"UNiTE_Orange\">{{cite web | last = UNiTE | author-link = UNiTE to End Violence against Women | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131220093826/http://www.unwomen.org/en/what-we-do/ending-violence-against-women/take-action | archive-date = 20 December 2013 |url=http://www.unwomen.org/en/what-we-do/ending-violence-against-women/take-action |title=Take action to Orange your day |publisher=[[UN Women]] |date= 2013 | accessdate = 20 December 2013}}</ref> Moreover, this campaign also announces every 25th of the month to be \"Orange Day\" or \"a day to take action to raise awareness and prevent violence against women and girls\".<ref name=\"UNiTE_Orange\" />\n\nIn conclusion, each level of activism is intertwined and has the common purpose to end violence against women. Activism on local levels can significantly affect national, transnational, and international levels as well. In a scholarly article on ''Combating Violence Against Women'', the authors illustrated from their research analysis on how the norms of international society can shape and influence policy making on the domestic or national level and vice versa. They argue that there are three mechanisms which have effects on the making of national policies as well as global agreements and conventions: \"1) the influence of global treaties and documents such as [[CEDAW]] on women's rights\" - on the national policies \"2) the influence of regional agreements on VAW (particularly after certain tipping points are reached)\" - on both domestic policies and international conventions and \"3) regional demonstration effects or pressure for conformity captured as diffusion within regions\" - on the international norms and agreements.<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\" />\n\n=== Achievements of the VAW movements ===\nOn the global level:\n* The first major document that highlights the recognition of violence against women as a human rights violation: the United Nations [[Declaration on the Elimination of Violence Against Women]] in Vienna, 1993.<ref name=\"Brown Thompson 2002\">{{cite book | last = Brown Thompson | first = Karen | chapter = Women's rights are human rights | editor-last1 = Khagram | editor-first1 = Sanjeev | editor-last2 = Riker | editor-first2 = James V. | editor-last3 = Sikkink | editor-first3 = Kathryn | title = Restructuring world politics: transnational social movements, networks, and norms | pages = 96&ndash;122 | publisher = University of Minnesota Press | location = Minneapolis | year = 2002 | isbn = 9780816639076 | ref = harv }}</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = Elman | first = R. Amy | title = Sexual equality in an integrated Europe: virtual equality | publisher = Palgrave Macmillan | location = Basingstoke, UK | series = Europe in Transition: the NYU European Studies Series | year = 2008 | isbn = 9780230610071 }}</ref><ref name=\"Weldon, S.L 2006\">{{cite journal | last = Weldon | first = S. Laurel | title = Inclusion, solidarity, and social movements: the global movement against gender violence | journal = [[Perspectives on Politics]] | volume = 4 | issue = 1 | pages = 55&ndash;74 | publisher =  [[Cambridge University Press]] | doi = 10.1017/S1537592706060063 | jstor = 3688626 | date = March 2006 | ref = harv }}</ref> It was a result of collective effort of global feminist movement to transform the Vienna conference from a general and mainstream human rights conference into the conference on women's rights. As before the other human rights organizations such as Amnesty International and Human Rights Watch did not focus on the issue of VAW and did not consider rape and domestic violence as violations of human rights despite of the fact that they also have agenda on women's rights.<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\" />\n* The 1995 [[Fourth World Conference on Women]] in Beijing<ref>{{cite book | last = UN | author-link = United Nations |title=Beijing Declaration and Platform for Action |url=https://www.un.org/womenwatch/daw/beijing/pdf/BDPfA%20E.pdf |publisher=United Nations | date = 1995 |accessdate=16 December 2013}}</ref> During the 4th Women Conference, VAW was emphasized and named as a critical concern. Also, the spillover effect was that this push highlighted the need for the development of \"new international norms\" that have often been used by activists and governments the proposition of legislation that provide other action to redress the acts of violence.<ref name=\"Brown Thompson 2002\"/><ref name=\"Weldon, S.L 2006\"/><ref>{{cite book | editor-last = F\u00e1bi\u00e1n | editor-first = Katalin | title = Domestic violence in postcommunist states: local activism, national policies, and global forces | publisher = Indiana University Press | location = Bloomington, Indiana| year = 2010 | isbn = 9780253222183 }}</ref>\n* Subsequently, the push from the global feminist movement also push for the fully incorporation of the VAW issues into the \"Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination Against Women\" or [[CEDAW]]<ref>{{cite book | last = CEDAW | author-link = CEDAW |title=Committee on the Elimination of Discrimination against Women |url=https://www.un.org/womenwatch/daw/cedaw/committee.htm |publisher=[[United Nations]] |date=31 December 2003 |accessdate=19 December 2013}}</ref> whereas the \"original text of [[CEDAW]] in 1979 did not explicitly mention violence against women\".<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\" />{{rp|556}}\n\nOn the regional level:\n* ''Americas'': the Inter-American Convention on Violence Against Women, which was formally announced and adopted by the [[Organization of American States]] (OAS) in 1994, immediately after the Vienna Conference<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\" />{{rp|557}}\n* ''Europe'': The [[European Union]] (EU)'s initiatives to combat violence against women after the 1990s: the 1997 resolution calling for a zero tolerance: specifically on UN human rights instruments of [[CEDAW]] and the [[Vienna Declaration and Programme of Action|Vienna Declaration]].\n** The [[Council of Europe]] also developed \"a series of initiatives\" related to the issue of VAW: \"the 2000 resolution on trafficking, the 2003 resolution on domestic violence, and the 2004 resolution on honor crimes\" as well as promoted \"the 2002 recommendation on the protection of women against violence and established its monitoring framework\".<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\" />{{rp|557}}\n* ''Africa'': \n** There emerged a series of regional meetings and agreements, which was triggered by the UN processes on the international level such as Third World Conference on Women in Nairobi, 1985; the 1993 Kampala Prep Com; the 1994 Africa-wide UN women's conference<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Tripp | first1 = Aili Mari | last2 = Casimiro | first2 = Isabel | last3 = Kwesiga | first3 = Joy | last4 = Mungwa | first4 = Alice | title = African women's movements: transforming political landscapes | publisher = Cambridge University Press | location = Cambridge New York | year = 2009 | isbn = 9780511479014 }}</ref> that led to the identification of VAW as a critical issue in the Southern African Women's Charter.<ref name=\"Htun&Weldon\" />{{rp|557}}\n\n==Access to justice for female victims of violence==\n\n===International and regional instruments===\nEfforts to fight violence against women can take many forms and access to justice, or lack thereof, for such violence varies greatly depending on the justice system. International and regional instruments are increasingly used as the basis for national legislation and policies to eradicate violence against women.\n\nThe Inter-American Convention to Prevent, Eradicate and Punish Violence Against Women \u2013 also known as the Bel\u00e9m do Par\u00e0 Convention, for instance, has been applied by the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights (IACHR) in its first case of domestic violence to condemn Brazil in the Maria da Penha case. This led the Brazilian government to enact in 2006 the Maria da Penha Law, the country's first law against domestic violence against women.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Spieler | first = Paula | title = The Maria da Penha Case and the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights: contributions to the debate on domestic violence against women in Brazil | journal = [[Indiana Journal of Global Legal Studies]] | volume = 18 | issue = 1 | pages = 121&ndash;143 | publisher = [[Indiana University Maurer School of Law]] | date = Winter 2011 | url = https://muse.jhu.edu/article/445824 | ref = harv | doi=10.2979/indjglolegstu.18.1.121}}</ref> There is also, for instance, the South Asian Agreement on Regional Cooperation's (SAARC) Protocol to End Trafficking in Women and Children.<ref name=\"Fried\" />\n\n===Examples of measures put in place===\nAs violence is often committed by a family member, women first started by lobbying their governments to set up shelters for domestic violence survivors. The Julia Burgos Protected House established in Puerto Rico in 1979 was the first shelter in Latin America and the Caribbean for \"battered women\". In 2003, 18 out of the 20 countries in the region had legislation on domestic or family violence, and 11 countries addressed sexual violence in their laws. Legislative measures to protect victims can include restraining orders, which can be found in Colombia, El Salvador, Guatemala, Paraguay, Venezuela, Turkey, the United States and many western European countries for instance.\n\nCourts can also be allowed by law (Germany, 2001) to order the perpetrator to leave the home so that victims do not have to seek shelter. Countries were urged to repeal discriminatory legislation by 2005 following the review of the Beijing Declaration and Platform for Action in 2000. Egypt, for instance, abolished a law that exempted men from rape charges when marrying their victims. However, the goal of antiviolence legislation is often to keep the families together, regardless of the best interests of women, which perpetuate domestic violence.<ref name=\"Fried\" />\n\nInnovative measures have been pioneered in a number of countries to end violence against women. In Brazil and Jordan, [[women's police stations]] have been introduced, and one-stop [[women's shelter]]s were created in Malaysia and Nicaragua.\n\n[[Marital rape]] has been illegal in every American state and the District of Columbia since 1993, but is rarely prosecuted in America.<ref name=\"rainn.org\">{{cite web |title=Marital rape | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20131201082952/http://www.rainn.org/public-policy/sexual-assault-issues/marital-rape | archive-date = 1 December 2013 |url=http://www.rainn.org/public-policy/sexual-assault-issues/marital-rape |website=rainn.org | publisher = [[Rape, Abuse and Incest National Network]] (RAINN) |date= |accessdate=8 December 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 the [[UN General Assembly]] passed its first resolution calling for the protection of defenders of women's human rights.<ref name=\"Norway Post\" /> The resolution urges states to put in place gender-specific laws and policies for the protection of women's human rights defenders and to ensure that defenders themselves are involved in the design and implementation of these measures, and calls on states to protect women's human rights defenders from reprisals for cooperating with the UN and to ensure their unhindered access to and communication with international human rights bodies and mechanisms.<ref name=\"awid.org\"/>\n\n=== Challenges faced by women in accessing justice and limitations of measures ===\nThere can be a de jure or de facto acceptance of violent behaviors and lack of remedies for victims.<ref name=\"Fried\" />\n\n*'''Lack of criminalization:''' in many places, acts of abuse, especially acts such as [[female genital mutilation]], [[marital rape]], [[forced marriage]] and [[child marriage]], are not criminalized, or are illegal but widely tolerated, with the laws against them being rarely enforced. There are instances where crimes against women are also categorized as minor offenses.\n*'''Lack of awareness of the existing laws:''' in many places, although there are laws against violence on the books, many women do not know of their existence. This is especially the case with marital rape - its criminalization being very recent in most countries.<ref>''Citations'':\n* {{cite book | last = AI | author-link = Amnesty International | title = ''Hungary \u2013'' Cries unheard: ''The failure to protect women from rape and sexual violence in the home''|url=https://www.amnesty.org/en/documents/eur27/002/2007/en/ |accessdate=12 December 2013 | format = PDF | id = EUR 27/002/2007 | publisher = [[Amnesty International]] }}\n* {{cite news | last = Staff writer | title = Hungary law 'fails rape victims' | url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/europe/6643727.stm | work=[[BBC News]] | date = 10 May 2007 | accessdate = 12 December 2013}}\n* {{cite news | last = Moy | first = Patsy |url=http://www.scmp.com/article/435610/publicity-urged-law-marital-rape |title=Publicity urged for law on marital rape |work=[[South China Morning Post]] |date= 23 November 2003 |accessdate=12 December 2013}}</ref>\n*'''Challenges in making a case in court:''' the burden of proof can be placed on the victim. For instance in the Philippines, before a change in law in 1997, rape used to be described as a crime against chastity; and virginity played an important role in court. In various countries, such as [[Bangladesh]], a woman's past sexual experience continues to be very important in a case of rape. Bangladesh has received criticism for its employment of the \"two-finger test\" in rape investigations. This test consists in a physical examination of women who report rape during which a doctor inserts two fingers in the woman's vagina to determine whether the woman is \"habituated to sex\". This examination has its origin in the country's British colonial-era laws dating back to 1872. This deters many women from reporting rape. More than 100 experts, including doctors, lawyers, police, and women's rights activists had signed a joint statement in 2013 asking for the test, which they called \"demeaning\", to be abolished, as it \"does not provide any evidence that is relevant to proving the offence\". This test is also performed in several other countries in the region, including India.<ref>''Citations'':\n* {{cite book | last = Press release |title=100 experts demand change in medical evidence laws and justice for rape victims |url= http://www.blast.org.bd/content/pressrelease/press-release-nc-2-2-2013.pdf |publisher=Bangladesh Legal Aid Services Trust | date = 2 February 2013 |accessdate=4 April 2016}}\n* {{cite news | last = Agence France-Presse | author-link = Agence France-Presse | title = Bangladesh activists urge ban on rape victim 'finger test' | url = http://www.ndtv.com/article/world/bangladesh-activists-urge-ban-on-rape-victim-finger-test-326175 | work = [[NDTV]] | date = 4 February 2013 | accessdate = 4 April 2016}}\n* {{cite news|last=Park |first=Madison |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/02/05/world/asia/rape-exam-india/index.html |title=Activists: Get rid of 'degrading' parts of India's sexual assault exam |work=[[CNN]] |date=5 February 2013  |accessdate=4 April 2016}}</ref> It can also be difficult to make a case of sexual assault in court, when members of the judiciary expect evidence of severe struggle and injury as determinative evidence of non-consent. On the other hand, there are measures, such as the 2012 law in Brazil, that allow for cases to be filed even without the representation of the victim.\n*'''Existing laws are insufficient, conflicting, and have no effect in practice:''' some laws on domestic violence, for instance, conflict with other provisions and ultimately contradict their goals. Legal frameworks can also be flawed when laws that integrate protection do so in isolation, notably in relation to immigration laws. Undocumented women in countries where they would have, in theory, access to justice, don't in practice for fear of being denounced and deported. The CEDAW Committee recommends that a State authority's obligation to report undocumented persons be repealed in national legislation.\n*'''The attitude of the police:''' women who report acts of violence most often come into contact first with police workers. Therefore, police attitudes are crucial in facilitating a sense of safety and comfort for women who have been victimized.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Logan | first1 = T. K. | last2 = Shannon | first2 = Lisa | last3 = Walker | first3 = Robert | title = Police attitudes toward domestic violence offenders | journal = [[Journal of Interpersonal Violence]] | volume = 21 | issue = 10 | pages = 1365&ndash;1374 | publisher = [[Sage Publications|Sage]] | doi = 10.1177/0886260506291653 | pmid = 16940401 | date = October 2006 | ref = harv }}</ref> When police officers have hostile attitudes towards victimized women, these women are prevented from obtaining justice.<ref>{{cite news | last = Travis | first = Alan | title = Police treatment of domestic abuse victims to be investigated | url = https://www.theguardian.com/society/2016/may/17/police-treatment-of-domestic-abuse-victims-to-be-investigated | work = [[The Guardian]] | date = 17 May 2016 | access-date = 21 October 2017}}</ref> Recognizing these problems, some countries have enacted [[women's police station]], which are [[police station]]s that specialize in certain crimes, such as [[sexual violence]], [[harassment]], [[domestic violence]] committed against women.\n\nMeasures to address violence against women range from access to legal-aid to the provision of shelters and hotlines for victims. Despite advances in legislation and policies, the lack of implementation of the measures put in place prevents significant progress in eradicating violence against women globally. This failure to apply existing laws and procedures is often due to the persisting issue of gender stereotyping.<ref>{{cite book | last = CEDAW | author-link = CEDAW | title = General discussion on women and access to justice | url = http://wilpf.org/cedaw-general-discussion-on-women-and-access-to-justice/ | publisher = [[United Nations]] | location = Geneva, Switzerland | date = 18 February 2013 | accessdate = 12 December 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Relation with marriage laws==\n[[File:Marriage_is_no_excuse_for_rape.png|thumb|Sign against justification of violence in marriage]] \n{{Further|Criticism of marriage|Sexism#Coverture_and_other_marriage_regulations}}\nThe relation between violence against women and marriage laws, regulations and traditions has also been discussed.<ref>{{cite book | last = Chambers | first = Clare | title = Recognizing marriage as a symbolic institution |url= http://citation.allacademic.com/meta/p_mla_apa_research_citation/0/4/1/2/5/p41259_index.html |publisher=American Political Science Association | location = Washington, D.C. |date= 1 September 2005 | accessdate = 12 December 2013}} Paper presented at the annual meeting of the American Political Science Association.\n:''For a later version of this paper see'':\n:* {{cite book | last = Chambers | first = Clare | title = Feminism, liberalism and marriage (workshop) | url = https://www.brown.edu/Research/ppw/past_07_08.html | publisher = Political Philosophy Workshop at [[Brown University]] | date = 10 April 2008 }} [https://www.brown.edu/Research/ppw/files/Feminism,%20Liberalism%20and%20Marriage.doc Word document.]</ref><ref>{{cite book | last = Jeffreys | first = Sheila | author-link = Sheila Jeffreys | title = The industrial vagina: the political economy of the global sex trade | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=9mlFgjEBYWYC | publisher = Routledge | location = London New York | year = 2009 | series = RIPE Series in Global Political Economy | isbn = 9780415412322 }}</ref> The US and English law subscribed until the 20th century to the system of [[coverture]], that is, a legal doctrine under which, upon marriage, a woman's legal rights were subsumed by those of her husband.<ref>{{cite book | last = Blackstone | first = William | author-link = William Blackstone | chapter = Husband and wife | chapterurl = http://www.lonang.com/exlibris/blackstone/bla-115.htm | title = Commentaries on the laws of England (1765-1769), vol 1: Of the rights of persons | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = Oxford, United Kingdom New York, NY | year = 2016 | origyear = 1765 | isbn = 9780199600991 }}</ref> Today, outside the West, many countries severely restrict the rights of married women: for example, in [[Yemen]], marriage regulations state that a wife must obey her husband and must not leave home without his permission.<ref>{{cite book | last = AI | author-link = Amnesty International | title = Yemen's dark side: discrimination and violence against women and girls | url = https://www.amnesty.org/en/documents/MDE31/014/2009/en/ |publisher=[[Amnesty International]] | id = MDE 31/014/2009 | date = November 2009 | accessdate = 12 December 2013}}</ref> In [[Iraq]] husbands have a legal right to \"punish\" their wives. The criminal code states at Paragraph 41 that there is no crime if an act is committed while exercising a legal right; examples of legal rights include: \"The punishment of a wife by her husband, the disciplining by parents and teachers of children under their authority within certain limits prescribed by law or by custom\".<ref>{{cite book | title = Statutory notice: The [Iraqi] penal-code with amendments | id = STS 251/88 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121021100954/http://law.case.edu/saddamtrial/documents/Iraqi_Penal_Code_1969.pdf | archive-date = 21 October 2012 | url = http://law.case.edu/saddamtrial/documents/Iraqi_Penal_Code_1969.pdf | publisher = Case Western Reserve University School of Law | date = 1969 | accessdate = 12 December 2013}}</ref> In the West, married women faced discrimination until just a few decades ago: for instance, in [[France]], married women received the right to work without their husband's permission in 1965.<ref>''Citations'':\n* {{cite journal | last = Allwood | first = Gill | title = Women in France |url=http://www.tandf.co.uk/journals/explore/cmcf-vsi-women-in-france.pdf | journal = Modern & Contemporary France |publisher=[[Taylor and Francis]] | accessdate = 12 December 2013}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://marinablue.fr/voicepress/frances-leading-women-show-the-way/ |title=France's leading women show the way | website = marinablue.fr |publisher=Paris Voice |date= November 1997| accessdate = 12 December 2013}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://www.womeninworldhistory.com/TWR-07.html|title= \"''The Wife is Obliged''\": The French Civil Code (Napoleonic Code) 1800-1820 | website = womeninworldhistory |publisher=Women in World History Curriculum | accessdate = 12 December 2013}}</ref> In [[Spain]], during the Franco era, a married woman required her husband's consent (''permiso marital'') for nearly all economic activities, including employment, ownership of property and traveling away from home; the permiso marital was abolished in 1975.<ref>{{cite book | last1 = Solsten | first1 = Eric | last2 = Meditz | first2 = Sandra W. | chapter = Social values and attitudes | chapterurl = http://countrystudies.us/spain/43.htm | editor-last1 = Solsten | editor-first1 = Eric | editor-last2 = Meditz | editor-first2 = Sandra W. | title = Spain: a country study | publisher = Library of Congress, Federal Research Division | location = Washington, DC | year = 1988 | oclc = 712557481}}</ref> Concerns exist about violence related to marriage - both inside marriage (physical abuse, sexual violence, restriction of liberty) and in relation to marriage customs ([[dowry]], [[bride price]], [[forced marriage]], [[child marriage]], [[marriage by abduction]], violence related to female premarital [[virginity]]). Claudia Card, professor of Philosophy at the University of Wisconsin-Madison, writes:<ref>{{cite journal | last = Card | first = Claudia | title = Against marriage and motherhood | journal = [[Hypatia (journal)|Hypatia: A Journal of Feminist Philosophy]] | volume = 11 | issue = 3 | pages = 1&ndash;23 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1527-2001.1996.tb01013.x | jstor = 3810319 | date = August 1996 | ref = harv }} [https://pol285.blog.gustavus.edu/files/2009/08/Card_Against_Marriage.pdf Pdf.]</ref>\n:\"The legal rights of access that married partners have to each other's persons, property, and lives makes it all but impossible for a spouse to defend herself (or himself), or to be protected against torture, rape, battery, stalking, mayhem, or murder by the other spouse... Legal marriage thus enlists state support for conditions conducive to murder and mayhem.\"\n\n==Istanbul Convention==\nThe [[Council of Europe Convention on preventing and combating violence against women and domestic violence]], also known as the Istanbul Convention, is the first legally binding instrument in Europe in the field of domestic violence and violence against women,<ref>https://www.oas.org/es/mesecvi/docs/CSW-SideEvent2014-Flyer-EN.pdf</ref> and came into force in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|author=Bureau des Trait\u00e9s |url=http://www.conventions.coe.int/Treaty/Commun/ChercheSig.asp?NT=210&CM=&DF=&CL=ENG |title=Liste compl\u00e8te |publisher=Conventions.coe.int |date= |accessdate=18 July 2016}}</ref>\nCountries which ratify it must ensure that the forms of violence defined in its text are outlawed. In its Preamble, the Convention states that \"the realisation of ''de jure'' and ''de facto'' equality between women and men is a key element in the prevention of violence against women\". The Convention also provides a definition of [[domestic violence]] as \"all acts of physical, sexual, psychological or economic violence that occur within the family or domestic unit or between former or current spouses or partners, whether or not the perpetrator shares or has shared the same residence with the victim\".<ref name=\"Istanbul\">{{cite web|url=http://www.conventions.coe.int/Treaty/EN/Treaties/Html/210.htm|title=Council of Europe \u2013 Convention on preventing and combating violence against women and domestic violence (CETS No. 210)|work=coe.int|accessdate=8 October 2015}}</ref> Although it is a Convention of the [[Council of Europe]], it is open to accession by any country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.coe.int/t/dghl/standardsetting/convention-violence/thematic_factsheets/IC%20Global%20Tool_EN.pdf |title=Archived copy |accessdate=8 February 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221131635/http://www.coe.int/t/dghl/standardsetting/convention-violence/thematic_factsheets/IC%20Global%20Tool_EN.pdf |archivedate=21 February 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n<!-- New links in alphabetical order please -->\n{{Columns-list|colwidth=30em|\n*[[Bodily integrity]]\n*[[Children's rights]]\n*[[Eve teasing]]\n*[[List of incidents of violence against women]], list of notable incidents of violence against women sorted by country and year\n*[[Men's rights movement]]\n*[[Military sexual trauma]]\n*[[Misogyny in horror films]]\n*[[Rhinotomy]]\n*[[School-related gender-based violence (SRGBV)]]\n*[[Sexism]]\n*[[Sexual assault in the U.S. military]]\n*[[United Nations Security Council Resolution 1325]]\n*[[Violence against LGBT people]]\n*[[Violence against men]]\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{Cite journal | last = Almosaed | first = Nora | title = Violence against women: a cross\u2010cultural perspective | journal = [[Institute of Muslim Minority Affairs#Journal of Muslim Minority Affairs|Journal of Muslim Minority Affairs]] | volume = 24 | issue = 1 | pages = 67&ndash;88 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] | doi = 10.1080/1360200042000212124 | date = 2004 | ref = harv }}\n* {{Cite news | last = Appiah | first = Kwame Anthony | author-link = Kwame Anthony Appiah | title = Convincing other cultures to change | work = [[Big Think]] | date = 21 September 2010 | url = http://bigthink.com/videos/convincing-other-cultures-to-change | url-status = bot: unknown | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131212131130/http://bigthink.com/videos/convincing-other-cultures-to-change | archivedate = 12 December 2013 | df = dmy-all }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Bellemare | first1 = Marc F. | last2 = Steinmetz | first2 = Tara L. | title = All in the family: explaining the persistence of female genital cutting in the Gambia | journal = [[Social Science Research Network]] | doi = 10.2139/ssrn.2280086 | ssrn = 2280086 | date = 17 June 2013  | url = http://marcfbellemare.com/wordpress/2013/06/explaining-the-persistence-of-female-genital-cutting-in-the-gambia/ | ref = harv }} [http://marcfbellemare.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/BellemareSteinmetzFGCJune2013.pdf Pdf.]\n* {{cite book | last1 = Dobash | first1 = Russell P. | last2 = Dobash | first2 = R. Emerson | title = Women, violence and social change | publisher = Routledge | location = Abingdon, Oxon | year = 2016 | isbn = 9781138174023 }}\n*{{Cite journal | last1 = Durham | first1 = Meenakshi G. | authorlink1 = Meenakshi Gigi Durham | title = \"Vicious Assault Shakes Texas Town\": the politics of gender violence in ''The New York Times''<nowiki>'</nowiki> coverage of a schoolgirl's gang rape | journal = Journalism Studies | volume = 14 | issue = 1 | pages = 1&ndash;12 | publisher = [[Taylor & Francis]] | doi = 10.1080/1461670X.2012.657907 | date = February 2013 | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite book | last = Heise | first = Lori L. | last2 = Pitanguy | first2 = Jacqueline | last3 = Germain | first3 = Adrienne | title = Violence against women: the hidden health burden | journal = World Health Statistics Quarterly. Rapport Trimestriel de Statistiques Sanitaires Mondiales | volume = 46 | issue = 1 | pages = 78\u201385 | publisher = World Bank | location = Washington, D.C | year = 1994 | isbn = 9780821329801 | pmid = 8237054 }} Discussion Paper No. 255\n* {{cite journal | last1 = James | first1 = Stanlie M. | title = Shades of othering: reflections on female circumcision/genital mutilation | journal = [[Signs (journal)|Signs: Journal of Women in Culture and Society]] | volume = 23 | issue = 4 | pages = 1031&ndash;1048 | publisher = [[University of Chicago Press]] | doi = 10.1086/495300 | jstor = 3175202 | date = Summer 1998 | ref = harv }} \n* {{cite journal | last1 = Jones | first1 = Helen | last2 = Diop | first2 = Nafissatou | last3 = Askew | first3 = Ian | last4 = Kabor\u00e9 | first4 = Inoussa | title = Female genital cutting practices in Burkina Faso and Mali and their negative health outcomes | journal = [[Studies in Family Planning]] | volume = 30 | issue = 3 | pages = 219&ndash;230 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.1111/j.1728-4465.1999.00219.x | pmid = 10546313 | date = September 1999 | ref = harv }} \n* {{cite journal | last1 = Jones | first1 = Wanda K. | last2 = Smith | first2 = Jack | last3 = Kieke, Jr. | first3 = Burney | last4 = Wilcox | first4 = Lynne | title = Female genital mutilation/female circumcision: who is at risk in the US? | journal = [[Public Health Reports]] | volume = 112 | issue = 5 | pages = 368&ndash;377  | pmc = 1381943 | date = September 1997 | ref = harv | pmid=9323387}} [https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC1381943/pdf/pubhealthrep00038-0014.pdf Pdf.]\n* {{Cite journal | last = Kelly | first = Liz | author-link = Liz Kelly | title = Inside outsiders: Mainstreaming violence against women into human rights discourse and practice | journal = International Feminist Journal of Politics | volume = 7 | issue = 4 | pages = 471&ndash;495 | publisher = [[Taylor and Francis]] | doi = 10.1080/14616740500284391 | date = December 2005 | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite journal | last = Mackie | first = Gerry | title = Female genital cutting: a harmless practice? | journal = [[Medical Anthropology Quarterly]] | volume = 17 | issue = 2 | pages = 135&ndash;158 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] on behalf of the [[American Anthropological Association]] | doi = 10.1525/maq.2003.17.2.135 | pmid = 12846114 | jstor = 3655332 | date = June 2003 | ref = harv }} [http://dss.ucsd.edu/~gmackie/documents/FGCHarmlessPractice.pdf Pdf.]\n* {{cite journal | last = Shell-Duncan | first = Bettina | last2 = Herniund | first2 = Yiva | title = Are there \"Stages of Change\" in the practice of female genital cutting?: Qualitative research findings from Senegal and The Gambia | journal = African Journal of Reproductive Health [La Revue Africaine de la Sant\u00e9 Reproductive] | volume = 10 | issue = 2 | pages = 57&ndash;71 | publisher = Women's Health and Action Research Centre (WHARC) | doi = 10.2307/30032459 | jstor = 30032459 | date = August 2006| url = http://www.bioline.org.br/abstract?id=rh06027&lang=en | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite book | last = Skaine | first = Rosemarie | title = Female genital mutilation: legal, cultural, and medical issues | publisher = McFarland & Company, Inc. | location = Jefferson, North Caroline | year = 2005 | isbn = 9780786421671 }}\n* {{cite book | last = Wagner | first = Natascha | title = Why female genital cutting persist? | series = Working Paper | publisher = University of Rotterdam | url = http://www.natascha-wagner.com/uploads/9/0/1/5/9015445/fgc_march2013.pdf | date = March 2013 }}\n* {{cite book | last = True | first = Jacqui | title = The political economy of violence against women | publisher = Oxford University Press | location = New York, NY | year = 2012 | isbn = 9780199755912 }}\n* {{cite journal | last = Wakabi | first = Wairagala | title = Africa battles to make female genital mutilation history | journal = [[The Lancet]] | volume = 369 | issue = 9567| pages = 1069&ndash;1070 | publisher = [[Elsevier]] | pmid = 17405200 | doi = 10.1016/S0140-6736(07)60508-X | date = 31 March 2007 | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite journal | last1 = Williams | first1 = Lindy | last2 = Sobieszczyk | first2 = Teresa | title = Attitudes surrounding the continuation of female circumcision in the Sudan: passing the tradition to the next generation | journal = [[Journal of Marriage and Family]] | volume = 59 | issue = 4 | pages = 966&ndash;981 | publisher = [[Wiley-Blackwell|Wiley]] | doi = 10.2307/353796 | jstor = 353796 | date = November 1997 | ref = harv }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*{{dmoz|Society/People/Women/Issues/Violence_and_Abuse}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110516094651/http://www.echr.coe.int/NR/rdonlyres/39C38938-2E29-4151-9280-D5AC063DD02E/0/FICHES_Violence_femmes_EN.pdf Violence against women], a factsheet on [[ECtHR]] case law\n* [http://www.endvawnow.org/ Virtual Knowledge Centre to End Violence against Women and Girls] (in English, French, and Spanish)\n* [http://www.ohchr.org/EN/Issues/Women/SRWomen/Pages/SRWomenIndex.aspx UN Special Rapporteur on violence against women, its causes and consequences]\n* [http://www.who.int/reproductivehealth/publications/fgm/en/index.html World Health Organization's reports on FGM], Health complications of female genital mutilation\n\n{{abuse}}\n{{Domestic violence}}\n{{Violence against women by country}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Violence Against Women}}\n[[Category:Violence against women| ]]\n[[Category:Sex industry]]\n[[Category:Feminism and health]]\n[[Category:Gender-related violence|Against Women]]\n[[Category:Misogyny]]\n[[Category:Crimes against women]]\n", "name_user": "Gracie15", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTypes of violence:added a link to the wikipedia page \"online gender-based violence\"", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Violence_against_women"}
{"title_page": "Todd Graham", "text_new": "{{short description|American football coach}}\n{{Infobox college coach\n| name = Todd Graham\n| image = Todd Graham at 2014 Sun Bowl.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = Graham at the [[2014 Sun Bowl]]\n| current_title = [[Head coach]]\n| current_team = [[Hawaii Rainbow Warriors football|Hawaii]]\n| current_conference = [[Mountain West Conference|MW]]\n| current_record = 0\u20130\n| contract = $760,000\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1964|12|5}}\n| birth_place = [[Mesquite, Texas]]\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| alma_mater = \n| player_years1 = 1983\u20131986\n| player_team1 = [[East Central Tigers football|East Central]]\n| player_years2 = 1987\n| player_team2 = [[Arizona Cardinals]]\n| player_positions = [[Defensive back]]\n| coach_years1 = 1988\u20131990\n| coach_team1 = [[Poteet High School (Mesquite, Texas)| Poteet HS (TX)]] (assistant)\n| coach_years2 = 1991\u20131993\n| coach_team2 = [[East Central Tigers football|East Central]] ([[Defensive coordinator|DC]])\n| coach_years3 = 1994\n| coach_team3 = [[Carl Albert High School|Carl Albert HS (OK)]]\n| coach_years4 = 1995\u20132000\n| coach_team4 = [[Allen High School (Allen, Texas)|Allen HS (TX)]]\n| coach_years5 = 2001\n| coach_team5 = [[West Virginia Mountaineers football|West Virginia]] (LB)\n| coach_years6 = 2002\n| coach_team6 = [[West Virginia Mountaineers football|West Virginia]] (co-DC)\n| coach_years7 = 2003\u20132005\n| coach_team7 = [[Tulsa Golden Hurricane football|Tulsa]] (AHC/DC)\n| coach_years8 = 2006\n| coach_team8 = [[Rice Owls football|Rice]]\n| coach_years9 = 2007\u20132010\n| coach_team9 = [[Tulsa Golden Hurricane football|Tulsa]]\n| coach_years10 = 2011\n| coach_team10 = [[Pittsburgh Panthers football|Pittsburgh]]\n| coach_years11 = 2012\u20132017\n| coach_team11 = [[Arizona State Sun Devils football|Arizona State]]\n| coach_years12 = 2020\u2013present\n| coach_team12 = [[Hawaii Rainbow Warriors football|Hawaii]]\n| overall_record = 95\u201361 (college) <!-- As of games through 12/29/17 -->\n| bowl_record = 5\u20134\n| tournament_record = \n| championships = 1 [[Pac-12 Conference|Pac-12 South Division]] (2013)<br>3 [[Conference USA|C-USA West Division]] (2007\u20132008, 2010)\n| awards = 1 [[Pac-12 Conference football individual awards#Coach of the Year|Pac-12 Coach of the Year]] (2013)<br>1 [[Conference USA|C-USA Coach of the Year]] (2006)\n| coaching_records = \n}}\n'''Michael Todd Graham''' (born December 5, 1964) is an [[American football]] coach and former player. He is the current head football coach at the [[University of Hawaii]]. Graham has served as the head football coach at [[Rice University]] (2006), the [[University of Tulsa]] (2007\u20132010), the [[University of Pittsburgh]] (2011) and [[Arizona State University]] (2012\u20132017).\n\n==Playing career==\nGraham was an all-district defensive back at [[North Mesquite High School]], from which he graduated in 1983. He then went on to play at [[East Central University]] in [[Ada, Oklahoma]], where he was a two-time All-[[National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics|NAIA]] defensive back. After graduation from East Central, Graham had a brief stint with the [[Arizona Cardinals]] of the [[NFL]].<ref>http://msn.foxsports.com/collegefootball/story/Arizona-State-coach-Todd-Graham-talks-Pittsburgh-Territorial-Cup-and-loyalty-to-Tempe-050112</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nGraham began his coaching career in 1988 as an assistant at [[Poteet High School (Mesquite, Texas)|Poteet High School]] in his hometown of Mesquite. He later held head coaching positions at [[Carl Albert High School]] in [[Midwest City, Oklahoma]], and [[Allen High School (Allen, Texas)|Allen High School]] in [[Allen, Texas]] before becoming linebackers coach under [[Rich Rodriguez]] at [[West Virginia University]] in 2001.<ref>[http://www.gtrnews.com/greater-tulsa-reporter/1646/head-football-coach-todd-graham-happy-to-be-at-tu Head Football Coach Todd Graham Happy to be at TU]</ref> The following season Graham was assigned to defensive co-coordinator.\n\nIn 2003, he was hired by [[Steve Kragthorpe]] as the defensive coordinator at Tulsa, where he helped guide the Golden Hurricane to two bowl games in three seasons. Graham built one of the best defensive units in [[Conference USA]] and the nation before leaving the position following his third year at Tulsa for his first head coaching stint.\n\n===Rice===\nGraham was hired as the head coach at Rice on January 1, 2006.<ref name=\"Rice bio\">{{cite web|title=Todd Graham|url=http://www.riceowls.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/graham_todd00.html|publisher=Rice University Athletics|accessdate=April 13, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070103194809/http://riceowls.cstv.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/graham_todd00.html|archivedate=January 3, 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> This followed the resignation of long-time coach [[Ken Hatfield]] after the Owls had finished 1\u201310 in 2005. At Rice, athletic director Chris Del Conte helped Graham raise $5.5 million for renovating [[Rice Stadium (Rice University)|Rice Stadium]] and replacing the dated [[AstroTurf]] with [[FieldTurf]]. He hired former [[University of Texas]] quarterback [[Major Applewhite]] as his offensive coordinator,<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=2284752 Applewhite named offensive coordinator at Rice]</ref> replacing the [[triple option offense]] Hatfield had been running with a more balanced attack. Behind quarterback Chase Clement and All-American receiver [[Jarett Dillard]], Rice pulled off the biggest turnaround of the 2006 season, finishing 7\u20135 and earning an invitation to the [[New Orleans Bowl]], the school's first bowl game since 1961.<ref name=\"Rice bio\"/> Graham was named [[Conference USA]] Coach of the Year, and was rewarded by the Rice administration with the offer of a significant pay raise and contract extension.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://the.ricethresher.org/sports/2007/01/12/graham_contract_extension|title=Graham strikes deal in contract extension|work=The Rice Thresher|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070714194404/http://the.ricethresher.org/sports/2007/01/12/graham_contract_extension|archivedate=July 14, 2007}}</ref>  After signing this extension, Graham left for Tulsa only a few days later.  Graham received much criticism for this move.  On November 24, 2007, when Tulsa played Rice at [[Rice Stadium (Rice University)|Rice Stadium]], the Rice University [[Marching Owl Band]] presented a [[halftime show]] named \"Todd Graham's Inferno\"<ref>[http://mob.rice.edu/history/scripts/2007/Nov24_Tulsa.shtml Todd Graham's Inferno]</ref> (based on Dante's \"[[The Divine Comedy]]\").  This resulted in a formal protest to [[Conference USA]] by Tulsa's athletic department. Chuck Throckmorton, the marching band's director, later apologized for offending anyone, but not for the show.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/news/story?id=3129832 Rice band's 'Todd Graham's Inferno' not a hit with Tulsa],</ref><ref>[https://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/sports/5335557.html Rice band director apologizes for Graham routine]</ref>  Following Graham's exodus, Rice hired [[David Bailiff]], who led Rice to its [[2008 Texas Bowl]], and its [[2012 Armed Forces Bowl]] and the 2013 Conference USA title.\n\n===Tulsa===\n\nWhen the Tulsa head coaching position was vacant following the 2002 season, Todd Graham sent in his application. But it was not until five years later that Graham would take over the reins as the Golden Hurricane head coach. After serving three years as Tulsa defensive coordinator and one year as Rice head coach, Graham was introduced as Tulsa's 27th head football coach on January 12, 2007.<ref name=\"Tulsa bio\">{{cite web|title=Todd Graham|url=http://www.tulsahurricane.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/graham_todd00.html|publisher=Tulsa University Athletics|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717112154/http://www.tulsahurricane.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/graham_todd00.html|archivedate=July 17, 2011}}</ref>\n\nFor his offensive coordinators, Graham turned to his good friend [[Gus Malzahn]], then offensive coordinator at the [[University of Arkansas]],<ref>[http://www.kait8.com/global/story.asp?s=5941114&ClientType=Printable Gus Malzahn Leaves Arkansas]</ref> as well as then WVU [[tight end]]s coach Herb Hand.<ref>[http://westvirginia.scout.com/2/609200.html Hand Leaves West Virginia For Tulsa]</ref> He also hired former Tulsa quarterback and [[Union Public Schools|Tulsa Union HS]] coach [[Bill Blankenship]] as wide receivers coach.\n\nWith an annual salary of $1.1 million Graham was the second highest-paid coach in  [[Conference USA]], behind SMU's [[June Jones]] in 2010.\n\nIn his final season at Tulsa, the team reached a 10\u20133 record that included a 28\u201327 upset at [[2010 Notre Dame Fighting Irish football team|Notre Dame]] and 62\u201335 win over #24-ranked [[2010 Hawaii Warriors football team|Hawaii]] in the [[2010 Hawaii Bowl]].<ref name=\"Pitt bio\">{{cite web|title=Todd Graham|url=http://www.pittsburghpanthers.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/graham_todd00.html|publisher=University of Pittsburgh Athletics|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111227134244/http://www.pittsburghpanthers.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/graham_todd00.html|archivedate=December 27, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Pitt===\nGraham was announced as Pitt's head coach on January 10, 2011,<ref name=\"Pitt bio\"/><ref>{{cite news | url=http://post-gazette.com/pg/11011/1117054-233.stm | title=Pitt's search ends with hiring of Tulsa's Graham |first=Paul | last=Zeise | first2=Bill | last2=Brink | newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette | location=Pittsburgh, PA | date=January 11, 2010 | accessdate=January 11, 2010 }}</ref> and subsequently led the team to a disappointing 6\u20136 regular season later that fall. Less than one year from his hiring, on the evening of December 13, Graham informed  Athletic Director [[Steve Pederson]] that he had discussed a head coaching opportunity at Arizona State.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.pittsburghpanthers.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/121411aaa.html | title=Keith Patterson Named Interim Coach for Pitt Football | publisher=PittsburghPanthers.com | date=December 14, 2011 | accessdate=December 14, 2011 }}</ref> After being informed he did not have permission to talk to the school about the job and refusing conversations with Pederson and another administrator, Graham resigned and subsequently accepted the head coaching job at Arizona State.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/11349/1197067-233.stm| title=Graham leaves Pitt for Arizona St. | first=Paul | last=Zeiss | newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette | date=December 15, 2011 | accessdate=December 15, 2011 }}</ref> Graham informed the Pitt players of his departure the following day by having a text message forwarded to the team by director of football operations Blair Philbrick.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://espn.go.com/college-football/story/_/id/7352624/todd-graham-takes-arizona-state-sun-devils-football-coaching-job-leaving-pittsburgh-panthers | title=Todd Graham to coach Sun Devils | publisher=ESPN.com | date=December 14, 2011 | accessdate=December 14, 2011 }}</ref> Two weeks prior to leaving Pitt, Graham referred to assistant coaches who left to join the staff of [[Rich Rodriguez]] at Arizona as \"nothing but mercenaries.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/11349/1197067-233.stm | work=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette | first=Paul | last=Zeise | title=Graham leaves Pitt for Arizona State | date=December 15, 2011 }}</ref> In later interviews, Graham claimed those comments were taken out of context.  He said he wasn't referring to the coaches who left Pittsburgh and that he was having a conversation with reporters generally about college football coaching and said, \"A lot of times coaches jump around everywhere, they're like mercenaries.\"<ref>http://www.cbssports.com/collegefootball/story/16543148/graham-might-have-run-out-on-pitt-but-what-regular-guy-wouldnt</ref>\n\nThe style in which Graham left, in combination with his quick departures from other universities, led to criticism of Graham in both local and national media.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://sports.yahoo.com/ncaa/football/news;_ylt=AqHA7cqj0spXI2VaQtt0E4I5nYcB?slug=pf-forde_graham_quits_pitt_asu_121511 | first=Pat | last=Ford | title=Graham\u2019s classless departure for ASU nothing new | publisher=Yahoo! Sports | date=December 15, 2011 | accessdate=December 16, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://espn.go.com/blog/bigeast/post/_/id/27739/pitt-has-to-start-over-again | title=Pitt has to start over \u2013 again | first=Andrea | last=Adelson | publisher=ESPN.com| date=December 14, 2011 | accessdate=December 16, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url= http://blog.chron.com/jeromesolomon/2011/12/todd-graham-makes-another-despicable-decision/  | title=Todd Graham makes another despicable decision | first=Jerome | last=Solomon | newspaper=Houston Chronicle | publisher=Chron.com | date=December 15, 2011 | accessdate=December 16, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.foxsportsarizona.com/12/15/11/Grahams-actions-belie-talk-of-character/landing_sundevils.html?blockID=627164&feedID=3702 | title=Graham's actions belie talk of 'character' |  first=Craig | last=Morgan | publisher=FoxSportsArizona.com | date=December 15, 2011 | accessdate=December 16, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/11348/1196961-233-0.stm | title=Pitt was a dry run for Graham | first=Gene | last=Collier |  newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette | date=December 14, 2011 | accessdate=December 16, 2011 }}</ref>  University of Pittsburgh players also openly criticized Graham for his quick departure. Defensive tackle [[Chas Alecxih]] said most players were \"shocked and appalled.\" Wide receiver [[Devin Street]]'s comments were a little more severe stating, \"It's been all a lie this whole time. Everything he told us has been a lie.\" Another one of Graham's players at the time, senior offensive tackle [[Lucas Nix]], stated that he felt Graham's exiting text message wasn't worthy of the trust the team had put into Graham and his program. \"We put our trust in him, and all he could do was send us a text message,\" Nix said.<ref>{{cite news|author=DiPaola, Jerry|title=Pitt left to pick up pieces after Graham exit|url=http://triblive.com/x/pittsburghtrib/sports/college/pitt/s_772129.html |newspaper=Pittsburgh Tribune-Review |date=December 14, 2011|accessdate=December 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Arizona State===\nGraham was announced as Arizona State University's head coach on December 14, 2011.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thesundevils.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/graham_todd00.html | title=Todd Graham Profile | publisher=Arizona Skjtate University | date=December 15, 2011 | accessdate=September 14, 2012}}</ref> In his first season at Arizona State, the Sun Devils went 8\u20135 securing their first winning season since 2007. With a win in the [[2012 Kraft Fight Hunger Bowl|Kraft Fight Hunger Bowl]] against the [[Navy Midshipmen]], the 2012 Sun Devils won the final three games of the season for the first time since 1978.<ref>{{cite web |author=Haller, Doug | url=https://www.azcentral.com/sports/asu/articles/20121229asu-football-routs-navy-in-the-kraft-fight-hunger-bowl.html| title=ASU football routs Navy in the Kraft Fight Hunger Bowl | work=The Arizona Republic | date=December 29, 2012 | accessdate=January 2, 2013 }}</ref> ESPN's Pac-12 Blog writer Ted Miller called Todd Graham's first season at Arizona State an \"unquestioned success.\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://espn.go.com/blog/pac12/post/_/id/50091/pac-12-power-rankings-week-14-2| title=Pac-12 Power Rankings Week 14 | publisher=ESPN | date=November 26, 2012 | accessdate=November 27, 2012 }}</ref> In 2013, Graham continued to build positive momentum and led ASU to win the Pac-12 South after defeating [[UCLA]] and rival [[University of Arizona]]. ASU finished the season 10\u20134 and ranked #21 in the AP Poll and #20 in the Coach's Poll.<ref>http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/recap?gameId=333270026</ref> For his efforts in leading ASU to a Pac-12 South championship, Graham received the 2013 Pac-12 Coach of the Year Award. In 2014, ASU finished with yet another 10 win season by going 10\u20133 and ranking #12 in the final AP Poll and #14 in the final Coach's Poll.  The season was capped off with Graham leading the Sun Devils to victory over [[Duke University]] in the [[Sun Bowl]]. <ref>http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=400610211</ref> The 2015 season saw a big drop off for the program as the Sun Devils finished a disappointing 6\u20137 with a 43\u201342 loss to the [[West Virginia Mountaineers]] in the [[Cactus Bowl]]. The trend continued into the next two seasons. The Sun Devils finished 2016 on a 6 game losing streak which culminated in a 5\u20137 record. 2017 would be Graham's final season. The team improved only slightly, finishing 7\u20136. Graham and Arizona State agreed to part ways after winning the last regular season game of the year against rival [[Arizona Wildcats football|Arizona]], and retaining the [[Arizona\u2013Arizona State football rivalry|Territorial Cup]]. The Sun Bowl against [[North Carolina State]] would be his last game as Arizona State head coach. The result was a 52\u201331 loss to the Wolfpack.\n\n===Hawaii===\nOn January 21, 2020, Graham was hired by the [[University of Hawaii]] as the 24th head football coach in the school's history after being away from college football for two years.<ref>https://www.khon2.com/sports/breaking-former-arizona-state-coach-todd-graham-to-become-new-hawaii-head-coach/</ref>\n\n==Head coaching record==\n===College===\n{{CFB Yearly Record Start | type = coach | team = | conf = | bowl = | poll = both }}\n{{CFB Yearly Record Subhead\n | name      = [[Rice Owls football|Rice Owls]]\n | conf      = [[Conference USA]]\n | startyear = 2006\n | endyear   = single\n}}\n