{"title_page": "St Mary's College, Melbourne", "text_new": "{{Infobox residential college\n| name = St Mary's College, University of Melbourne \n| image = [[File:St Mary's College (University of Melbourne).jpg|250px|Front Gate]]\n| alt =\n| caption = The front gate of St Mary's College\n| shield = Logo of St Mary's College Melbourne.jpg\n| shield_alt =\n| shield_caption = Shield of the college\n| scarf = <!-- {{scarf|{{cell|color1}}{{cell|color2}}...}} -->\n| university = [[University of Melbourne]]\n| location = Corner of Tin Alley and 871 [[Swanston Street]], Parkville, [[Melbourne, Victoria]]\n| quad = \n| coordinates = {{coord|37|47|46|S|144|57|50|E|region:AU-VIC_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| full_name =\n| name_Latin =\n| motto = Ut Testimonium Perhibeam Veritati\n| motto_lang =\n| motto_English = That I may bear witness to the truth \n| founder = <!-- or | founders = -->\n| established = 1918 \n| named_for = [[Mary (mother of Jesus)]] <!-- or | namesake = -->\n| previous_names = St Mary's Hall\n| status = \n| colours = Navy Blue and Red\n{{colorbox|Navy}} {{colorbox|Red}}\n| principal = Dr Darcy McCormack\n| undergraduates = 161\n| postgraduates = 8\n| senior_tutor = \n| res_tutors = 8\n| website = [http://www.stmarys.unimelb.edu.au/ St Mary's College website]\n| location_map = \n| map_size = \n}}\n\n'''St Mary's College''' is a medium-sized [[residential college]] affiliated with the [[University of Melbourne]].<ref name=\"unimelbourne\">[http://www.colleges.unimelb.edu.au/colleges/college-stmarys.html University of Melbourne: St Mary's College]</ref><ref name=\"loreto\">[http://www.loreto.org.au/Home/What-We-Do/Education/Schools-Colleges.aspx Loreto South East Asia and Australia: Our Schools and Colleges] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203134136/http://www.loreto.org.au/Home/What-We-Do/Education/Schools-Colleges.aspx |date=2012-02-03 }}</ref> It was founded on and still practices the Catholic tradition.<ref name=\"unimelbourne\"/> \n\n==Location==\nThe college is located on [[Swanston Street]] in Parkville, a suburb of Melbourne.<ref name=\"stmaryscollegehistory\"/>\n\n==History==\nSt Mary's College was originally established in 1918 as St Mary's Hall, catering to women mainly from the country.<ref name=\"loreto\"/><ref name=\"stmaryscollegehistory\">[http://www.stmarys.unimelb.edu.au/?page_id=12 St Mary's College: History]</ref> Formerly on The Avenue in Parkville, it moved to its present position on the corner of Tin Alley and Swanston Street in 1966.<ref name=\"stmaryscollegehistory\"/> It was in that year that it became a college, the female affiliate of the Catholic male [[Newman College (University of Melbourne)|Newman College]].<ref name=\"stmaryscollegehistory\"/>\n\nIn 1977, St Mary's became co-residential. It now exists independent of Newman.<ref name=\"stmaryscollegehistory\"/> Since its inception until 1996, St Mary's College was administered by the [[Sisters of Loreto]].<ref name=\"loreto\"/><ref name=\"stmaryscollegehistory\"/>The leadership and governance of the college is now the responsibility of the Catholic Archdiocese of Melbourne and the Catholic Bishops of the Country dioceses.\n\nIn 2004, the Allan & Maria Myers Academic Centre, a joint facility shared between St Mary\u2019s and Newman College, was opened. It was designed by [[Maggie Edmond]] and [[Peter Corrigan]] to reflect the overall academic vision of both colleges to enhance the educational facilities and opportunities available to the students of the colleges. The centre contains a library, tutorial rooms, music practice rooms, student lounges and information technology facilities.\n\n==Student body==\nIt is home to around 170 students, the majority who are undergraduate students attending the University of Melbourne, although a very small percentage attend either the [[Australian Catholic University]], [[Monash University, Parkville campus]], or [[RMIT University]].\n\nThe majority of students at St Mary's are from rural and regional Victoria, and some are interstate or international students.<ref name=\"unimelbourne\"/> The college has a very strong sporting tradition, particularly in the disciplines of [[Australian rules football]] and netball. Its official colours are navy blue and red. In 2016 the St Mary's Women's Rowing VIII rowed their way to a drought breaking victory in second division, the first win since 1962. This victory was repeated in 2017.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.stmarys.unimelb.edu.au/ St Mary's College website]\n\n{{University of Melbourne}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Marys College (University of Melbourne)}}\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1918]]\n[[Category:Residential colleges of the University of Melbourne]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox residential college\n| name = St Mary's College, University of Melbourne \n| image = [[File:St Mary's College (University of Melbourne).jpg|250px|Front Gate]]\n| alt =\n| caption = The front gate of St Mary's College\n| shield = Logo of St Mary's College Melbourne.jpg\n| shield_alt =\n| shield_caption = Shield of the college\n| scarf = <!-- {{scarf|{{cell|color1}}{{cell|color2}}...}} -->\n| university = [[University of Melbourne]]\n| location = Corner of Tin Alley and 871 [[Swanston Street]], Parkville, [[Melbourne, Victoria]]\n| quad = \n| coordinates = {{coord|37|47|46|S|144|57|50|E|region:AU-VIC_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| full_name =\n| name_Latin =\n| motto = Ut Testimonium Perhibeam Veritati\n| motto_lang =\n| motto_English = That I may bear witness to the truth \n| founder = <!-- or | founders = -->\n| established = 1918 \n| named_for = [[Mary (mother of Jesus)]] <!-- or | namesake = -->\n| previous_names = St Mary's Hall\n| status = \n| colours = Navy Blue and Red\n{{colorbox|Navy}} {{colorbox|Red}}\n| principal = Dr Darcy McCormack\n| undergraduates = 161\n| postgraduates = 8\n| senior_tutor = \n| res_tutors = 8\n| website = [http://www.stmarys.unimelb.edu.au/ St Mary's College website]\n| location_map = \n| map_size = \n}}\n\n'''St Mary's College''' is a medium-sized [[residential college]] affiliated with the [[University of Melbourne]].<ref name=\"unimelbourne\">[http://www.colleges.unimelb.edu.au/colleges/college-stmarys.html University of Melbourne: St Mary's College]</ref><ref name=\"loreto\">[http://www.loreto.org.au/Home/What-We-Do/Education/Schools-Colleges.aspx Loreto South East Asia and Australia: Our Schools and Colleges] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120203134136/http://www.loreto.org.au/Home/What-We-Do/Education/Schools-Colleges.aspx |date=2012-02-03 }}</ref> It was founded on and still practices the Catholic tradition.<ref name=\"unimelbourne\"/> \n\n==Location==\nThe college is located on [[Swanston Street]] in Parkville, a suburb of Melbourne.<ref name=\"stmaryscollegehistory\"/>\n\n==History==\nSt Mary's College was originally established in 1918 as St Mary's Hall, catering to women mainly from the country.<ref name=\"loreto\"/><ref name=\"stmaryscollegehistory\">[http://www.stmarys.unimelb.edu.au/?page_id=12 St Mary's College: History]</ref> Formerly on The Avenue in Parkville, it moved to its present position on the corner of Tin Alley and Swanston Street in 1966.<ref name=\"stmaryscollegehistory\"/> It was in that year that it became a college, the female affiliate of the Catholic male [[Newman College (University of Melbourne)|Newman College]].<ref name=\"stmaryscollegehistory\"/>\n\nIn 1977, St Mary's became co-residential. It now exists independent of Newman.<ref name=\"stmaryscollegehistory\"/> Since its inception until 1996, St Mary's College was administered by the [[Sisters of Loreto]].<ref name=\"loreto\"/><ref name=\"stmaryscollegehistory\"/>The leadership and governance of the college is now the responsibility of the Catholic Archdiocese of Melbourne and the Catholic Bishops of the Country dioceses.\n\nIn 2004, the Alan & Maria Myers Academic Centre, a joint facility shared between St Mary\u2019s and Newman College, was opened. It was designed by [[Maggie Edmond]] and [[Peter Corrigan]] to reflect the overall academic vision of both colleges to enhance the educational facilities and opportunities available to the students of the colleges. The centre contains a library, tutorial rooms, music practice rooms, student lounges and information technology facilities.\n\n==Student body==\nIt is home to around 170 students, the majority who are undergraduate students attending the University of Melbourne, although a very small percentage attend either the [[Australian Catholic University]], [[Monash University, Parkville campus]], or [[RMIT University]].\n\nThe majority of students at St Mary's are from rural and regional Victoria, and some are interstate or international students.<ref name=\"unimelbourne\"/> The college has a very strong sporting tradition, particularly in the disciplines of [[Australian rules football]] and netball. Its official colours are navy blue and red. In 2016 the St Mary's Women's Rowing VIII rowed their way to a drought breaking victory in second division, the first win since 1962. This victory was repeated in 2017.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.stmarys.unimelb.edu.au/ St Mary's College website]\n\n{{University of Melbourne}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Saint Marys College (University of Melbourne)}}\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1918]]\n[[Category:Residential colleges of the University of Melbourne]]\n", "name_user": "AussieOxonian", "label": "safe", "comment": "Corrected spelling of name.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St_Mary%27s_College,_Melbourne"}
